 Hin]] (race 1)<br />[[Frans Hin]] (race 2 & 3)}}\n                    | crew01      = {{Sailor|[[Johan Hin]]}}\n                    | boatsname   = Beatrijs III\n                    | fleetrace01 = {{Fleetrace|place=2|points=2}}\n                    | fleetrace02 = {{Fleetrace|place=CAN|points=0}}\n                    | fleetrace03 = {{Fleetrace|place=1|points=1}}\n                    | fleetrace04 = {{Fleetrace|place=1|points=1}}\n                    | total       = 4\n                  }}\n                  {{Sailing result line\n                    | year        = 1920\n                    | rank        = silver\n                    | countrycode = NED\n                    | helmsman    = {{Sailor|[[Arnoud van der Biesen]]}}\n                    | crew01      = {{Sailor|[[Petrus Beukers]]}}\n                    | boatsname   = Boreas\n                    | fleetrace01 = {{Fleetrace|place=1|points=1}}\n                    | fleetrace02 = {{Fleetrace|place=CAN|points=0}}\n                    | fleetrace03 = {{Fleetrace|place=1|points=1}}\n                    | fleetrace04 = {{Fleetrace|place=DNF|points=3}}\n                    | total       = 6\n                  }}\n  | legendlines = {{sailing result legend\n                    |DNF = yes\n                    |CAN = yes\n                  }}\n\n}}\n\n== Daily standings ==\n[[File:1920 12' DINGHY Positions during the serie.png|500px|thumb|left|Graph showing the daily standings in the 12' Dinghy during the 1920 Summer Olympics]]\n{{clear}}\n\n== Notes ==\n* This was the first Olympic event ever, and the only Olympic sailing event that was held outside the organizing country.\n* During race No. II one of the marks was drifting the race was cancelled (Nullified). Since the organizers did not have the time to re-sail the race that week the two remaining races were rescheduled for September 3. Because both contenders were Dutch, the organizers requested the Dutch Olympic Committee to organize the race in Amsterdam [[IJ (Amsterdam)|Buiten Y]].\n* [[Cornelis Hin]] helmed in race No. I and the cancelled race No. II, [[Frans Hin]] helmed the two races in Amsterdam.\n\n== Other information ==\n\n===Sailors===\nDuring the Sailing regattas at the 1920 Summer Olympics among others the following persons were competing in the various classes:\n{{Gallery\n  |title=12' Dinghy sailors at the 1920 Olympic Games\n  |width=210\n  |height=150\n  |lines=3\n  |File:Cornelis Hin.jpg|Cornelis Hin, helmed the two races in Ostend\n  |File:Johan Hin.jpg|Johan Hin, crewed all races\n}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite web \n    |title      = Digital Library Collection (Official Olympic Reports 1896 - 2008)\n    |url        = http://search.la84.org/search\n    |work       = Digital Library Collection at la84.org\n    |publisher  = la84foundation\n    |accessdate = 6 February 2015\n  }}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n  <ref name     = \"A\">\n    {{cite book \n      |title=Olympic Games 1920 \u2013 Officiel Report\n      |editor= Belgium Olympic Committee \n      |year=1957\n      |url=http://la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1920/1920.pdf\n      |format=PDF \n      |accessdate=8 February 2015\n    }}\n</ref>\n  <ref name     = \"B\">\n    {{cite web \n      | title=Olympic Medal Winners \n      | publisher=[[International Olympic Committee]] \n      |url=http://www.olympic.org/uk/athletes/results/search_r_uk.asp \n      | accessdate=7 February 2015 \n    }}\n</ref>\n  <ref name     = \"C\">\n    {{cite web \n      | title=Nederlands goud (5) \n      | author=Heijmans, Jeroen \n      | url=http://www.sportgeschiedenis.nl/2007/06/24/nederlands-goud-5.aspx\n      | accessdate=8 February 2015 \n    }}\n</ref>\n}}\n{{IOC games|games=1920 Summer Olympics }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sailing at the 1920 Summer Olympics - 12' Dinghy}}\n[[Category:Sailing at the 1920 Summer Olympics|12' Dinghy]]\n[[Category:12 foot dinghy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Olympic event\n  |event          = 12' Dinghy<ref name=\"A\" />\n  |games          = 1920 Summer\n  |image          = 12 foot dinghy.svg\n  |image_size     = 100px\n  |caption        = Line drawing of the 12' Dinghy\n  |venue          = {{BEL}}, [[Ostend]] <br /> {{NED}}, [[Amsterdam]]\n  |dates          = First race: {{Start date|df=yes|1920|07|07}}<br />Last race: {{End date|df=yes|1920|09|03}}\n  |competitors    = 5\n  |nations        = 1\n  |teams          = 2\n  |gold           = [[Cornelis Hin]], <br />[[Johan Hin]], <br />[[Frans Hin]]\n  |goldNOC        = NED\n  |silver         = [[Arnoud van der Biesen]], <br />[[Petrus Beukers]]\n  |silverNOC      = NED\n  |prev           = \n  |next           = [[Sailing at the 1928 Summer Olympics \u2013 12' Dinghy|1928]]\n}}\n{{Classes used for Sailing at the Summer Olympics|year = 1920}}\nThe '''[[12 foot dinghy|12' Dinghy]]''' was a sailing event on the [[Sailing at the 1920 Summer Olympics]] program in [[Ostend]] and [[Amsterdam]]. Four races were scheduled. 5 sailors, on 2 boats, from 1 nation entered.\n\n== Race schedule<ref name=\"C\" />==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em auto; font-size:90%;position:relative;\"\n|-\n|bgcolor=#00cc33 align=center|&nbsp;\u25cf&nbsp;||Opening ceremony|| bgcolor=#3399ff align=center|&nbsp;\u25cf&nbsp;||Event competitions || bgcolor=#ffcc00 align=center|&nbsp;\u25cf&nbsp;||Event finals ||bgcolor=#ee3333|&nbsp;\u25cf&nbsp;||Closing ceremony\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em auto; font-size:90%; line-height:1.25em;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Date \n!colspan=4|July {{BEL}}!!colspan=3|September {{NED}}\n|-\n!7<br />Wed!!8<br />Thu!!9<br />Fri!!10<br />Sat!!3<br />Fri!!4<br />Sat!!5<br />Sun\n|- align=\"center\"\n| align=\"left\" | 12' Dinghy (planning)\n| bgcolor=#3399ff |<span style=\"line-height:0.7em;\">\u25cf </span>\n| bgcolor=#3399ff |<span style=\"line-height:0.7em;\">\u25cf </span>\n| bgcolor=#3399ff |<span style=\"line-height:0.7em;\">\u25cf </span>\n| bgcolor=#ffcc00 |<span style=\"line-height:0.7em;\">\u25cf </span>\n|\n|\n|\n|- align=\"center\"\n|-\n! Total gold medals !! !!   !!  !! 1 !!   !!   !!\n|-\n|- align=\"center\"\n| align=\"left\" | 12' Dinghy (actual)\n| bgcolor=#3399ff |<span style=\"line-height:0.7em;\">1 </span> \n| \n| \n| \n| bgcolor=#ffcc00 |<span style=\"line-height:0.7em;\">2 </span>  \n| colspan=2|Dutch national races\n|- align=\"center\"\n|-\n! Total gold medals !! !! !! !!  !! 1 !! !!\n|-\n|}\n\n== Course area ==\n{{Multiple image\n | title     = 12' Dinghy 1920 Olympic Course Areas\n | align     = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 300\n | image1    = 1920 Sailing Olympic Course Area.png\n | caption1  = Ostend, Belgium\n | image2    = Buiten IJ.png\n | caption2  = Buiten Y. The Netherlands\n}}\n{{clear}}\n\n== Weather conditions <ref name=\"A\" />==\n{{Improve Olympic Sailing Article|class= |image=Stormclouds.jpg|year=1920|section=Weather conditions|date=23 February 2015}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:90%\"\n|-\n!Date!!Max temperature!!Wind speed!!Average wind direction\n|-\n|7 July 1920||colspan=3 align=center|Unknown \n|-\n|8 July 1920||colspan=3 align=center|Unknown \n|-\n|10 September 1920||align=center|{{convert|18.8|C|F}}||align=left|{{convert|3.6|m/s|kn}} -<br />{{convert|8.2|m/s|kn}}||align=center|[[File:NNW Wind.svg|50px]]\n|}\n\n== Final results<ref name=\"B\" /> ==\nThe [[Scoring systems for Sailing at the Summer Olympics#1920 Olympic scoring|1920 Olympic scoring]] system was used. All competitors were male.\n{{Sailing result block | event = Olympics | crew = yes | sailno = no | boatsname = yes | races = 4 | total = yes | netto = no\n  | resultlines = {{Sailing result line\n                    | year        = 1920\n                    | rank        = gold\n                    | countrycode = NED\n                    | helmsman    = {{Sailor|[[Cornelis Hin]] (race 1)<br />[[Frans Hin]] (race 2 & 3)}}\n                    | crew01      = {{Sailor|[[Johan Hin]]}}\n                    | boatsname   = Beatrijs III\n                    | fleetrace01 = {{Fleetrace|place=2|points=2}}\n                    | fleetrace02 = {{Fleetrace|place=CAN|points=0}}\n                    | fleetrace03 = {{Fleetrace|place=1|points=1}}\n                    | fleetrace04 = {{Fleetrace|place=1|points=1}}\n                    | total       = 4\n                  }}\n                  {{Sailing result line\n                    | year        = 1920\n                    | rank        = silver\n                    | countrycode = NED\n                    | helmsman    = {{Sailor|[[Arnoud van der Biesen]]}}\n                    | crew01      = {{Sailor|[[Petrus Beukers]]}}\n                    | boatsname   = Boreas\n                    | fleetrace01 = {{Fleetrace|place=1|points=1}}\n                    | fleetrace02 = {{Fleetrace|place=CAN|points=0}}\n                    | fleetrace03 = {{Fleetrace|place=1|points=1}}\n                    | fleetrace04 = {{Fleetrace|place=DNF|points=3}}\n                    | total       = 6\n                  }}\n  | legendlines = {{sailing result legend\n                    |DNF = yes\n                    |CAN = yes\n                  }}\n\n}}\n\n== Daily standings ==\n[[File:1920 12' DINGHY Positions during the serie.png|500px|thumb|left|Graph showing the daily standings in the 12' Dinghy during the 1920 Summer Olympics]]\n{{clear}}\n\n== Notes ==\n* This was the first Olympic event ever, and the only Olympic sailing event that was held outside the organizing country\n* During race No. II one of the marks was drifting the race was cancelled (Nullified). Since the organizers did not have the time to re-sail the race that week the two remaining races were rescheduled for September 3. Because both contenders were Dutch, the organizers requested the Dutch Olympic Committee to organize the race in Amsterdam [[IJ (Amsterdam)|Buiten Y]]\n* [[Cornelis Hin]] helmed in race No. I and the cancelled race No. II, [[Frans Hin]] helmed the two races in Amsterdam\n\n== Other information ==\n\n===Sailors===\nDuring the Sailing regattas at the 1920 Summer Olympics among others the following persons were competing in the various classes:\n{{Gallery\n  |title=12' Dinghy sailors at the 1920 Olympic Games\n  |width=210\n  |height=150\n  |lines=3\n  |File:Cornelis Hin.jpg|Cornelis Hin, helmed the two races in Ostend\n  |File:Johan Hin.jpg|Johan Hin, crewed all races\n}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite web \n    |title      = Digital Library Collection (Official Olympic Reports 1896 - 2008)\n    |url        = http://search.la84.org/search\n    |work       = Digital Library Collection at la84.org\n    |publisher  = la84foundation\n    |accessdate = 6 February 2015\n  }}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n  <ref name     = \"A\">\n    {{cite book \n      |title=Olympic Games 1920 \u2013 Officiel Report\n      |editor= Belgium Olympic Committee \n      |year=1957\n      |url=http://la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1920/1920.pdf\n      |format=PDF \n      |accessdate=8 February 2015\n    }}\n</ref>\n  <ref name     = \"B\">\n    {{cite web \n      | title=Olympic Medal Winners \n      | publisher=[[International Olympic Committee]] \n      |url=http://www.olympic.org/uk/athletes/results/search_r_uk.asp \n      | accessdate=7 February 2015 \n    }}\n</ref>\n  <ref name     = \"C\">\n    {{cite web \n      | title=Nederlands goud (5) \n      | author=Heijmans, Jeroen \n      | url=http://www.sportgeschiedenis.nl/2007/06/24/nederlands-goud-5.aspx\n      | accessdate=8 February 2015 \n    }}\n</ref>\n}}\n{{IOC games|games=1920 Summer Olympics }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sailing at the 1920 Summer Olympics - 12' Dinghy}}\n[[Category:Sailing at the 1920 Summer Olympics|12' Dinghy]]\n[[Category:12 foot dinghy]]\n", "name_user": "Berlin2019", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sailing_at_the_1920_Summer_Olympics_%E2%80%93_12%27_Dinghy"}
{"title_page": "Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{More medical citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|False information about coronavirus}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\n'''Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic''' consists of [[conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] and [[disinformation]] that emerged regarding the origin, scale, prevention and treatment surrounding the [[COVID-19]] disease and the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ensuing pandemic]] related to the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]] virus.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |title=China coronavirus: Misinformation spreads online about origin and scale |date=January 30, 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200204163412/https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=GUAR>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum | title=Bat soup, dodgy cures and 'diseasology': the spread of coronavirus misinformation | date=January 31, 2020 | access-date=February 3, 2020 | first=Josh | last=Taylor | name-list-format = vanc | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202141231/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum | archive-date=February 2, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Lowy>{{Cite news|first=Natasha|last=Kassam| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.lowyinstitute.org/the-interpreter/disinformation-and-coronavirus|work=The Interpreter|publisher=Lowy Institute|title=Disinformation and coronavirus|date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=RunningList>{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/janelytvynenko/coronavirus-disinformation-spread |title=Here's A Running List Of Disinformation Spreading About The Coronavirus |website=Buzzfeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206212717/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/janelytvynenko/coronavirus-disinformation-spread |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Disinformation and [[misinformation]] can be spread through social media,<ref name=Lowy /><ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/social-media-posts-spread-bogus-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/ |title=Social Media Posts Spread Bogus Coronavirus Conspiracy Theory |first=Jessica |last=McDonald | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 24, 2020 |work=Factcheck.org |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200206102802/https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/social-media-posts-spread-bogus-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/ |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> text messages,<ref name=\"FTTextMsg\">{{cite web|author=Hannah Murphy, Mark Di Stefano & Katrina Manson|url=https://www.ft.com/content/34b6df5a-ea4a-471f-8ac9-606580480049|title=Huge text message campaigns spread coronavirus fake news|date=March 20, 2020|work=Financial Times}}</ref><ref name=FriendsAunt>{{cite news|first=Mihir|last=Zaveri| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-text-messages-national-quarantine.html|title=Be Wary of Those Texts From a Friend of a Friend's Aunt|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> [[mass media]],<ref name=\"fp_0414conspiracy\">{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/04/14/as-the-coronavirus-spreads-conspiracy-theories-are-going-viral-too/|title=As the Coronavirus Spreads, Conspiracy Theories Are Going Viral Too|website=Foreign Policy|date= 14 April 2020|first=Elise |last=Thomas | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> as well as the [[state media]] of countries such as China, [[Iran]] and [[Turkmenistan]],<ref name=Lowy /><ref name=\"presstv\">{{cite journal|last=Frantzman|first=Seth| name-list-format = vanc |title=Iran's regime pushes antisemitic conspiracies about coronavirus|journal=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=March 8, 2020|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iran-News/Irans-regime-pushes-antisemitic-conspiracies-about-coronavirus-620212|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310213820/https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iran-News/Irans-regime-pushes-antisemitic-conspiracies-about-coronavirus-620212|archive-date=March 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/04/did-turkmenistan-really-ban-the-word-coronavirus/|title=Did Turkmenistan Really Ban the Word 'Coronavirus'?|last=Putz|first=Catherine| name-list-format = vanc |website=thediplomat.com|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> and they may be propagated by celebrities, politicians, or other prominent public figures.<ref name=20200408theguardian>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2020/apr/08/influencers-being-key-distributors-of-coronavirus-fake-news |title= Influencers among 'key distributors' of coronavirus misinformation |first=Jim |last=Waterson | name-list-format = vanc |date= April 8, 2020 |work=The Guardian }}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://rsf.org/en/news/coronavirus-limits-turkmenistan|title=Coronavirus off limits in Turkmenistan {{!}} Reporters without borders|date=March 31, 2020|publisher=Reports Without Borders|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><section begin=\"Intro\" /> Medical misinformation about ways to prevent, treat, and self-diagnose coronavirus disease has circulated on social media.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Robert H. |last1=Shmerling |title=Be careful where you get your news about coronavirus |url=https://www.health.harvard.edu/blog/be-careful-where-you-get-your-news-about-coronavirus-2020020118801 |website=Harvard Health Blog |access-date=March 25, 2020 |date=February 1, 2020}}</ref> Some false claims may be commercial scams offering at-home tests, supposed preventives, and \"miracle\" cures.<ref name=\"Beware\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/31/coronavirus-covid-19-fake-tests-cures|title=Covid-19: beware online tests and cures, experts say|last=Knight|first=Victoria| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 31, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"alex jones\">{{cite news|last1=Ferr\u00e9-Sadurn\u00ed|first1=Luis|last2=McKinley|first2=Jesse | name-list-format = vanc |title=Alex Jones Is Told to Stop Selling Sham Anti-Coronavirus Toothpaste|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=March 16, 2020|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314143913/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[World Health Organization]] has declared an \"infodemic\" of incorrect information about the virus, which poses risks to global health.<ref name=Lowy /><section end=Intro/>\n\nSome misinformation and disinformation claimed the virus was a [[bio-weapon]] with a patented [[vaccine]], a [[population control]] scheme, or the result of a [[Espionage|spy operation]].<ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\" /><ref name=RunningList /><ref name=\"vox_misinfo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |title=How tech companies are scrambling to deal with coronavirus hoaxes |last=Ghaffary |first=Shirin |last2=Heilweil |first2=Rebecca | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200208004124/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Some of these misinformation and conspiracy theories may have state involvement.<ref name=\"presstv\" /><ref name=\"20200312theguardian\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/12/conspiracy-theory-that-coronavirus-originated-in-us-gaining-traction-in-china |title='American coronavirus': China pushes propaganda casting doubt on virus origin |first=Lily |last=Kuo |date=March 13, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp3051939\">{{cite news |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/russia-central-asia/article/3051939/coronavirus-russia-pushing-fake-news-about-us-using |title=Coronavirus: Russia pushing fake news about US using outbreak to 'wage economic war' on China, officials say |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |via=[[South China Morning Post]] |date=February 23, 2020 |access-date=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223223639/https://www.scmp.com/news/world/russia-central-asia/article/3051939/coronavirus-russia-pushing-fake-news-about-us-using |archive-date=February 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some world leaders have also downplayed the threat of the virus and disseminated misinformation.<ref name=bolsonaro>{{cite web|first=Uri |last=Friedman | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2020/03/bolsonaro-coronavirus-denial-brazil-trump/608926/ |title=Bolsonaro Leads the Coronavirus-Denial Movement |work=The Atlantic |date=March 27, 2020 |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"stat\">{{cite web |last1=Thielking |first1=Megan |title=Experts warn Trump's misinformation about coronavirus is dangerous |url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/26/trump-mixed-messages-on-coronavirus/ |website=STAT |access-date=April 5, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"obrador=coronavirus\">{{cite news |title=Mexico: Mexicans Need Accurate COVID-19 Information |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2020/03/26/mexico-mexicans-need-accurate-covid-19-information |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><section end=Intro/>\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n== Types and origin ==\nAccording to a study published by the [[Reuters Institute for the Study of Journalism]], most misinformation related to COVID-19 involves \"various forms of reconfiguration, where existing and often true information is spun, twisted, recontextualised, or reworked.\" While less misinformation \"was completely fabricated.\" The study found no [[Deepfake|deep fakes]] in the studied sample. The study also found that \"top-down misinformation from politicians, celebrities, and other prominent public figures,\" while accounting for a minority of the samples, captured a majority of the social media engagement. According to their classification, the largest category of misinformation (39%) includes \"misleading or false claims about the actions or policies of public authorities, including government and international bodies like the WHO or the UN.\"<ref name=\"reuters-institute\">{{cite web|first1=J. Scott|last1=Brennen|first2=Felix|last2=Simon|first3=Philip N.|last3=Howard|first4=Rasmus Kleis|last4=Nielsen|url=https://reutersinstitute.politics.ox.ac.uk/types-sources-and-claims-covid-19-misinformation|title=Types, sources, and claims of COVID-19 misinformation |work=Reuters Institute|date=7 April 2020|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Combative efforts ==\n\nOn February 2, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) described a \"massive infodemic\", citing an over-abundance of reported information, accurate and false, about the virus that \"makes it hard for people to find trustworthy sources and reliable guidance when they need it.\" The WHO stated that the high demand for timely and trustworthy information has incentivised the creation of a direct WHO 24/7 myth-busting hotline where its communication and social media teams have been monitoring and responding to misinformation through its website and social media pages.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite report | vauthors=((World Health Organization)) | year=2020 | title=Novel Coronavirus (&lrm;2019-nCoV)&lrm;: situation report, 13 | publisher=[[World Health Organization]] | hdl=10665/330778 | hdl-access=free }}</ref><ref name=un1056672>{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1056672 |title=Coronavirus: UN health agency moves fast to tackle 'infodemic'; Guterres warns against stigmatization |date=February 4, 2020 |website=UN News |access-date=February 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205080207/https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1056672 |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{cite web |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/says-theres-no-effective-coronavirus-200035999.html |title=WHO Says There's No Effective Coronavirus Treatment Yet |publisher=Yahoo! Finance |access-date=February 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206043018/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/says-theres-no-effective-coronavirus-200035999.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The WHO specifically debunked several claims as false, including the claim that a person can tell if they have the virus or not simply by holding their breath; the claim that drinking large amounts of water will protect against the virus; and the claim that gargling salt water prevents infection.<ref name=20200317cnn>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-myths-debunking-holding-breath-10-seconds-trnd/index.html|title=One dangerous coronavirus 'self-check test' is circulating on social media. Here's why you should avoid it.|last=Elassar|first=Alaa| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 17, 2020|publisher=CNN|access-date=March 17, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317050148/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-myths-debunking-holding-breath-10-seconds-trnd/index.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFacebook, Twitter and Google said they were working with WHO to address \"misinformation\".<ref name=20200206nytimes>{{Cite news |last=Richtel |first=Matt | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/06/health/coronavirus-misinformation-social-media.html |title=W.H.O. Fights a Pandemic Besides Coronavirus: an 'Infodemic' |date=February 6, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 7, 2020 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206224226/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/06/health/coronavirus-misinformation-social-media.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a blogpost, Facebook stated they would remove content flagged by global health organizations and local authorities that violate its content policy on misinformation leading to \"physical harm\".<ref name=20200201reuters>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-facebook-idUSKBN1ZV388 |title=As coronavirus misinformation spreads on social media, Facebook removes posts |date=February 1, 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206071606/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-facebook-idUSKBN1ZV388 |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Facebook is also giving free advertising to WHO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inverse.com/innovation/facebook-is-giving-the-world-health-organization-free-ads-to-combat-the-coronavirus|title=Facebook announces how it plans to help fight the coronavirus|website=Inverse|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306204741/https://www.inverse.com/innovation/facebook-is-giving-the-world-health-organization-free-ads-to-combat-the-coronavirus|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of February, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] removed over one million products claimed to cure or protect against coronavirus, and removed tens of thousands of listings for health products whose prices were \"significantly higher than recent prices offered on or off Amazon\", although numerous items were \"still being sold at unusually high prices\" as of February 28.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-51675183|title = Amazon culls one million fake coronavirus products|work = BBC News|date = February 28, 2020|access-date = March 1, 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200301082532/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-51675183|archive-date = March 1, 2020|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nMillions of instances of COVID-19 misinformation have occurred across a number of online platforms.<ref>{{cite arXiv |title= The COVID-19 Social Media Infodemic |first1= Matteo |last1= Cinelli |first2= Walter |last2= Quattrociocchi |first3= Alessandro |last3= Galeazzi |first4=Carlo Michele |last4=Valensise |first5= Emanuele |last5= Brugnoli |first6= Ana Lucia |last6=Schmidt |first7= Paola |last7= Zola |first8=Fabiana |last8=Zollo |first9=Antonio |last9=Scala | name-list-format = vanc |date= March 10, 2020 |class= cs.SI |eprint= 2003.05004 }}</ref> Other [[fake news]] researchers noted certain rumors started in China; many of them later spread to Korea and the United States, prompting several universities in Korea to start the multilingual Facts Before Rumors campaign to separate common claims seen online.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000739/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18241 |title= 'Fact before rumors' campaign just began by the IBS Data Science Group |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 26, 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |access-date= March 31, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000971/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18234&pageIndex=1&searchCnd=&searchWrd= |title= \ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4\uc640 \uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9 |first=Cha|last=Meeyoung| name-list-format = vanc |author-link=Cha Meeyoung |date= March 24, 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://dongascience.donga.com/news.php?idx=35457 |title=\"\ub3d9\ub0a8\uc544\u00b7\ub0a8\ubbf8 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \uac00\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4 \ub9c9\uace0 '\uc9c4\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4' \uc804\ud558\uc790\" \uad6d\ub0b4 \uacfc\ud559\uc790 \ud314 \uac77\uc5b4 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 25, 2020 |website= Donga Science |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.hankyung.com/opinion/article/2020032509531 |title= [\ucc28\ubbf8\uc601\uc758 \ub370\uc774\ud130\ub85c \ubcf8 \uc138\uc0c1] '\uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9'\uc758 \uc2dc\ub300 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 25, 2020 |website= \ud55c\uad6d\uacbd\uc81c |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref>\n\nThe media has praised Wikipedia's coverage of COVID-19 and its combating the inclusion of misinformation through efforts led by the [[meta:Wiki Project Med Foundation|Wiki Project Med Foundation]] and the English-language Wikipedia's [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Medicine|WikiProject Medicine]], among other groups.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.wired.com/story/how-wikipedia-prevents-spread-coronavirus-misinformation/ | title = How Wikipedia Prevents the Spread of Coronavirus Misinformation | first=  Noam | last = Cohem | date = March 15, 2020 | access-date = April 11, 2020 | work = [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://slate.com/technology/2020/03/coronavirus-wikipedia-policies.html | title = The Coronavirus Is Stress-Testing Wikipedia's Policies | first= Stephan | last= Harrison | name-list-format = vanc | date = March 19, 2020 | access-date = April 11, 2020 | work = [[Salon (magazine)|Salon]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/.premium.MAGAZINE-why-wikipedia-is-immune-to-coronavirus-1.8751147 | title = Why Wikipedia Is Immune to Coronavirus | first = Omer | last = Benjakob | date = April 8, 2020 | access-date = April 11, 2020 | work = [[Haaretz]] }}</ref>\n\nMany local newspapers have been severely affected by losses in advertising revenues from coronavirus; journalists have been laid off, and some have closed altogether.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hsu |first1=Tiffany |last2=Tracy |first2=Marc | name-list-format = vanc |title=Local News Outlets Dealt a Crippling Blow by This Biggest of Stories |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/business/media/coronavirus-local-news.html |work=The New York Times |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMany newspapers with [[paywall]]s lowered them for some or all of their coronavirus coverage.<ref name=\"Paywalls\">{{cite news |last1=Jerde |date=March 12, 2020 |first1=Sara |title=Major Publishers Take Down Paywalls for Coronavirus Coverage |url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/major-publishers-take-down-paywalls-for-coronavirus-coverage/ |access-date=March 25, 2020 |work=Adweek}}</ref><ref name=\"newspaywalls\">{{cite web |last1=Kottke |first1=Jason |title=Media Paywalls Dropped for COVID-19 Crisis Coverage |url=https://kottke.org/20/03/media-paywalls-dropped-for-covid-19-crisis-coverage |website=kottke.org |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> Many scientific publishers made scientific papers related to the outbreak [[open access]].<ref name=\"AutoDW-255\">{{cite press release |url=https://wellcome.ac.uk/press-release/sharing-research-data-and-findings-relevant-novel-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak |title=Sharing research data and findings relevant to the novel coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak |work=wellcome.ac.uk |date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 13, 2020}}</ref> Some scientists chose to share their results quickly on [[preprint]] servers such as [[bioRxiv]].<ref name=\"AutoDW-256\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-research-preprint-servers/ |title=Coronavirus Research Is Moving at Top Speed \u2013 With a Catch |work=Wired |last1=Rogers |first1=Adam |date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 13, 2020 |issn=1059-1028}}</ref>\n\n== Conspiracy theories ==\n\n[[Conspiracy theory|Conspiracy theories]] have appeared in both social media and mainstream news outlets, and are heavily influenced by geopolitics.<ref name=al-watsm /> ''[[Al Jazeera English|Al Jazeera]]'' reported that mainstream outlets which had spread conspiracy theories included domestic and overseas Russian state media ([[Channel One Russia]] and [[RT (TV network)|RT]] ), the British tabloid the ''[[Daily Mail]]'', and conservative media in the United States.<ref name=al-watsm>{{cite web|last=Sharma|first=Gouri | name-list-format = vanc | date=March 5, 2020 | url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/conspiracy-theories-coronavirus-200303170729373.html|title=Why are there so many conspiracy theories around the coronavirus?|publisher=Al Jazeera|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Bioengineered virus ===\nIt has been repeatedly claimed that the virus was deliberately created by humans.\n\n''[[Nature Medicine]]'' published an article arguing against the conspiracy theory that the virus was created artificially. The high-affinity binding of the virus' [[peplomer]]s to human [[angiotensin-converting enzyme 2]] (ACE2) was shown to be \"most likely the result of [[natural selection]] on a human or human-like ACE2 that permits another optimal binding solution to arise\".<ref name=\"NM\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Andersen KG, Rambaut A, Lipkin WI, Holmes EC, Garry RF | title = The proximal origin of SARS-CoV-2 | journal = Nature Medicine | volume = 26 | issue = 4 | pages = 450\u2013452 | date = April 2020 | pmid = 32284615 | doi = 10.1038/s41591-020-0820-9 | url = https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-020-0820-9 | doi-access = free }}</ref> In case of [[genetic manipulation]], one of the several [[Reverse genetics|reverse-genetic]] systems for [[betacoronavirus]]es would probably have been used, while the genetic data irrefutably showed that the virus is not derived from a previously used virus template.<ref name=\"NM\" /> The overall molecular structure of the virus was found to be distinct from the known coronaviruses and most closely resembles that of viruses of [[bat]]s and [[pangolins]] that were little studied and never known to harm humans.<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.livescience.com/coronavirus-not-human-made-in-lab.html |title=The coronavirus did not escape from a lab. Here's how we know|first=Jeanna|last=Bryner | name-list-format = vanc |publisher=[[Live Science]]| access-date =March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' quoted virus expert and global co-lead coronavirus investigator Trevor Bedford: \"There is no evidence whatsoever of genetic engineering that we can find\", and \"The evidence we have is that the mutations [in the virus] are completely consistent with natural evolution\".<ref name=\"FT5\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.ft.com/content/a6392ee6-4ec6-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5 | title=Coronavirus was not genetically engineered in a Wuhan lab, says expert | first=Clive | last=Cookson| name-list-format = vanc  | date=February 14, 2020 | access-date=February 14, 2020 | newspaper=[[Financial Times]] | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214112755/https://www.ft.com/content/a6392ee6-4ec6-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5 | archive-date=February 14, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> Bedford further explained, \"The most likely scenario, based on genetic analysis, was that the virus was transmitted by a bat to another mammal between 20\u201370 years ago. This intermediary animal\u2014not yet identified\u2014passed it on to its first human host in the city of Wuhan in late November or early December 2019\".<ref name=\"FT5\" />\n\nOn 19 February 2020, ''[[The Lancet]]'' published a letter of a group of scientists condemning \"conspiracy theories suggesting that COVID-19 does not have a natural origin.\"<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Charles|last1=Calisher |first2=Dennis|last2=Carroll |first3=Rita|last3=Colwell |first4=Ronald B|last4=Corley |first5=Peter|last5=Daszak |first6=Christian|last6=Drosten |first7=Luis|last7=Enjuanes |first8=Jeremy|last8=Farrar |first9=Hume|last9=Field |first10=Josie|last10=Golding |first11=Alexander|last11=Gorbalenya |first12=Bart|last12=Haagmans |first13=James M|last13=Hughes |first14=William B|last14=Karesh |first15=Gerald T|last15=Keusch |first16=Sai Kit|last16=Lam |first17=Juan|last17=Lubroth |first18=John S|last18=Mackenzie |first19=Larry|last19=Madoff |first20=Jonna|last20=Mazet |first21=Peter|last21=Palese |first22=Stanley|last22=Perlman |first23=Leo|last23=Poon |first24=Bernard|last24=Roizman |first25=Linda|last25=Saif |first26=Kanta|last26=Subbarao |first27=Mike|last27=Turner|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(20)30418-9/fulltext|title=Statement in support of the scientists, public health professionals, and medical professionals of China combatting COVID-19|journal=The Lancet|volume=395|issue=10226|date=19 February 2020|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30418-9}}</ref>\n\n=== Chinese biological weapon ===\n\n==== United States ====\n{{further|Cyberwarfare in the United States|Propaganda in the United States}}\nIn January 2020, [[BBC News]] published an article about coronavirus misinformation, citing two January 24 articles from ''[[The Washington Times]]'' that said the virus was part of a Chinese biological weapons program, based at the [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] (WIV).<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' later published an article debunking the conspiracy theory, citing US experts who explained why the WIV was unsuitable for bioweapon research, that most countries had abandoned bioweapons as fruitless, and that there was no evidence that the virus was genetically engineered.<ref name=\"20200129washingtonpost\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/01/29/experts-debunk-fringe-theory-linking-chinas-coronavirus-weapons-research/ |title=Experts debunk fringe theory linking China's coronavirus to weapons research |date=January 29, 2020 |website=The Washington Post |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200131185716/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/01/29/experts-debunk-fringe-theory-linking-chinas-coronavirus-weapons-research/ |archive-date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn January 29, financial news website and blog [[ZeroHedge]] suggested without evidence that a scientist at the WIV created the COVID-19 strain responsible for the coronavirus outbreak. Zerohedge listed the full contact details of the scientist supposedly responsible, a practice known as [[doxing]], by including the scientist's name, photo, and phone number, suggesting to readers that they \"pay [the Chinese scientist] a visit\" if they wanted to know \"what really caused the coronavirus pandemic.\"<ref name=\"the verge\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/1/31/21117663/twitter-zero-hedge-suspended-platform-manipulation-policy-doxxing-coronavirus |title=Markets blogger Zero Hedge suspended from Twitter after doxxing a Chinese scientist |last=Peters |first=Jay | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |website=The Verge |access-date=February 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206214044/https://www.theverge.com/2020/1/31/21117663/twitter-zero-hedge-suspended-platform-manipulation-policy-doxxing-coronavirus |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Twitter later permanently suspended the blog's account for violating its platform-manipulation policy.<ref name=20200131bloomberg>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-01/zero-hedge-permanently-suspended-from-twitter-for-harassment |title=Zero Hedge Permanently Suspended From Twitter for 'Harassment' |last=Datoo |first=Siraj | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |website=Bloomberg |url-status=live |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202214859/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-01/zero-hedge-permanently-suspended-from-twitter-for-harassment |archive-date=February 2, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, ''[[Buzzfeed News]]'' reported on an internet meme of a link between the logo of the WIV and \"[[Umbrella Corporation]]\", the agency that created the virus responsible for a [[zombie apocalypse]] in the ''[[Resident Evil]]'' franchise. Posts online noted that \"{{sic|Racoon}}\" (the main city in ''Resident Evil'') was an anagram of \"Corona\".<ref name=\"SNOPES\" /> [[Snopes]] noted that the logo was not from the WIV, but a company named Shanghai Ruilan Bao Hu San Biotech Ltd (located some {{convert|500|mi}} away in Shanghai), and that the correct name of the city in Resident Evil was \"Raccoon City\".<ref name=\"SNOPES\">{{cite web | url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/resident-evil-umbrella-coronavirus/ | title=Is the 'Umbrella Corporation' Logo Oddly Similar to a Wuhan Biotech Lab's? | first=Dan | last=Evon | name-list-format = vanc | date=January 29, 2020 | access-date=February 10, 2020 | website=[[Snopes]] }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, US Senator [[Tom Cotton]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Arkansas|AR]]) and [[Francis Boyle]], a law professor, suggested that the virus may have been a Chinese bioweapon;<ref name=\"cotton\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/482228-chinese-ambassador-on-cotton-coronavirus-comments-its-very-harmful | title=Chinese ambassador on Cotton coronavirus comments: 'It's very harmful to stir up' unsubstantiated rumors | newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] | first=Zack | last=Budryk | name-list-format = vanc | access-date=February 11, 2020 | date=February 9, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210153906/https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/482228-chinese-ambassador-on-cotton-coronavirus-comments-its-very-harmful | archive-date=February 10, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> multiple medical experts have indicated there is no evidence for this.<ref name=\"fact checking\">{{cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/18/politics/coronavirus-cotton-fact-check/index.html |title=Fact-checking Tom Cotton's claims about the coronavirus |first=Tara |last=Subramaniam | name-list-format = vanc |date=February 18, 2020 |publisher=CNN |access-date=February 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219234740/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/18/politics/coronavirus-cotton-fact-check/index.html |archive-date=February 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Conservative political commentator [[Rush Limbaugh]] said on ''[[The Rush Limbaugh Show]]''\u2014 the most popular radio show in the US\u2014that the virus was probably \"a [[ChiCom]] laboratory experiment\" and that the Chinese government was using the virus and the media hysteria surrounding it to bring down Donald Trump.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/rush-limbaugh/rush-limbaugh-coronavirus-effort-get-trump|title=Rush Limbaugh: \"The coronavirus is an effort to get Trump\"|website=Media Matters for America}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/rush-limbaugh-claims-chinese-are-trying-to-weaponize-coronavirus-to-bring-down-trump|title= Rush Limbaugh claims Chinese are 'trying to weaponize' coronavirus to 'bring down' Trump|date= February 25, 2020|access-date= February 25, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162810/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/rush-limbaugh-claims-chinese-are-trying-to-weaponize-coronavirus-to-bring-down-trump|archive-date= February 29, 2020|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 6, the White House asked scientists and medical researchers to rapidly investigate the origins of the virus to address both the current spread and \"to inform future outbreak preparation and better understand animal/human and environmental transmission aspects of coronaviruses.\"<ref name=go68807304>{{cite web| date=February 6, 2020| title=White House asks scientists to investigate origins of coronavirus| url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-asks-scientists-investigate-origins-coronavirus/story?id=68807304| access-date=February 28, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208032258/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-asks-scientists-investigate-origins-coronavirus/story?id=68807304| archive-date=February 8, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> American magazine ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' said that Xi Jinping's \"political agenda may turn out to be a root cause of the epidemic\" and that his [[Belt and Road Initiative]] has \"made it possible for a local disease to become a global menace\".<ref name=al-watsm />\n\nThe ''Inverse'' reported that \"Christopher Bouzy, the founder of Bot Sentinel, conducted a Twitter analysis for Inverse and found [online] bots and [[Internet troll|trollbots]] are making an array of false claims. These bots are claiming China intentionally created the virus, that it's a biological weapon, that Democrats are overstating the threat to hurt Donald Trump and more. While we can't confirm the origin of these bots, they are decidedly pro-Trump.\"<ref name=inverse>{{cite news |title=Bots are waging a coronavirus disinformation campaign on social media |url=https://www.inverse.com/mind-body/coronavirus-usa-2020 |work=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]] |date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nConservative commentator [[Josh Bernstein (talk show host)|Josh Bernstein]] claimed that the Democratic Party and the \"medical deep state\" were collaborating with the Chinese government to create and release the coronavirus to bring down Donald Trump. Bernstein went on to suggest that those responsible should be locked in a room with infected coronavirus patients as punishment.<ref name=\"bernstein\">{{cite web|url= https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/josh-bernstein-the-coronavirus-outbreak-is-a-democratic-and-chinese-conspiracy-against-trump/|title= Josh Bernstein: The Coronavirus Outbreak Is a Democratic and Chinese Conspiracy Against Trump|access-date= March 12, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312173241/https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/josh-bernstein-the-coronavirus-outbreak-is-a-democratic-and-chinese-conspiracy-against-trump/|archive-date= March 12, 2020|url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=usatoday5065736002>{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Matthew |title=Fact check: Coronavirus did not spread in the US because of an anti-Trump conspiracy |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2020/03/17/fact-check-coronavirus-spread-not-anti-trump-conspiracy/5065736002/ |access-date=March 31, 2020 |work=USA Today |issue=2 |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Jerry Falwell Jr.]], the president of [[Liberty University]], promoted a conspiracy theory on [[Fox News]] that North Korea and China conspired together to create the coronavirus.<ref name=fox-falwell>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/coronavirus-covid-19/fox-guest-jerry-falwell-jr-speculates-north-korea-got-together-china-create|title=Fox guest Jerry Falwell Jr. speculates that North Korea \"got together with China\" to create coronavirus|website=Media Matters for America|access-date=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317093144/https://www.mediamatters.org/coronavirus-covid-19/fox-guest-jerry-falwell-jr-speculates-north-korea-got-together-china-create|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He also said that people were overreacting to the coronavirus outbreak and that Democrats were trying to use the situation to harm President Trump.<ref>{{cite news |last= Heim |first= Joe | name-list-format = vanc |title= Liberty University President Jerry Falwell Jr. says in-person classes to continue |date= March 13, 2020 |access-date= March 15, 2020 |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]] |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/liberty-university-president-jerry-falwell-jr-says-in-person-classes-to-continue/2020/03/13/70b23a58-654e-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html |quote= 'It\u2019s just strange to me how so many are overreacting,' Falwell said, comparing media coverage of the novel coronavirus to coverage of earlier epidemics. 'It makes you wonder if there\u2019s a political reason for that. Impeachment didn\u2019t work, and the Mueller report didn\u2019t work, and Article 25 didn\u2019t work. And so maybe now this is their next attempt to get Trump.' |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200317141436/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/liberty-university-president-jerry-falwell-jr-says-in-person-classes-to-continue/2020/03/13/70b23a58-654e-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html |archive-date= March 17, 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n==== United Kingdom ====\n\nConservative MP [[Tobias Ellwood]], chair of the [[Defence Select Committee]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|UK House of Commons]], publicly questioned the role of the Chinese Army's Wuhan Institute for Biological Products and called for the \"greater transparency over the origins of the coronavirus\".<ref name=20200229telegraph>{{Cite news|last=Ellwood|first=Tobias | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/02/29/transparency-will-convince-world-china-friend/|title=Transparency will convince the world China is a friend|date=February 29, 2020|work=The Telegraph|access-date=March 3, 2020|issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302000503/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/02/29/transparency-will-convince-world-china-friend/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It has also been reported that a member of [[Cabinet Office Briefing Rooms|COBRA]], a government committee tasked with dealing with crisis, has stated while government intelligence does not dispute that the virus has a zoonotic origin, it also does not discount the idea of a leak from a Wuhan laboratory, saying that \"Perhaps it is no coincidence that there is that laboratory in Wuhan.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://asiatimes.com/2020/04/wuhan-lab-virus-leak-no-longer-discounted-cobra/ |title=Wuhan lab virus leak 'no longer discounted': Cobra |first= Dave |last= Makichuk | name-list-format = vanc |work=Asia Times|date=April 6, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==== India ====\nAmidst a rise in [[Sinophobia]], there have been conspiracy theories reported on India's social networks that the virus is a state-supported \"a bioweapon that went rogue\" and also fake videos alleging that Chinese authorities are killing citizens to prevent its spread.<ref name=scmp3075445>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075445/coronavirus-anti-chinese-conspiracy-theories-go-viral|title=Coronavirus: anti-Chinese conspiracy theories go viral in India|date=March 16, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Ukraine ====\nAccording to the ''[[Kyiv Post]]'', two common conspiracy theories online in Ukraine are that American author [[Dean Koontz]] predicted the pandemic in his 1981 novel ''[[The Eyes of Darkness]]'', and that the coronavirus was a bioweapon leaked from a secret lab in Wuhan.<ref name=20200318kyivpost>{{cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/coronavirus-misinformation-goes-viral-in-ukraine.html|title=Coronavirus misinformation goes viral in Ukraine|date=March 18, 2020|website=Kyiv Post|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== US biological weapon ===\n==== Russia ====\n\n{{further|Cyberwarfare by Russia|Propaganda in the Russian Federation|Russia\u2013European Union relations#Allegations of Russian intimidation and destabilisation of EU states}}\nOn February 22, US officials alleged that Russia is behind an ongoing disinformation campaign, using thousands of social media accounts on Twitter, Facebook and [[Instagram]] to deliberately promote unfounded conspiracy theories, claiming that the virus is a biological weapon manufactured by the [[CIA]] and the US is waging economic war on China using the virus.<ref name=\"guardian-rus-disinfo\">{{Cite news |last=Glenza |first=Jessica | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-russia-disinformation-campaign-us-officials |title=Coronavirus: US says Russia behind disinformation campaign |date=February 22, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=February 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225051450/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-russia-disinformation-campaign-us-officials |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp3051939\" /><ref name=yahoo171730161>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/us-accuses-russia-huge-coronavirus-171730161.html |title=US accuses Russia of huge coronavirus disinformation campaign |work=[[The Independent]] |first=Kate |last=Ng | name-list-format = vanc |date=February 23, 2020 |access-date=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224090721/https://news.yahoo.com/us-accuses-russia-huge-coronavirus-171730161.html |archive-date=February 24, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The acting assistant secretary of state for Europe and [[Eurasia]], [[Philip T. Reeker|Philip Reeker]], said that \"Russia's intent is to sow discord and undermine US institutions and alliances from within\" and \"by spreading disinformation about coronavirus, Russian malign actors are once again choosing to threaten public safety by distracting from the global health response.\"<ref name=\"guardian-rus-disinfo\" /> Russia denies the allegation, saying \"this is a deliberately false story\".<ref name=bbc51599009>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51599009 |title=Coronavirus: Russia denies spreading US conspiracy on social media |date=February 23, 2020 |publisher=BBC |access-date=February 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225053306/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51599009 |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to US-based ''[[The National Interest]]'' magazine, although official Russian channels had been muted on pushing the US biowarfare conspiracy theory, other Russian media elements do not share the Kremlin's restraint.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\">{{Cite news |url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/some-russia-think-coronavirus-us-biological-weapon-121731 |title=Some in Russia Think the Coronavirus Is a U.S. Biological Weapon |last=Episkopos |first=Mark | name-list-format = vanc |date=February 7, 2020 |work=[[The National Interest]] |access-date=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223172332/https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/some-russia-think-coronavirus-us-biological-weapon-121731 |archive-date=February 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Zvezda'', a news outlet funded by the Russian Defense Ministry, published an article titled \"Coronavirus: American biological warfare against Russia and China\", claiming that the virus is intended to damage the Chinese economy, weakening its hand in the next round of trade negotiations.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\" /> Ultra-nationalist politician and leader of the [[Liberal Democratic Party of Russia]], [[Vladimir Zhirinovsky]], claimed on a Moscow radio station that the virus was an experiment by [[the Pentagon]] and pharmaceutical companies. Politician [[Igor Nikulin (politician)|Igor Nikulin]] made rounds on Russian television and news media, arguing that Wuhan was chosen for the attack because the presence of a BSL-4 virus lab provided a cover story for the Pentagon and CIA about a Chinese bio-experiment leak.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\" /> An EU-document claims 80 attempts by Russian media to spread disinformation related to the epidemic.<ref name=reuters2020-03-18>{{cite news |title=Russia deploying coronavirus disinformation to sow panic in West, EU document says |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21518F |agency=Reuters  |date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319222849/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21518F |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[East StratCom Task Force]], the [[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]] news agency was active publishing stories claiming that the virus was invented in Latvia, that it was used by [[Communist Party of China]] to curb [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests|protests in Hong Kong]], that it was introduced intentionally to reduce the number of elder people in Italy, that it was targeted against the [[Yellow vests movement|Yellow Vests]] movement, and making many other claims. Sputnik branches in countries including Armenia, Belarus, Spain, and in the middle east came up with customized versions of these stories.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://euvsdisinfo.eu/sputnik-coronavirus-could-be-designed-to-kill-elderly-italians/|title=Sputnik: Coronavirus Could be Designed to Kill Elderly Italians|date=March 25, 2020|website=EU vs DISINFORMATION|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Iran ====\n\n{{further|Propaganda in Iran}}\nAccording to ''[[Radio Farda]]'', Iranian cleric Seyyed Mohammad Saeedi accused US President [[Donald Trump]] of targeting [[Qom]] with coronavirus \"to damage its culture and honor\". Saeedi claimed that Trump is fulfilling his promise to hit Iranian cultural sites, if Iranians took revenge for the [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|US airstrike]] that killed of [[Quds Force]] Commander [[Qasem Soleimani]].<ref name=radiofarda30449087>{{Cite news|url=https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iran-cleric-blames-trump-for-coronavirus-outbreak-in-religious-city/30449087.html|title=Iran Cleric Blames Trump For Coronavirus Outbreak in Religious City|date=February 22, 2020|work=[[Radio Farda]]|access-date=February 26, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223170405/https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iran-cleric-blames-trump-for-coronavirus-outbreak-in-religious-city/30449087.html|archive-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIranian TV personality Ali Akbar Raefipour claimed that the coronavirus was part of a \"hybrid warfare\" programme waged by the United States on Iran and China.<ref name=bbc51677530>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Misinformation and false medical advice spreads in Iran |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51677530 |work=BBC News |date=February 29, 2020 |access-date=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301202336/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51677530 |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nBrigadier General Gholam Reza Jalali, head of Iranian Civil Defense Organization, claimed that the coronavirus is likely a biological attack on China and Iran with economic goals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.farsnews.ir/newstext.aspx?nn=13981213000410|title=Civil Defense Chief: Coronavirus Likely Biological Attack against China, Iran|date=March 3, 2020|agency=[[Fars News Agency]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304231742/http://en.farsnews.ir/newstext.aspx?nn=13981213000410|archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=toi-civildefense>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/virus-is-biological-attack-on-china-and-iran-iranian-civil-defense-chief-claims/|title=Virus is biological attack on China and Iran, Iranian civil defense chief claims|date=March 4, 2020|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305173532/https://www.timesofisrael.com/virus-is-biological-attack-on-china-and-iran-iranian-civil-defense-chief-claims/|archive-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Hossein Salami]], the head of [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]] (IRGC), claimed that the coronavirus outbreak in Iran may be due to a US \"biological attack\".<ref name=20200305alarabiya>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/05/Coronavirus-may-be-US-biological-attack-IRGC-head.html|title=Coronavirus may be US 'biological attack': IRGC head Hossein Salami|date=March 5, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306204737/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/05/Coronavirus-may-be-US-biological-attack-IRGC-head.html|archive-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Several Iranian politicians, including [[Hossein Amir-Abdollahian]], [[Rasoul Falahati]], [[Alireza Panahian]], [[Abolfazl Hasanbeigi]] and [[Gholamali Jafarzadeh Imanabadi]], also made similar remarks.<ref name=20200316iranwire>{{Cite news|url=https://iranwire.com/en/features/6815|title=The Lie that Triggered Khamenei's 'Biological Attack' Conspiracy Theory|date=March 16, 2020|work=IranWire}}</ref>\nHowever, Iran's deputy health minister [[Reza Malekzadeh]] rejected the biological warfare theory.<ref name=20200314alarabiyaA>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/14/Coronavirus-Iran-s-deputy-health-minister-rejects-biological-warfare-theory.html|title=Coronavirus: Iran's deputy health minister rejects biological warfare theory|date=March 14, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317205520/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/14/Coronavirus-Iran-s-deputy-health-minister-rejects-biological-warfare-theory.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFormer Iranian president [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] sent a letter to the [[United Nations]] on March 9, claiming that \"it is clear to the world that the mutated coronavirus was produced in lab\" and that COVID-19 is \"a new weapon for establishing and/or maintaining political and economic upper hand in the global arena.\"<ref name=20200309washingtonexaminer>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/biologic-war-former-iranian-president-says-coronavirus-was-produced-in-laboratories|title='Biologic war': Former Iranian president says coronavirus was 'produced in laboratories'|date=March 9, 2020|agency=[[Washington Examiner]]|access-date=March 11, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311071331/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/biologic-war-former-iranian-president-says-coronavirus-was-produced-in-laboratories|archive-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAyatollah [[Hashem Bathaie Golpayegani]] claimed that \"America is the source of coronavirus, because America went head to head with China and realised it cannot keep up with it economically or militarily.\"<ref name=20200319alarabiya>{{Cite news |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/features/2020/03/19/Video-Senior-Iranian-cleric-who-died-from-coronavirus-blamed-US-for-outbreak |title=Video: Senior Iranian cleric who died from coronavirus blamed US for outbreak |date=March 19, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== China ====\n\n{{further|Cyberwarfare by China|Propaganda in China|Chinese information operations and information warfare}}\nAccording to London-based ''[[The Economist]]'', plenty of conspiracy theories exist on China's internet about COVID-19 being the CIA's creation to keep China down.<ref name=20200208economist>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/08/chinas-rulers-see-the-coronavirus-as-a-chance-to-tighten-their-grip |title=China's rulers see the coronavirus as a chance to tighten their grip |date=February 8, 2020 |work=[[The Economist]] |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200229034330/https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/08/chinas-rulers-see-the-coronavirus-as-a-chance-to-tighten-their-grip |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[NBC News]] however has noted that there have also been debunking efforts of US-related conspiracy theories posted online, with a WeChat search of \"Coronavirus is from the U.S.\" reported to mostly yield articles explaining why such claims are unreasonable.<ref name=nbcnews1151291>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/coronavirus-rumors-misinformation-swirl-unchecked-china-n1151291|title=Coronavirus rumors \u2013 and misinformation \u2013 swirl unchecked in China|publisher=NBC News|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> According to an investigation by [[ProPublica]], such conspiracy theories and disinformation have been propagated under the direction of [[China News Service]], the country's second largest government-owned media outlet controlled by the [[United Front Work Department]].<ref name=20200326propublica>{{Cite news|last=Kao|first=Jeff| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.propublica.org/article/how-china-built-a-twitter-propaganda-machine-then-let-it-loose-on-coronavirus|title=How China Built a Twitter Propaganda Machine Then Let It Loose on Coronavirus|date=March 26, 2020|work=[[ProPublica]]|access-date=March 31, 2020|last2=Li|first2=Mia Shuang}}</ref> ''[[Global Times]]'' and [[Xinhua News Agency]] have similarly been implicated in propagating disinformation related to COVID-19's origins.<ref name=20200405telegraph>{{Cite news|last=Dodds|first=Laurence| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2020/04/05/china-floods-facebook-instagram-undeclared-coronavirus-propaganda/|title=China floods Facebook with undeclared coronavirus propaganda ads blaming Trump|date=April 5, 2020|work=The Telegraph|access-date=April 5, 2020|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nMultiple conspiracy articles in Chinese from the SARS era resurfaced during the outbreak with altered details, claiming that SARS is biological warfare conducted by the US against China. Some of these articles said that [[BGI Group]] from China sold genetic information of the Chinese people to the US, with the US then being able to deploy the virus specifically targeting the [[genome]] of Chinese individuals.<ref name=setn677313>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u570b\u5bb6\u9577\u6307\u7a31\u300c\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u662f\u7f8e\u570b\u6295\u653e\u75c5\u6bd2\u300d\u3000\u7db2\u53cb\u50bb\u7206\u773c|url=https://www.setn.com/News.aspx?NewsID=677313|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219211548/https://www.setn.com/News.aspx?NewsID=677313|archive-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 26, Chinese military news site Xilu published an article detailing how the virus was artificially combined by the US to \"precisely target Chinese people\".<ref name=xilu1000010001>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u75c5\u6bd24\u4e2a\u5173\u952e\u86cb\u767d\u88ab\u66ff\u6362\uff0c\u53ef\u7cbe\u51c6\u653b\u51fb\u534e\u4eba|url=http://www.xilu.com/20200126/1000010001119697.html|access-date=February 7, 2020|work=\u897f\u9646\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211022551/http://www.xilu.com/20200126/1000010001119697.html|archive-date=February 11, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}} The article was removed after early February.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nSome articles on popular sites in China have also cast suspicion on US military athletes participating in the Wuhan [[2019 Military World Games]], which lasted until the end of October 2019, and have suggested that they deployed the virus. They claim the inattentive attitude and disproportionately below-average results of American athletes in the games indicate they might have been there for other purposes and they might actually be bio-warfare operatives. Such posts stated that their place of residence during their stay in Wuhan was also close to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]], where the first known cluster of cases occurred.<ref name=szhgh221836>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e3a\u4ec0\u4e48\u6b66\u6c49\u8fd9\u573a\u761f\u75ab\uff0c\u5fc5\u987b\u5f97\u9760\u89e3\u653e\u519b\uff1f|url=http://www.szhgh.com/Article/opinion/zatan/2020-01-30/221836.html|access-date=February 21, 2020|publisher=\u7ea2\u6b4c\u4f1a\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221185358/http://www.szhgh.com/Article/opinion/zatan/2020-01-30/221836.html|archive-date=February 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, this conspiracy theory was endorsed by [[Zhao Lijian]], a spokesperson from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China.<ref name=\"Taiwan News March 2020\">{{cite web |last1=Cheng |first1=Ching-Tse |title=China's foreign ministry accuses US military of bringing virus to Wuhan |url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3896257 |work=Taiwan News |access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref name=thehill487308>{{cite web |last1=Budryk |first1=Zack |title=China, pushing conspiracy theory, accuses US Army of bringing coronavirus to Wuhan |url=https://thehill.com/policy/international/487308-china-pushing-conspiracy-theory-us-army-bringing-coronavirus-wuhan |newspaper=The Hill |access-date=March 13, 2020|date=March 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tang |first1=Didi |title=China accuses US of bringing coronavirus to Wuhan |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/china-accuses-us-of-bringing-coronavirus-to-wuhan-c9rrfbrs7 |work=The Times |access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 13, the US government summoned Chinese Ambassador [[Cui Tiankai]] to Washington DC over the coronavirus conspiracy theory.<ref name=20200314alarabiyaB>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/world/2020/03/14/US-summons-China-s-ambassador-to-Washington-over-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory.html|title=US summons China's ambassador to Washington over coronavirus conspiracy theory|date=March 14, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316012205/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/world/2020/03/14/US-summons-China-s-ambassador-to-Washington-over-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory.html|archive-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Arab world ====\n\nAccording to Washington DC-based nonprofit [[Middle East Media Research Institute]], numerous writers in the Arabic press have promoted the conspiracy theory that COVID-19, as well as SARS and the swine flu virus, were deliberately created and spread by the US to sell vaccines against these diseases, and it is \"part of an economic and psychological war waged by the US against China with the aim of weakening it and presenting it as a backward country and a source of diseases\".<ref name=\"MEMRI-arab-disinfo\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.memri.org/reports/arab-writers-coronavirus-part-biological-warfare-waged-us-against-china |title=Arab Writers: The Coronavirus Is Part Of Biological Warfare Waged By The U.S. Against China |date=February 6, 2020 |publisher=[[Middle East Media Research Institute]] |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209043001/https://www.memri.org/reports/arab-writers-coronavirus-part-biological-warfare-waged-us-against-china |archive-date=February 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Iraqi political analyst Sabah Al-Akili on [[Aletejah TV|Al-Etejah TV]], Saudi daily [[Al Watan (Saudi Arabia)|Al-Watan]] writer Sa'ud Al-Shehry, Syrian daily [[Al-Thawra (newspaper)|Al-Thawra]] columnist Hussein Saqer, and Egyptian journalist Ahmad Rif'at on Egyptian news website Vetogate, were some examples given by MEMRI as propagators of the US biowarfare conspiracy theory in the Arabic world.<ref name=\"MEMRI-arab-disinfo\" />\n\n==== Philippine ====\n\nA Filipino Senator, [[Tito Sotto]], played a bioweapon conspiracy video in a February 2020 Senate hearing, suggesting that the coronavirus is biowarfare waged against China.<ref name=\"nypost-rubio\">{{Cite news|last=Rubio|first=Marco| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/03/russia-china-and-iran-are-waging-disinformation-war-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Marco Rubio: Russia, China and Iran are waging disinformation war over coronavirus|date=March 3, 2020|work=[[New York Post]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304233343/https://nypost.com/2020/03/03/russia-china-and-iran-are-waging-disinformation-war-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=philstar1990332>{{Cite news|last=San Juan|first=Ratziel| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/04/1990332/bioweapon-conspiracy-video-creeps-senate-coronavirus-hearing|title=Bioweapon conspiracy video creeps into Senate coronavirus hearing|date=February 4, 2020|work=[[The Philippine Star]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310163521/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/04/1990332/bioweapon-conspiracy-video-creeps-senate-coronavirus-hearing|archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Venezuela ====\n\n[[2017 Constituent National Assembly|Constituent Assembly]] member Elvis M\u00e9ndez declared that the coronavirus was a \"bacteriological sickness created in '89, in '90 and historically\" and that it was a sickness \"inoculated by the ''[[gringo]]s''\". M\u00e9ndez theorized that the virus was a weapon against Latin America and China and that its purpose was \"to demoralize the person, to weaken to install their system\".<ref name=20200307somostuvoz>{{cite web|url=http://www.somostuvoz.net/destacado/constituyente-elvis-mendez-el-coronavirus-lo-inocularon-los-gringos/|title=Constituyente Elvis M\u00e9ndez: \"El coronavirus lo inocularon los gringos\"|last=Web|first=Master| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 7, 2020|website=Somos Tu Voz|language=es|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318065112/http://www.somostuvoz.net/destacado/constituyente-elvis-mendez-el-coronavirus-lo-inocularon-los-gringos/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Anti-Muslim ===\n\n{{further|2020 Tablighi Jamaat coronavirus hotspot in Delhi|Islamophobia}}\nIn India, Muslims have been blamed for spreading infection following the emergence of cases linked to a [[Tablighi Jamaat]] religious gathering.<ref name=newsweek1496011>{{cite journal|title=India's Coronavirus Outbreak Stokes Islamophobia as Muslims blamed for spreading infection|journal=[[Newsweek]]|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.newsweek.com/indias-coronavirus-outbreak-stokes-islamophobia-muslims-blamed-spreading-infection-1496011|access-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There are reports of vilification of Muslims on social media and attacks on individuals in India.<ref name=firstpost8231371>{{cite journal|first=Pinak Pani|last=Datta| name-list-format = vanc |title=Coronavirus outbreak sparks racist attacks on people from North East, stokes Islamophobia on social media|journal=[[Firstpost]]|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/coronavirus-outbreak-sparks-racist-attacks-on-people-from-north-east-stokes-islamophobia-on-social-media-8231371.html}}</ref> Claims have been made Muslims are selling food contaminated with coronavirus and that a mosque in Patna was sheltering people from Italy and Iran.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Nishita|last=Jha| name-list-format = vanc |title=A Cluster Of Coronavirus Cases Can Be Traced Back to a Single Mosque And Now 200 Million Muslims Are Being Vilified|journal=[[Buzzfeed News]]|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/nishitajha/coronavirus-india-muslims-tablighi-jamaat}}</ref> These claims were shown to be false.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Priyanka|last=Jha| name-list-format = vanc |title=No, foreign nationals from Italy, Iran weren't hiding in Patna mosque to avoid coronavirus testing|journal=[[Firstpost]]|date=March 28, 2020|url=https://www.altnews.in/were-50-foreigners-from-itlay-iran-and-china-hiding-in-mosque-due-to-corona-virus-detained-in-bihar-kurji/}}</ref> In the UK, there are reports of far-right groups blaming Muslims for the coronavirus outbreak and falsely claiming that mosques remained open after the national ban on large gatherings.<ref name=20200405theguardian>{{cite journal|first=Nazia|last=Parveen| name-list-format = vanc |title=Police investigate UK far-right groups over anti-Muslim coronavirus claims|journal=[[The Guardian]]|date=April 5, 2020|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/police-investigate-uk-far-right-groups-over-anti-muslim-coronavirus-claims/}}</ref>\n\n=== Antisemitic ===\n\n{{further|Antisemitic canard}}\nIran's [[Press TV]] asserted that \"Zionist elements developed a deadlier strain of coronavirus against Iran\".<ref name=\"presstv\" />\nSimilarly, various Arab media outlets accused Israel and the United States of creating and spreading COVID-19, [[avian flu]], and [[SARS]].<ref name=jpost617021>{{cite journal|title=Arab media accuse US, Israel of coronavirus conspiracy against China|journal=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=February 9, 2020|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Arab-media-accuse-US-Israel-of-coronavirus-conspiracy-against-China-617021|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301063057/https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Arab-media-accuse-US-Israel-of-coronavirus-conspiracy-against-China-617021|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Users on social media offered a variety of theories, including the supposition that Jews had manufactured COVID-19 to precipitate a global stock market collapse and thereby profit via [[insider trading]],<ref name=forward441421>{{cite journal|first=Irene|last=Connelly| name-list-format = vanc |title=Online anti-Semitism thrives around coronavirus, even on mainstream platforms|journal=[[The Forward]]|url=https://forward.com/news/441421/anti-semitic-coronavirus-response-thrives-online-even-on-mainstream/}}</ref> while a guest on Turkish television posited a more ambitious scenario in which Jews and Zionists had created COVID-19, avian flu, and [[Crimean\u2013Congo hemorrhagic fever]] to \"design the world, seize countries, [and] neuter the world's population\".<ref name=20200314timesofisrael>{{cite journal|first=Eric|last=Cortellessa| name-list-format = vanc |title=Conspiracy theory that Jews created virus spreads on social media, ADL says|journal=[[The Times of Israel]]|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/conspiracy-theory-that-jews-created-virus-spreads-on-social-media-adl-says/|date=March 14, 2020|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314133541/https://www.timesofisrael.com/conspiracy-theory-that-jews-created-virus-spreads-on-social-media-adl-says/|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIsraeli attempts to develop a [[COVID-19 vaccine]] prompted mixed reactions. Grand Ayatollah [[Naser Makarem Shirazi]] denied initial reports that he had ruled that a Zionist-made vaccine would be [[halal]],<ref name=jpost621230>{{cite news|last=Joffre|first=Tzvi| name-list-format = vanc |title=Iranian cleric denies approving use of coronavirus vaccine from Israel|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iranian-cleric-denies-approving-use-of-coronavirus-vaccine-from-Israel-621230|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> and one Press TV journalist tweeted that \"I'd rather take my chances with the virus than consume an Israeli vaccine\".<ref name=jpost620900>{{cite news|title=Would a Zionist coronavirus cure be Halal? Iranian cleric says yes|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Is-Zionist-coronavirus-cure-Halal-Iranian-cleric-says-yes-620900|date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> A columnist for the Turkish ''[[Yeni Akit]]'' asserted that such a vaccine could be a ruse to carry out [[Compulsory sterilization|mass sterilization]].<ref name=jpost621393>{{cite news|last=Edmunds|first=Donna Rachel| name-list-format = vanc |title=Coronavirus is a Zionist plot, say Turkish politicians, media, public|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Antisemitism/Coronavirus-is-a-Zionist-plot-say-Turkish-politicians-media-public-621393|date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn alert by the US [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] regarding the possible threat of far-right extremists intentionally spreading the coronavirus mentioned blame being assigned to Jews and Jewish leaders for causing the pandemic and several statewide shutdowns across the US.<ref name=go69737522>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/white-supremacists-encouraging-members-spread-coronavirus-cops-jews/story?id=69737522|title=White supremacists encouraging their members to spread coronavirus to cops, Jews, FBI says|first=Josh|last=Margolin| name-list-format = vanc |website=[[ABC News]]|date=March 23, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Spy operation ===\n\nSome people have alleged that the coronavirus was stolen from a Canadian virus research lab by Chinese scientists. [[Health Canada]] and the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] said that conspiracy theory had \"no factual basis\".<ref name=nofact /> The stories seem to have been derived<ref name=\"buzz_doxx\" /> from a July 2019 news article<ref name=escorted /> stating that some Chinese researchers had their security access to a [[National Microbiology Laboratory|Canadian Level 4 virology facility]] revoked in a [[RCMP|federal police]] investigation; Canadian officials described this as an administrative matter and said that \"there is absolutely no risk to the Canadian public.\"<ref name=escorted>{{cite news |last1=Pauls |first1=Karen Pauls |title=Chinese researcher escorted from infectious disease lab amid RCMP investigation |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/chinese-researcher-escorted-from-infectious-disease-lab-amid-rcmp-investigation-1.5211567 |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |date=July 14, 2019 |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206011635/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/chinese-researcher-escorted-from-infectious-disease-lab-amid-rcmp-investigation-1.5211567 |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThis article was published by the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] (CBC);<ref name=\"buzz_doxx\">{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/a-pro-trump-blog-has-doxed-a-chinese-scientist-it-falsely |title=A Pro-Trump Blog Doxed A Chinese Scientist It Falsely Accused Of Creating The Coronavirus As A Bioweapon |last=Broderick |first=Ryan | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |website=BuzzFeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210034232/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/a-pro-trump-blog-has-doxed-a-chinese-scientist-it-falsely |archive-date=February 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> responding to the conspiracy theories, the CBC later stated that \"CBC reporting never claimed the two scientists were spies, or that they brought any version of the coronavirus to the lab in Wuhan\". While pathogen samples were transferred from the lab in [[Winnipeg]], Canada to Beijing, China, on March 31, 2019, neither of the samples was a coronavirus, the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] says that the shipment conformed to all federal policies, and there has not been any statement that the researchers under investigation were responsible for sending the shipment. The current location of the researchers under investigation by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] is not being released.<ref name=nofact>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/china-coronavirus-online-chatter-conspiracy-1.5442376 |title=Online claims that Chinese scientists stole coronavirus from Winnipeg lab have 'no factual basis' |last=Yates |first=Karen |last2=Pauls |first2=Jeff | name-list-format = vanc |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |time=January 27, 2020 |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208134329/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/china-coronavirus-online-chatter-conspiracy-1.5442376 |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E7%A7%91%E5%AD%A6%E5%AE%B6%E4%BB%8E%E6%B8%A9%E5%B0%BC%E4%BC%AF%E5%AE%9E%E9%AA%8C%E5%AE%A4%E4%B8%AD%E7%AA%83%E5%8F%96-%E5%86%A0%E7%8A%B6%E7%97%85%E6%AF%92%E7%9A%84%E7%BD%91%E7%BB%9C%E4%BC%A0%E8%A8%80-%E6%B2%A1%E6%9C%89%E4%BA%8B%E5%AE%9E%E6%A0%B9%E6%8D%AE-1.5448165 |title=Chinese translation: \u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\u5bb6\u4ece\u6e29\u5c3c\u4f2f\u5b9e\u9a8c\u5ba4\u4e2d\u7a83\u53d6 \u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u7684\u7f51\u7edc\u4f20\u8a00'\u6ca1\u6709\u4e8b\u5b9e\u6839\u636e' |last=Yates |first=Karen |last2=Pauls |first2=Jeff | name-list-format = vanc |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |time=January 27, 2020 |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201040447/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E7%A7%91%E5%AD%A6%E5%AE%B6%E4%BB%8E%E6%B8%A9%E5%B0%BC%E4%BC%AF%E5%AE%9E%E9%AA%8C%E5%AE%A4%E4%B8%AD%E7%AA%83%E5%8F%96-%E5%86%A0%E7%8A%B6%E7%97%85%E6%AF%92%E7%9A%84%E7%BD%91%E7%BB%9C%E4%BC%A0%E8%A8%80-%E6%B2%A1%E6%9C%89%E4%BA%8B%E5%AE%9E%E6%A0%B9%E6%8D%AE-1.5448165 |archive-date=February 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200128factcheck\">{{cite web |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/coronavirus-wasnt-sent-by-spy-from-canada/ |title=Coronavirus Wasn't Sent by 'Spy' From Canada |first=Saranac Hale |last=Spencer | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 28, 2020 |website=Factcheck.org |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130160015/https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/coronavirus-wasnt-sent-by-spy-from-canada/ |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the midst of the coronavirus epidemic, a senior research associate and expert in biological warfare with the [[Begin-Sadat Center for Strategic Studies]], referring to a [[NATO]] press conference, identified suspicions of espionage as the reason behind the expulsions from the lab, but made no suggestion that coronavirus was taken from the Canadian lab or that it is the result of bioweapons defense research in China.<ref name=20200129besacenter>{{cite web |url=https://besacenter.org/perspectives-papers/china-biological-warfare/ |title=China and Viruses: The Case of Dr. Xiangguo Qiu |last=Shoham | name-list-format = vanc |first=Dany |publisher=Begin-Sadat Center for Strategic Studies |date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Population control scheme ===\n\nAccording to the BBC, Jordan Sather, a conspiracy theory [[YouTuber]] supporting the [[QAnon|far-right QAnon conspiracy theory]] and the [[Vaccine hesitancy|anti-vax]] movement, has falsely claimed the outbreak was a population control scheme created by [[Pirbright Institute]] in England and by former [[Microsoft]] CEO [[Bill Gates]]. This belief is held mostly by [[Paleolibertarianism|right-wing libertarians]], [[New World Order (conspiracy theory)|NWO conspiracy theorists]], and [[Christian fundamentalism|Christian Fundamentalists]].<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\"20200123buzzfeednews\">{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/qanon-supporters-and-anti-vaxxers-are-spreading-a-hoax-that |title=QAnon Supporters And Anti-Vaxxers Are Spreading A Hoax That Bill Gates Created The Coronavirus |last=Broderick |first=Ryan | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 23, 2020 |website=BuzzFeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130075624/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/qanon-supporters-and-anti-vaxxers-are-spreading-a-hoax-that |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Accidental leakage ===\nA number of allegations have emerged on the [[Wuhan Institute of Virology#Concerns as source|link]] between the virus and [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] (WIV), among these is that the virus was an accidental leakage from WIV.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web | website=BBC News China | url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/chinese-news-51388024 | title=[TRANSLATED] Wuhan Pneumonia: \"Wuhan Virus Research Institute\" in the eyes of the outbreak and fake news storm | date=February 5, 2020 | access-date=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216162120/https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/chinese-news-51388024 | archive-date=February 16, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> In 2017, US molecular biologist [[Richard H. Ebright]], expressed caution when the WIV was expanded to become mainland China's first [[biosafety level 4]] (BSL\u20134) laboratory, noting previous escapes of the SARS virus at other Chinese laboratories.<ref name=\"nature\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Cyranoski D | title = Inside the Chinese lab poised to study world's most dangerous pathogens | journal = Nature | volume = 542 | issue = 7642 | pages = 399\u2013400 | date = February 2017 | pmid = 28230144 | doi = 10.1038/nature.2017.21487 | bibcode = 2017Natur.542..399C | doi-access = free }}</ref> While Ebright refuted several conspiracy theories regarding the WIV (e.g. bioweapons research, that the virus was engineered), he told BBC China that this did not represent the possibility that the virus can be \"completely ruled out\" from entering the population due to a laboratory accident.<ref name=\"BBC\" />\n\nOn 14 February 2020, Chinese scientist explored the possibility of accidental leakage and published speculations on scientific [[social networking]] website [[ResearchGate]]. The paper was neither [[peer-reviewed]] nor presented any evidence for its claims.<ref name=\"fullfact_0417origin\">{{cite web|url=https://fullfact.org/health/coronavirus-government-laboratory/|title=There's no evidence that the 2019 coronavirus originated in a Chinese government laboratory|date=17 February 2020|website=FullFact|last=Lewis|first=Kate}}</ref> On March 5, the author of paper told ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' in an interview why he decided to withdrew the paper by the end of February, stating: \"the speculation about the possible origins in the post was based on published papers and media, and was not supported by direct proofs.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/global-opinions/how-did-covid-19-begin-its-initial-origin-story-is-shaky/2020/04/02/1475d488-7521-11ea-87da-77a8136c1a6d_story.html|title=How did covid-19 begin? Its initial origin story is shaky. |website=Washington Post|last=Ignatius |first=David }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/coronavirus-epidemic-draws-scrutiny-to-labs-handling-deadly-pathogens-11583349777|title=Coronavirus Epidemic Draws Scrutiny to Labs Handling Deadly Pathogens|website=Wall Street Journal|last=Areddy|first=James T.|date=5 March 2020}}</ref> Several newspapers have referenced the paper.<ref name=\"fullfact_0417origin\" /> ''[[Scientific American]]'' reported that [[Shi Zhengli]], the lead researcher at WIV, started investigation on mishandling of experimental materials in the lab records, especially during disposal. She also tried to cross-check the novel coronavirus genome with the genetic information of other bat coronaviruses her team had collected. The result showed none of the sequences matched those of the viruses her team had sampled from bat caves.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/how-chinas-bat-woman-hunted-down-viruses-from-sars-to-the-new-coronavirus1/|title=How China\u2019s \u201cBat Woman\u201d Hunted Down Viruses from SARS to the New Coronavirus|website=Scientific American |date=11 March 2020|last=Qiu |first=Jane }}</ref>\n\nIn February, it has been alleged that the first person infected may have been a researcher at the institute named Huang Yanling.<ref name=\"scmp0216_huangyanling\" /> Rumours circulated on Chinese social media that the researcher had become infected and died, prompting a denial from WIV, saying that she was a graduate student enrolled in the Institute until 2015 and is not the patient zero.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whiov.ac.cn/tzgg_105342/202002/t20200216_5500201.html |title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\u9662\u6b66\u6c49\u75c5\u6bd2\u7814\u7a76\u6240\u58f0\u660e |date=February 16, 2020 |work=Wuhan Institute of Virology }}</ref><ref name=\"scmp0216_huangyanling\">{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3050872/chinese-research-lab-denies-rumours-links-first-coronavirus |title=Chinese research lab denies rumours of links to first coronavirus patient |date=16 February 2020|first=Jun |last= Mai | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> In April, the conspiracy theory started to circulate around on Youtube and got picked up by conservative media, ''National Review''.<ref name=20200403nationalreview>{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2020/04/coronavirus-china-trail-leading-back-to-wuhan-labs/ |title= The Trail Leading Back to the Wuhan Labs |first= Jim |last=Geraghty | name-list-format = vanc |date=April 3, 2020|work=National Review}}</ref><ref name=\"fp_0414conspiracy\"/>\n\nThe ''[[South China Morning Post]]'' (SCMP) reported that one of the WIV's lead researchers, [[Shi Zhengli]], was the particular focus of personal attacks in Chinese social media alleging that her work on bat-based viruses was the source of the virus; this led Shi to post: \"I swear with my life, [the virus] has nothing to do with the lab\". When asked by the SCMP to comment on the attacks, Shi responded: \"My time must be spent on more important matters\".<ref name=\"SCMP\">{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] | url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3049397/bat-ladys-cave-exploits-offer-hope-beat-virus-sneakier-sars | title=Coronavirus: bat scientist's cave exploits offer hope to beat virus 'sneakier than Sars' | first=Stephen | last=Chen | name-list-format = vanc | date=February 6, 2020 | access-date=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207210442/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3049397/bat-ladys-cave-exploits-offer-hope-beat-virus-sneakier-sars | archive-date=February 7, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Caixin]]'' reported Shi made further public statements against \"perceived [[Tinfoil hat|tinfoil-hat]] theories about the new virus's source\", quoting her as saying: \"The novel 2019 coronavirus is nature punishing the human race for keeping uncivilized living habits. I, Shi Zhengli, swear on my life that it has nothing to do with our laboratory\".<ref name=caixinglobal101512828>{{cite web | url=https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-02-07/wuhan-virology-lab-deputy-director-again-slams-coronavirus-conspiracies-101512828.html | title=Wuhan Virology Lab Deputy Director Again Slams Coronavirus Conspiracies | website=[[Caixin]] | first1=Yang | last1=Rui | first2=Feng | last2=Yuding | first3=Zhao | last3=Jinchao | first4=Matthew | last4=Walsh | name-list-format = vanc | date=February 7, 2020 | access-date=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219215801/https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-02-07/wuhan-virology-lab-deputy-director-again-slams-coronavirus-conspiracies-101512828.html | archive-date=February 19, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> Immunologist [[Vincent Racaniello]] stated that virus leaking theory \"reflect a lack of understanding of the genetic make-up of Sars-CoV-2 and its relationship to the bat virus\". He states that the bat virus researched in the institution \"would not have been able to infect humans \u2013 the human Sars-CoV-2 has additional changes that allows it to infect humans.\"<ref name=\"scmp0411\">{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3079391/bat-virus-bioweapon-what-science-says-about-covid-19-origins |title=Bat virus? Bioweapon? What the science says about Covid-19 origins |date=11 April 2020|first=Simone |last= McCarthy|first2=Stephen |last2=Chen | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref>\n\nOn April 14, the US [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]], General [[Mark A. Milley|Mark Milley]], in response to questions about the virus being manufactured in a lab, said \"... it\u2019s inconclusive, although the weight of evidence seems to indicate natural. But we don\u2019t know for certain.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/14/covid-19-origin-lab-general-mark-milley |title=US military chief: 'Weight of evidence' that Covid-19 did not originate in a lab |first=Julian |last=Borger | name-list-format = vanc |date= 14 April 2020 |work=The Guardian }}</ref> Days later, multiple media outlets confirmed that U.S. intelligence officials were investigating the possibility that the virus started in the WIV.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dilanian |first1=Ken |title=U.S. intel community examining whether coronavirus emerged accidentally from a Chinese lab |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/china/u-s-intel-community-examining-whether-coronavirus-emerged-accidentally-chinese-n1185371 |website=NBC News |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Strobel |first1=Warren P. |title=U.S. Intelligence Sifts Evidence for Origins of Coronavirus |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-intelligence-sifts-evidence-for-origins-of-coronavirus-11587077170 |website=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gazis |first1=Olivia |title=U.S. intelligence community still investigating origins of COVID-19 outbreak, including whether it was a lab accident |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-covid-19-origins-investigation-wuhan-lab-accident/ |website=CBS News |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Campbell |first1=Josh |title=US explores possibility that coronavirus spread started in Chinese lab, not a market |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/15/politics/us-intelligence-virus-started-chinese-lab/index.html |website=CNN |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n=== Nurse whistleblower ===\n\nOn January 24, a video circulated online appearing to be of a nurse named ''Jin Hui''<ref name=\"theinitium20200130\">{{cite web|url=https://theinitium.com/article/20200130-repost-pansci-2019ncov-misinformation/|title=\u6cdb\u79d1\u5b78\uff1a\u95dc\u65bc\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u768420\u500b\u50b3\u8a00\uff0c\u54ea\u4e9b\u662f\u771f\u54ea\u4e9b\u662f\u5047\uff1f|website=The Initium|date=January 30, 2020|language=Chinese|first1=Peiqi|last1=Luo|first2=Yingkai|last2=Liao| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=February 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202120919/https://theinitium.com/article/20200130-repost-pansci-2019ncov-misinformation/|archive-date=February 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> in [[Hubei]] describing a far more dire situation in Wuhan than purported by Chinese officials. The video claimed that more than 90,000 people had been infected with the virus in China, the virus can spread from one person to 14 people and the virus is starting the second mutation.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |title=Facebook, Twitter, and YouTube struggle with coronavirus hoaxes |last=Ghaffary |first=Shirin | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |website=Vox |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208004124/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The video attracted millions of views on various social media platforms and was mentioned in numerous online reports. However, the BBC noted that contrary to its English subtitles in one of the video's existing versions, the woman does not claim to be either a nurse or a doctor in the video and that her suit and mask do not match the ones worn by medical staff in Hubei.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /> The video's claim of 90,000 infected cases is noted to be 'unsubstantiated'.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\":10\" />\n\n=== Alleged leak of death toll ===\n\nOn February 25, ''[[Taiwan News]]'' published an article, claiming [[Tencent]] accidentally leaked the real numbers of death and infection in China. ''Taiwan News'' suggests the ''Tencent Epidemic Situation Tracker'' had briefly showed infected cases and death tolls many times higher of the official figure, citing a Facebook post by 38-year-old Taiwanese beverage store owner ''Hiroki Lo'' and an anonymous Taiwanese [[netizen]].<ref name=taiwannews3871594>{{cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3871594|title=Tencent may have accidentally leaked real data on Wuhan virus deaths|first=Keoni|last=Everington | name-list-format = vanc |website=[[Taiwan News]]|date=February 2, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200217020907/https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3871594|archive-date=February 17, 2020|access-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The article was referenced by other news outlets such as ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and widely circulated on Twitter, Facebook, 4chan, sparked a wide range of conspiracy theories that the screenshot indicates the real death toll instead of the ones published by health officials.<ref name=bloommag /> Justin Lessler, associate professor at the Bloomberg School of Public Health, claims the numbers of the alleged \"leak\" are unreasonable and unrealistic, citing the case fatality rate as far lower than the 'leaked information'. A spokesman of Tencent responded to the news article, claiming the image was doctored, and it features \"false information which we never published\".<ref name=inews1411992>{{cite web |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/coronavirus-death-toll-story-fake-china-virus-explained-1411992 |title=A massively shared story about the 'real' Coronavirus death toll is fake: Here's how we know |date=February 11, 2020 |website=iNews |last=Sharma |first=Ruchira | name-list-format = vanc |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229191409/https://inews.co.uk/news/coronavirus-death-toll-story-fake-china-virus-explained-1411992 |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nKeoni Everington, author of the original news article, defended and asserted the authenticity of the leak.<ref name=\"bloommag\" /> Brian Hioe and Lars Wooster of ''New Bloom Magazine'' debunked the theory from data on other websites, which were using Tencent's database to generate custom visualizations while showing none of the inflated figures appearing in the images promulgated by ''Taiwan News''. Thus, they concluded the screenshot was digitally fabricated.<ref name=\"bloommag\">{{cite web |url=https://newbloommag.net/2020/02/12/coronavirus-taiwan-news/ |title=TAIWAN NEWS PUBLISHES COVID-19 MISINFORMATION AS EPIDEMIC SPREADS |first=Brian |last=Hioe |first2=Lars |last2=Wooster | name-list-format = vanc |website=New Bloom Magazine |date=February 12, 2020 |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229191408/https://newbloommag.net/2020/02/12/coronavirus-taiwan-news/ |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Misinformation against Taiwan ===\n\n{{further|Cross-Strait relations}}\nOn February 26, 2020, Taiwanese [[Central News Agency (Republic of China)|Central News Agency]] reported that large amounts of misinformation had appeared on Facebook claiming [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Taiwan|the pandemic in Taiwan]] had lost control, the Taiwanese Government had covered up the total number of cases, and that President [[Tsai Ing-wen]] had been infected. The Taiwan fact-checking organization had suggested the misinformation on Facebook shared similarities with [[mainland China]] due to its use of [[simplified Chinese]] and mainland China vocabulary. The organization warns the purpose of the misinformation is to attack the government.<ref name=cna2020022604>{{cite news|url=https://www.cna.com.tw/news/firstnews/202002260428.aspx|script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u75ab\u60c5\u8b20\u8a00\u591a \u4e8b\u5be6\u67e5\u6838\u4e2d\u5fc3\u63073\u5927\u5171\u540c\u9ede|date=February 26, 2020|agency=[[Central News Agency (Republic of China)|Central News Agency]] |language=zh-tw}}</ref><ref name=taipeitimes2003731764>{{cite news |title=Virus Outbreak: Chinese trolls decried for fake news |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/02/28/2003731764 |work=Taipei Times |date=February 28, 2020 |access-date=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301114540/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/02/28/2003731764 |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=20200229reuters>{{cite news |title=Taiwan accuses China of waging cyber 'war' to disrupt virus fight |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/taiwan-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-39-idUSKBN20N09C |agency=Reuters |date=February 29, 2020 |access-date=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301160250/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/taiwan-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-39-idUSKBN20N09C |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Taiwan's [[Ministry of Justice Investigation Bureau]] warned that mainland China was trying to undermine trust in factual news by portraying the Taiwanese Government reports as fake news. Taiwanese authorities have been ordered to use all possible means to track whether the messages were linked to instructions given by the Communist Party of China. The PRC's [[Taiwan Affairs Office]] denied the claims calling them lies and said that Taiwan's [[Democratic Progressive Party]] was \"inciting hatred\" between the two sides. They then claimed that the \"DPP continues to politically manipulate the virus\".<ref name=20200303reuters>{{cite news |first1=Yimou |last1=Lee |first2=Ben |last2=Blanchard | name-list-format = vanc |title='Provocative' China pressures Taiwan with fighters, fake news amid virus outbreak |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-taiwan-china/provocative-china-pressures-taiwan-with-fighters-fake-news-amid-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN20Q08M |agency=Reuters |access-date=March 5, 2020 |quote=\"We have been told to track if the origins are linked to instructions given by the Communist Party, using all possible means,\" the official said, adding that authorities had increased scrutiny on online platforms, including chat rooms. |date=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305160849/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-taiwan-china/provocative-china-pressures-taiwan-with-fighters-fake-news-amid-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN20Q08M |archive-date=March 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to ''[[The Washington Post]]'', China has used organized disinformation campaigns against Taiwan for decades.<ref name=washingtonpost3400200>{{cite web |last1=Fifield |first1=Anna |title=Russia's disinformation campaign in the U.S. has nothing on China's efforts in Taiwan |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/russias-disinformation-campaign-in-the-us-has-nothing-on-chinas-efforts-in-taiwan/2020/01/08/3400200a-231a-11ea-b034-de7dc2b5199b_story.html |work=The Washington Post |access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNick Monaco the research director of the Digital Intelligence Lab at Institute for the Future analyzed the posts and concluded that the majority appear to have come from ordinary users in China not the state. However, he criticized the Chinese government making to decision to allow the information to spread beyond China's [[Great Firewall]] which he described as \"malicious.\"<ref name=npr814709530>{{cite web |title=With Odds Against It, Taiwan Keeps Coronavirus Corralled |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/13/814709530/with-odds-against-it-taiwan-keeps-coronavirus-corralled |publisher=NPR |access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> According to ''Taiwan News'', nearly 1 in 4 cases of misinformation are believed to be connected to mainland China.<ref name=taiwannews3904042>{{cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3904042|title=One-fourth of coronavirus misinformation in Taiwan comes from Chinese trolls: CIB|website=Taiwan News|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2020 the [[American Institute in Taiwan]] announced that it was partnering with the Taiwan FactCheck Center to help combat misinformation about the COVID-19 outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Chen |last1=Yun-yu |first2=Matthew |last2=Mazzetta | name-list-format = vanc |title=AIT partners with local group to combat COVID-19 disinformation |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003270016 |website=focustaiwan.tw |publisher=Focus Taiwan |access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Misrepresented World Population Project map ===\n\nIn early February, a decade-old map illustrating a hypothetical viral outbreak published by the World Population Project (part of the [[University of Southampton]]) was misappropriated by a number of Australian media news outlets (and British tabloids ''The Sun'', ''Daily Mail'' and ''Metro'')<ref name=\":4\" /> which claimed the map represented the 2020 coronavirus outbreak. This misinformation was then spread via the social media accounts of the same media outlets, and while some outlets later removed the map, the BBC reported that a number of news sites had yet to retract the map.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|author=Reality Check team|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51504512|title=How a misleading coronavirus map went global|date=February 19, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219013538/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51504512|archive-date=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Misreported death ===\nDespite sufficient data gathered in regards of case fatality rates by age group,<ref name=\"covidstats\">{{Cite journal|url=https://ourworldindata.org/coronavirus|title=Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19) \u2013 Statistics and Research|first1=Max|last1=Roser|first2=Hannah|last2=Ritchie|first3=Esteban|last3=Ortiz-Ospina|first4=Joe|last4=Hasell|date=March 4, 2020|journal=Our World in Data|via=ourworldindata.org}}</ref> rumours of young people with no premorbidities dying of [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]] virus were circulating social media and were even published by large daily newspapers.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52041709|title=Chloe Middleton: Woman, 21, died with 'no underlying health issues'|website=BBC|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"express\">{{cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/1260123/Chloe-Middleton-coronavirus-death-UK-latest-Facebook-video-COVID-19-symptoms|title=Heartbreak as healthy 21-year-old dies from coronavirus \u2013 'It's not just a virus'|website=Express|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> However, many of these media reports have proven to be false or misrepresented upon closer inspection \u2013 such cases included news about a 21-year old spanish football coach Francisco Garcia<ref name=\"yahoosport\">{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/spanish-football-coach-francisco-garcia-163153573.html|title=Spanish football coach Francisco Garcia dies of coronavirus aged 21|website=Sports Yahoo|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> and British 21-year old woman Chloe Middleton.<ref name=\"theguardian\">{{cite web|url=https://archive.is/20200329015127/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/27/chloe-middleton-death-21-year-old-not-recorded-nhs-covid-19-related|title=Chloe Middleton: death of 21-year-old not recorded as Covid-19|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"spiked\">{{cite web|url=https://www.spiked-online.com/2020/03/27/chloe-middleton-the-coronavirus-death-that-wasnt/|title=Chloe Middleton: the coronavirus death that wasn't|website=Spiked|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>{{MEDCN|date=April 2020}}<!--implication that young people without co-morbidities can't die-->\n\n=== Decline in cellphone subscriptions ===\nThere was a decrease of nearly 21 million cellphone subscriptions among the three largest cellphone carriers in China, which led to the spread of misinformation that this is evidence for millions of deaths due to the coronavirus in China.<ref name=laj-dicu /> However, the decline in cellphone subscriptions is actually attributed to people cancelling phone services as a result of a downturn in the social and economic life during the outbreak.<ref name=laj-dicu>{{cite web |last1=Lajka |first1=Arijeta |title=Drop in cellphone users in China wrongly attributed to coronavirus deaths |url=https://apnews.com/afs:Content:8717250566 |website=AP NEWS |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Medical misinformation ==\n{{Main|List of unproven methods against COVID-19}}\n<!--This article is becoming longer by the day. Please try to add new content in the :List of unproven methods against COVID-19\" page instead of doing so here-->\nWidely circulated posts on social media have made many unfounded claims of methods against coronavirus. Some of these claims are scams, and some promoted methods are dangerous and unhealthy.<ref name=WHO_myths /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Andrew |title=Social media awash with fake treatments for coronavirus |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/social-media-awash-with-fake-treatments-for-coronavirus-20200326-p54e9q.html |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> For misinformation that is a direct claim of a method to prevent, diagnose, or treat COVID-19, see [[List of unproven methods against COVID-19]]. This section deals only with other misinformation or prevent/diagnose/treat claims with wider social consquences.\n\n=== COVID-19 recovery ===\nIt has been wrongly claimed that anyone infected with COVID-19 will have the virus in their bodies for life. While there is no curative treatment, infected individuals can recover from the disease, eliminating the virus from their bodies; getting supportive medical care early can help.<ref name=WHO_myths />\n\n=== Vaccine pre-existence ===\nIt was reported that multiple social media posts have promoted a conspiracy theory claiming the virus was known and that a vaccine was already available. [[PolitiFact]] and [[FactCheck.org]] noted that no vaccine currently exists for COVID-19. The patents cited by various social media posts reference existing patents for genetic sequences and vaccines for other strains of coronavirus such as the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus|SARS coronavirus]].<ref name=20200123politifact>{{cite web |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/jan/23/facebook-posts/there-outbreak-china-wuhan-coronavirus-there-not-v/ |title=No, there is no vaccine for the Wuhan coronavirus |first=Tom |last=Kertscher | name-list-format = vanc |website=Politifact |date=January 23, 2020 |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207133056/https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/jan/23/facebook-posts/there-outbreak-china-wuhan-coronavirus-there-not-v/ |archive-date=February 7, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\" /> The WHO reported as of February 5, 2020 that amid news reports of \"breakthrough\" drugs being discovered to treat people infected with the virus, there were no known effective treatments;<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-treatments-who-idUSKBN1ZZ1M6 |title=WHO: 'no known effective' treatments for new coronavirus |date=February 5, 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=February 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205155653/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-treatments-who-idUSKBN1ZZ1M6 |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> this included antibiotics and herbal remedies not being useful.<ref name=aljazeera2002020934>{{cite news |title=Dispelling the myths around the new coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2020/02/dispelling-myths-coronavirus-outbreak-200202093426388.html |access-date=February 8, 2020 |publisher=Al Jazeera |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206033735/https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2020/02/dispelling-myths-coronavirus-outbreak-200202093426388.html?utm_source=website&utm_medium=article_page&utm_campaign=read_more_links |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[COVID-19 vaccine|Scientists are working to develop a vaccine]], but as of March 18, 2020, no vaccine candidates have completed clinical trials.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n=== Cocaine ===\nCocaine does not protect against COVID-19. Several viral tweets purporting that snorting [[cocaine]] would sterilize one's nostrils of the coronavirus spread around Europe and Africa. In response, the [[French Ministry of Health]] released a public service announcement debunking this claim, saying \"No, cocaine does NOT protect against COVID-19. It is an addictive drug that causes serious side effects and is harmful to people\u2019s health.\" The [[World Health Organisation]] also debunked the claim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/news/french-government-cocaine-coke-coronavirus-hoax/|title=Sorry to the French People Who Thought Cocaine Would Protect Them From Coronavirus|last=Crellin|first=Zac | name-list-format = vanc |website=Pedestrian.TV|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311082415/https://www.pedestrian.tv/news/french-government-cocaine-coke-coronavirus-hoax/|archive-date=March 11, 2020|url-status=live|date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Ethnic resistance/susceptibilty ===\n\nThere have been claims that specific [[ethnicities]] are more or less vulnerable to COVID-19. COVID-19 is a new [[zoonotic]] disease, so no population has yet had the time to develop [[population immunity]].{{medcn|date=April 2020}}\n\nBeginning on February 11, reports, quickly spread via Facebook, implied that a Cameroonian student in China had been completely cured of the virus due to his African genetics. While a student was successfully treated, other media sources have noted that no evidence implies Africans are more resistant to the virus and labeled such claims as false information.<ref name=20200212afp>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/black-people-arent-more-resistant-novel-coronavirus|title=Black people aren't more resistant to novel coronavirus|date=February 12, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|access-date=February 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216141447/https://factcheck.afp.com/black-people-arent-more-resistant-novel-coronavirus|archive-date=February 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Kenyan Secretary of Health [[Mutahi Kagwe]] explicitly refuted rumors that \"those with black skin cannot get coronavirus\", while announcing Kenya's first case on March 13.<ref name=20200313cnn>{{cite news|title=Minister rejects false rumors that 'those with black skin cannot get coronavirus' as Kenya records first case|first1=Mia|last1=Alberti|first2=Bethlehem|last2=Feleke| name-list-format = vanc |publisher=CNN|url=https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-13-20-intl-hnk/h_daa3fbd19db18fdbb4be569a9613fe96|date=March 13, 2020|access-date=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319003805/https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-13-20-intl-hnk/h_daa3fbd19db18fdbb4be569a9613fe96|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This myth was cited as a contributing factor in the disproportionately high rates of infection and death observed among African Americans.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Poston |first1=Ben |last2=Barboza |first2=Tony |last3=Jennings |first3=Angel | name-list-format = vanc |title=L.A. releases first racial breakdown of coronavirus fatalities; blacks have higher death rate|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=April 7, 2020 |access-date=April 10, 2020 |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-04-07/l-a-releases-first-racial-breakdown-of-coronavirus-fatalities-african-americans-have-higher-death-rate}}</ref><ref name=usatoday2961323001>{{cite news|last=Barfield Berry |first=Deborah | name-list-format = vanc  |title=Black people dying from coronavirus at much higher rates in cities across the USA | newspaper=USA Today |date=April 7, 2020 |access-date=April 10, 2020 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2020/04/07/who-dying-coronavirus-more-black-people-die-major-cities/2961323001/}}</ref>\n\nThere have been claims of \"Indian immunity\": that the people of India have more immunity to the COVID-19 virus due to living conditions in India. This idea was deemed \"absolute drivel\" by Dr. Anand Krishnan, professor at the Centre for Community Medicine of the [[All India Institute of Medical Sciences]] (AIIMS). He said that there was no [[population immunity]] to the COVID-19 virus yet, as it is new, and it is not even clear whether people who have recovered from COVID-19 will have lasting immunity, as this happens with some viruses but not with others.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vegetarian food, Indian immunity won\u2019t prevent Covid-19, says Anand Krishnan |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/coronavirus-cases-cure-symptoms-precautions-aiims-6314643/ |work=The Indian Express |date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] claimed that the virus was genetically targeted at Iranians by the USA, and this is why it is [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|seriously affecting Iran]]. He did not offer any evidence.<ref name=\"independent-corona\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Iran's leader suggests US cooked up 'special version' of virus to target country |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/iran-coronavirus-us-target-country-special-version-covid19-a9417206.html |work=The Independent |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=france2420200322>{{cite news |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200322-iran-s-supreme-leader-khamanei-refuses-us-help-to-fight-coronavirus-citing-conspiracy-theory |title=Iran's Khamanei refuses US help to fight coronavirus, citing conspiracy theory |date= March 22, 2020|publisher=France 24 }}</ref>\n\n===COVID-19 xenophobic blaming by ethnicity===<!--not sure if this doesn't belong with some of the nationally-based blaming above-->\nCOVID-19-related [[xenophobic]] attacks have been made against people the attacker blamed for COVID-19 on the basis of their ethnicity. The [[Asian Australian Alliance]] did a survey on attacks against Asian Australians in April 2020; 81% of victims said they believed the attack against them was related to the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zhou |first1=Naaman |title=Survey of Covid-19 racism against Asian Australians records 178 incidents in two weeks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/17/survey-of-covid-19-racism-against-asian-australians-records-178-incidents-in-two-weeks |work=The Guardian |date=17 April 2020}}</ref> [[White supremacist]] groups have blamed COVID-19 on non-whites and advocated deliberately infecting minorities they dislike, such as Jews.<ref>{{cite web |title=World \u2013 as-world-struggles-to-stop-deaths-far-right-celebrates-covid-19 \u2013 News \u2013 msn |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/as-world-struggles-to-stop-deaths-far-right-celebrates-covid-19/ |website=www.msn.com}}</ref>\n\n<!--On the basis of historical examples, there have been warnings about discriminating by immunity.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Olivarius |first1=Kathryn |title=The Dangerous History of Immunoprivilege |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/opinion/coronavirus-immunity-passports.html |website=The New York Times |date=12 April 2020}}</ref>-->\n\n=== 5G ===\nThe theories linking 5G mobile phone networks to COVID-19 were described as the \"worst kind of fake news\" by Professor Steve Powis, national medical director of [[NHS England]].<ref name=\"ie-mast-fires-surge-in-the-uk-over-easter-weekend-amid-5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theories\" /> Viruses cannot be transmitted by [[radio waves]]. COVID-19 is spreading in many countries which do not have 5G networks.<ref name=WHO_myths />\n\nIn February 2020, [[BBC News]] reported that conspiracy theorists on social media groups alleged a link between coronavirus and [[5G]] mobile networks, claiming that [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|Wuhan]] and [[Diamond Princess outbreak]]s were [[Wireless device radiation and health|directly caused by electromagnetic fields and the introduction of 5G and wireless technologies]]. Some conspiracy theorists also alleged that the coronavirus outbreak was [[cover-up]] for a 5G-related illness.<ref name=\"bbc-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51646309|title=Coronavirus: Fake news is spreading fast|work=[[BBC]]|date=February 26, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Rory|last=Cellan-Jones| name-list-format = vanc |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317062547/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51646309|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2020, Thomas Cowan, a [[Alternative medicine|holistic medical practitioner]] who trained as a physician and operates on probation with [[Medical Board of California]], alleged that coronavirus is caused by 5G, based on the claims that [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|African countries were not affected significantly by the pandemic]] and Africa was not a 5G region.<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\" /><ref name=\"cbc-5g\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/fact-check-viral-video-coronavirus-1.5506595|title= Viral video claiming 5G caused pandemic easily debunked|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date= March 23, 2020 |first1=Katie |last1=Nicholson |first2=Jason |last2=Ho |first3=Jeff |last3=Yates| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-date= March 26, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326125553/https://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/fact-check-viral-video-coronavirus-1.5506595}}</ref> Cowan also falsely alleged that the viruses were wastes from cells that are poisoned by electromagnetic fields and historical viral pandemics coincided with the major developments in radio technology.<ref name=\"cbc-5g\" /> The video of his claims went viral and was recirculated by celebrities including [[Woody Harrelson]], [[John Cusack]], and singer [[Keri Hilson]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Satariano |first1=Adam |last2=Alba |first2=Davey | name-list-format = vanc |title=Burning Cell Towers, Out of Baseless Fear They Spread the Virus |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/10/technology/coronavirus-5g-uk.html |work=The New York Times |date=10 April 2020}}</ref> The claims may also have been recirculated by an alleged \"coordinated disinformation campaign\", similar to campaigns used by the [[Internet Research Agency]] in Saint Petersburg, Russia.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gallagher |first1=Ryan |title=5G Virus Conspiracy Theory Fueled by Coordinated Effort |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-09/covid-19-link-to-5g-technology-fueled-by-coordinated-effort |access-date=12 April 2020 |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=9 April 2020}}</ref> The claims were criticized on social media and debunked by [[Reuters]],<ref name=\"reuters-5g\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-coronavirus-5g/false-claim-5g-networks-are-making-people-sick-not-coronavirus-idUSKBN2133TI|title=False claim: 5G networks are making people sick, not Coronavirus|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=March 17, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320023007/https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-coronavirus-5g/false-claim-5g-networks-are-making-people-sick-not-coronavirus-idUSKBN2133TI|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'',<ref name=usatoday2873731001>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/2020/03/21/did-5-g-cause-coronavirus-covid-19-pandemic/2873731001/ |title= Here's why 5G and coronavirus are not connected |last=O'Donnell |first=Bob | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 21, 2020 |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=March 22, 2020|archive-date=March 21, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321213438/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/2020/03/21/did-5-g-cause-coronavirus-covid-19-pandemic/2873731001/}}</ref> [[Full Fact]]<ref name=20200313fullfact>{{cite web |url=https://fullfact.org/online/coronavirus-5G/ |title= These claims about the new coronavirus and 5G are unfounded |last=Krishna |first= Rachael | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 13, 2020 |work=[[Full Fact]] |access-date=March 22, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320160841/https://fullfact.org/online/coronavirus-5G/|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[American Public Health Association]] executive director [[Georges C. Benjamin]].<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/youtube-video-suggests-5g-internet-causes-coronavirus-people-are-falling-it-1493321|title= Youtube Video Suggests 5G Internet Causes Coronavirus and People Are Falling For It|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=March 19, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Kelly|last=Wynne | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref><ref name=\"huffington-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/keri-hilson-5g-did-not-cause-coronavirus_n_5e6f8ba7c5b6dda30fce0348|title=No, Keri Hilson, 5G Did Not Cause Coronavirus|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=March 16, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Taryn|last=Finley| name-list-format = vanc |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319232700/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/keri-hilson-5g-did-not-cause-coronavirus_n_5e6f8ba7c5b6dda30fce0348|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter telecommunications masts in several parts of the United Kingdom were the subject of arson attacks, British Cabinet Office Minister [[Michael Gove]] said the theory that COVID-19 virus may be spread by [[5G]] wireless communication is \"just nonsense, dangerous nonsense as well.\"<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-britain-5g/5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory-is-dangerous-fake-nonsense-uk-says-idUSKBN21M0MS 5G coronavirus conspiracy theory is dangerous fake nonsense, UK says] Reuters Technology News, April 4, 2020</ref> [[Vodafone UK|Vodafone]] announced that two Vodafone masts and two it shares with [[O2 (UK)|O2]] had been targeted.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2020/04/06/5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory-telecom-tower-fires/|title=5G-coronavirus conspiracy theory spurs rash of telecom tower arson fires|website=Fortune}}</ref>\n\nBy April 6, 2020 at least 20 mobile phone masts in the UK had been vandalised since the previous Thursday.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims>{{Cite news|title=At least 20 UK phone masts vandalised over false 5G coronavirus claims|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/06/at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims|last=Waterson|first=Jim| name-list-format = vanc |date=April 6, 2020|access-date=April 11, 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|last2=Hern|first2=Alex}}</ref> Because of slow rollout of 5G in the UK, many of the damaged masts had only 3G and 4G equipment.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims /> Mobile phone and home broadband operators estimated there were at least 30 incidents of confronting engineers maintaining equipment in the week up to April 6.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims /> There have been eleven incidents of attempted arson at mobile phone masts in the Netherlands, including one case where \"Fuck 5G\" was written, as well as in Ireland and Cyprus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2330065-brand-bij-vier-zendmasten-heel-sterk-vermoeden-van-brandstichting.html|title=Brand bij vier zendmasten: 'Heel sterk vermoeden van brandstichting'|date=April 10, 2020|work=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting]]|access-date=April 11, 2020|url-status=live|language=nl}}</ref><!-- FT article not paywalled --><ref>{{cite news|last1=Fildes|first1=Nic|last2=Di Stefano|first2=Mark|last3=Murphy|first3=Hannah | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.ft.com/content/1eeedb71-d9dc-4b13-9b45-fcb7898ae9e1|title=How a 5G coronavirus conspiracy spread across Europe|work=Financial Times|date=16 April 2020|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> Facebook has deleted multiple messages encouraging attacks on 5G equipment.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims />\n\nEngineers working for [[Openreach]] posted pleas on anti-5G Facebook groups asking to be spared abuse as they are not involved with maintaining mobile networks.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies>{{Cite news|title=Broadband engineers threatened due to 5G coronavirus conspiracies|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/03/broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies|last=Waterson|first=Jim| name-list-format = vanc |date=April 3, 2020|access-date=April 5, 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Mobile UK said that the incidents were affecting attempts to maintain networks that support home working and provide critical connections to vulnerable customers, emergency services and hospitals.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies /> A widely circulated video shows people working for broadband company Community Fibre being abused by a woman who accuses them of installing 5G as part of a plan to kill the population.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies />\n\nYouTube announced that it would reduce the amount of content claiming links between 5G and coronavirus.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory>{{Cite news|title=YouTube moves to limit spread of false coronavirus 5G theory|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory|last=Hern|first=Alex| name-list-format = vanc |date=April 5, 2020|access-date=April 5, 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Videos that are conspiratorial about 5G that do not mention coronavirus would not be removed, though they might be considered \"borderline content\", removed from search recommendations and losing advertising revenue.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory /> The discredited theories had been promoted by British conspiracy theorist [[David Icke]] in videos (subsequently removed) on YouTube and Vimeo, and an interview by [[London Live]] TV network, prompting calls for action by [[Ofcom]].<ref name=bbc52198946>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-52198946  Leo Kelion, \"Coronavirus: YouTube tightens rules after David Icke 5G interview\", ''BBC News'', 7 April 2020]. Retrieved April 7, 2020</ref><ref name=extremetech308888>{{Cite web|url=https://www.extremetech.com/extreme/308888-youtube-says-it-will-remove-5g-misinformation-as-frightened-people-burn-cell-towers|title=YouTube Says It Will Remove 5G Misinformation After People Burn Cell Towers \u2013 ExtremeTech|website=extremetech.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 April 2020, [[Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na|Garda\u00ed]] were investigating fires at 5G masts in [[County Donegal]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]].<ref name=tj-5g-masts-set-on-fire-donegal>{{Cite news|title=Garda\u00ed suspect fires at 5G masts were deliberate after coal found|url=https://www.thejournal.ie/5g-masts-set-on-fire-donegal-5073466-Apr2020/|last=Maguire|first=Stephen| name-list-format = vanc |date=13 April 2020|access-date=14 April 2020|work=[[TheJournal.ie]]}}</ref> Garda\u00ed and fire services had attended the fires the previous night in an attempt to put them out.<ref name=tj-5g-masts-set-on-fire-donegal /> Although Garda\u00ed were awaiting results of tests they were treating the fires as deliberate.<ref name=tj-5g-masts-set-on-fire-donegal />\n\nThere were 20 suspected arson attacks on phone masts in the UK over the [[Easter]] 2020 weekend.<ref name=\"ie-mast-fires-surge-in-the-uk-over-easter-weekend-amid-5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theories\">{{cite news |title=Mast fires surge in the UK over Easter weekend amid 5G-coronavirus conspiracy theories |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/world/mast-fires-surge-in-the-uk-over-easter-weekend-amid-5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theories-994035.html |agency=Press Association |newspaper=[[Irish Examiner]]|date=14 April 2020}}</ref> These included an incident in [[Dagenham]] where three men were arrested on suspicion of arson, a fire in [[Huddersfield]] that affected a mast used by emergency services and a fire in a mast that provides mobile connectivity to the [[NHS Nightingale Hospital Birmingham]].<ref name=\"ie-mast-fires-surge-in-the-uk-over-easter-weekend-amid-5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theories\" />\n\n[[Ofcom]] issued guidance to [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]] following comments by [[Eamonn Holmes]] after comments made by Holmes about 5G and coronavirus on [[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]].<ref name=bbc-ofcom-rules-on-eamonn-holmes-and-david-icke-comments>{{Cite news|title=Coronavirus: Ofcom rules on Eamonn Holmes and David Icke comments|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-52358920|date=20 April 2020|access-date=20 April 2020|publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref> Ofcom said the comments were \"ambiguous\" and \"ill-judged\" and they \"risked undermining viewers' trust in advice from public authorities and scientific evidence\".<ref name=bbc-ofcom-rules-on-eamonn-holmes-and-david-icke-comments/> Ofcom also local channel [[London Live (TV channel)|London Live]] in breach of standards for an interview it had with David Icke who it said had \"\nexpressed views which had the potential to cause significant harm to viewers in London during the pandemic\".<ref name=bbc-ofcom-rules-on-eamonn-holmes-and-david-icke-comments/>\n\n=== Vegetarian immunity ===\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}<!--this seems to be more complex tahn just a claim that if you dont' eat meat you will not get infected-->\nClaims that [[vegetarian]]s are immune to coronavirus spread online in India, causing \"#NoMeat_NoCoronaVirus\" to trend on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web|access-date=March 3, 2020|title='No Meat, No Coronavirus' Makes No Sense|url=https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|website=The Wire|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303034133/https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>{{better source|date=April 2020}} Eating meat does not have an effect on COVID-19 spread, except for people [[zoonosis|near where animals are slaughtered]], said Dr. Anand Krishnan, professor at the Centre for Community Medicine of the [[All India Institute of Medical Sciences]] (AIIMS).<ref>{{cite web |title=Vegetarian food, Indian immunity won\u2019t prevent Covid-19, says Anand Krishnan |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/coronavirus-cases-cure-symptoms-precautions-aiims-6314643/ |website=The Indian Express |date=15 March 2020}}</ref> Fisheries, Dairying and Animal Husbandry Minister Giriraj Singh said that the rumour had significantly affected industry, with the price of a chicken falling to a third of pre-pandemic levels. He also described efforts to improve the hygiene of the meat supply chain.<ref>{{cite news |title=Non-vegetarian food does not cause COVID-19, says Minister |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/non-vegetarian-food-does-not-cause-covid-19-says-minister/article31003791.ece |work=The Hindu |date=6 March 2020 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\n=== Alcohol (ethanol and poisonous methanol) ===\nContrary to some reports, drinking alcohol does not protect against COVID-19, and can increase health risks<ref name=WHO_myths /> ([[Short-term effects of alcohol consumption|short term]] and [[Long-term effects of alcohol|long term]]). [[Drinking alcohol]] is [[ethanol]]; other [[alcohols]], such as [[methanol]], which causes [[methanol poisoning]], are acutely poisonous, and may be present in badly-prepared alcoholic beverages.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Beauchamp GA, Valento M | title = Toxic Alcohol Ingestion: Prompt Recognition And Management In The Emergency Department | journal = Emergency Medicine Practice | volume = 18 | issue = 9 | pages = 1\u201320 | date = September 2016 | pmid = 27538060 }}</ref>\n\nIran has reported incidents of methanol poisoning, caused by the false belief that drinking alcohol would cure or protect against coronavirus;<ref name=\"independent-methanol\" /> [[Alcohol in Iran|alcohol is banned in Iran]], and [[bootleg alcohol]] may [[Bootleg alcohol#Safety|contain methanol]].<ref name=\"slate-methanol\" /> According to Iranian media, nearly 300 people have died and over a thousand have become ill due to [[Methanol toxicity|methanol poisoning]], while [[Associated Press]] gave figures of around 480 deaths with 2,850 others affected.<ref name=\"ap-nytimes-methanol\" /> Iranian social media had circulated a story from British tabloids that a British man and others had been cured of coronavirus with [[whiskey]] and honey,<ref name=\"independent-methanol\" /><ref name=mirror21418662>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/coronavirus-first-brit-who-caught-21418662 |title=Coronavirus: British man who caught virus 'beat flu with glass of hot whisky' |work=The Mirror |date=February 3, 2020 }}</ref> which combined with the use of alcohol-based<!--not just ethanol!--> [[hand sanitizer]]s as disinfectants, led to the false belief that drinking high-proof alcohol can kill the virus.<ref name=\"independent-methanol\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/iran-coronavirus-methanol-drink-cure-deaths-fake-a9429956.html |title= Coronavirus: Hundreds dead in Iran from drinking methanol amid fake reports it cures disease |first=Bel |last=Trew| name-list-format = vanc  |work=[[The Independent]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"slate-methanol\">{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/03/hundreds-die-iran-drinking-bootleg-alcohol-methanol-coronavirus-cure-social-media.html |title= Hundreds Die in Iran From Bootleg Alcohol Being Peddled Online as Fake Coronavirus Remedy |first=Elliot |last=Hannon | name-list-format = vanc |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ap-nytimes-methanol\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/27/world/middleeast/ap-ml-virus-outbreak-iran-a-deadly-drink.html |title= In Iran, False Belief a Poison Fights Virus Kills Hundreds |work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 28, 2020|archive-date=March 28, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200328174609/https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/27/world/middleeast/ap-ml-virus-outbreak-iran-a-deadly-drink.html}}</ref>\n\nSimilar incidents have occurred in Turkey, with 30 [[Turkmens|Turkmenistan citizens]] dying from methanol poisoning related to coronavirus cure claims.<ref name=20200325cnnturk>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnnturk.com/video/turkiye/9-kisi-daha-saf-alkolden-oldu |title=9 ki\u015fi daha saf alkolden \u00f6ld\u00fc |date=March 25, 2020 |website=[[CNN T\u00fcrk]] |access-date=March 28, 2020 |language=Turkish}}</ref><ref name=hurriyet41473161>{{cite web |url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/katil-sahte-alkol-41473161 |title= Katil: Sahte alkol |date=March 20, 2020 |website=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |last=Ayd\u0131n |first=\u00c7etin | name-list-format = vanc |access-date=March 28, 2020 |language=Turkish}}</ref>\n\n=== Efficacy of hand sanitiser, \"antibacterial\" soaps ===\nClaims that [[hand sanitiser]] is merely \"antibacterial not antiviral\", and therefore not effective against the coronavirus, have spread widely on Twitter and other social networks, not only in the US but also elsewhere. While the effectiveness of sanitiser depends on the specific ingredients, most hand sanitiser sold commercially{{medical citation needed|date=April 2020}} does destroy the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/health/does-hand-sanitiser-sanitizer-kill-coronavirus-antiviral-antibacterial-viral-tweet/|title=Those Viral Posts Claiming Hand Sanitiser Doesn't Kill Coronavirus Are Wrong & Here's Why|last=Crellin|first=Zac | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 4, 2020|website=Pedestrian.TV|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305012603/https://www.pedestrian.tv/health/does-hand-sanitiser-sanitizer-kill-coronavirus-antiviral-antibacterial-viral-tweet/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> [[Hand sanitizer]] is recommended against COVID-19,<ref name=WHO_myths /> though unlike soap, it is not effective against all types of germs.<ref>{{cite web |title=Show Me the Science \u2013 When & How to Use Hand Sanitizer in Community Settings |author=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |url=https://www.cdc.gov/handwashing/show-me-the-science-hand-sanitizer.html |website=www.cdc.gov |language=en-us |date=3 March 2020}}</ref> Washing in soap and water for at least 20 seconds is recommended by the US Centers for Disease Control as the best way to clean hands in most situations. However, if soap and water are not available, a hand sanitizer that is at least 60% alcohol can be used instead, unless hands are visibly dirty or greasy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/disinfecting-your-home.html |website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |language=en-us |date=11 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=When and How to Wash Your Hands|author= Centers for Disease Control |url=https://www.cdc.gov/handwashing/when-how-handwashing.html |website=www.cdc.gov |language=en-us |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> The US CDC and the Food and Drug Administration recommend plain soap; there is no evidence that \"[[antibacterial soap]]s\" are any better, and limited evidence that they might be worse long-term.<ref>{{cite web |author=Center for Drug Evaluation and Research |title=Q&A for Consumers: Hand Sanitizers and COVID-19 |url=https://www.fda.gov/drugs/information-drug-class/qa-consumers-hand-sanitizers-and-covid-19 |website=FDA |language=en |date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Antibacterial Soap? You Can Skip It, Use Plain Soap and Water |url=https://www.fda.gov/consumers/consumer-updates/antibacterial-soap-you-can-skip-it-use-plain-soap-and-water |website=FDA |author=Office of the Commissioner |language=en |date=16 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Public use of face masks ===\nSeveral governments and institutions have initially dismissed the use of face masks by the general population, often with misleading or incomplete information about the usefulness of masks.<ref name=\"thenational.scot\">{{cite web |author= Watterson, Andrew |title=Through all the misinformation, what is the truth of wearing face masks? |url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/18385472.misinformation-truth-wearing-face-masks/ |website=The National |date=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vanityfair.com\">{{cite web |last1=Frank |first1=T. A. |title=\"I Was Looking at Them in the Wrong Way\": Mask Misinformation and the Failure of the Elites |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2020/04/mask-misinformation-and-the-failure-of-the-elites |website=Vanity Fair |date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=npr-wta>{{cite web |last1=Huo |first1=Jingnan |title=Why There Are So Many Different Guidelines For Face Masks For The Public |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/04/10/829890635/why-there-so-many-different-guidelines-for-face-masks-for-the-public |website=NPR.org |date=10 April 2020}}</ref> Zeynep Tufekci, an associate professor at the University of North Carolina, suggests that the authorities dismissed mask usage by the general public in their messaging to manage shortages of supplies rather than confronting the reality of the situation.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite web |last1=Tufekci |first1=Zeynep |title=Why Telling People They Don\u2019t Need Masks Backfired |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/opinion/coronavirus-face-masks.html |website=The New York Times |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> Some news commentators have also similarly suggested that this messaging is due to the shortages, as governments did not act quickly, and therefore goes beyond the science or was a lie.<ref name=npr-wta/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Carlson |first1=Tucker |title=Tucker Carlson: We understand there's a shortage of medical masks. Stop lying to us and tell the truth |url=https://www.foxnews.com/opinion/tucker-carlson-shortage-medical-masks-stop-lying |website=Fox News |date=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Abrupt reversals on face mask policy raise new questions |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200405-coronavirus-abrupt-reversal-on-mask-policy-in-france-and-the-us-raises-new-questions |website=France 24 |date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Walther |first1=Matthew |title=The noble lie about masks and coronavirus should never have been told |url=https://theweek.com/articles/906647/noble-lie-about-masks-coronavirus-should-never-have-been-told |website=The Week |date=4 April 2020}}</ref> Tufekci remarks that the public received contradictory pieces of information about the usage of face masks, while they had been better informed about other preventive measures such as hand washing and social distancing.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>\n\nJeremy Howard, researcher at the  University of San Francisco, stated that there is a \"senseless and unscientific push for the general public to avoid wearing masks\" and that delays for official recommendations to catch up with scientific thinking may prove to be disastrous.<ref name=hj-wapo /> He noted that there is no good reason given to avoid wearing a mask, even a home-made mask, in public, noting that the evidence does not support an anti-mask push to the public and quoting the [[Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention]] director-general [[George Fu Gao]]'s statement that \"Many people have asymptomatic or presymptomatic infections. If they are wearing face masks, it can prevent droplets that carry the virus from escaping and infecting others.\"<ref name=hj-wapo>{{cite web |last1=Howard |first1=Jeremy |title=Simple DIY masks could help flatten the curve. We should all wear them in public. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2020/03/28/masks-all-coronavirus/ |website=Washington Post |date=28 March 2020}}</ref> Lawrence Gostin, professor at the Georgetown University, mentioned that, few weeks ago, even informed members of the general public would have said that face masks do not work as a result of the [[World Health Organization]] and [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] guidelines, but that would not have been correct based upon the then-known science about potential benefits of masks for the public.<ref name=npr-wta />\n\nAndrew Watterson, professor at the University of Stirling, stated that, even though there is no evidence that non-medical masks are an effective means of respiratory protection, there is some evidence they may reduce the transmission of viruses, and that the WHO concluded that there was no evidence to recommend for or against non-medical face masks, which is different than stating that they do not work.<ref name=\"thenational.scot\" /> Harvard epidemiologist Bill Hanage remarked about masks that \"You're not wearing them to stop yourself getting infected, but to stop someone else getting infected,\" and said that the dismissive outlook of masks is a wrong way to look at it.<ref name=\"vanityfair.com\"/> Howard said that wearing masks is considered a [[prosocial behavior]] in which one protects others in one's community in certain countries, which is a stark contrast to the messaging in countries where mask wearing is discouraged, and should be part of the solution.<ref name=hj-wapo />\n\n=== Ibuprofen ===\nA tweet from French health minister [[Olivier V\u00e9ran]], a bulletin from the French health ministry, and a small speculative study in ''[[The Lancet Respiratory Medicine]]'' raised concerns about ibuprofen worsening COVID-19, which spread extensively on social media. The European Medicines Agency<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/03/18/818026613/advice-from-france-to-avoid-ibuprofen-for-covid-19-leaves-experts-baffled|title=Concerned About Taking Ibuprofen For Coronavirus Symptoms? Here's What Experts Say|website=NPR.org}}</ref> and the World Health Organization recommended COVID-19 patients keep taking ibuprofen as directed, citing lack of convincing evidence of any danger.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/health/medical/fact-finders-do-ibuprofen-and-other-common-medications-make-covid-19-symptoms-worse/ar-BB12O16s|title=Fact Finders: Do ibuprofen and other common medications make COVID-19 symptoms worse?|website=www.msn.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Helicopter spraying ===\nIn some Asian countries, it has been claimed that one should stay at home on particular days when helicopters spray disinfectant over homes for killing off COVID-19; no such spraying is taking place.<ref name=20200326afpA>{{cite news |title=False claim circulates online that certain countries in Asia are using helicopters to spray 'COVID-19 disinfectant' |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claim-circulates-online-certain-countries-asia-are-using-helicopters-spray-covid-19 |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330085147/https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claim-circulates-online-certain-countries-asia-are-using-helicopters-spray-covid-19|archive-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200320afp>{{cite news |title=Indian authorities refute 'fake' advisory which claimed disinfectant would be sprayed across India to tackle COVID-19 |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/indian-authorities-refute-fake-advisory-which-claimed-disinfectant-would-be-sprayed-across-india |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408121452/https://factcheck.afp.com/indian-authorities-refute-fake-advisory-which-claimed-disinfectant-would-be-sprayed-across-india|archive-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Mosquitos ===\nIt has been claimed that [[mosquitos]] transmit coronavirus. There is no evidence that this is true; coronavirus spreads through small droplets of saliva and snot.<ref name=WHO_myths /> Colder northern-hemisphere countries have had COVID-19 spread long before the first mosquitos of spring emerge.\n\n=== Cruise ships safety from infection ===\n[[File:COVID-19 Outbreak World Map per Capita.svg|thumb|upright=1.8|Claims by cruise-ship operators notwithstanding, there are many cases of coronaviruses in hot climates; some countries on the [[Caribbean]], the [[Mediterranean]], and the [[Persian Gulf]] are severely affected.]]\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships}}\nIn March 2020, the ''[[Miami New Times]]'' reported that managers at [[Norwegian Cruise Line]] had prepared a set of responses intended to convince wary customers to book cruises, including \"blatantly false\" claims that the coronavirus \"can only survive in cold temperatures, so the Caribbean is a fantastic choice for your next cruise\", that \"[s]cientists and medical professionals have confirmed that the warm weather of the spring will be the end of the [c]oronavirus\", and that the virus \"cannot live in the amazingly warm and tropical temperatures that your cruise will be sailing to.\"<ref name=\"nmt-cardona\">{{cite web|url=https://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/coronavirus-norwegian-cruise-line-leaked-emails-show-booking-strategy-11590056|title=Leaked Emails: Norwegian Pressures Sales Team to Mislead Potential Customers About Coronavirus|last1=Cardona|first1=Alexi C.|date=March 11, 2020|work=Miami New Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312003229/https://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/coronavirus-norwegian-cruise-line-leaked-emails-show-booking-strategy-11590056|archive-date=March 12, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFlu is seasonal (becoming less frequent in the summer) in some countries, but not in others. While it is possible that the COVID-19 coronavirus will also show some seasonality, it is not yet known.<ref name=\"newsweek-02-11-2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/could-coronavirus-really-killed-hot-weather-scientists-weigh-1486709|title=Could Coronavirus Really Be Killed by Hot Weather? Scientists Weigh In|last1=Gander|first1=Kashmira|date=February 11, 2020|magazine=Newsweek|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310145434/https://www.newsweek.com/could-coronavirus-really-killed-hot-weather-scientists-weigh-1486709|archive-date=March 10, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020|quote=Dr. Ravinder Kanda, senior lecturer in evolutionary genomics at Oxford Brookes University, U,.K., told Newsweek: \"Little is known about the seasonal dynamics of this particular virus\u2014we cannot take it for granted that the warmer weather will simply drive the virus out of existence.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"time-gunia\">{{cite news|url=https://time.com/5790880/coronavirus-warm-weather-summer/|title=Will Warmer Weather Stop the Spread of the Coronavirus? Don't Count on It, Say Experts|last1=Gunia|first1=Amy|date=February 28, 2020|magazine=Time|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309112416/https://time.com/5790880/coronavirus-warm-weather-summer/|archive-date=March 9, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020|quote=Dr. Nancy Messionnier of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, warned against assuming the number of cases will slow as the weather warms. \"I think it\u2019s premature to assume that,\" she said during a call with reporters on February 12. \"We haven\u2019t been through even a single year with this pathogen.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"fox-farber\">{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-die-out-warm-weather-trump|title=Will the coronavirus die out as the weather warms?|last1=Farber|first1=Madeline|date=February 20, 2020|publisher=Fox News Channel|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305173144/https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-die-out-warm-weather-trump|archive-date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020|quote=\"We hope that the gradual spring will help this virus recede, but our crystal ball is not very clear. The new coronavirus is a respiratory virus, and we know respiratory viruses are often seasonal, but not always. For example, influenza (flu) tends to be seasonal in the U.S., but in other parts of the world, it exists year-round. Scientists don\u2019t fully understand why even though we have been studying [the] flu for many years,\" Dr. William Schaffner, the medical director of the National Foundation for Infectious Diseases, told Fox News in an email.}}</ref>{{medical citation needed|date=April 2020}} The COVID-19 coronavirus spread along international air travel routes, including to tropical locations.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Venkatesh S, Memish ZA | title = SARS: the new challenge to international health and travel medicine | journal = Eastern Mediterranean Health Journal = La Revue De Sante De La Mediterranee Orientale = Al-Majallah Al-Sihhiyah Li-Sharq Al-Mutawassit | volume = 10 | issue = 4-5 | pages = 655\u201362 | date = 25 January 2004 | pmid = 16335659 | url = https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00885-w }}</ref> [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships|Outbreaks on cruise ships]], where an older population lives in close quarters, frequently touching surfaces which others have touched, were common.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Browne A, Ahmad SS, Beck CR, Nguyen-Van-Tam JS | title = The roles of transportation and transportation hubs in the propagation of influenza and coronaviruses: a systematic review | journal = Journal of Travel Medicine | volume = 23 | issue = 1 | pages = tav002 | date = January 2016 | pmid = 26782122 | doi = 10.1093/jtm/tav002 | url = https://academic.oup.com/jtm/article/23/1/tav002/2635586 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Mallapaty S | title = What the cruise-ship outbreaks reveal about COVID-19 | journal = Nature | volume = 580 | issue = 7801 | pages = 18 | date = April 2020 | pmid = 32218546 | doi = 10.1038/d41586-020-00885-w }}</ref>\n\nIt seems that COVID-19 can be transmitted in all climates.<ref name=WHO_myths>{{cite web |title=Myth busters |url=https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public/myth-busters |website=www.who.int |publisher=World Health Organization |language=en}}</ref> It has seriously affected many warm-climate countries. For instance, [[Dubai]], with an [[Climate of Dubai|year-round average daily high of 28.0 Celsius (82.3\u00b0F)]] and [[Dubai International Airport|the airport said to have the world's most international traffic]], has had [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Arab Emirates|thousands of cases]].\n\n=== Country-specific ===\n\n==== Australia ====\n\nA warning, claiming to be from the [[Australia Department of Health]] said that coronavirus  spreads through petrol pumps  and that everyone should wear gloves when filling up petrol in their cars.<ref name=20200325afpA>{{cite news |title=Australia's Department of Health did not issue a warning that 'using petrol pumps can spread COVID-19' |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/australias-department-health-did-not-issue-warning-using-petrol-pumps-can-spread-covid-19 |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331182810/https://factcheck.afp.com/australias-department-health-did-not-issue-warning-using-petrol-pumps-can-spread-covid-19|archive-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA Twitter post claimed that scientists from the \"Australian Medical University\" had developed a vaccine for the coronavirus. It accepted 0.1 [[Bitcoin]] as payment for a vaccination kit and promised shipping in 5\u201310 days. It was later removed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/social-media-awash-with-fake-treatments-for-coronavirus-20200326-p54e9q.html|title=Social media awash with fake treatments for coronavirus|last=Taylor|first=Andrew | name-list-format = vanc |date=2020-03-28|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407123958/https://www.smh.com.au/national/social-media-awash-with-fake-treatments-for-coronavirus-20200326-p54e9q.html|archive-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Brazil ====\nIn Brazil, a video was widely shared claiming that vinegar was more effective than hand sanitiser against the coronavirus. That was disproved, as \"there is no evidence that [[acetic acid]] is effective against the virus\" and, even if there was, \"its concentration in common household vinegar is low\".<ref name=20200304abril>{{cite web|url=https://saude.abril.com.br/blog/e-verdade-ou-fake-news/alcool-em-gel-nao-evita-infeccao-por-novo-coronavirus-e-fake/|title=\u00c1lcool em gel n\u00e3o evita infec\u00e7\u00e3o por novo coronav\u00edrus? \u00c9 fake!|last=Pinheiro|first=Chlo\u00e9 | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 4, 2020|language=pt-br|trans-title=Hand sanitiser does not prevent infection by coronavirus? Fake!|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nChloroform and ether based drug [[:pt:Cheirinho-da-lol\u00f3|''lol\u00f3'']] was said to cure the disease in messages spread in Brazil. Other so called cures in messages spreading in Brazil were avocado and mint tea, hot whiskey and honey, essential oils, vitamins C and D,<ref name=otempo2307041>{{cite web|url=https://www.otempo.com.br/cidades/e-fake-news-lolo-nao-cura-coronavirus-e-representa-risco-a-saude-1.2307041|title=\u00c9 fake news: lol\u00f3 n\u00e3o cura coronav\u00edrus e representa risco \u00e0 sa\u00fade|first=Rafaela|last=Mansur| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 6, 2020|language=pt|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307135307/https://www.otempo.com.br/cidades/e-fake-news-lolo-nao-cura-coronavirus-e-representa-risco-a-saude-1.2307041|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> fennel tea (supposedly similar to the medicine [[Tamiflu]], according to a false e-mail attributed to a hospital director) and cocaine.<ref name=20200304uol>{{cite web|url=https://noticias.uol.com.br/confere/ultimas-noticias/2020/03/04/lolo-cocaina-cha-nada-disso-mata-coronavirus-e-dicas-de-cura-sao-falsas.htm|title=Lol\u00f3, coca\u00edna, ch\u00e1: nada disso mata coronav\u00edrus, e dicas de cura s\u00e3o falsas|author=Lucas Borges Teixeira|date=March 4, 2020|language=pt|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316182615/https://noticias.uol.com.br/confere/ultimas-noticias/2020/03/04/lolo-cocaina-cha-nada-disso-mata-coronavirus-e-dicas-de-cura-sao-falsas.htm|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Canada ====\nA fake [[Costco]] [[product recall]] notice circulated on social media purporting that Kirkland-brand bath tissue had been contaminated with COVID-19 [sic] due to the item being made in China. No evidence supports that SARS-CoV 2 can survive for prolonged periods of time (like what might happen during shipping) on surfaces, and Costco has not issued such a recall.<ref name=20200313afp>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/costco-not-recalling-bath-tissue-due-novel-coronavirus-contamination|title=Costco is not recalling bath tissue due to novel coronavirus contamination|date=March 13, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/faq.html|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19)|date=February 11, 2020|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/coronavirus-can-stay-infectious-for-days-on-surfaces/2020/03/12/9b54a99e-6472-11ea-845d-e35b0234b136_story.html|title=Coronavirus can stay infectious for days on surfaces. But it's still okay to check your mail.|website=The Washington Post|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== China ====\n\nVarious national and party-held Chinese media heavily advertised an \"overnight research\" report by [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] and Shanghai Institute of Materia Medica, [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]], on how {{lang|zh-Latn|shuanghuanglian}}, an herb mixture from [[traditional Chinese medicine]] (TCM), can effectively inhibit the novel coronavirus. The report has led to a purchase craze of {{lang|zh-Latn|shuanghuanglian}}.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wee |first1=Sui-Lee |title=In Coronavirus, China Weighs Benefits of Buffalo Horn and Other Remedies |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/world/asia/coronavirus-traditional-chinese-medicine.html |work=The New York Times |date=February 5, 2020 |access-date=February 15, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200206125038/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/world/asia/coronavirus-traditional-chinese-medicine.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSince its third version, the COVID management guidelines from the [[National Health Commission]] recommends using TCM to treat the disease.<ref name=bbc51485559>{{cite news |script-title=zh:\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u6cbb\u7597\uff1a\u8bb2\u7a76\u5b9e\u8bc1\u7684\u897f\u533b\u548c\u81ea\u6211\u5b9a\u4f4d\u7684\u4e2d\u836f |url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/science-51485559 |website=BBC News |date=February 14, 2020 |language=zh-Hans |trans-title=Treating the novel coronavirus: the empirical Western medicine and the self-positioning Chinese medicine}}</ref> In Wuhan, the local authorities have pushed for a set of TCM prescriptions to be used for every case since early February.<ref name=cctv200125>{{cite web |language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u533b\u6765\u4e86\uff018\u4e2a\u9632\u6cbb\u201c\u534f\u5b9a\u65b9\u201d \u8f85\u52a9\u6cbb\u7597\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u80ba\u708e |url=http://news.cctv.com/2020/01/25/ARTIce5OB5W3sORPe90dPEJh200125.shtml |website=CCTV News |access-date=February 15, 2020 |trans-title=Here comes Chinese medicine! 8 \"agreed-on prescriptions\" help prevent and treat the new coronavirus pneumonia}}</ref><ref name=epochtimes11842894>{{cite web |language=zh-Hans |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u8981\u6c42\u6240\u6709\u60a3\u8005\u5fc5\u987b\u5403\u4e2d\u836f \u7f51\u6c11\u8d28\u7591 |url=https://www.epochtimes.com/gb/20/2/4/n11842894.htm |website=Epoch Times |access-date=February 15, 2020 |date=February 4, 2020 |trans-title=Wuhan wants all patients put on TCM; Netizens question}}</ref> One formula was promoted at the national level by mid February.<ref name=sina2164147>{{Cite news|url=http://news.sina.com.cn/o/2020-02-17/doc-iimxxstf2164147.shtml|script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u56fd\u53d1\u5e03 {{!}} \u56fd\u5bb6\u4e2d\u533b\u836f\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40\uff1a\u6e05\u80ba\u6392\u6bd2\u6c64\u5bf9\u6cbb\u7597\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u6709\u7597\u6548|work=Chinanet|publisher=Sina News|access-date=February 17, 2020|language=zh-Hans |trans-title=National Administration of Traditional Chinese Medicine: The \"lung-clearing detoxing decoction\" is effective against COVID-19}}</ref> The local field hospitals were explicitly TCM-oriented. According to state-owned media, as of March 16, 2020, 91.91% of all Hubei patients have used TCM, with the rate reaching 99% in field hospitals and 94% in bulk quarantine areas.<ref name=xinhuanet1125720410>{{cite news |script-title=zh:ICU\u5185\u5916\u7684\u4e2d\u897f\u533b\u5408\u4f5c\u2014\u2014\u4e13\u5bb6\u8c08\u4e2d\u533b\u836f\u5728\u6297\u51fb\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u4e2d\u7684\u91cd\u8981\u4f5c\u7528 |language=zh-Hans |trans-title=Co-operation between Chinese and Western medicine inside and outside of the ICU \u2013 experts talk about the vital role of TCM in the fight against COVID-19 |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/politics/2020-03/16/c_1125720410.htm |agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nClaims originating from China circulated, stating that saline solutions could kill the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/saline-solution-kills-china-coronavirus-experts-refute-online-rumour|title=Saline solution kills China coronavirus? Experts refute online rumour|date=2020-01-24|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401153714/https://factcheck.afp.com/saline-solution-kills-china-coronavirus-experts-refute-online-rumour|archive-date=2020-04-01|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Estonia ====\nOn February 27, 2020, the Estonian Minister of the Interior [[Mart Helme]] stated at a government press conference that the [[common cold]] had been renamed as the coronavirus and that in his youth nothing like that existed. He recommended wearing warm socks and mustard patches as well as spreading goose fat on one's chest as treatments for the virus. Helme also said that the virus would pass within a few days to a week just like the common cold.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.delfi.ee/news/paevauudised/eesti/video-mart-helme-kulmetushaigus-on-nuud-siis-umber-ristitud-koroonaviiruseks-mingit-hadaolukorda-eestis-pole?id=89066557date=2%20March%202020|title=VIDEO {{!}} Mart Helme: k\u00fclmetushaigus on n\u00fc\u00fcd siis \u00fcmber ristitud koroonaviiruseks. Mingit h\u00e4daolukorda Eestis pole|last=Vasli|first=Karoliina| name-list-format = vanc |date=February 27, 2020 |website=[[Delfi (web portal)|Delfi]] |url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311135111/https://www.delfi.ee/news/paevauudised/eesti/video-mart-helme-kulmetushaigus-on-nuud-siis-umber-ristitud-koroonaviiruseks-mingit-hadaolukorda-eestis-pole?id=89066557date=2%20March%202020|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Greece ====\nDespite the coronavirus outbreak, on March 9, the [[Church of Greece]] announced that the [[Holy Communion]], in which churchgoers eat pieces of bread soaked in wine from the same chalice, would continue as a practice.<ref name=\"Reuters 9 March\">{{cite news | first1=Michele |last1=Kambas |first2=George |last2=Georgiopoulos | name-list-format = vanc | title=In era of coronavirus, Greek church says Holy Communion will carry on | agency=Reuters | date=March 9, 2020 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-greece-church-idUSKBN20W2N1 | access-date=March 10, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312174830/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-greece-church-idUSKBN20W2N1 | archive-date=March 12, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Holy Synod#The Greek Holy Synod|Holy Synod]] stated that the Holy Communion \"cannot be the cause of the spread of illness\", with Metropolitan Seraphim saying that the wine was without blemish because it represented the blood and body of Christ, and that \"whoever attends Holy Communion is approaching God, who has the power to heal\".<ref name=\"Reuters 9 March\" />\n\nNew Democracy MP Elena Rapti also said that she was going and that if there was deep faith, the Communion was healing.<ref name=\"ref 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.heise.de/tp/features/Corona-Panik-nur-fuer-Unglaeubige-4678649.html|title=Corona-Panik nur f\u00fcr Ungl\u00e4ubige?|last=Aswestopoulos|first=Wassilis| name-list-format = vanc |website=heise online|language=de|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310205222/https://www.heise.de/tp/features/Corona-Panik-nur-fuer-Unglaeubige-4678649.html|archive-date=March 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Church furthermore refused to restrict Christians from taking the Holy Communion.<ref name=dw52742226>{{cite web|publisher=Deutsche Welle|title=Inside Europe: Greek Orthodox Church weighs in on coronavirus|date=March 13, 2020|url=https://www.dw.com/en/inside-europe-greek-orthodox-church-weighs-in-on-coronavirus/av-52742226|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318181239/https://www.dw.com/en/inside-europe-greek-orthodox-church-weighs-in-on-coronavirus/av-52742226|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In public statements, several clerics urged worshippers to continue taking part in the Holy Communion, justifying it by saying that Jesus never got sick,<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\">{{cite web | last=Brzozowski | first=Alexandra | last2=Michalopoulos | first2=Sarantis | name-list-format = vanc | title=Catholics take measures against coronavirus while Greek Orthodox Church 'prays' | website=euractiv.com | date=March 9, 2020 | url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/health-consumers/news/catholics-take-measures-against-coronavirus-while-greek-orthodox-church-prays/ |access-date=March 18, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318181234/https://www.euractiv.com/section/health-consumers/news/catholics-take-measures-against-coronavirus-while-greek-orthodox-church-prays/ | archive-date=March 18, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> while the Bishop of Piraeus Seraphim announced that only those who took part in masses without true faith could be affected.<ref name=\"ref 1\" /> There were furthermore reports that the CoVid 19 hotline was informing concerned believers that there was no risk of contagion at the sacrament.<ref name=\"ref 1\" />\n\nSome high-profile Greek medical doctors publicly supported the continuation of practicing Holy Communion, causing a sharp reaction by the Greek Association of Hospital Doctors.<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\" /> Eleni Giamarellou, a professor of infectious diseases at the University of Athens, announced that there was no danger, and that she was accepting communion with faith in God, so she could not become infected.<ref name=\"ref 1\" /> The Greek Association of Hospital Doctors criticized these professionals for putting their religious beliefs before science.<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\" />\n\nIt was also reported that a right-wing populist party leader of the party [[Greek Solution]], [[Kyriakos Velopoulos]], sells a hand cream via his TV shop, which supposedly would completely kill COVID-19, although it is not approved by medical authorities.<ref name=\"ref 1\" />\n\n==== India ====\n{{main|Misinformation related to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\nPolitical activist [[Chakrapani (politician)|Swami Chakrapani]] and [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|Member of the Legislative Assembly]] [[Suman Haripriya]] claimed that drinking cow urine and applying cow dung on the body can cure COVID-19.<ref name=indiatimes73952691>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|title=Coronavirus: Can cow dung and urine help cure the novel coronavirus?|website=The Times of India|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206035509/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=firstpost8111021>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|title=Novel coronavirus can be cured with gaumutra, gobar claims Assam BJP MLA Suman Haripriya|website=Firstpost|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304051130/https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> WHO's chief scientist [[Soumya Swaminathan (scientist)|Soumya Swaminathan]] criticised politicians incautiously spreading such misinformation without an evidence base.<ref name=20200303ndtv>{{cite web|url=https://swachhindia.ndtv.com/novel-coronavirus-outbreak-indias-response-and-surveillance-has-been-quite-robust-says-whos-chief-scientist-42015|title=Novel Coronavirus Outbreak: \"India's Response And Surveillance Has Been Quite Robust,\" Says WHO's Chief Scientist|publisher=NDTV|access-date=March 5, 2020|date=March 3, 2020|quote=\"Q: In a situation like this when we need scientific solution to a medical crisis, when you get in our country for examples, political leaders saying things like co''[sic]'' dung or cow urine can be beneficial in fixing something like coronavirus, do we end up taking a step back after such statements, as we need to deal with the issue in a modern scientific manner. <br />A: I completely agree, I think all the public figures including politicians need to be extra careful when it comes to making such statements, because they have such a huge following. Its really important for them to say things that are based on some scientific evidence and rationing''[sic; probably \"reasoning\" typo]''.... when it comes to the claims of cures of this infection we should be extremely careful about our statements and it should be made by the people who know what they\u2019re talking about. And has to be baked''[sic]'' by evidence\"}}</ref> Dr Shailendra Saxena of the [[Indian Virological Society]] stated that there is no evidence that cow urine has any anti-viral effect, and eating cow dung might even create a new [[zoonosis]].<ref name=BBC_tea>{{Cite news|last=team| name-list-format = vanc |first=Reality Check|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51910099|title=India's coronavirus health myths fact-checked|date=2020-03-25|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB}}</ref>{{medcn|date=April 2020}}<!--not clear if doc is a subject expert-->\n\nParliamentarian [[Ramesh Bidhuri]] of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] claimed that experts say using [[Namaste]] as a greeting prevents transmission of COVID-19, but using Arabic greetings like [[Adab (gesture)|Adab]] and [[As-salamu alaykum]] does not prevent it as they direct air into the mouth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/video/955329/coronavirus-saying-aadab-sends-infected-air-into-the-mouth-claims-bjp-leader-ramesh-bidhuri|title=Coronavirus: Saying aadab sends infected air into the mouth, claims BJP leader Ramesh Bidhuri|website=Scroll.in|access-date=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317065950/https://scroll.in/video/955329/coronavirus-saying-aadab-sends-infected-air-into-the-mouth-claims-bjp-leader-ramesh-bidhuri|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=deccanherald811390>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/experts-have-said-namaskar-not-adaab-or-assalamu-alaikum-will-help-prevent-coronavirus-says-bjp-mp-ramesh-bidhuri-811390.html|title=Experts have said namaskar, not adaab or assalamu alaikum, will help prevent coronavirus, says BJP MP Ramesh Bidhuri|website=Deccan Herald|access-date=March 15, 2020|date=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317192721/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/experts-have-said-namaskar-not-adaab-or-assalamu-alaikum-will-help-prevent-coronavirus-says-bjp-mp-ramesh-bidhuri-811390.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMisinformation that the government is spreading an \"anti-corona\" drug in the country during [[Janata curfew]], a stay-at-home curfew enforced in India, went viral on social media.<ref name=20200320hindustantimes>{{cite news |title=Is government spraying coronavirus vaccine using airplanes? No, it's fake news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/it-s-viral/is-government-spraying-coronavirus-vaccine-using-airplanes-no-it-s-fake-news/story-QmSDrfLW8SkSghT2TUf5cK.html |access-date=March 22, 2020 |work=Hindustan Times |date=March 20, 2020 }}</ref> The notion that the vibrations generated by clapping together during Janata curfew will kill the virus was debunked by the media.<ref name=thenewsminute120844>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/mohanlal-many-others-share-fake-info-clapping-may-kill-virus-pib-debunks-120844 |access-date=March 22, 2020 |work=thenewsminute.com |title=Mohanlal, many others share fake info that 'clapping may kill virus', PIB debunks}}</ref> [[Amitabh Bachchan]] was heavily criticised for one of his tweets, which claimed vibrations from clapping, blowing conch shells as part of Sunday's Janata Curfew would have reduced or destroyed coronavirus potency as it was \u2018[[Amavasya]]\u2019, the darkest day of the month.<ref>{{cite news |title=Amitabh Bachchan deletes post on 'clapping vibrations destroy virus potency' after being called out |url=https://trib.al/Bcqp2dp |work=The Hindu |date=March 23, 2020 }}</ref> Misinformation has spread that the lifetime of SARS-CoV-2 is only 12 hours and staying home for 14 hours during Janata curfew would break the chain of transmission.<ref name=indiatoday1>{{cite news |author=Ratna |title=Fact Check: Social media users give misleading twist to PM Modi's concept of 'Janta curfew' |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/fact-check/story/social-media-users-give-misleading-twist-pm-modi-janta-curfew-1658195-2020-03-21 |access-date=March 22, 2020 |work=India Today }}</ref> Another message claimed that observing Janata curfew will result in the reduction of COVID-19 cases by 40%.<ref name=indiatoday1 />\n\nIn India, fake news circulated that the [[World Health Organization]] warned against eating cabbage to prevent coronavirus infection.<ref name=20200331afp>{{cite news |title=WHO did not warn against eating cabbage during the COVID-19 pandemic |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/who-did-not-warn-against-eating-cabbage-during-covid-19-pandemic |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 31, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402070033/https://factcheck.afp.com/who-did-not-warn-against-eating-cabbage-during-covid-19-pandemic|archive-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The poisonous fruit of the [[Datura]] plant as a preventive measure for COVID-19 resulted in eleven people being hospitalized in India. They ate the fruit, following the instructions from a [[TikTok]] video that propagated misinformation regarding the prevention of COVID-19.<ref name=thenewsminute122136>{{cite news |title=11 in AP hospitalised after following TikTok poisonous 'remedy' for COVID-19 |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/11-ap-hospitalised-after-following-tiktok-poisonous-remedy-covid-19-122136 |access-date=April 9, 2020 |work=thenewsminute.com}}</ref><ref name=thehindu31282688>{{cite news |last1=Reporter |first1=Staff |title=Twelve taken ill after consuming 'coronavirus shaped' datura seeds |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/twelve-taken-ill-after-consuming-coronavirus-shaped-datura-seeds/article31282688.ece |access-date=April 9, 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=April 7, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nAn \"anti-coronavirus\" mattress was advertised as being anti-fungal, anti-allergic, dustproof and waterproof and that it could fight the coronavirus.<ref name=\":0CVP\">{{Cite news|last=team|first=Reality Check|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51910099|title=India's coronavirus health myths fact-checked|date=March 25, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nClaims of neem leaves or ''[[Azadirachta indica]]'' as remedies for COVID-19 were circulated in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1825466|title=No scientific evidence neem can cure COVID-19 infection \u2013 Experts|website=[[Bernama]]|date=26 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408122745/https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1825466|archive-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere were also claims that a 30 year-old Indian textbook lists aspirin, anti-histamines and nasal spray as treatments for COVID-19. The textbook actually talks about [[coronaviruses]] in general, as a family of viruses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/hoax-circulates-online-old-indian-textbook-lists-treatments-covid-19|title=Hoax circulates online that an old Indian textbook lists treatments for COVID-19|date=April 9, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n==== Italy ====\nThere are claims that wearing shoes at one's home is the reason behind the spread of the coronavirus in Italy.<ref name=20200409afp>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-refute-misleading-claim-wearing-shoes-indoors-main-reason-hike-covid-19-infections|title=Hoax circulates online that people wearing shoes indoors triggered hike in COVID-19 cases in Italy|date=April 9, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n==== Nigeria ====\nFollowing the first reported case of COVID-19 in Nigeria on February 28, untested cures and treatments began to spread via platforms like [[WhatsApp]].<ref name=qz1810219>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/africa/1810219/nigerias-coronavirus-case-may-spark-wave-of-fake-news-and-fears/|title=Nigeria's biggest battle with coronavirus will be beating misinformation|last=Kazeem|first=Yomi| name-list-format = vanc |website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz Africa]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162841/https://qz.com/africa/1810219/nigerias-coronavirus-case-may-spark-wave-of-fake-news-and-fears/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> There were also claims that chloroquine was used to cure over 12,000 COVID-19 patients.<ref name=20200221afp>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/anti-malaria-drug-has-proven-effective-treating-coronavirus-has-not-cured-12552-patients |title=Anti-malaria drug has proven effective in treating coronavirus but has not cured 12,552 patients &#124; AFP Fact Check |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=February 21, 2020 |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Pakistan ====\nReligious and scientific misconceptions related to the coronavirus was widespread in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news |title=Only 38% Pakistanis can recall state helpline for coronavirus: report |url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/282463-only-38-pakistanis-can-recall-state-helpline-for-coronavirus-report |access-date=13 April 2020 |work=www.geo.tv}}</ref> According to a survey research conducted by [[Ipsos]], 82% of people in Pakistan believed that performing [[wudu]]/ablution five times a day will keep them protected from contracting Coronavirus. Meanwhile 67% polled believed that jamaat (congregation prayer) cannot become a source of infection<ref name=\"thenews/1\">{{cite news |title=88pc Pakistanis aware of COVID-19 implications: poll |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/643643-88pc-pakistanis-aware-of-covid-19-implications-poll |access-date=13 April 2020 |work=www.thenews.com.pk |language=en}}</ref> and 48% people believed that shaking hands cannot infect anyone since it is [[Sunnah]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.samaa.tv/news/2020/04/myths-pakistanis-believe-wuzu-protects-you-from-covid/|title=Myths: Pakistanis believe wuzu protects you from COVID {{!}} SAMAA|publisher=Samaa TV|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Philippines ====\nPosts on social media claimed that volcanic ash from the eruption of the [[Taal Volcano]] on January 12, 2020 in the Philippines was the cause of low infection rates in the country, stating that it could kill the virus and had \"anti-viral\" and \"disinfectant qualities\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/world-health-organization-refutes-misleading-claim-volcanic-ash-can-kill-coronavirus|title=World Health Organization refutes misleading claim that volcanic ash can kill coronavirus|date=2020-03-09|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408104634/https://factcheck.afp.com/world-health-organization-refutes-misleading-claim-volcanic-ash-can-kill-coronavirus|archive-date=2020-04-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nClaims from the Philippines circulated that sap from [[Tinospora|''tinospora crispa'']] plants could serve as an antibiotic against the coronavirus when used as an eye drop. It also made the claim that the coronavirus is from the skin and crawls to the eyes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/philippine-health-experts-dismiss-misleading-online-claim-tinospora-crispa-plants-can-treat-novel|title=Philippine health experts dismiss misleading online claim that tinospora crispa plants can treat novel coronavirus|date=2020-02-05|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408105720/https://factcheck.afp.com/philippine-health-experts-dismiss-misleading-online-claim-tinospora-crispa-plants-can-treat-novel|archive-date=2020-04-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThere were also claims that an anti-viral injection was developed as a cure in the Philippines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/philippine-authorities-warn-anti-viral-injection-has-not-yet-been-approved-treating-covid-19|title=Philippine authorities warn anti-viral injection has not yet been approved for treating COVID-19|date=April 15, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n==== South Korea ====\nSouth Korean \"conservative populist\" Jun Kwang-hun told his followers that there was no risk to mass public gatherings as the virus was impossible to contract outdoors. Many of his followers are elderly.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Khatouki |first1=Christopher |title=Clandestine Cults and Cynical Politics: How South Korea Became the New Coronavirus Epicenter |url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/clandestine-cults-and-cynical-politics-how-south-korea-became-the-new-coronavirus-epicenter/ |website=thediplomat.com |publisher=The Diplomat |access-date=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313065620/https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/clandestine-cults-and-cynical-politics-how-south-korea-became-the-new-coronavirus-epicenter/ |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 17, around 79 church devotees were infected with the virus at the [[River of Grace Community Church]] after followers had salt-water sprayed into their mouths under the belief that this would protect them from the virus.<ref name=scmp3075421>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|title=Coronavirus: saltwater spray infects 46 church-goers in South Korea|date=March 16, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074249/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=upi9881584365>{{cite news|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|title=South Korea church used saltwater spray amid coronavirus outbreak|agency=United Press International|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074251/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There were also fake news of discovery of a vaccine against COVID-19.<ref name=20200325afpB>{{cite news |title=This photo shows a COVID-19 test kit developed by a South Korean company |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/photo-shows-covid-19-test-kit-developed-south-korean-company |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327125546/https://factcheck.afp.com/photo-shows-covid-19-test-kit-developed-south-korean-company|archive-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Senegal ====\nOn Facebook, a widely shared post claimed that 7 Senegalese children had died because they had received a COVID-19 vaccine. No such vaccine exists, although some are in clinical trials.<ref name=20200408afp>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/senegalese-children-did-not-die-coronavirus-vaccine-which-does-not-yet-exist|title=Senegalese children did not die from a coronavirus vaccine (which does not yet exist)|date=April 8, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n==== Sri Lanka ====\n\nA claim that [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] could protect against the coronavirus appeared on Youtube, along with a petition to legalize cannabis in Sri Lanka.<ref name=20200219afp>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/sri-lankan-health-experts-stress-there-no-evidence-cannabis-boosts-immunity-against-novel|title=Sri Lankan health experts stress there is no evidence that cannabis boosts immunity against the novel coronavirus|date=February 19, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> A fake [[Fox News]] article also claimed that [[Cannabidiol|CBD oil]] was a potential cure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/thomasbrewster/2020/03/19/coronavirus-scam-alert-beware-fake-fox-news-text-messages-promising-a-cbd-oil-cure/|title=Coronavirus Scam Alert: Beware Fake Fox News Articles Promising A CBD Oil Cure|last=Brewster|first=Thomas| name-list-format = vanc |website=Forbes|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Thailand ====\n\nClaims that Vitamin D pills could help prevent the coronavirus circulated on social media in Thailand.<ref name=20200227afp>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-say-there-no-evidence-vitamin-d-effective-preventing-novel-coronavirus-infection|title=Health experts say there is no evidence vitamin D is effective in preventing novel coronavirus infection|date=February 27, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA Thai media website stated that ''[[andrographis paniculata]]'' could boost the immune systems and relieve symptoms of coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/thai-health-experts-say-there-no-evidence-green-chiretta-herb-can-prevent-novel-coronavirus|title=Thai health experts say there is no evidence the 'green chiretta' herb can prevent the novel coronavirus|date=2020-02-06|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408110538/https://factcheck.afp.com/thai-health-experts-say-there-no-evidence-green-chiretta-herb-can-prevent-novel-coronavirus|archive-date=2020-04-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA widely shared post on Facebook claimed that Italian doctors who were infected with COVID-19 were treating patients as normal in Italy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/video-actually-shows-scene-mexican-television-series-aired-2010|title=This video actually shows a scene from a Mexican television drama|date=April 13, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n==== United States ====\nSome [[QAnon]] proponents, including Jordan Sather, and others, have promoted gargling \"[[Miracle Mineral Supplement]]\" (actually [[Chlorine dioxide]], a chemical used in some industrial applications as a bleach that may cause life-threatening reactions and even death) as a way of preventing or curing the disease. The Food and Drug Administration has warned multiple times that drinking MMS is \"dangerous\" as it may cause \"severe vomiting\" and \"acute liver failure\".<ref name=\"bleach\">{{cite news|last=Sommer|first=Will| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/qanon-conspiracy-theorists-magic-cure-for-coronavirus-is-drinking-lethal-bleach|title=QAnon-ers' Magic Cure for Coronavirus: Just Drink Bleach!|date=January 28, 2020|newspaper=[[Daily Beast]]|access-date=February 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210223501/https://www.thedailybeast.com/qanon-conspiracy-theorists-magic-cure-for-coronavirus-is-drinking-lethal-bleach|archive-date=February 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, [[televangelist]] [[Jim Bakker]] promoted a [[colloidal silver]] solution sold on his website, as a remedy for coronavirus COVID-19; [[naturopath]] Sherrill Sellman, a guest on his show, falsely stated that it \"hasn't been tested on this strain of the coronavirus, but it's been tested on other strains of the coronavirus and has been able to eliminate it within 12 hours.\"<ref name=newsweek1487069>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/televangelist-show-guest-promotes-silver-solution-cure-coronavirus-1487069|title=TELEVANGELIST SELLS $125 'SILVER SOLUTION' AS CURE FOR CORONAVIRUS|last1=Moyler|first1=Hunter|date=February 12, 2020|work=Newsweek|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215044054/https://www.newsweek.com/televangelist-show-guest-promotes-silver-solution-cure-coronavirus-1487069|archive-date=February 15, 2020|access-date=February 15, 2020}}</ref> The US Food and Drug Administration and New York Attorney General's office both issued cease-and-desist orders against Bakker, and he was sued by the state of Missouri over the sales.<ref name=npr814550474>{{cite news| first=Matthew S.| last=Schwartz | name-list-format = vanc | title=Missouri Sues Televangelist Jim Bakker For Selling Fake Coronavirus Cure| publisher=NPR| date=March 11, 2020| access-date=March 16, 2020| url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/11/814550474/missouri-sues-televangelist-jim-bakker-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-cure| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312105326/https://www.npr.org/2020/03/11/814550474/missouri-sues-televangelist-jim-bakker-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-cure| archive-date=March 12, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=20200309theguardian>{{cite news| last=Aratani| first=Lauren | name-list-format = vanc | title=New York attorney general to televangelist: stop touting product as coronavirus cure| newspaper=The Guardian| date=March 9, 2020| access-date=March 16, 2020| url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/09/jim-bakker-letitia-james-coronavirus-product-stop-promoting| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313205221/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/09/jim-bakker-letitia-james-coronavirus-product-stop-promoting| archive-date=March 13, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe New York Attorney General's office also issued a cease-and-desist order to radio host [[Alex Jones]], who was selling silver-infused toothpaste that he falsely claimed can kill the virus and had been verified by federal officials,<ref name=theverge21177998>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21177998/new-york-attorney-general-alex-jones-infowars-coronavirus-cures-prevention|title=Alex Jones ordered to stop selling fake coronavirus cures|last=Porter|first=Jon| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 13, 2020|website=The Verge|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316135410/https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21177998/new-york-attorney-general-alex-jones-infowars-coronavirus-cures-prevention|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> causing a Jones spokesman to deny the products had been sold for the purpose of treating any disease.<ref name=\"alex jones\" /> The FDA would later threaten Jones with legal action and seizure of several silver-based products if he continued to promote their use against coronavirus.<ref name=politico178629>{{cite news|last=Owermohle |first=Sarah | name-list-format = vanc | title=FDA warns Alex Jones over false coronavirus claims| date=April 9, 2020| access-date=April 9, 2020 | work=Politico| url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/09/fda-warns-alex-jones-over-false-coronavirus-claims-178629}}</ref>\n\nAnother televangelist, [[Kenneth Copeland]], claimed on Victory Channel during a programme called \"Standing Against Coronavirus\", that he can cure television viewers of {{nowrap|COVID-19}} directly from the TV studio. The viewers had to touch the television screen to receive the spiritual healing.<ref name=newsweek1492044>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/conservative-pastor-claims-he-healed-viewers-coronavirus-through-their-tv-screens-1492044|title=Conservative pastor claims he \"healed\" viewers of coronavirus through their TV screens|last=Lemon|first=Jason| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 12, 2020|website=Newsweek|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316135415/https://www.newsweek.com/conservative-pastor-claims-he-healed-viewers-coronavirus-through-their-tv-screens-1492044|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=20200313pinknews>{{cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/13/kenneth-copeland-anti-lgbt-televangelist-coronavirus-covid19-heal-virus-pandemic/|title=This anti-LGBT+ televangelist tried to heal people of the coronavirus through their televisions|date=March 13, 2020|website=PinkNews|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314150419/https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/13/kenneth-copeland-anti-lgbt-televangelist-coronavirus-covid19-heal-virus-pandemic/|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe US [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] arrested actor Keith Lawrence Middlebrook for selling a fake COVID-19 cure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/celebrity/actor-keith-middlebrook-arrested-by-fbi-for-allegedly-peddling-bogus-coronavirus-cure/ar-BB11LQpX?ocid=ientp|title=Actor Keith Middlebrook arrested by FBI for allegedly peddling bogus coronavirus cure|publisher=MSN|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe hypothesis of Stanford military historian Victor Davis Hanson, that the coronavirus was circulating in California in fall 2019, was widely shared but debunked by genetic analysis.<ref name=20200410slate>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/technology/2020/04/coronavirus-circulating-california-2019-bunk.html|title=No, You Did Not Get COVID-19 in the Fall of 2019|first=Jane C.|last=Hu | name-list-format = vanc |date=April 10, 2020|website=Slate}}</ref>\n\n==== Venezuela ====\nIn February 2020, {{ill|Mar\u00eda Alejandra D\u00edaz|es}}, a member of the [[2017 Constituent National Assembly|Venezuelan Constituent Assembly]], promoted a recipe that she claimed would cure COVID-19. The recipe consisted of ingredients often purported to prevent and cure colds, including [[Cymbopogon|lemon grass]], [[Sambucus|elder]], ginger, black pepper, lemon and honey. D\u00edaz also described the virus as a bioterrorism weapon.<ref name=20200305efectococuyo>{{cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/cocuyo-chequea/coronavirus-te-medicinal/|title=\u00bfEl coronavirus se puede curar con un t\u00e9 de plantas? #DatosCoronavirus|date=March 5, 2020|website=[[Efecto Cocuyo]]|language=Spanish|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Government ==\n=== American ===\n\nAccording to Washington Post, the US Republican government members were largely influenced by series of articles by [[Richard Epstein|Richard A. Epstein]] of the [[Hoover Institution]], who in a series of articles consistently played down the scale of the epidemics, ridiculed the \"panic\" being spread by \"progressives\", made a number of incorrect statements about the SARS-CoV-2 virus, misapplied and misconstrued Darwinian evolutionary theory in regards to the pandemics, and predicted \"about 500 deaths at the end\" of the epidemics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/q-and-a/the-contrarian-coronavirus-theory-that-informed-the-trump-administration|title=The Contrarian Coronavirus Theory That Informed the Trump Administration|last=Chotiner|first=Isaac | name-list-format = vanc |website=The New Yorker|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral members of the [[U.S. Senate]]\u2014particularly [[Richard Burr]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[North Carolina|NC]]) and [[Kelly Loeffler]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Georgia (U.S. state)|GA]])\u2014have come under [[2020 Congressional insider trading scandal|scrutiny for sales of large amounts of stocks]] before the financial markets crashed due to the outbreak, sparking accusations that they had insider knowledge from closed-door briefings, while many of them publicly downplayed the risks posed by the health crisis to the U.S. public.<ref name=hal-st>{{cite web |last1=Halper |first1=Evan |title=Stock trades by Senate Intelligence Committee chair after coronavirus briefings trigger investigation |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/story/2020-03-20/stock-trades-by-lawmakers-who-got-coronavirus-briefings |website=Los Angeles Times |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=vis-al2>{{cite web |last1=Visser |first1=Nick |title=At Least 2 GOP Senators Dumped Millions in Stock After Coronavirus Briefings |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/stock-sales-gop-senators-coronavirus_n_5e741524c5b63c3b648d8374 |website=HuffPost |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=bl-hd>{{cite web |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=How damning are Richard Burr's and Kelly Loeffler's coronavirus stock trades? Let's break it down. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/20/richard-burrs-kelly-loefflers-suspiciously-well-timed-stock-trades-during-coronavirus-examined/ |website=The Washington Post |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200320euractiv>{{cite web |last1=Lawton |first1=Sarah |title=As COVID-19 cases grew, US Senators sold off stocks and downplayed risks |url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/global-europe/news/as-covid-19-cases-grew-us-senators-sold-off-stocks-and-downplayed-risks/ |website=Euractiv |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> For instance, an audio recording from February 27 revealed that Burr ([[Senate Intelligence Committee]] chairman) gave dire warnings to a small group of well-connected constituents in private, contrasted in severity to his public statements and not known to the public, that the virus is \"much more aggressive in its transmission than anything that we have seen in recent history,\" advising against travel to Europe (13 days before official warnings, 15 days before the ban), saying that schools will be likely be closed (16 days before the closure), and suggesting that the military might be mobilized (learned three weeks later from the recording).<ref name=npr818192535>{{cite web |last1=Mak |first1=Tim |title=Weeks Before Virus Panic, Intelligence Chairman Privately Raised Alarm, Sold Stocks |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/19/818192535/burr-recording-sparks-questions-about-private-comments-on-covid-19 |publisher=NPR |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Bill de Blasio]], the mayor of New York City, gave wrong instructions during a [[photo op]] public [[3-1-1]] call.<ref name=20200326nymag>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/bill-de-blasio-had-his-worst-week-as-new-york-city-mayor.html|title=When New York Needed Him Most, Bill de Blasio Had His Worst Week As Mayor|last=Freedlander|first=David| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 26, 2020|website=Intelligencer|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Presidential ====\n{{See also|Veracity of statements by Donald Trump}}\nUS President [[Donald Trump]] and his top economic adviser [[Larry Kudlow]] have been accused of spreading misinformation about the coronavirus. On February 25, Trump said, \"I think that whole situation will start working out. We're very close to a vaccine.\"<ref name=20200225huffpost>{{cite news |title=Larry Kudlow Claims Coronavirus 'Contained' In U.S. as CDC Warns of Likely Spread |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/larry-kudlow-coronavirus-misinformation_n_5e556f11c5b64c1d5620ddb1 |work=[[HuffPost]] |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200226buzzfeednews>{{cite news |title=Trump's Biggest Supporters Think the Coronavirus Is a Deep State Plot |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/trump-supporters-coronavirus-deep-state-qanon |work=BuzzFeed |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=theverge21153035>{{cite news |title=Trump's reckless coronavirus statements put the entire US at risk |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/25/21153035/coronavirus-response-trump-vaccine-covid19-cdc-who-health-crisis |work=The Verge |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vox-mis\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/2/26/21154253/trump-ebola-tweets-coronavirus|title=Trump is facing a coronavirus threat. Let's look back at how he talked about Ebola|date=February 26, 2020|work=Vox}}</ref> At the time, [[SARS-CoV-2]] had been spreading in the United States undetected for weeks,<ref name=theatlantic607348>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/03/how-many-americans-really-have-coronavirus/607348/|title=The Official Coronavirus Numbers Are Wrong, and Everyone Knows It|first=Alexis C.|last=Madrigal| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 3, 2020|website=The Atlantic|access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307000203/https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/03/how-many-americans-really-have-coronavirus/607348/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and new vaccine development may require a minimum of a year to prove safety and efficacy to gain regulatory approval.<ref name=npr804628081>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/02/12/804628081/timetable-for-a-vaccine-against-the-new-coronavirus-maybe-this-fall|title=Timetable for a Vaccine Against the New Coronavirus? Maybe This Fall|publisher=NPR|first=Joe|last=Palc | name-list-format = vanc|date=February 12, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303155745/https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/02/12/804628081/timetable-for-a-vaccine-against-the-new-coronavirus-maybe-this-fall|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In an interview with [[Sean Hannity]] on March 4, Trump also claimed that the [[Mortality rate|death rate]] published by the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] was false, that the correct fatality rate was less than 1 percent, and said, \"Well, I think the 3.4 percent is really a false number\",<ref name=usatoday4961519002>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/05/coronavirus-trump-disputes-world-health-organization-death-rate/4961519002/|title=Coronavirus death rate is 3.4%, World Health Organization says, Trump says 'hunch' tells him that's wrong|first=David|last=Jackson| name-list-format = vanc |website=USA Today|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305211222/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/05/coronavirus-trump-disputes-world-health-organization-death-rate/4961519002/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SwqV0VHR4-E |title=Trump says he has a hunch about the coronavirus. Here are the facts \u2013 YouTube |access-date=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310145305/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SwqV0VHR4-E |archive-date=March 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=nbcnews1151006>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/just-my-hunch-trump-contradicts-health-experts-coronavirus-n1151006|title=Trump has many hunches about the coronavirus. Here's what the experts say.|publisher=NBC News|access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306162252/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/just-my-hunch-trump-contradicts-health-experts-coronavirus-n1151006|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> that the potential impact of the outbreak was exaggerated by Democrats plotting against him, and that it was safe for infected individuals to go to work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/05/trumps-latest-coronavirus-lies-have-galling-subtext/|title=Opinion {{!}} Trump's latest coronavirus lies have a galling subtext|first=Greg|last=Sargent| name-list-format = vanc |website=The Washington Post|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306034904/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/05/trumps-latest-coronavirus-lies-have-galling-subtext/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Walters|first=Joanna| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/trump-coronavirus-who-global-death-rate-false-number|title=Trump calls WHO's global death rate from coronavirus 'a false number'|date=March 5, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=March 5, 2020|last2=Aratani|first2=Lauren |issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305151056/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/trump-coronavirus-who-global-death-rate-false-number|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In a later tweet, Trump denied that he had made claims regarding infected individuals going to work, contrary to footage from the interview.<ref name=\":1\" />\n[[File:Coronavirus Press Conference USA.jpg|thumb|240px|President [[Donald Trump]] and members of the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] brief the media]]\nThe White House accused media of intentionally stoking fears of the virus to destabilize the administration.<ref name=bbc51667670>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51667670|title=Media 'using virus to topple Trump' \u2013 White House|date=February 28, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162842/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51667670|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''Stat News'' reported that \"President [[Cabinet of Donald Trump|Trump and members of his administration]] have also said that US containment of the virus is 'close to airtight' and that the virus is only as deadly as the seasonal flu. Their statements range from false to unproven, and in some cases, underestimate the challenges that public health officials must contend with in responding to the virus.\"<ref name=stat /> Around the same time that the \"airtight\" claim was made, SARS-CoV-2 was already past containment; the first case of community spread of the virus had been confirmed, and it was spreading faster than [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus]], with a [[case fatality rate]] at least seven times the rate for seasonal flu.<ref name=msnbc7944608558>{{cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow/watch/u-s-unready-to-deal-with-potential-coronavirus-spread-79446085581|title=U.S. unready to deal with potential coronavirus spread|publisher=MSNBC|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303192803/https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow/watch/u-s-unready-to-deal-with-potential-coronavirus-spread-79446085581|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/coronavirus-may-spread-faster-than-who-estimate|title=Coronavirus may spread faster than WHO estimate|website=Medical News Today|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304134154/https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/coronavirus-may-spread-faster-than-who-estimate|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=20200225statnews>{{cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/25/new-data-from-china-buttress-fears-about-high-coronavirus-fatality-rate-who-expert-says/|title=New China coronavirus data buttress fears about high fatality rate|date=February 25, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302010337/https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/25/new-data-from-china-buttress-fears-about-high-coronavirus-fatality-rate-who-expert-says/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nTrump has repeatedly compared COVID-19 to influenza, despite COVID-19 having a mortality rate estimated to be around ten times higher. On February 26, he stated: \"This is a flu. This is like a flu\". On March 9, Trump compared the 546 known U.S. cases of COVID-19 at the time and the 22 known deaths at the time to the tens of thousands of U.S. deaths from flu each year. On March 24, Trump argued that: \"We lose thousands and thousands of people a year to the flu ... But we've never closed down the country for the flu.\" On March 27, he stated: \"You can call it a flu\". On March 31, Trump changed his stance: \"It's not the flu ... It's vicious ... I knew everything. I knew it could be horrible, and I knew it could be maybe good.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Now Trump says it's wrong to compare coronavirus to regular flu |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200401-now-trump-says-it-s-wrong-to-compare-coronavirus-to-regular-flu |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |agency=[[Agence France Presse]] |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Baker |first1=Peter |title=Trump Confronts a New Reality Before an Expected Wave of Disease and Death |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/01/us/politics/coronavirus-trump.html |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 1, 2020 |archiveurl=http://archive.ph/i262n |archivedate=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Turse |first1=Nick |title=Misinformation hampered Ebola response. The same thing could happen with coronavirus |url=https://theintercept.com/2020/04/06/misinformation-coronavirus-ebola-congo/ |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |work=[[The Intercept]] |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Remarks by President Trump, Vice President Pence, and Members of the Coronavirus Task Force in a Fox News Virtual Town Hall |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-vice-president-pence-members-coronavirus-task-force-fox-news-virtual-town-hall/ |publisher=[[The White House]] |accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2, Trump told the media that he had heard that a [[COVID-19 vaccine]] would be available in \"a matter of months\", with \"a year [being] an outside number\", after Trump attended a discussion where his senior health official [[Anthony Fauci]] told him this process would take \"a year to a year and a half\" (at a minimum, Fauci later said). During that discussion, Trump repeatedly quizzed the leaders of pharmaceutical companies on the time needed to produce vaccines, stating \"I like the sound of a couple of months better\". The length of time required is due to regulatory bodies requiring multiple rounds of tests before vaccines being approved for the public's use.<ref name=20200303washingtonpost>{{cite news |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=Trump's baffling coronavirus vaccine event |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/03/trumps-baffling-coronavirus-vaccine-event/ |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, Trump blamed the [[Barack Obama administration]] for making \"a decision\" that delayed [[COVID-19 testing]] by the Trump administration. The policy in question had never been modified by the Obama administration, despite plans to do so. The policy's [[Project Bioshield Act|overall legal roots date to 2004]], before the Obama administration. Under the umbrella of [[Emergency Use Authorization]]s, the old policy stated that laboratory-developed tests \"should not be used for clinical diagnoses without FDA's approval, clearance, or authorization during an emergency declaration\". However, this policy was historically treated as a recommendation and generally unenforced, with no clear legal authority of the FDA in this area. The Trump administration continued to require laboratories to apply to the FDA for approval, but allowed the laboratories to test while the FDA processed the applications.<ref name=20200306politifact>{{cite news |last1=Greenberg |first1=Jon |title=False: Donald Trump stated on March 4, 2020 in a meeting at the White House: \"The Obama administration made a decision on testing that turned out to be very detrimental to what we're doing\" on the coronavirus. |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/mar/06/donald-trump/trump-wrongly-blames-obama-limits-coronavirus-test/ |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Politifact]] |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, Trump over-promised on the availability of COVID-19 testing in the United States, claiming that: \"Anybody that wants a test can get a test.\" Firstly, there were criteria needed to qualify for a test; recommendations were needed from doctors or health officials to approve testing. Secondly, the lack of test supplies resulted in some being denied tests even though doctors wanted to test them.<ref name=20200312khn>{{cite news |url=https://khn.org/news/donald-trumps-wrong-claim-that-anybody-can-get-tested-for-coronavirus/ |title=Donald Trump's Wrong Claim That 'Anybody' Can Get Tested For Coronavirus |last=Valverde |first=Miriam | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 12, 2020 |work=[[Kaiser Health News]] |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200320cnnA>{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |last2=Subramaniam |first2=Tara | name-list-format = vanc |title=Trump made 33 false claims about the coronavirus crisis in the first two weeks of March |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/22/politics/fact-check-trump-coronavirus-false-claims-march/index.html |access-date=March 23, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Trump falsely claimed that the drug [[chloroquine]] was approved by the [[Food and Drug Administration]] as a treatment for COVID-19. This led the FDA to state that it had not approved any drugs or therapies for COVID-19. While Trump claimed that \"we're going to be able to make that drug available almost immediately\", the leader of the FDA stated that the drug would still need to be tested in a \"large, pragmatic [[clinical trial]]\" on subjects infected with COVID-19.<ref name=20200320cnnB>{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |title=Fact check: Trump wrongly claims FDA 'approved' drug chloroquine to treat the coronavirus |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/19/politics/fact-check-chloroquine-trump-fda/index.html |access-date=March 22, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> While Trump promoted chloroquine as a potential \"game changer\", Fauci stated that positive results thus far were still based on \"anecdotal evidence\" and not \"definitive\" evidence from clinical trials.<ref name=go69716324>{{cite news |last1=Flaherty |first1=Anne |last2=Phelps |first2=Jordyn | name-list-format = vanc |title=Fauci throws cold water on Trump's declaration that malaria drug chloroquine is a 'game changer' |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fauci-throws-cold-water-trumps-declaration-malaria-drug/story?id=69716324 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[ABC News]] |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Trump also remarked that re-purposing existing drugs for COVID-19 is \"safe\" and \"not killing people\" (chloroquine is a form of treatment for malaria, while its derivative hydroxychloroquine is a form of treatment for lupus or arthritis), however most drugs may cause [[side effects]].<ref name=VerganoMarch23>{{cite news |last1=Vergano |first1=Dan |title=Chloroquine Is Being Touted As A Miracle Drug For Coronavirus, But There Are Reasons To Be Wary |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/danvergano/chloroquine-dangers-coronavirus?bfsource=relatedmanual |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Buzzfeed News]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Potentially serious side effects from chloroquine or hydroxychloroquine include [[irregular heartbeat]]s, [[tinnitus]], [[blurred vision]], [[muscle weakness]] or \"mental changes\".<ref name=VerganoMarch23 /><ref name=20200323military>{{cite news |last1=Kime |first1=Patricia |title=Drug Touted as COVID-19 Treatment Has Troubling Side Effects, Experts Say |url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2020/03/23/drug-touted-covid-19-treatment-has-troubling-side-effects-experts-say.html |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[military.com]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Overdoses of these drugs have been documented in scientific literature, including fatal overdoses.<ref name=VerganoMarch23 /> Demand for chloroquine in [[Lagos]], [[Nigeria]] sharply increased after Trump's comments, with three people overdosing by March 23.<ref name=20200323cnn>{{cite news |last1=Busari |first1=Stephanie |first2=Bukola |last2=Adebayo | name-list-format = vanc |title=Nigeria records chloroquine poisoning after Trump endorses it for coronavirus treatment |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/23/africa/chloroquine-trump-nigeria-intl/index.html|access-date=March 24, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> A married couple in their 60s living in the [[state of Arizona]] ingested a fish tank cleaner product containing chloroquine phosphate; the man died while the woman survived in critical condition. The woman stated that they intended to self-medicate against the coronavirus after hearing Trump tout the potential benefits of chloroquine during a public briefing.<ref name=nbcnews1167166>{{cite news |last1=Edwards |first1=Erika |last2=Hillyard |first2=Vaughn | name-list-format = vanc |title=Man dies after ingesting chloroquine in an attempt to prevent coronavirus |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/man-dies-after-ingesting-chloroquine-attempt-prevent-coronavirus-n1167166 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200323buzzfeednews>{{cite news |last1=Sacks |first1=Brianna |title=A Man Died After Self-Medicating with a Drug Trump Promoted As A Potential Treatment for the Coronavirus |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/briannasacks/man-died-chloroquine-phosphate-coronavirus |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Buzzfeed News]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, Trump addressed a shortage of [[ventilator]] supply in the United States, claiming that carmaker companies [[General Motors]] (GM) and [[Ford]] \"are making them right now\" when the companies were not producing ventilators at the time, and had yet to change their factories' production abilities.<ref name=20200323apnews>{{cite news |last1=Krisher |first1=Tom |last2=Yen |first2=Hope | name-list-format = vanc |title=AP FACT CHECK: Trump hype on auto industry and ventilators |url=https://apnews.com/17868870ddfc526c6c7f454d651b6d7f |access-date=March 24, 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Trump ordered General Motors to produce ventilators under the [[Defense Production Act]] on March 27. It was announced on April 8 that General Motors would deliver around 6,000 ventilators for the [[Strategic National Stockpile]] at the start of June; and around a further 24,000 by the end of August.<ref name=20200408cnbc>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/08/gm-to-build-30000-ventilators-for-us-for-489point4-million.html|publisher=CNBC|title=GM to build 30,000 ventilators for national stockpile for ,89.4&nbsp;million|date=April 8, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> At the end of March, Ford formed a partnership with [[General Electric]] to make ventilators, aiming to start production by April 20 and to deliver 50,000 ventilators by July 4.<ref name=20200330clickondetroit>{{cite news|url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/local/2020/03/30/ford-partners-with-ge-to-produce-50000-ventilators-in-100-days-amid-michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak/|date=March 30, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020|title=Ford partners with GE to produce 50,000 ventilators in 100 days amid Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak|work=Click On Detroit}}</ref><ref name=20200406cbsnews>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/ford-rawsonville-plant-michigan-ventilator-factory/|publisher=CBS|title=Ford converts Michigan auto plant into ventilator factory, promising 50,000 devices by July 4|date=April 6, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, Trump claimed that his administration \"inherited a broken test\" for COVID-19. \"That wasn't from us. That's been there a long time,\" he said. The claim was illogical because no previous administration could have prepared a test for a disease which had yet to emerge. COVID-19 emerged during Trump's presidency, at the end of 2019. The test was designed in 2020 by the Centers for Disease Control under the Trump administration.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Greenberg |first1=Jon |title=Trump blames past administrations for a flawed COVID-19 test. The test couldn't have existed earlier |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/mar/31/donald-trump/trump-blames-past-administrations-flawed-covid-19-/ |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |work=[[Politifact]] |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Trump continued to make the false claim on April 19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rupar |first1=Aaron |title=Why Trump\u2019s efforts to blame Obama for the coronavirus make absolutely no sense |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/4/20/21227903/trump-blames-obama-coronavirus |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Brazilian ===\n\n[[File:Jair Bolsonaro.jpg|thumb|Brazilian president [[Jair Bolsonaro]] repeatedly attempted to downplay the pandemic and even tried to force Brazilian states to revoke social isolation measures]]\nWhen the outbreak began in Brazil, many Brazilian states, including [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], which is the hotspot of the outbreak in Brazil, imposed harsh social isolation measures that included the shutdown of schools and non-essential business. Fearing an economic crash caused by those measures and the collapse of popular approval, the Brazilian Government, led by far-right president [[Jair Bolsonaro]], started to promote denialism of COVID-19's lethality, downplaying the disease by claiming that it was just a \"little Flu\" and accusing the media of promoting panic and hysteria.<ref name=bolsonaro />\n\nBolsonaro openly attempted to force sub-national governments (both states and municipalities) into revoking the social isolation measures by launching a campaign called \"o Brasil n\u00e3o pode parar\" (Brazil Can't stop), which received massive backlash from both the media and the public and was blocked by a court order.<ref name=bbc52080830>{{cite news|last=Watson |first=Katy | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-52080830 |title=Coronavirus: Brazil's Bolsonaro in denial and out on a limb |work=BBC News |date=March 29, 2020 |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=aljazeera2003301816>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Cowie  | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/indepth/features/deny-defy-bolsonaro-approach-coronavirus-brazil-200330181645501.html&ved=0ahUKEwiU3qnRhcboAhUXIbkGHVtIBuQQyM8BCEAwBQ&usg=AOvVaw2_LFMc5Zd8yIztZChUZKyg&ampcf=1 |title=Deny and defy: Bolsonaro's approach to the coronavirus in Brazil |publisher=Al Jazeera |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome analysts have noted that Bolsonaro's positions mimic the early positions of U.S. president [[Donald Trump]], who also tried to downplay the pandemic before adopting harsher measures.<ref name=vox21195469>{{cite web|first=Alex |last=Ward | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/30/21195469/coronavirus-usa-china-brazil-mexico-spain-italy-iran&ved=0ahUKEwiU3qnRhcboAhUXIbkGHVtIBuQQxfQBCDYwAw&usg=AOvVaw0DiuDCpjq5DJvxsE_0khld |title=Coronavirus: How Trump and other world leaders who denied the threat endangered us |date=March 30, 2020 |publisher=Vox |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Chinese ===\n==== Mishandling of crisis ====\n[[File:Xi jinping and Li keqiang.jpg|thumb|240px|[[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] general secretary [[Xi Jinping]] (left) and [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]] Premier [[Li Keqiang]]]]\n[[Whistleblower|Whistleblowing]] from various Chinese doctors, including [[Li Wenliang]] publishing data from [[Ai Fen]] on December 30, 2019, revealed that Wuhan hospital authorities were already aware that the virus was a SARS-like coronavirus and patients were already placed under quarantine.<ref>{{Citation|title=Wuhan doctor who was punished for trying to warn of coronavirus succumbs to the disease|date=February 6, 2020|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/02/06/wuhan-doctor-punished-trying-warn-coronavirus-dies-infection/|work=Hong Kong Free Press|access-date=March 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304083225/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/02/06/wuhan-doctor-punished-trying-warn-coronavirus-dies-infection/|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Wuhan Health Commission still insisted that the illness spreading in Wuhan at the time was not SARS on January 5, 2020.<ref name=20200105theguardian>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/05/mystery-illness-to-strike-chinese-city-is-not-sars-say-authorities-wuhan|title=Mystery illness in Chinese city not Sars, say authorities|website=The Guardian|date=January 5, 2020|access-date=March 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109170148/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/05/mystery-illness-to-strike-chinese-city-is-not-sars-say-authorities-wuhan|archive-date=January 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the early stages of the outbreak, the Chinese [[National Health Commission]] said that they had no \"clear evidence\" of human-to-human transmissions.<ref name=\"SCMPH2H\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3048460/paper-human-transmission-coronavirus-sets-social-media-storm|title=Paper on human transmission of coronavirus sets off social media storm in China|date=January 31, 2020|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205122018/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3048460/paper-human-transmission-coronavirus-sets-social-media-storm|archive-date=February 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On January 20, the Chinese National Health Commission announced that human-to-human transmission of the coronavirus had already occurred.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kuo |first1=Lily |title=China confirms human-to-human transmission of coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/20/coronavirus-spreads-to-beijing-as-china-confirms-new-cases |access-date=19 April 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=21 January 2020}}</ref> Later research published on January 29, 2020 indicated that among officially confirmed cases, human-to-human transmission may have started in December of the previous year, and the delay of disclosure on the results until then, rather than earlier in January, was met with criticism towards health authorities.<ref name=\"SCMPH2H\" /> [[Wang Guangfa]], one of the health officials, said that \"There was uncertainty regarding the human-to-human transmission\",<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://new.qq.com/omn/20200201/20200201A03EDU00.html|title=\u536b\u5065\u59d4\u4e13\u5bb6\u7ec4\u6210\u5458\u738b\u5e7f\u53d1\u56de\u5e94\"\u53ef\u9632\u53ef\u63a7\"\uff1a\u5e76\u65e0\u4e0d\u59a5 \u5916\u754c\u5b58\u5728\u8bef\u89e3_\u817e\u8baf\u65b0\u95fb|website=new.qq.com|access-date=March 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201074528/https://new.qq.com/omn/20200201/20200201A03EDU00.html|archive-date=February 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> but he was infected by a patient within 10 days of making the statement.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=creaders2181398>{{cite web|url=http://news.creaders.net/china/2020/01/21/2181398.html|title=\u4e0a\u592e\u89c6\u79f0\u75ab\u60c5\u53ef\u63a7 \u4e2d\u5171\u4e13\u5bb6\u81ea\u5df1\u4e2d\u62db\u88ab\u9694\u79bb \u2013 \u4e07\u7ef4\u8bfb\u8005\u7f51|website=news.creaders.net|access-date=March 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302172357/http://news.creaders.net/china/2020/01/21/2181398.html|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 27, 2020, the ''Daily Beast'' reported the editor of state-owned People's Daily tweeted an image of a [[Modular building|modular container building]] used for marketing purposes by Henan K-Home Steel Structure Co., Ltd. and not of the actual hospital. The tweet stated that the 1st building of the [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] had been completed in 16 hours. Some claim this post is part of the Chinese government's misinformation campaign to hype certain aspects of the government's response.<ref name=20200127thedailybeast>{{cite news |title=The Chinese Government Is Spreading Coronavirus Disinformation |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/coronavirus-disinformation-being-spread-by-chinese-government-to-convince-foreigners-its-doing-a-good-job |work=The Daily Beast |date=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\nThe tweet was later removed and replaced with a video of the modular container buildings being assembled at [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] again stating the first building had been completed in 16 hours.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=zlj517 |number=1221828307144134656 |date=March 22, 2020 |title=Lijian Zhao}}</ref>\n\nOn February 15, 2020, China's [[paramount leader]] and [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|Party general secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]] published an article which claimed he had been aware of the epidemic since January 7, 2020 and issued an order to contain the spread of the disease during a meeting on that day. However, a record of that same meeting released beforehand shows that there was zero mention of the epidemic throughout.<ref name=yahoo00163380>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.co.jp/byline/endohomare/20200216-00163380/|website=Yahoo! Japan News|date=February 16, 2020|title=\u7fd2\u8fd1\u5e73\u300c1\u67087\u65e5\u306b\u611f\u67d3\u5bfe\u7b56\u6307\u793a\u300d\u306f\u865a\u507d\u304b|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200216131334/https://news.yahoo.co.jp/byline/endohomare/20200216-00163380/|archive-date=February 16, 2020|url-status=live|quote=According to the issue of Chinese Communist Party Central Magazine \"[[Qiushi]]\" printed on February 15, Xi Jinping wrote, in the February 3rd meeting he claimed he had already warned about the novel coronavirus pneumonia on the January 7th meeting. However, there are no record of such in neither the February 3 meeting minute nor the January 7 meeting minute. Which indicate this is a retrospectively made excuse and Xi Jinping have made a lie.}}</ref><ref name=20200217cnn>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/17/asia/china-coronavirus-xi-jinping-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Did Xi Jinping know about the coronavirus outbreak earlier than first suggested?|date=February 17, 2020|publisher=CNN|first=James|last=Griffiths| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219052546/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/17/asia/china-coronavirus-xi-jinping-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Origin of virus ====\n\nIn response to the outbreak Chinese government officials launched a coordinated [[disinformation]] campaign seeking to spread doubt about the origin of the coronavirus and its outbreak.<ref name=RoginPost>{{cite web|first=Josh|last=Rogin| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/18/chinas-coronavirus-propaganda-campaign-is-putting-lives-risk/|title=China's coronavirus propaganda campaign is putting lives at risk|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=March 18, 2020|author-link=Josh Rogin|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319145226/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/18/chinas-coronavirus-propaganda-campaign-is-putting-lives-risk/|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat>{{cite news|first1=Ben|last1=Westcott|first2=Steven|last2=Jiang | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/13/asia/china-coronavirus-us-lijian-zhao-intl-hnk/index.html|publisher=CNN|date=March 13, 2020|title=Chinese diplomat promotes conspiracy theory that US military brought coronavirus to Wuhan|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182148/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/13/asia/china-coronavirus-us-lijian-zhao-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A review of Chinese state media and social media posts in early March 2020, conducted by the ''Washington Post'', found that anti-American conspiracy theories circulating among Chinese users \"gained steam through a mix of unexplained official statements magnified by social media, censorship and doubts stoked by state media and government officials.\"<ref name=ShihChinaEncourage>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/conspiracy-theorists-blame-the-us-for-coronavirus-china-is-happy-to-encourage-them/2020/03/05/50875458-5dc8-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|title=Conspiracy theorists blame U.S. for coronavirus. China is happy to encourage them.|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=March 5, 2020|first=Gerry|last=Shih| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318050859/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/conspiracy-theorists-blame-the-us-for-coronavirus-china-is-happy-to-encourage-them/2020/03/05/50875458-5dc8-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> U.S. Department of State officials,<ref name=AFPDangerous>{{cite news|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/03/16/us-summons-chinese-ambassador-dangerous-ridiculous-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/|title=US summons Chinese ambassador over 'dangerous and ridiculous' coronavirus conspiracy theory|agency=Agence France-Presse|date=March 16, 2020|first=Shaun|last=Tandon| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316125651/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/03/16/us-summons-chinese-ambassador-dangerous-ridiculous-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as University of Chicago political science professor [[Dali Yang]], an authority on Chinese politics, have stated that the  \"Chinese campaign\" appears intended to deflect attention away from the Chinese government's mishandling of the crisis.<ref name=ShihChinaEncourage />\n\nAt a press conference on March 12, 2020, two spokesmen for the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs ([[Zhao Lijian]] and [[Geng Shuang]]) promoted the conspiracy theory that the coronavirus had been \"bio-engineered\" by Western powers; and suggested that the U.S. government, specifically the U.S. Army, had spread the virus.<ref name=\"Taiwan News March 2020\" /><ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat /> No evidence supports these claims.<ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat /><ref name=20200318cnn>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/asia/trump-chinese-virus-tweet-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Trump and Beijing agree on the coronavirus crisis: It's someone else's fault|publisher=CNN|first=James|last=Griffiths| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 18, 2020|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318173526/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/asia/trump-chinese-virus-tweet-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Zhao also pushed these conspiracy theories on Twitter, which is [[Internet censorship in China|blocked in mainland China]] but is used as a [[public diplomacy]] tool by Chinese officials, who use the platform to promote the Chinese government and defend it against criticism.<ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat /> China's ambassador to South Africa also amplified these claims on Twitter.<ref name=RoginPost /><ref name=20200328voanews>{{Cite news|last=Yuwen|first=Cheng| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.voanews.com/usa/us-pushes-back-against-russian-chinese-iranian-coronavirus-disinformation|title=US Pushes Back Against Russian, Chinese, Iranian Coronavirus Disinformation|date=March 28, 2020|publisher=[[Voice of America]]|access-date=March 28, 2020|last2=Zhan|first2=Qiao}}</ref> Some Chinese state media had propagated the speculation that the virus may have spread in Italy before the Wuhan outbreak, after Italian doctor Giuseppe Remuzzi mentioned reports of strange pneumonia cases in November and December, he later said his words were twisted.<ref>{{cite news |title=An Italian doctor is now key to China's efforts to sow confusion over the coronavirus's origins |url=https://qz.com/1823417/italy-now-key-to-china-coronavirus-origin-propaganda-efforts/ |access-date=March 25, 2020 |work=Quartz}}</ref><ref name=scmp3076792>{{cite news |last1=Ho |first1=Matt |title=Italian professor repeats warning coronavirus may have spread outside China last year |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3076792/italian-professor-repeats-warning-coronavirus-may-have-spread |access-date=March 25, 2020 |work=South China Morning Post |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> In addition, articles from [[CounterPunch|''Counterpunch'']],<ref name=20200320counterpunch>{{Cite web|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2020/03/20/fighting-covid-19-in-cuba-china-and-the-united-states/|title=Fighting COVID 19 in Cuba, China and the United States|date=March 20, 2020|website=CounterPunch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> and ''[[Asia Times]]'',<ref name=20200317asiatimes>{{Cite web|url=https://asiatimes.com/2020/03/china-locked-in-hybrid-war-with-us/|title=China locked in hybrid war with US|last=Escobar|first=Pepe| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 17, 2020|website=Asia Times Online|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> as well as the Chinese scientist [[Zhong Nanshan]] have brought up speculations that the virus may not have originated in China.<ref name=scmp3077442>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3077442/coronavirus-pathogen-could-have-been-spreading-humans-decades|title=Coronavirus 'may have been quietly spreading long before pandemic'|date=March 29, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn \"intentional disinformation campaign\" by China was discussed among the [[Group of Seven]] (G7),<ref name=20200325reuters>{{cite news |first1=Arshad |last1=Mohammed |first2=David |last2=Brunnstrom | name-list-format = vanc |title=Pompeo says G7 discussed China's coronavirus 'disinformation' |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-heath-coronavirus-pompeo-china/pompeo-says-g7-discussed-chinas-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21C2N9 |agency=Reuters |access-date=March 31, 2020 |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> and the Chinese efforts were condemned by the U.S. Department of State,<ref name=RoginPost /> which criticized Chinese authorities for spreading \"dangerous and ridiculous\" conspiracy claims.<ref name=AFPDangerous /> The U.S. summoned China's ambassador to the United States, [[Cui Tiankai]], to issue a \"stern representation\" over the Chinese government's claims.<ref name=AFPDangerous />\n\n==== Statistics on fatalities ====\n\nOn March 27, 2020, doubts were raised about the accuracy of Chinese data relating to the official death toll of 2,535 in Wuhan as Chinese news outlet [[Caixin]] published photos of a truck unloading 2,500 boxed [[funeral urn]]s arriving from Hankou [[funeral home]] and a further 3,500 boxed funeral urns inside Jingya Hall. People collecting ashes faced large wait times because of poor communication, a lack of enough staff and the quantity of ashes that had to be searched to locate the correct box. It is alleged that this shows that many people who have died with COVID-19 symptoms but were not tested and those who have died of other health complications due to an overloaded medical system have been excluded from any official death counts.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-27/stacks-of-urns-in-wuhan-prompt-new-questions-of-virus-s-toll | title=Stacks of Urns in Wuhan Prompt New Questions of Virus's Toll | date=March 27, 2020 | access-date=March 28, 2020 | first1=Sharon | last1=Chen | first2=Dandan | last2=Li | first3=Claire| last3=Che | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref><ref name=20200327telegraph>{{cite newspaper| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/27/doubts-surface-chinese-virus-death-toll-thousands-urns-spotted/ | title=Doubts surface over Chinese virus death toll after thousands of urns spotted in Wuhan | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=March 27, 2020 | access-date=March 28, 2020 | first1=Sophia | last1=Yan | first2=Nicola| last2=Smith | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> It is unclear how many funeral urns have any relation to COVID-19 victims. Official records show that in 2019 there were around 14,000 cremations in Wuhan per quarter,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mzj.wuhan.gov.cn/tjxx/387166.jhtml | title=Wuhan Civil Affairs Bureau \u2013 Quarterly Report of Civil Affairs Statistics for the 4th Quarter of 2019 | date=March 13, 2020 | access-date=April 1, 2020 }}</ref> with 13,856 cremations reported for the 4th Quarter in Wuhan.<ref name=\"auto1\" /> Some articles<ref name=20200327japantimes>{{cite newspaper| url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/03/27/asia-pacific/science-health-asia-pacific/china-corona-toll/ | title=Stacks of urns in Wuhan prompt new questions about virus's toll | newspaper=[[Japan Times]] | date=March 27, 2020 | access-date=March 29, 2020 }}</ref> appearing in late March, however, initially reported an incorrect figure of 56,007 cremations in Wuhan for the 4th Quarter. This was based on a misunderstanding of how the Wuhan Civil Affairs data is reported, with quarterly figures representing the cumulative total of the year-to-date, rather than the quarter in question.<ref name=metabunk237642>{{cite web | url=https://www.metabunk.org/threads/wuhan-funeral-urns-as-an-indicator-of-death-rate.11175/#post-237642 | title=Wuhan Funeral Urns as an Indicator of Death Rate | date=March 31, 2020 | access-date=April 1, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n=== Cuban ===\nIn Cuba, Cuban president [[Miguel D\u00edaz Canel]] claimed on Twitter that Cuban [[Interferon alfa-2b]] was being used to treat and cure COVID-19 in China, linking to an article written by state-owned newspaper ''[[Granma (newspaper)|Granma]]''.{{ref|a}} The Chinese embassy in Cuba also made similar claims. Several Latin American news outlets<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvn-2.com/mundo/caribe/Medicamento-cubano-usado-China-coronavirus_0_5528447147.html|title=Medicamento cubano es usado en China contra el coronavirus|date=March 8, 2020|website=TVN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elperiodico-digital.com/2020/03/19/solicitan-a-la-presidente-que-considere-ingreso-de-medicina-cubana/|title=Solicitan a la presidente que considere ingreso de medicina cubana|work=El Peri\u00f3dico|date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> relayed the story, which was also relayed on social media, and the claims were eventually translated to Portuguese and French.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://factual.afp.com/el-antiviral-cubano-interferon-alfa-2b-se-usa-en-china-para-tratar-enfermos-del-nuevo-coronavirus|title=El antiviral cubano Interfer\u00f3n Alfa 2B se usa en China para tratar a enfermos del nuevo coronavirus, pero no es ni una vacuna ni una cura|date=March 18, 2020|website=AFP Factual}}</ref> In reality, the interferon was made by a Chinese company, in China, using Cuban technology, and it was under clinical trials in China as a potential cure, but it was not actively being used as such, as the claims suggested.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\n=== Iranian ===\n[[File:Ali Khamenei in 2020 Friday Prayer 06.jpg|thumb|Iran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] has suggested the U.S. government is responsible for the spread of coronavirus.]]\nIran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] said that the U.S. created \"a special version\" of the virus that is \"specifically built for Iran using the genetic data of Iranians which they have obtained through different means\".<ref name=\"independent-corona\" /><ref name=france2420200322 />\n\n=== Mexican ===\nMexico's federal government has been slow to respond to the COVID-19 pandemic as of late March 2020, with a great deal of criticism.<ref name=\"poor-coronavirus\">{{cite news |title=Mexican governor prompts outrage with claim poor are immune to coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/26/mexican-governor-miguel-barbosa-prompts-outrage-with-claim-poor-are-immune-to-covid-19 |work=The Guardian |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> President [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador]] has continued to hold rallies, be tactile with crowds, and downplay the threat of coronavirus to Mexicans' health and to the Mexican economy.<ref name=\"obrador=coronavirus\" /><ref name=20200402slate>{{cite news |title=AMLO Goes off the Rails |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/04/coronavirus-amlo-mexico-president.html |work=Slate |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Russian ===\nThe European Union watchdog group [[EUvsDisinfo]] reported that Russia was pushing what they believe was false information related to the [[SARS-CoV-2]] pandemic through \"pro-Kremlin outlets\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://euvsdisinfo.eu/the-kremlin-and-disinformation-about-coronavirus/|title=The Kremlin And Disinformation about Coronavirus|website=EUvsDisinfo|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 18, Russian presidential spokesman [[Dmitry Peskov]] denounced the findings.<ref>{{cite web |title='Russophobic': Kremlin Denies Evidence of Russian COVID-19 Disinformation Campaign |url=https://www.polygraph.info/a/kremlin-blames-russophobia-for-report-on-russian-coronavirus-disinfo/30498024.html |website=polygraph.info |access-date=March 31, 2020 |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Turkmen ===\n[[Reporters Without Borders]] reported that the [[government of Turkmenistan]] had banned the word \"coronavirus\" and that people could be arrested for wearing masks or discussing the pandemic.<ref name=\"Banned Use Of The Word\">{{cite news |title=Turkmenistan Has Banned Use of the Word 'Coronavirus' |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824611607/turkmenistan-has-banned-use-of-the-word-coronavirus |access-date=April 1, 2020 |publisher=NPR  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401090543/https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824611607/turkmenistan-has-banned-use-of-the-word-coronavirus |archive-date=April 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=npr824611607>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824611607/turkmenistan-has-banned-use-of-the-word-coronavirus |title=Turkmenistan Has Banned Use of the Word 'Coronavirus' : Coronavirus Live Updates |publisher=NPR |date=March 31, 2020 |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The organization later corrected their report, clarifying that the word itself was not banned, but maintained that it had been removed from informational brochures and that the government was restricting information about the virus and providing \"very one-sided information\".<ref name=20200331rsf>{{Cite web|url=https://rsf.org/en/news/coronavirus-limits-turkmenistan|title=Coronavirus off limits in Turkmenistan &#124; Reports Without Borders|date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> According to ''Chronicles of Turkmenistan'', state media did not begin reporting on the measures that had been taken until March 25.<ref name=20200402nytimes>{{cite news |last1=Kramer |first1=Andrew E. |title='The Fields Heal Everyone': Post-Soviet Leaders' Coronavirus Denial |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/02/world/asia/coronavirus-denial-post-soviet.html |access-date=April 2, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The BBC quoted an anonymous Turkmen citizen who stated that citizens may get into trouble for suggesting that the coronavirus is already on Turkmenistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-52186521|title=Why has this country reported no virus cases?|first=Abdujalil|last=Abdurasulov| name-list-format = vanc |date=April 7, 2020|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> The BBC article also states that the Turkmen government is working to control a possible outbreak.\n\n== Scams ==\n\nThe UN WHO has warned of criminal scams involving perpetrators who misrepresent themselves as representatives of the WHO seeking personal information from victims via email or phone.<ref name=un1058381>{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1058381 |title=UN health agency warns against coronavirus COVID-19 criminal scams |publisher=United Nations |date=February 29, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308013146/https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1058381 |archive-date=March 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also, the [[Federal Communications Commission]] has warned consumers not to click on links in suspicious emails or give out personal information in emails, text messages or phone calls claiming to be representatives from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcc.gov/covid-scams |title=COVID-19 Consumer Warnings and Safety Tips |publisher=Federal Communications Commission |date=March 31, 2020 |access-date=April 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Many financial companies, like [[Wells Fargo]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wellsfargo.com/jump/enterprise/coronavirus-response |title=COVID-19: We're here for you \u2013 Wells Fargo |publisher=Wells Fargo |access-date=April 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[LoanDepot]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://start.loandepot.com/assets/int-email/disaster/COVID19ServicingCommunicationv6.0.pdf |title=COVID-19 Information |publisher=LoanDepot |access-date=April 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> have posted similar warnings on their websites.\n\nCybersecurity firm [[Check Point]] stated there has been a large increase in [[phishing]] attacks to lure victims into unwittingly installing a computer virus under the guise of coronavirus-themed emails containing attachments. Cyber-criminals use deceptive domains such as \"cdc-gov.org\" instead of the correct \"cdc.gov\", or even [[domain spoofing|spoof the original domain]] so it resembles specific websites. Over 4,000 coronavirus-related domains have been registered.<ref name=vox21164745>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/5/21164745/coronavirus-phishing-email-scams |title=Coronavirus email scams are trying to cash in on your fear |work=vox.com |first=Sara |last=Morrison| name-list-format = vanc  |date=March 5, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306153955/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/5/21164745/coronavirus-phishing-email-scams |archive-date=March 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPolice in New Jersey, United States reported incidents of criminals knocking on people's doors and claiming to be from the CDC. They then attempt to sell products at inflated prices or otherwise scam victims under the guise of educating and protecting the public from the coronavirus.<ref name=yahoo171111975>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-sinister-people-knocking-doors-171111975.html |title=Coronavirus: Sinister people are knocking on doors claiming to be part of official disease response, police warn |work=The Independent |via=[[Yahoo! News]] |first=Andrew |last=Griffin | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 10, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311172735/https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-sinister-people-knocking-doors-171111975.html |archive-date=March 11, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nLinks that purportedly direct to the [[Johns Hopkins University]] coronavirus map, but instead direct to a false site that spreads [[malware]] have been circulating on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hackers are using coronavirus concerns to trick you, cybersecurity pros warn |date=March 15, 2020 |first=Wallace |last=Witkowski | name-list-format = vanc |work=[[MarketWatch]] |url= https://www.marketwatch.com/story/hackers-are-using-coronavirus-concerns-to-trick-you-cybersecurity-pros-warn-2020-03-12 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200407120751/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/hackers-are-using-coronavirus-concerns-to-trick-you-cybersecurity-pros-warn-2020-03-12 |archive-date=April 7, 2020 |url-status=live |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article241171546.html|title=Hackers made their own coronavirus map to spread malware, feds warn |work=The Miami Herald |date=March 13, 2020 |access-date=March 14, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200315021637/https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article241171546.html |archive-date=March 15, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Miscellaneous ==\n=== Bat soup ===\nSome media outlets, including ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and [[RT (TV network)|RT]], as well as individuals, disseminated a video showing a Chinese woman eating a bat, falsely suggesting that it was filmed in Wuhan and connecting it to the outbreak.<ref name=\"20200127foreignpolicy\">{{Cite news |first=James |last=Palmer | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-wuhan-virus/ |title=Don't Blame Bat Soup for the Wuhan Virus |date=January 27, 2020 |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |access-date=February 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203090706/https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-wuhan-virus/ |archive-date=February 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=20200130theguardianB /> However, the widely circulated video contains unrelated footage of a Chinese travel [[vlogger]], Wang Mengyun, eating bat soup in the island country of [[Palau]] in 2016.<ref name=20200127foreignpolicy /><ref name=\"20200130theguardianB\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum |title=Bat soup, dodgy cures and 'diseasology': the spread of coronavirus misinformation |first=Josh |last=Taylor | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 30, 2020 |website=The Guardian |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208030512/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200129news\">{{cite web |url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/food/food-warnings/chinese-influencer-wang-mengyun-aka-bat-soup-girl-breaks-silence/news-story/63ef0cec5b6d448d1843e2e1bcadb14d |title=Chinese influencer Wang Mengyun, aka 'Bat soup girl' breaks silence |first=Marnie |last=O'Neill | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 29, 2020 |website=news.au |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208145637/https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/food/food-warnings/chinese-influencer-wang-mengyun-aka-bat-soup-girl-breaks-silence/news-story/63ef0cec5b6d448d1843e2e1bcadb14d |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"fx-bso\">{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/food-drink/coronavirus-chinese-blogger-eats-bat-soup |title=Coronavirus: Outrage over Chinese blogger eating 'bat soup' sparks apology |last=Gaynor |first=Gerren Keith | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 28, 2020 |publisher=Fox News Channel |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204201417/https://www.foxnews.com/food-drink/coronavirus-chinese-blogger-eats-bat-soup |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Wang posted an apology on [[Microblogging in China|Weibo]],<ref name=20200129news /><ref name=fx-bso /> in which she said that she had received abuse and threats,<ref name=20200129news /> and that she had only wanted to showcase [[Palauan cuisine]].<ref name=20200129news /><ref name=fx-bso /> The spread of misinformation about bat consumption has been characterized by [[Xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|xenophobic and racist sentiment]] toward Asians.<ref name=al-watsm /><ref name=20200301washingtonpost>{{cite web |last1=Romm |first1=Tony |title=Millions of tweets peddled conspiracy theories about coronavirus in other countries, an unpublished U.S. report says |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/02/29/twitter-coronavirus-misinformation-state-department/ |website=The Washington Post |date=March 1, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309040454/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/02/29/twitter-coronavirus-misinformation-state-department/ |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=20200203latimes>{{cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Suhauna |title=Fear of coronavirus fuels racist sentiment targeting Asians |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-03/fear-panic-around-the-coronavirus-fuels-racist-sentiment |website=Los Angeles Times |date=February 3, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205072802/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-03/fear-panic-around-the-coronavirus-fuels-racist-sentiment |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In contrast, scientists suggest that the virus originated in bats and migrated into an intermediary host animal before infecting people.<ref name=al-watsm /><ref name=bru-14bc>{{cite web|first1=Hilary|last1=Brueck|access-date=March 7, 2020|title=14 bogus claims about the coronavirus, including a fake coconut-oil cure and a false link to imported packages|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/wuhan-coronavirus-myths-red-meat-bleach-antibiotics-and-sesame-oil-2020-2|website=Business Insider|date=February 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206102658/https://www.businessinsider.com/wuhan-coronavirus-myths-red-meat-bleach-antibiotics-and-sesame-oil-2020-2/|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Simpsons'' prediction ===\nClaims that ''[[The Simpsons]]'' had predicted the coronavirus pandemic in 1993, accompanied by a doctored screenshot from the show (where the text \"Corona Virus\" was layered over the original text \"Apocalypse Meow\", without blocking it from view), were later found out to be false, with the claim being widely spread on social media.<ref name=20200303afp>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/image-simpsons-was-digitally-altered-make-it-look-it-predicted-novel-coronavirus|title=An image from The Simpsons was digitally altered to make it look like it predicted the novel coronavirus|date=March 3, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref><ref name=chicagotribune20200229>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-ent-simpsons-predicts-coronavirus-20200229-q6ekedk665bzvlrgdcvdgm6eqy-story.html|title=Did 'The Simpsons' really predict the coronavirus outbreak? Twitter thinks so|first=Christi|last=Carras| name-list-format = vanc |website=Chicago Tribune}}</ref>\n\n=== Corona beer misassociation ===\nA poll was released showing that 38% of American beer-drinkers have refused to drink [[Corona (beer)|Corona-brand beer]].<ref name=prnewswire301012225>{{cite press release|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/5wpr-survey-reveals-38-of-beer-drinking-americans-wouldnt-buy-corona-now-301012225.html?mod=article_inline|title=5WPR Survey Reveals 38% of Beer-Drinking Americans Wouldn't Buy Corona Now|publisher=5W Public Relations|date=February 27, 2020|agency=PR Newswire}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/cornavirus-corona-beer-they-have-nothing-to-do-with-each-other/|first=Kate|last=Gibson| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 1, 2020|title=Survey finds 38% of beer-drinking Americans say they won't order a Corona|publisher=CBS News|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306171055/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/cornavirus-corona-beer-they-have-nothing-to-do-with-each-other/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This statistic is not considered a reliable indication of an American belief that drinking the beer causes the virus, even though assumptions have been made along this line in the media and among the public.<ref name=bar-astw /><ref name=theatlantic607240>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/about-corona-poll/607240/|title=What the Dubious Corona Poll Reveals|last=Mounk|first=Yascha| name-list-format = vanc |date=February 28, 2020|website=The Atlantic|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312073643/https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/about-corona-poll/607240/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There is no direct link between the virus and the beer brand,<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=bar-astw>{{cite web|url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/americans-say-they-wont-drink-corona-because-of-coronavirus-but-sales-are-up-5-51583610529|title=Americans Say They Won't Drink Corona Beer Because of Coronavirus. Sales Are Up 5% Anyway.|last=Root|first=Al| name-list-format = vanc |website=Barron's|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307220916/https://www.barrons.com/articles/americans-say-they-wont-drink-corona-because-of-coronavirus-but-sales-are-up-5-51583610529|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> but rather, both names draw upon the Latin ''corona'', meaning 'crown'.\n\n=== Hospital conditions ===\nU.S. hospitals have been silencing doctors and other staff, threatening to fire them if they publicly speak about inadequacies in working-conditions and lack of equipment.<ref name=bl-sil>{{cite web |last1= Carville |first1= Olivia |last2= Court |first2= Emma |last3= Brown |first3= Kristen V | name-list-format = vanc |title= Hospitals Tell Doctors They'll Be Fired If They Speak Out About Lack of Gear |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-31/hospitals-tell-doctors-they-ll-be-fired-if-they-talk-to-press |website= Bloomberg | date= March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200401businessinsider>{{cite web |last1= Collman |first1= Ashley |title= Hospitals are threatening to fire health workers who speak to the media during the coronavirus outbreak |url= https://www.businessinsider.com/coroanvirus-hospital-health-workers-speaking-to-media-threatened-lose-job-2020-4 |website= Business Insider |date= April 1, 2020}}</ref> The Washington State Nurses Association states that there is an effort by hospitals to preserve their image.<ref name=bl-sil />\n\nSome conservative figures{{Who|date=April 2020}} in the United States downplayed the scale of the pandemic, stating that it has been exaggerated{{by whom|date=April 2020}} as part of an effort to hurt President Trump. Some people pointed to empty hospital parking lots as evidence that the virus has been exaggerated. Despite the empty parking lots, many hospitals in New York City and other places experienced thousands of COVID-19-related hospitalizations.<ref name=20200401nationalobserver>{{cite web\n|url= https://www.nationalobserver.com/2020/04/01/analysis/right-wing-conspiracy-theories-go-mainstream-amid-mounting-covid-19-death-toll\n|title= Right-wing conspiracy theories go mainstream amid mounting COVID-19 death toll|first= Caroline|last= Orr| name-list-format = vanc\n|date= April 1, 2020|website= National Observer|access-date= April 2, 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n=== Return of wildlife ===\nDuring the pandemic, many false and misleading images or news reports about the environmental impact of the coronavirus pandemic were shared by [[clickbait]] journalism sources and social media.<ref name=\"natgeo\" />\n\nA viral post that originated on [[Weibo (company)|Weibo]] and spread on Twitter claimed that a pack of elephants descended on a village under quarantine in China's [[Yunnan]], got drunk on corn wine, and passed out in a tea garden.<ref name=20200319ktvb>{{cite web |url=https://www.ktvb.com/article/news/verify/verify-did-elephants-get-drunk-on-corn-wine-while-humans-were-social-distancing/277-0c48ef63-33ec-478f-be6a-4ebdeb4b0299 |title=Verify: Did elephants get drunk on corn wine while humans were social distancing? |last=Spry Jr |first=Terry | name-list-format = vanc  |publisher=KTVB |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The state-owned {{citation needed span|date=April 2020|[[China News Service]]|reason=National Geographic links to Xinhua, not China News Service}} debunked the claim that the elephants got drunk on corn wine and noted that wild elephants were a common sight in the village; the image attached to the post was originally taken at the Asian Elephant Research Center in Yunnan in December 2019.<ref name=\"natgeo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2020/03/coronavirus-pandemic-fake-animal-viral-social-media-posts/ |title=Fake animal news abounds on social media as coronavirus upends life |author=Daly, Natasha |work=National Geographic |date=March 20, 2020 |access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing reports of reduced pollution levels in Italy as a result of lockdowns, images purporting to show swans and dolphins swimming in [[Venice]] canals went viral on social media. The image of the swans was revealed to have been taken in [[Burano]], where swans are common, while footage of the dolphins was filmed at a port in [[Sardinia]] hundreds of miles away.<ref name=\"natgeo\" /> The Venice mayor's office clarified that the reported water clarity in the canals was due to the lack of sediment being kicked up by boat traffic, not due to a lack of water pollution that was initially reported.<ref name=thehill488286>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |title=As Italy quarantines over coronavirus, swans appear in Venice canals, dolphins swim up playfully |author=Srikanth, Anagha |work=The Hill |date=March 18, 2020 |access-date=March 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319215915/https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown of India]], a video clip purporting to show the extremely rare [[Malabar large-spotted civet|Malabar civet]] (a [[critically endangered]], possibly [[Extinction|extinct]] species) walking the empty streets of [[Meppayur]] went viral on social media. Experts later identified the civet in the video as actually being the much more common [[small Indian civet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/spotted-malabar-civet-coronavirus/|title=Was a Rare Malabar Civet Spotted During COVID-19 Lockdown?|website=Snopes.com|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Another viral Indian video clip showed a pod of [[humpback whale]]s allegedly returning to the [[Arabian Sea]] offshore from [[Mumbai]] following the shutdown of shipping routes; however, this video was found to have actually been taken in 2019 in the [[Java Sea]].<ref name=20200405hindustantimes>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/it-s-viral/fact-check-does-viral-video-show-whales-swimming-at-bombay-high-here-s-the-truth/story-zEOP8acFmCXrK39s4VGJaK.html|title=Fact Check: Does viral video show whales swimming at Bombay High? Here's the truth|date=April 5, 2020|website=Hindustan Times|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Lions freed on the streets ===\nA social media joke suggesting that lions had been freed to keep people off the streets in Moscow was passed around as if it were true.<ref name=bbc52118949>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/stories-52118949/coronavirus-how-can-you-stop-the-spread-of-misinformation|title=Coronavirus: How can you stop an 'infodemic'?|website=BBC News|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== UK\u00a320 banknote ===\nA tweet started an internet meme that [[Bank of England]] [[Bank of England \u00a320 note|\u00a320 banknotes]] contained a picture of a 5G mast and the SARSCoV-2 virus.  Facebook and YouTube removed items pushing this story, and fact checking organisations established that the picture is of [[Margate Lighthouse]] and the \"virus\" is the staircase at the [[Tate Britain]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fullfact.org/online/5g-coronavirus-20-note/|title=\u00a320 notes don't have a secret message about 5G and coronavirus|first=Grace|last=Rahman| name-list-format = vanc |website=Full Fact}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/banknotes/polymer-20-pound-note The new \u00a320 note] The Bank of England</ref><ref>[https://turnercontemporary.org/support-us/what-can-i-do-with-my-old-20-note/ New \u00a320 note to feature Margate's Turner Contemporary] Turner Contemporary</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Criticism of response to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n* [[Buck passing]]\n* [[List of conspiracy theories]]\n* [[SARS conspiracy theory]]\n\n== Notes ==\n\n: 1.{{note|a}}''Granma'' is owned by the ruling political party in Cuba, the Communist Party of Cuba.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public/myth-busters World Health Organization: Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) advice for the public: Myth busters]\n* [https://www.politifact.com/coronavirus/ Coronavirus] at [[Politifact]]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Conspiracy theories}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Misinformation related to the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Alternative medicine]]\n[[Category:Biological warfare]]\n[[Category:China\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Communication of falsehoods]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories in China]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories in the United States]]\n[[Category:Fake news]]\n[[Category:Medical-related conspiracy theories]]\n[[Category:Misinformation]]\n[[Category:Pseudohistory]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscience]]\n[[Category:Disinformation operations]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{More medical citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|False information about coronavirus}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\n'''Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic''' consists of [[conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] and [[disinformation]] that emerged regarding the origin, scale, prevention and treatment surrounding the [[COVID-19]] disease and the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ensuing pandemic]] related to the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]] virus.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |title=China coronavirus: Misinformation spreads online about origin and scale |date=January 30, 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200204163412/https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=GUAR>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum | title=Bat soup, dodgy cures and 'diseasology': the spread of coronavirus misinformation | date=January 31, 2020 | access-date=February 3, 2020 | first=Josh | last=Taylor | name-list-format = vanc | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202141231/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum | archive-date=February 2, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Lowy>{{Cite news|first=Natasha|last=Kassam| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.lowyinstitute.org/the-interpreter/disinformation-and-coronavirus|work=The Interpreter|publisher=Lowy Institute|title=Disinformation and coronavirus|date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=RunningList>{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/janelytvynenko/coronavirus-disinformation-spread |title=Here's A Running List Of Disinformation Spreading About The Coronavirus |website=Buzzfeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206212717/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/janelytvynenko/coronavirus-disinformation-spread |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Disinformation and [[misinformation]] can be spread through social media,<ref name=Lowy /><ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/social-media-posts-spread-bogus-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/ |title=Social Media Posts Spread Bogus Coronavirus Conspiracy Theory |first=Jessica |last=McDonald | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 24, 2020 |work=Factcheck.org |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200206102802/https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/social-media-posts-spread-bogus-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/ |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> text messages,<ref name=\"FTTextMsg\">{{cite web|author=Hannah Murphy, Mark Di Stefano & Katrina Manson|url=https://www.ft.com/content/34b6df5a-ea4a-471f-8ac9-606580480049|title=Huge text message campaigns spread coronavirus fake news|date=March 20, 2020|work=Financial Times}}</ref><ref name=FriendsAunt>{{cite news|first=Mihir|last=Zaveri| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-text-messages-national-quarantine.html|title=Be Wary of Those Texts From a Friend of a Friend's Aunt|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> [[mass media]],<ref name=\"fp_0414conspiracy\">{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/04/14/as-the-coronavirus-spreads-conspiracy-theories-are-going-viral-too/|title=As the Coronavirus Spreads, Conspiracy Theories Are Going Viral Too|website=Foreign Policy|date= 14 April 2020|first=Elise |last=Thomas | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> as well as the [[state media]] of countries such as China, [[Iran]] and [[Turkmenistan]],<ref name=Lowy /><ref name=\"presstv\">{{cite journal|last=Frantzman|first=Seth| name-list-format = vanc |title=Iran's regime pushes antisemitic conspiracies about coronavirus|journal=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=March 8, 2020|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iran-News/Irans-regime-pushes-antisemitic-conspiracies-about-coronavirus-620212|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310213820/https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iran-News/Irans-regime-pushes-antisemitic-conspiracies-about-coronavirus-620212|archive-date=March 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/04/did-turkmenistan-really-ban-the-word-coronavirus/|title=Did Turkmenistan Really Ban the Word 'Coronavirus'?|last=Putz|first=Catherine| name-list-format = vanc |website=thediplomat.com|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> and they may be propagated by celebrities, politicians, or other prominent public figures.<ref name=20200408theguardian>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2020/apr/08/influencers-being-key-distributors-of-coronavirus-fake-news |title= Influencers among 'key distributors' of coronavirus misinformation |first=Jim |last=Waterson | name-list-format = vanc |date= April 8, 2020 |work=The Guardian }}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://rsf.org/en/news/coronavirus-limits-turkmenistan|title=Coronavirus off limits in Turkmenistan {{!}} Reporters without borders|date=March 31, 2020|publisher=Reports Without Borders|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><section begin=\"Intro\" /> Medical misinformation about ways to prevent, treat, and self-diagnose coronavirus disease has circulated on social media.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Robert H. |last1=Shmerling |title=Be careful where you get your news about coronavirus |url=https://www.health.harvard.edu/blog/be-careful-where-you-get-your-news-about-coronavirus-2020020118801 |website=Harvard Health Blog |access-date=March 25, 2020 |date=February 1, 2020}}</ref> Some false claims may be commercial scams offering at-home tests, supposed preventives, and \"miracle\" cures.<ref name=\"Beware\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/31/coronavirus-covid-19-fake-tests-cures|title=Covid-19: beware online tests and cures, experts say|last=Knight|first=Victoria| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 31, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"alex jones\">{{cite news|last1=Ferr\u00e9-Sadurn\u00ed|first1=Luis|last2=McKinley|first2=Jesse | name-list-format = vanc |title=Alex Jones Is Told to Stop Selling Sham Anti-Coronavirus Toothpaste|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=March 16, 2020|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314143913/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[World Health Organization]] has declared an \"infodemic\" of incorrect information about the virus, which poses risks to global health.<ref name=Lowy /><section end=Intro/>\n\nSome misinformation and disinformation claimed the virus was a [[bio-weapon]] with a patented [[vaccine]], a [[population control]] scheme, or the result of a [[Espionage|spy operation]].<ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\" /><ref name=RunningList /><ref name=\"vox_misinfo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |title=How tech companies are scrambling to deal with coronavirus hoaxes |last=Ghaffary |first=Shirin |last2=Heilweil |first2=Rebecca | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200208004124/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Some of these misinformation and conspiracy theories may have state involvement.<ref name=\"presstv\" /><ref name=\"20200312theguardian\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/12/conspiracy-theory-that-coronavirus-originated-in-us-gaining-traction-in-china |title='American coronavirus': China pushes propaganda casting doubt on virus origin |first=Lily |last=Kuo |date=March 13, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp3051939\">{{cite news |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/russia-central-asia/article/3051939/coronavirus-russia-pushing-fake-news-about-us-using |title=Coronavirus: Russia pushing fake news about US using outbreak to 'wage economic war' on China, officials say |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |via=[[South China Morning Post]] |date=February 23, 2020 |access-date=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223223639/https://www.scmp.com/news/world/russia-central-asia/article/3051939/coronavirus-russia-pushing-fake-news-about-us-using |archive-date=February 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some world leaders have also downplayed the threat of the virus and disseminated misinformation.<ref name=bolsonaro>{{cite web|first=Uri |last=Friedman | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2020/03/bolsonaro-coronavirus-denial-brazil-trump/608926/ |title=Bolsonaro Leads the Coronavirus-Denial Movement |work=The Atlantic |date=March 27, 2020 |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"stat\">{{cite web |last1=Thielking |first1=Megan |title=Experts warn Trump's misinformation about coronavirus is dangerous |url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/26/trump-mixed-messages-on-coronavirus/ |website=STAT |access-date=April 5, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"obrador=coronavirus\">{{cite news |title=Mexico: Mexicans Need Accurate COVID-19 Information |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2020/03/26/mexico-mexicans-need-accurate-covid-19-information |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><section end=Intro/>\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n== Types and origin ==\nAccording to a study published by the [[Reuters Institute for the Study of Journalism]], the most misinformation related to COVID-19 involves \"various forms of reconfiguration, where existing and often true information is spun, twisted, recontextualised, or reworked.\" While less misinformation \"was completely fabricated.\" The study found no [[Deepfake|deep fakes]] in the studied sample. The study also found that \"top-down misinformation from politicians, celebrities, and other prominent public figures,\" while accounting for a minority of the samples, captured a majority of the social media engagement. According to their classification, the largest category of misinformation (39%) includes \"misleading or false claims about the actions or policies of public authorities, including government and international bodies like the WHO or the UN.\"<ref name=\"reuters-institute\">{{cite web|first1=J. Scott|last1=Brennen|first2=Felix|last2=Simon|first3=Philip N.|last3=Howard|first4=Rasmus Kleis|last4=Nielsen|url=https://reutersinstitute.politics.ox.ac.uk/types-sources-and-claims-covid-19-misinformation|title=Types, sources, and claims of COVID-19 misinformation |work=Reuters Institute|date=7 April 2020|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Combative efforts ==\n\nOn February 2, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) described a \"massive infodemic\", citing an over-abundance of reported information, accurate and false, about the virus that \"makes it hard for people to find trustworthy sources and reliable guidance when they need it.\" The WHO stated that the high demand for timely and trustworthy information has incentivised the creation of a direct WHO 24/7 myth-busting hotline where its communication and social media teams have been monitoring and responding to misinformation through its website and social media pages.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite report | vauthors=((World Health Organization)) | year=2020 | title=Novel Coronavirus (&lrm;2019-nCoV)&lrm;: situation report, 13 | publisher=[[World Health Organization]] | hdl=10665/330778 | hdl-access=free }}</ref><ref name=un1056672>{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1056672 |title=Coronavirus: UN health agency moves fast to tackle 'infodemic'; Guterres warns against stigmatization |date=February 4, 2020 |website=UN News |access-date=February 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205080207/https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1056672 |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{cite web |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/says-theres-no-effective-coronavirus-200035999.html |title=WHO Says There's No Effective Coronavirus Treatment Yet |publisher=Yahoo! Finance |access-date=February 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206043018/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/says-theres-no-effective-coronavirus-200035999.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The WHO specifically debunked several claims as false, including the claim that a person can tell if they have the virus or not simply by holding their breath; the claim that drinking large amounts of water will protect against the virus; and the claim that gargling salt water prevents infection.<ref name=20200317cnn>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-myths-debunking-holding-breath-10-seconds-trnd/index.html|title=One dangerous coronavirus 'self-check test' is circulating on social media. Here's why you should avoid it.|last=Elassar|first=Alaa| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 17, 2020|publisher=CNN|access-date=March 17, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317050148/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-myths-debunking-holding-breath-10-seconds-trnd/index.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFacebook, Twitter and Google said they were working with WHO to address \"misinformation\".<ref name=20200206nytimes>{{Cite news |last=Richtel |first=Matt | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/06/health/coronavirus-misinformation-social-media.html |title=W.H.O. Fights a Pandemic Besides Coronavirus: an 'Infodemic' |date=February 6, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 7, 2020 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206224226/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/06/health/coronavirus-misinformation-social-media.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a blogpost, Facebook stated they would remove content flagged by global health organizations and local authorities that violate its content policy on misinformation leading to \"physical harm\".<ref name=20200201reuters>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-facebook-idUSKBN1ZV388 |title=As coronavirus misinformation spreads on social media, Facebook removes posts |date=February 1, 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206071606/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-facebook-idUSKBN1ZV388 |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Facebook is also giving free advertising to WHO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inverse.com/innovation/facebook-is-giving-the-world-health-organization-free-ads-to-combat-the-coronavirus|title=Facebook announces how it plans to help fight the coronavirus|website=Inverse|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306204741/https://www.inverse.com/innovation/facebook-is-giving-the-world-health-organization-free-ads-to-combat-the-coronavirus|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of February, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] removed over one million products claimed to cure or protect against coronavirus, and removed tens of thousands of listings for health products whose prices were \"significantly higher than recent prices offered on or off Amazon\", although numerous items were \"still being sold at unusually high prices\" as of February 28.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-51675183|title = Amazon culls one million fake coronavirus products|work = BBC News|date = February 28, 2020|access-date = March 1, 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200301082532/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-51675183|archive-date = March 1, 2020|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nMillions of instances of COVID-19 misinformation have occurred across a number of online platforms.<ref>{{cite arXiv |title= The COVID-19 Social Media Infodemic |first1= Matteo |last1= Cinelli |first2= Walter |last2= Quattrociocchi |first3= Alessandro |last3= Galeazzi |first4=Carlo Michele |last4=Valensise |first5= Emanuele |last5= Brugnoli |first6= Ana Lucia |last6=Schmidt |first7= Paola |last7= Zola |first8=Fabiana |last8=Zollo |first9=Antonio |last9=Scala | name-list-format = vanc |date= March 10, 2020 |class= cs.SI |eprint= 2003.05004 }}</ref> Other [[fake news]] researchers noted certain rumors started in China; many of them later spread to Korea and the United States, prompting several universities in Korea to start the multilingual Facts Before Rumors campaign to separate common claims seen online.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000739/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18241 |title= 'Fact before rumors' campaign just began by the IBS Data Science Group |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 26, 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |access-date= March 31, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000971/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18234&pageIndex=1&searchCnd=&searchWrd= |title= \ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4\uc640 \uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9 |first=Cha|last=Meeyoung| name-list-format = vanc |author-link=Cha Meeyoung |date= March 24, 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://dongascience.donga.com/news.php?idx=35457 |title=\"\ub3d9\ub0a8\uc544\u00b7\ub0a8\ubbf8 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \uac00\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4 \ub9c9\uace0 '\uc9c4\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4' \uc804\ud558\uc790\" \uad6d\ub0b4 \uacfc\ud559\uc790 \ud314 \uac77\uc5b4 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 25, 2020 |website= Donga Science |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.hankyung.com/opinion/article/2020032509531 |title= [\ucc28\ubbf8\uc601\uc758 \ub370\uc774\ud130\ub85c \ubcf8 \uc138\uc0c1] '\uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9'\uc758 \uc2dc\ub300 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 25, 2020 |website= \ud55c\uad6d\uacbd\uc81c |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref>\n\nThe media has praised Wikipedia's coverage of COVID-19 and its combating the inclusion of misinformation through efforts led by the [[meta:Wiki Project Med Foundation|Wiki Project Med Foundation]] and the English-language Wikipedia's [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Medicine|WikiProject Medicine]], among other groups.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.wired.com/story/how-wikipedia-prevents-spread-coronavirus-misinformation/ | title = How Wikipedia Prevents the Spread of Coronavirus Misinformation | first=  Noam | last = Cohem | date = March 15, 2020 | access-date = April 11, 2020 | work = [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://slate.com/technology/2020/03/coronavirus-wikipedia-policies.html | title = The Coronavirus Is Stress-Testing Wikipedia's Policies | first= Stephan | last= Harrison | name-list-format = vanc | date = March 19, 2020 | access-date = April 11, 2020 | work = [[Salon (magazine)|Salon]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/.premium.MAGAZINE-why-wikipedia-is-immune-to-coronavirus-1.8751147 | title = Why Wikipedia Is Immune to Coronavirus | first = Omer | last = Benjakob | date = April 8, 2020 | access-date = April 11, 2020 | work = [[Haaretz]] }}</ref>\n\nMany local newspapers have been severely affected by losses in advertising revenues from coronavirus; journalists have been laid off, and some have closed altogether.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hsu |first1=Tiffany |last2=Tracy |first2=Marc | name-list-format = vanc |title=Local News Outlets Dealt a Crippling Blow by This Biggest of Stories |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/business/media/coronavirus-local-news.html |work=The New York Times |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMany newspapers with [[paywall]]s lowered them for some or all of their coronavirus coverage.<ref name=\"Paywalls\">{{cite news |last1=Jerde |date=March 12, 2020 |first1=Sara |title=Major Publishers Take Down Paywalls for Coronavirus Coverage |url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/major-publishers-take-down-paywalls-for-coronavirus-coverage/ |access-date=March 25, 2020 |work=Adweek}}</ref><ref name=\"newspaywalls\">{{cite web |last1=Kottke |first1=Jason |title=Media Paywalls Dropped for COVID-19 Crisis Coverage |url=https://kottke.org/20/03/media-paywalls-dropped-for-covid-19-crisis-coverage |website=kottke.org |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> Many scientific publishers made scientific papers related to the outbreak [[open access]].<ref name=\"AutoDW-255\">{{cite press release |url=https://wellcome.ac.uk/press-release/sharing-research-data-and-findings-relevant-novel-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak |title=Sharing research data and findings relevant to the novel coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak |work=wellcome.ac.uk |date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 13, 2020}}</ref> Some scientists chose to share their results quickly on [[preprint]] servers such as [[bioRxiv]].<ref name=\"AutoDW-256\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-research-preprint-servers/ |title=Coronavirus Research Is Moving at Top Speed \u2013 With a Catch |work=Wired |last1=Rogers |first1=Adam |date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 13, 2020 |issn=1059-1028}}</ref>\n\n== Conspiracy theories ==\n\n[[Conspiracy theory|Conspiracy theories]] have appeared in both social media and mainstream news outlets, and are heavily influenced by geopolitics.<ref name=al-watsm /> ''[[Al Jazeera English|Al Jazeera]]'' reported that mainstream outlets which had spread conspiracy theories included domestic and overseas Russian state media ([[Channel One Russia]] and [[RT (TV network)|RT]] ), the British tabloid the ''[[Daily Mail]]'', and conservative media in the United States.<ref name=al-watsm>{{cite web|last=Sharma|first=Gouri | name-list-format = vanc | date=March 5, 2020 | url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/conspiracy-theories-coronavirus-200303170729373.html|title=Why are there so many conspiracy theories around the coronavirus?|publisher=Al Jazeera|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Bioengineered virus ===\nIt has been repeatedly claimed that the virus was deliberately created by humans.\n\n''[[Nature Medicine]]'' published an article arguing against the conspiracy theory that the virus was created artificially. The high-affinity binding of the virus' [[peplomer]]s to human [[angiotensin-converting enzyme 2]] (ACE2) was shown to be \"most likely the result of [[natural selection]] on a human or human-like ACE2 that permits another optimal binding solution to arise\".<ref name=\"NM\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Andersen KG, Rambaut A, Lipkin WI, Holmes EC, Garry RF | title = The proximal origin of SARS-CoV-2 | journal = Nature Medicine | volume = 26 | issue = 4 | pages = 450\u2013452 | date = April 2020 | pmid = 32284615 | doi = 10.1038/s41591-020-0820-9 | url = https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-020-0820-9 | doi-access = free }}</ref> In case of [[genetic manipulation]], one of the several [[Reverse genetics|reverse-genetic]] systems for [[betacoronavirus]]es would probably have been used, while the genetic data irrefutably showed that the virus is not derived from a previously used virus template.<ref name=\"NM\" /> The overall molecular structure of the virus was found to be distinct from the known coronaviruses and most closely resembles that of viruses of [[bat]]s and [[pangolins]] that were little studied and never known to harm humans.<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.livescience.com/coronavirus-not-human-made-in-lab.html |title=The coronavirus did not escape from a lab. Here's how we know|first=Jeanna|last=Bryner | name-list-format = vanc |publisher=[[Live Science]]| access-date =March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' quoted virus expert and global co-lead coronavirus investigator Trevor Bedford: \"There is no evidence whatsoever of genetic engineering that we can find\", and \"The evidence we have is that the mutations [in the virus] are completely consistent with natural evolution\".<ref name=\"FT5\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.ft.com/content/a6392ee6-4ec6-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5 | title=Coronavirus was not genetically engineered in a Wuhan lab, says expert | first=Clive | last=Cookson| name-list-format = vanc  | date=February 14, 2020 | access-date=February 14, 2020 | newspaper=[[Financial Times]] | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214112755/https://www.ft.com/content/a6392ee6-4ec6-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5 | archive-date=February 14, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> Bedford further explained, \"The most likely scenario, based on genetic analysis, was that the virus was transmitted by a bat to another mammal between 20\u201370 years ago. This intermediary animal\u2014not yet identified\u2014passed it on to its first human host in the city of Wuhan in late November or early December 2019\".<ref name=\"FT5\" />\n\nOn 19 February 2020, ''[[The Lancet]]'' published a letter of a group of scientists condemning \"conspiracy theories suggesting that COVID-19 does not have a natural origin.\"<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Charles|last1=Calisher |first2=Dennis|last2=Carroll |first3=Rita|last3=Colwell |first4=Ronald B|last4=Corley |first5=Peter|last5=Daszak |first6=Christian|last6=Drosten |first7=Luis|last7=Enjuanes |first8=Jeremy|last8=Farrar |first9=Hume|last9=Field |first10=Josie|last10=Golding |first11=Alexander|last11=Gorbalenya |first12=Bart|last12=Haagmans |first13=James M|last13=Hughes |first14=William B|last14=Karesh |first15=Gerald T|last15=Keusch |first16=Sai Kit|last16=Lam |first17=Juan|last17=Lubroth |first18=John S|last18=Mackenzie |first19=Larry|last19=Madoff |first20=Jonna|last20=Mazet |first21=Peter|last21=Palese |first22=Stanley|last22=Perlman |first23=Leo|last23=Poon |first24=Bernard|last24=Roizman |first25=Linda|last25=Saif |first26=Kanta|last26=Subbarao |first27=Mike|last27=Turner|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(20)30418-9/fulltext|title=Statement in support of the scientists, public health professionals, and medical professionals of China combatting COVID-19|journal=The Lancet|volume=395|issue=10226|date=19 February 2020|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30418-9}}</ref>\n\n=== Chinese biological weapon ===\n\n==== United States ====\n{{further|Cyberwarfare in the United States|Propaganda in the United States}}\nIn January 2020, [[BBC News]] published an article about coronavirus misinformation, citing two January 24 articles from ''[[The Washington Times]]'' that said the virus was part of a Chinese biological weapons program, based at the [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] (WIV).<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' later published an article debunking the conspiracy theory, citing US experts who explained why the WIV was unsuitable for bioweapon research, that most countries had abandoned bioweapons as fruitless, and that there was no evidence that the virus was genetically engineered.<ref name=\"20200129washingtonpost\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/01/29/experts-debunk-fringe-theory-linking-chinas-coronavirus-weapons-research/ |title=Experts debunk fringe theory linking China's coronavirus to weapons research |date=January 29, 2020 |website=The Washington Post |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200131185716/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/01/29/experts-debunk-fringe-theory-linking-chinas-coronavirus-weapons-research/ |archive-date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn January 29, financial news website and blog [[ZeroHedge]] suggested without evidence that a scientist at the WIV created the COVID-19 strain responsible for the coronavirus outbreak. Zerohedge listed the full contact details of the scientist supposedly responsible, a practice known as [[doxing]], by including the scientist's name, photo, and phone number, suggesting to readers that they \"pay [the Chinese scientist] a visit\" if they wanted to know \"what really caused the coronavirus pandemic.\"<ref name=\"the verge\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/1/31/21117663/twitter-zero-hedge-suspended-platform-manipulation-policy-doxxing-coronavirus |title=Markets blogger Zero Hedge suspended from Twitter after doxxing a Chinese scientist |last=Peters |first=Jay | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |website=The Verge |access-date=February 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206214044/https://www.theverge.com/2020/1/31/21117663/twitter-zero-hedge-suspended-platform-manipulation-policy-doxxing-coronavirus |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Twitter later permanently suspended the blog's account for violating its platform-manipulation policy.<ref name=20200131bloomberg>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-01/zero-hedge-permanently-suspended-from-twitter-for-harassment |title=Zero Hedge Permanently Suspended From Twitter for 'Harassment' |last=Datoo |first=Siraj | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |website=Bloomberg |url-status=live |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202214859/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-01/zero-hedge-permanently-suspended-from-twitter-for-harassment |archive-date=February 2, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, ''[[Buzzfeed News]]'' reported on an internet meme of a link between the logo of the WIV and \"[[Umbrella Corporation]]\", the agency that created the virus responsible for a [[zombie apocalypse]] in the ''[[Resident Evil]]'' franchise. Posts online noted that \"{{sic|Racoon}}\" (the main city in ''Resident Evil'') was an anagram of \"Corona\".<ref name=\"SNOPES\" /> [[Snopes]] noted that the logo was not from the WIV, but a company named Shanghai Ruilan Bao Hu San Biotech Ltd (located some {{convert|500|mi}} away in Shanghai), and that the correct name of the city in Resident Evil was \"Raccoon City\".<ref name=\"SNOPES\">{{cite web | url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/resident-evil-umbrella-coronavirus/ | title=Is the 'Umbrella Corporation' Logo Oddly Similar to a Wuhan Biotech Lab's? | first=Dan | last=Evon | name-list-format = vanc | date=January 29, 2020 | access-date=February 10, 2020 | website=[[Snopes]] }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, US Senator [[Tom Cotton]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Arkansas|AR]]) and [[Francis Boyle]], a law professor, suggested that the virus may have been a Chinese bioweapon;<ref name=\"cotton\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/482228-chinese-ambassador-on-cotton-coronavirus-comments-its-very-harmful | title=Chinese ambassador on Cotton coronavirus comments: 'It's very harmful to stir up' unsubstantiated rumors | newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] | first=Zack | last=Budryk | name-list-format = vanc | access-date=February 11, 2020 | date=February 9, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210153906/https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/482228-chinese-ambassador-on-cotton-coronavirus-comments-its-very-harmful | archive-date=February 10, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> multiple medical experts have indicated there is no evidence for this.<ref name=\"fact checking\">{{cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/18/politics/coronavirus-cotton-fact-check/index.html |title=Fact-checking Tom Cotton's claims about the coronavirus |first=Tara |last=Subramaniam | name-list-format = vanc |date=February 18, 2020 |publisher=CNN |access-date=February 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219234740/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/18/politics/coronavirus-cotton-fact-check/index.html |archive-date=February 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Conservative political commentator [[Rush Limbaugh]] said on ''[[The Rush Limbaugh Show]]''\u2014 the most popular radio show in the US\u2014that the virus was probably \"a [[ChiCom]] laboratory experiment\" and that the Chinese government was using the virus and the media hysteria surrounding it to bring down Donald Trump.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/rush-limbaugh/rush-limbaugh-coronavirus-effort-get-trump|title=Rush Limbaugh: \"The coronavirus is an effort to get Trump\"|website=Media Matters for America}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/rush-limbaugh-claims-chinese-are-trying-to-weaponize-coronavirus-to-bring-down-trump|title= Rush Limbaugh claims Chinese are 'trying to weaponize' coronavirus to 'bring down' Trump|date= February 25, 2020|access-date= February 25, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162810/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/rush-limbaugh-claims-chinese-are-trying-to-weaponize-coronavirus-to-bring-down-trump|archive-date= February 29, 2020|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 6, the White House asked scientists and medical researchers to rapidly investigate the origins of the virus to address both the current spread and \"to inform future outbreak preparation and better understand animal/human and environmental transmission aspects of coronaviruses.\"<ref name=go68807304>{{cite web| date=February 6, 2020| title=White House asks scientists to investigate origins of coronavirus| url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-asks-scientists-investigate-origins-coronavirus/story?id=68807304| access-date=February 28, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208032258/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-asks-scientists-investigate-origins-coronavirus/story?id=68807304| archive-date=February 8, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> American magazine ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' said that Xi Jinping's \"political agenda may turn out to be a root cause of the epidemic\" and that his [[Belt and Road Initiative]] has \"made it possible for a local disease to become a global menace\".<ref name=al-watsm />\n\nThe ''Inverse'' reported that \"Christopher Bouzy, the founder of Bot Sentinel, conducted a Twitter analysis for Inverse and found [online] bots and [[Internet troll|trollbots]] are making an array of false claims. These bots are claiming China intentionally created the virus, that it's a biological weapon, that Democrats are overstating the threat to hurt Donald Trump and more. While we can't confirm the origin of these bots, they are decidedly pro-Trump.\"<ref name=inverse>{{cite news |title=Bots are waging a coronavirus disinformation campaign on social media |url=https://www.inverse.com/mind-body/coronavirus-usa-2020 |work=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]] |date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nConservative commentator [[Josh Bernstein (talk show host)|Josh Bernstein]] claimed that the Democratic Party and the \"medical deep state\" were collaborating with the Chinese government to create and release the coronavirus to bring down Donald Trump. Bernstein went on to suggest that those responsible should be locked in a room with infected coronavirus patients as punishment.<ref name=\"bernstein\">{{cite web|url= https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/josh-bernstein-the-coronavirus-outbreak-is-a-democratic-and-chinese-conspiracy-against-trump/|title= Josh Bernstein: The Coronavirus Outbreak Is a Democratic and Chinese Conspiracy Against Trump|access-date= March 12, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312173241/https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/josh-bernstein-the-coronavirus-outbreak-is-a-democratic-and-chinese-conspiracy-against-trump/|archive-date= March 12, 2020|url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=usatoday5065736002>{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Matthew |title=Fact check: Coronavirus did not spread in the US because of an anti-Trump conspiracy |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2020/03/17/fact-check-coronavirus-spread-not-anti-trump-conspiracy/5065736002/ |access-date=March 31, 2020 |work=USA Today |issue=2 |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Jerry Falwell Jr.]], the president of [[Liberty University]], promoted a conspiracy theory on [[Fox News]] that North Korea and China conspired together to create the coronavirus.<ref name=fox-falwell>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/coronavirus-covid-19/fox-guest-jerry-falwell-jr-speculates-north-korea-got-together-china-create|title=Fox guest Jerry Falwell Jr. speculates that North Korea \"got together with China\" to create coronavirus|website=Media Matters for America|access-date=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317093144/https://www.mediamatters.org/coronavirus-covid-19/fox-guest-jerry-falwell-jr-speculates-north-korea-got-together-china-create|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He also said that people were overreacting to the coronavirus outbreak and that Democrats were trying to use the situation to harm President Trump.<ref>{{cite news |last= Heim |first= Joe | name-list-format = vanc |title= Liberty University President Jerry Falwell Jr. says in-person classes to continue |date= March 13, 2020 |access-date= March 15, 2020 |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]] |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/liberty-university-president-jerry-falwell-jr-says-in-person-classes-to-continue/2020/03/13/70b23a58-654e-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html |quote= 'It\u2019s just strange to me how so many are overreacting,' Falwell said, comparing media coverage of the novel coronavirus to coverage of earlier epidemics. 'It makes you wonder if there\u2019s a political reason for that. Impeachment didn\u2019t work, and the Mueller report didn\u2019t work, and Article 25 didn\u2019t work. And so maybe now this is their next attempt to get Trump.' |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200317141436/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/liberty-university-president-jerry-falwell-jr-says-in-person-classes-to-continue/2020/03/13/70b23a58-654e-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html |archive-date= March 17, 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n==== United Kingdom ====\n\nConservative MP [[Tobias Ellwood]], chair of the [[Defence Select Committee]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|UK House of Commons]], publicly questioned the role of the Chinese Army's Wuhan Institute for Biological Products and called for the \"greater transparency over the origins of the coronavirus\".<ref name=20200229telegraph>{{Cite news|last=Ellwood|first=Tobias | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/02/29/transparency-will-convince-world-china-friend/|title=Transparency will convince the world China is a friend|date=February 29, 2020|work=The Telegraph|access-date=March 3, 2020|issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302000503/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/02/29/transparency-will-convince-world-china-friend/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It has also been reported that a member of [[Cabinet Office Briefing Rooms|COBRA]], a government committee tasked with dealing with crisis, has stated while government intelligence does not dispute that the virus has a zoonotic origin, it also does not discount the idea of a leak from a Wuhan laboratory, saying that \"Perhaps it is no coincidence that there is that laboratory in Wuhan.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://asiatimes.com/2020/04/wuhan-lab-virus-leak-no-longer-discounted-cobra/ |title=Wuhan lab virus leak 'no longer discounted': Cobra |first= Dave |last= Makichuk | name-list-format = vanc |work=Asia Times|date=April 6, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==== India ====\nAmidst a rise in [[Sinophobia]], there have been conspiracy theories reported on India's social networks that the virus is a state-supported \"a bioweapon that went rogue\" and also fake videos alleging that Chinese authorities are killing citizens to prevent its spread.<ref name=scmp3075445>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075445/coronavirus-anti-chinese-conspiracy-theories-go-viral|title=Coronavirus: anti-Chinese conspiracy theories go viral in India|date=March 16, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Ukraine ====\nAccording to the ''[[Kyiv Post]]'', two common conspiracy theories online in Ukraine are that American author [[Dean Koontz]] predicted the pandemic in his 1981 novel ''[[The Eyes of Darkness]]'', and that the coronavirus was a bioweapon leaked from a secret lab in Wuhan.<ref name=20200318kyivpost>{{cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/coronavirus-misinformation-goes-viral-in-ukraine.html|title=Coronavirus misinformation goes viral in Ukraine|date=March 18, 2020|website=Kyiv Post|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== US biological weapon ===\n==== Russia ====\n\n{{further|Cyberwarfare by Russia|Propaganda in the Russian Federation|Russia\u2013European Union relations#Allegations of Russian intimidation and destabilisation of EU states}}\nOn February 22, US officials alleged that Russia is behind an ongoing disinformation campaign, using thousands of social media accounts on Twitter, Facebook and [[Instagram]] to deliberately promote unfounded conspiracy theories, claiming that the virus is a biological weapon manufactured by the [[CIA]] and the US is waging economic war on China using the virus.<ref name=\"guardian-rus-disinfo\">{{Cite news |last=Glenza |first=Jessica | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-russia-disinformation-campaign-us-officials |title=Coronavirus: US says Russia behind disinformation campaign |date=February 22, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=February 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225051450/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-russia-disinformation-campaign-us-officials |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp3051939\" /><ref name=yahoo171730161>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/us-accuses-russia-huge-coronavirus-171730161.html |title=US accuses Russia of huge coronavirus disinformation campaign |work=[[The Independent]] |first=Kate |last=Ng | name-list-format = vanc |date=February 23, 2020 |access-date=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224090721/https://news.yahoo.com/us-accuses-russia-huge-coronavirus-171730161.html |archive-date=February 24, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The acting assistant secretary of state for Europe and [[Eurasia]], [[Philip T. Reeker|Philip Reeker]], said that \"Russia's intent is to sow discord and undermine US institutions and alliances from within\" and \"by spreading disinformation about coronavirus, Russian malign actors are once again choosing to threaten public safety by distracting from the global health response.\"<ref name=\"guardian-rus-disinfo\" /> Russia denies the allegation, saying \"this is a deliberately false story\".<ref name=bbc51599009>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51599009 |title=Coronavirus: Russia denies spreading US conspiracy on social media |date=February 23, 2020 |publisher=BBC |access-date=February 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225053306/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51599009 |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to US-based ''[[The National Interest]]'' magazine, although official Russian channels had been muted on pushing the US biowarfare conspiracy theory, other Russian media elements do not share the Kremlin's restraint.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\">{{Cite news |url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/some-russia-think-coronavirus-us-biological-weapon-121731 |title=Some in Russia Think the Coronavirus Is a U.S. Biological Weapon |last=Episkopos |first=Mark | name-list-format = vanc |date=February 7, 2020 |work=[[The National Interest]] |access-date=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223172332/https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/some-russia-think-coronavirus-us-biological-weapon-121731 |archive-date=February 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Zvezda'', a news outlet funded by the Russian Defense Ministry, published an article titled \"Coronavirus: American biological warfare against Russia and China\", claiming that the virus is intended to damage the Chinese economy, weakening its hand in the next round of trade negotiations.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\" /> Ultra-nationalist politician and leader of the [[Liberal Democratic Party of Russia]], [[Vladimir Zhirinovsky]], claimed on a Moscow radio station that the virus was an experiment by [[the Pentagon]] and pharmaceutical companies. Politician [[Igor Nikulin (politician)|Igor Nikulin]] made rounds on Russian television and news media, arguing that Wuhan was chosen for the attack because the presence of a BSL-4 virus lab provided a cover story for the Pentagon and CIA about a Chinese bio-experiment leak.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\" /> An EU-document claims 80 attempts by Russian media to spread disinformation related to the epidemic.<ref name=reuters2020-03-18>{{cite news |title=Russia deploying coronavirus disinformation to sow panic in West, EU document says |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21518F |agency=Reuters  |date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319222849/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21518F |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[East StratCom Task Force]], the [[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]] news agency was active publishing stories claiming that the virus was invented in Latvia, that it was used by [[Communist Party of China]] to curb [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests|protests in Hong Kong]], that it was introduced intentionally to reduce the number of elder people in Italy, that it was targeted against the [[Yellow vests movement|Yellow Vests]] movement, and making many other claims. Sputnik branches in countries including Armenia, Belarus, Spain, and in the middle east came up with customized versions of these stories.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://euvsdisinfo.eu/sputnik-coronavirus-could-be-designed-to-kill-elderly-italians/|title=Sputnik: Coronavirus Could be Designed to Kill Elderly Italians|date=March 25, 2020|website=EU vs DISINFORMATION|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Iran ====\n\n{{further|Propaganda in Iran}}\nAccording to ''[[Radio Farda]]'', Iranian cleric Seyyed Mohammad Saeedi accused US President [[Donald Trump]] of targeting [[Qom]] with coronavirus \"to damage its culture and honor\". Saeedi claimed that Trump is fulfilling his promise to hit Iranian cultural sites, if Iranians took revenge for the [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|US airstrike]] that killed of [[Quds Force]] Commander [[Qasem Soleimani]].<ref name=radiofarda30449087>{{Cite news|url=https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iran-cleric-blames-trump-for-coronavirus-outbreak-in-religious-city/30449087.html|title=Iran Cleric Blames Trump For Coronavirus Outbreak in Religious City|date=February 22, 2020|work=[[Radio Farda]]|access-date=February 26, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223170405/https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iran-cleric-blames-trump-for-coronavirus-outbreak-in-religious-city/30449087.html|archive-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIranian TV personality Ali Akbar Raefipour claimed that the coronavirus was part of a \"hybrid warfare\" programme waged by the United States on Iran and China.<ref name=bbc51677530>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Misinformation and false medical advice spreads in Iran |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51677530 |work=BBC News |date=February 29, 2020 |access-date=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301202336/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51677530 |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nBrigadier General Gholam Reza Jalali, head of Iranian Civil Defense Organization, claimed that the coronavirus is likely a biological attack on China and Iran with economic goals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.farsnews.ir/newstext.aspx?nn=13981213000410|title=Civil Defense Chief: Coronavirus Likely Biological Attack against China, Iran|date=March 3, 2020|agency=[[Fars News Agency]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304231742/http://en.farsnews.ir/newstext.aspx?nn=13981213000410|archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=toi-civildefense>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/virus-is-biological-attack-on-china-and-iran-iranian-civil-defense-chief-claims/|title=Virus is biological attack on China and Iran, Iranian civil defense chief claims|date=March 4, 2020|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305173532/https://www.timesofisrael.com/virus-is-biological-attack-on-china-and-iran-iranian-civil-defense-chief-claims/|archive-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Hossein Salami]], the head of [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]] (IRGC), claimed that the coronavirus outbreak in Iran may be due to a US \"biological attack\".<ref name=20200305alarabiya>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/05/Coronavirus-may-be-US-biological-attack-IRGC-head.html|title=Coronavirus may be US 'biological attack': IRGC head Hossein Salami|date=March 5, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306204737/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/05/Coronavirus-may-be-US-biological-attack-IRGC-head.html|archive-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Several Iranian politicians, including [[Hossein Amir-Abdollahian]], [[Rasoul Falahati]], [[Alireza Panahian]], [[Abolfazl Hasanbeigi]] and [[Gholamali Jafarzadeh Imanabadi]], also made similar remarks.<ref name=20200316iranwire>{{Cite news|url=https://iranwire.com/en/features/6815|title=The Lie that Triggered Khamenei's 'Biological Attack' Conspiracy Theory|date=March 16, 2020|work=IranWire}}</ref>\nHowever, Iran's deputy health minister [[Reza Malekzadeh]] rejected the biological warfare theory.<ref name=20200314alarabiyaA>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/14/Coronavirus-Iran-s-deputy-health-minister-rejects-biological-warfare-theory.html|title=Coronavirus: Iran's deputy health minister rejects biological warfare theory|date=March 14, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317205520/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/14/Coronavirus-Iran-s-deputy-health-minister-rejects-biological-warfare-theory.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFormer Iranian president [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] sent a letter to the [[United Nations]] on March 9, claiming that \"it is clear to the world that the mutated coronavirus was produced in lab\" and that COVID-19 is \"a new weapon for establishing and/or maintaining political and economic upper hand in the global arena.\"<ref name=20200309washingtonexaminer>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/biologic-war-former-iranian-president-says-coronavirus-was-produced-in-laboratories|title='Biologic war': Former Iranian president says coronavirus was 'produced in laboratories'|date=March 9, 2020|agency=[[Washington Examiner]]|access-date=March 11, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311071331/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/biologic-war-former-iranian-president-says-coronavirus-was-produced-in-laboratories|archive-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAyatollah [[Hashem Bathaie Golpayegani]] claimed that \"America is the source of coronavirus, because America went head to head with China and realised it cannot keep up with it economically or militarily.\"<ref name=20200319alarabiya>{{Cite news |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/features/2020/03/19/Video-Senior-Iranian-cleric-who-died-from-coronavirus-blamed-US-for-outbreak |title=Video: Senior Iranian cleric who died from coronavirus blamed US for outbreak |date=March 19, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== China ====\n\n{{further|Cyberwarfare by China|Propaganda in China|Chinese information operations and information warfare}}\nAccording to London-based ''[[The Economist]]'', plenty of conspiracy theories exist on China's internet about COVID-19 being the CIA's creation to keep China down.<ref name=20200208economist>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/08/chinas-rulers-see-the-coronavirus-as-a-chance-to-tighten-their-grip |title=China's rulers see the coronavirus as a chance to tighten their grip |date=February 8, 2020 |work=[[The Economist]] |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200229034330/https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/08/chinas-rulers-see-the-coronavirus-as-a-chance-to-tighten-their-grip |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[NBC News]] however has noted that there have also been debunking efforts of US-related conspiracy theories posted online, with a WeChat search of \"Coronavirus is from the U.S.\" reported to mostly yield articles explaining why such claims are unreasonable.<ref name=nbcnews1151291>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/coronavirus-rumors-misinformation-swirl-unchecked-china-n1151291|title=Coronavirus rumors \u2013 and misinformation \u2013 swirl unchecked in China|publisher=NBC News|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> According to an investigation by [[ProPublica]], such conspiracy theories and disinformation have been propagated under the direction of [[China News Service]], the country's second largest government-owned media outlet controlled by the [[United Front Work Department]].<ref name=20200326propublica>{{Cite news|last=Kao|first=Jeff| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.propublica.org/article/how-china-built-a-twitter-propaganda-machine-then-let-it-loose-on-coronavirus|title=How China Built a Twitter Propaganda Machine Then Let It Loose on Coronavirus|date=March 26, 2020|work=[[ProPublica]]|access-date=March 31, 2020|last2=Li|first2=Mia Shuang}}</ref> ''[[Global Times]]'' and [[Xinhua News Agency]] have similarly been implicated in propagating disinformation related to COVID-19's origins.<ref name=20200405telegraph>{{Cite news|last=Dodds|first=Laurence| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2020/04/05/china-floods-facebook-instagram-undeclared-coronavirus-propaganda/|title=China floods Facebook with undeclared coronavirus propaganda ads blaming Trump|date=April 5, 2020|work=The Telegraph|access-date=April 5, 2020|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nMultiple conspiracy articles in Chinese from the SARS era resurfaced during the outbreak with altered details, claiming that SARS is biological warfare conducted by the US against China. Some of these articles said that [[BGI Group]] from China sold genetic information of the Chinese people to the US, with the US then being able to deploy the virus specifically targeting the [[genome]] of Chinese individuals.<ref name=setn677313>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u570b\u5bb6\u9577\u6307\u7a31\u300c\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u662f\u7f8e\u570b\u6295\u653e\u75c5\u6bd2\u300d\u3000\u7db2\u53cb\u50bb\u7206\u773c|url=https://www.setn.com/News.aspx?NewsID=677313|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219211548/https://www.setn.com/News.aspx?NewsID=677313|archive-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 26, Chinese military news site Xilu published an article detailing how the virus was artificially combined by the US to \"precisely target Chinese people\".<ref name=xilu1000010001>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u75c5\u6bd24\u4e2a\u5173\u952e\u86cb\u767d\u88ab\u66ff\u6362\uff0c\u53ef\u7cbe\u51c6\u653b\u51fb\u534e\u4eba|url=http://www.xilu.com/20200126/1000010001119697.html|access-date=February 7, 2020|work=\u897f\u9646\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211022551/http://www.xilu.com/20200126/1000010001119697.html|archive-date=February 11, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}} The article was removed after early February.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nSome articles on popular sites in China have also cast suspicion on US military athletes participating in the Wuhan [[2019 Military World Games]], which lasted until the end of October 2019, and have suggested that they deployed the virus. They claim the inattentive attitude and disproportionately below-average results of American athletes in the games indicate they might have been there for other purposes and they might actually be bio-warfare operatives. Such posts stated that their place of residence during their stay in Wuhan was also close to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]], where the first known cluster of cases occurred.<ref name=szhgh221836>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e3a\u4ec0\u4e48\u6b66\u6c49\u8fd9\u573a\u761f\u75ab\uff0c\u5fc5\u987b\u5f97\u9760\u89e3\u653e\u519b\uff1f|url=http://www.szhgh.com/Article/opinion/zatan/2020-01-30/221836.html|access-date=February 21, 2020|publisher=\u7ea2\u6b4c\u4f1a\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221185358/http://www.szhgh.com/Article/opinion/zatan/2020-01-30/221836.html|archive-date=February 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, this conspiracy theory was endorsed by [[Zhao Lijian]], a spokesperson from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China.<ref name=\"Taiwan News March 2020\">{{cite web |last1=Cheng |first1=Ching-Tse |title=China's foreign ministry accuses US military of bringing virus to Wuhan |url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3896257 |work=Taiwan News |access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref name=thehill487308>{{cite web |last1=Budryk |first1=Zack |title=China, pushing conspiracy theory, accuses US Army of bringing coronavirus to Wuhan |url=https://thehill.com/policy/international/487308-china-pushing-conspiracy-theory-us-army-bringing-coronavirus-wuhan |newspaper=The Hill |access-date=March 13, 2020|date=March 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tang |first1=Didi |title=China accuses US of bringing coronavirus to Wuhan |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/china-accuses-us-of-bringing-coronavirus-to-wuhan-c9rrfbrs7 |work=The Times |access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 13, the US government summoned Chinese Ambassador [[Cui Tiankai]] to Washington DC over the coronavirus conspiracy theory.<ref name=20200314alarabiyaB>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/world/2020/03/14/US-summons-China-s-ambassador-to-Washington-over-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory.html|title=US summons China's ambassador to Washington over coronavirus conspiracy theory|date=March 14, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316012205/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/world/2020/03/14/US-summons-China-s-ambassador-to-Washington-over-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory.html|archive-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Arab world ====\n\nAccording to Washington DC-based nonprofit [[Middle East Media Research Institute]], numerous writers in the Arabic press have promoted the conspiracy theory that COVID-19, as well as SARS and the swine flu virus, were deliberately created and spread by the US to sell vaccines against these diseases, and it is \"part of an economic and psychological war waged by the US against China with the aim of weakening it and presenting it as a backward country and a source of diseases\".<ref name=\"MEMRI-arab-disinfo\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.memri.org/reports/arab-writers-coronavirus-part-biological-warfare-waged-us-against-china |title=Arab Writers: The Coronavirus Is Part Of Biological Warfare Waged By The U.S. Against China |date=February 6, 2020 |publisher=[[Middle East Media Research Institute]] |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209043001/https://www.memri.org/reports/arab-writers-coronavirus-part-biological-warfare-waged-us-against-china |archive-date=February 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Iraqi political analyst Sabah Al-Akili on [[Aletejah TV|Al-Etejah TV]], Saudi daily [[Al Watan (Saudi Arabia)|Al-Watan]] writer Sa'ud Al-Shehry, Syrian daily [[Al-Thawra (newspaper)|Al-Thawra]] columnist Hussein Saqer, and Egyptian journalist Ahmad Rif'at on Egyptian news website Vetogate, were some examples given by MEMRI as propagators of the US biowarfare conspiracy theory in the Arabic world.<ref name=\"MEMRI-arab-disinfo\" />\n\n==== Philippine ====\n\nA Filipino Senator, [[Tito Sotto]], played a bioweapon conspiracy video in a February 2020 Senate hearing, suggesting that the coronavirus is biowarfare waged against China.<ref name=\"nypost-rubio\">{{Cite news|last=Rubio|first=Marco| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/03/russia-china-and-iran-are-waging-disinformation-war-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Marco Rubio: Russia, China and Iran are waging disinformation war over coronavirus|date=March 3, 2020|work=[[New York Post]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304233343/https://nypost.com/2020/03/03/russia-china-and-iran-are-waging-disinformation-war-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=philstar1990332>{{Cite news|last=San Juan|first=Ratziel| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/04/1990332/bioweapon-conspiracy-video-creeps-senate-coronavirus-hearing|title=Bioweapon conspiracy video creeps into Senate coronavirus hearing|date=February 4, 2020|work=[[The Philippine Star]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310163521/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/04/1990332/bioweapon-conspiracy-video-creeps-senate-coronavirus-hearing|archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Venezuela ====\n\n[[2017 Constituent National Assembly|Constituent Assembly]] member Elvis M\u00e9ndez declared that the coronavirus was a \"bacteriological sickness created in '89, in '90 and historically\" and that it was a sickness \"inoculated by the ''[[gringo]]s''\". M\u00e9ndez theorized that the virus was a weapon against Latin America and China and that its purpose was \"to demoralize the person, to weaken to install their system\".<ref name=20200307somostuvoz>{{cite web|url=http://www.somostuvoz.net/destacado/constituyente-elvis-mendez-el-coronavirus-lo-inocularon-los-gringos/|title=Constituyente Elvis M\u00e9ndez: \"El coronavirus lo inocularon los gringos\"|last=Web|first=Master| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 7, 2020|website=Somos Tu Voz|language=es|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318065112/http://www.somostuvoz.net/destacado/constituyente-elvis-mendez-el-coronavirus-lo-inocularon-los-gringos/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Anti-Muslim ===\n\n{{further|2020 Tablighi Jamaat coronavirus hotspot in Delhi|Islamophobia}}\nIn India, Muslims have been blamed for spreading infection following the emergence of cases linked to a [[Tablighi Jamaat]] religious gathering.<ref name=newsweek1496011>{{cite journal|title=India's Coronavirus Outbreak Stokes Islamophobia as Muslims blamed for spreading infection|journal=[[Newsweek]]|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.newsweek.com/indias-coronavirus-outbreak-stokes-islamophobia-muslims-blamed-spreading-infection-1496011|access-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There are reports of vilification of Muslims on social media and attacks on individuals in India.<ref name=firstpost8231371>{{cite journal|first=Pinak Pani|last=Datta| name-list-format = vanc |title=Coronavirus outbreak sparks racist attacks on people from North East, stokes Islamophobia on social media|journal=[[Firstpost]]|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/coronavirus-outbreak-sparks-racist-attacks-on-people-from-north-east-stokes-islamophobia-on-social-media-8231371.html}}</ref> Claims have been made Muslims are selling food contaminated with coronavirus and that a mosque in Patna was sheltering people from Italy and Iran.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Nishita|last=Jha| name-list-format = vanc |title=A Cluster Of Coronavirus Cases Can Be Traced Back to a Single Mosque And Now 200 Million Muslims Are Being Vilified|journal=[[Buzzfeed News]]|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/nishitajha/coronavirus-india-muslims-tablighi-jamaat}}</ref> These claims were shown to be false.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Priyanka|last=Jha| name-list-format = vanc |title=No, foreign nationals from Italy, Iran weren't hiding in Patna mosque to avoid coronavirus testing|journal=[[Firstpost]]|date=March 28, 2020|url=https://www.altnews.in/were-50-foreigners-from-itlay-iran-and-china-hiding-in-mosque-due-to-corona-virus-detained-in-bihar-kurji/}}</ref> In the UK, there are reports of far-right groups blaming Muslims for the coronavirus outbreak and falsely claiming that mosques remained open after the national ban on large gatherings.<ref name=20200405theguardian>{{cite journal|first=Nazia|last=Parveen| name-list-format = vanc |title=Police investigate UK far-right groups over anti-Muslim coronavirus claims|journal=[[The Guardian]]|date=April 5, 2020|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/police-investigate-uk-far-right-groups-over-anti-muslim-coronavirus-claims/}}</ref>\n\n=== Antisemitic ===\n\n{{further|Antisemitic canard}}\nIran's [[Press TV]] asserted that \"Zionist elements developed a deadlier strain of coronavirus against Iran\".<ref name=\"presstv\" />\nSimilarly, various Arab media outlets accused Israel and the United States of creating and spreading COVID-19, [[avian flu]], and [[SARS]].<ref name=jpost617021>{{cite journal|title=Arab media accuse US, Israel of coronavirus conspiracy against China|journal=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=February 9, 2020|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Arab-media-accuse-US-Israel-of-coronavirus-conspiracy-against-China-617021|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301063057/https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Arab-media-accuse-US-Israel-of-coronavirus-conspiracy-against-China-617021|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Users on social media offered a variety of theories, including the supposition that Jews had manufactured COVID-19 to precipitate a global stock market collapse and thereby profit via [[insider trading]],<ref name=forward441421>{{cite journal|first=Irene|last=Connelly| name-list-format = vanc |title=Online anti-Semitism thrives around coronavirus, even on mainstream platforms|journal=[[The Forward]]|url=https://forward.com/news/441421/anti-semitic-coronavirus-response-thrives-online-even-on-mainstream/}}</ref> while a guest on Turkish television posited a more ambitious scenario in which Jews and Zionists had created COVID-19, avian flu, and [[Crimean\u2013Congo hemorrhagic fever]] to \"design the world, seize countries, [and] neuter the world's population\".<ref name=20200314timesofisrael>{{cite journal|first=Eric|last=Cortellessa| name-list-format = vanc |title=Conspiracy theory that Jews created virus spreads on social media, ADL says|journal=[[The Times of Israel]]|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/conspiracy-theory-that-jews-created-virus-spreads-on-social-media-adl-says/|date=March 14, 2020|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314133541/https://www.timesofisrael.com/conspiracy-theory-that-jews-created-virus-spreads-on-social-media-adl-says/|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIsraeli attempts to develop a [[COVID-19 vaccine]] prompted mixed reactions. Grand Ayatollah [[Naser Makarem Shirazi]] denied initial reports that he had ruled that a Zionist-made vaccine would be [[halal]],<ref name=jpost621230>{{cite news|last=Joffre|first=Tzvi| name-list-format = vanc |title=Iranian cleric denies approving use of coronavirus vaccine from Israel|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iranian-cleric-denies-approving-use-of-coronavirus-vaccine-from-Israel-621230|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> and one Press TV journalist tweeted that \"I'd rather take my chances with the virus than consume an Israeli vaccine\".<ref name=jpost620900>{{cite news|title=Would a Zionist coronavirus cure be Halal? Iranian cleric says yes|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Is-Zionist-coronavirus-cure-Halal-Iranian-cleric-says-yes-620900|date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> A columnist for the Turkish ''[[Yeni Akit]]'' asserted that such a vaccine could be a ruse to carry out [[Compulsory sterilization|mass sterilization]].<ref name=jpost621393>{{cite news|last=Edmunds|first=Donna Rachel| name-list-format = vanc |title=Coronavirus is a Zionist plot, say Turkish politicians, media, public|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Antisemitism/Coronavirus-is-a-Zionist-plot-say-Turkish-politicians-media-public-621393|date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn alert by the US [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] regarding the possible threat of far-right extremists intentionally spreading the coronavirus mentioned blame being assigned to Jews and Jewish leaders for causing the pandemic and several statewide shutdowns across the US.<ref name=go69737522>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/white-supremacists-encouraging-members-spread-coronavirus-cops-jews/story?id=69737522|title=White supremacists encouraging their members to spread coronavirus to cops, Jews, FBI says|first=Josh|last=Margolin| name-list-format = vanc |website=[[ABC News]]|date=March 23, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Spy operation ===\n\nSome people have alleged that the coronavirus was stolen from a Canadian virus research lab by Chinese scientists. [[Health Canada]] and the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] said that conspiracy theory had \"no factual basis\".<ref name=nofact /> The stories seem to have been derived<ref name=\"buzz_doxx\" /> from a July 2019 news article<ref name=escorted /> stating that some Chinese researchers had their security access to a [[National Microbiology Laboratory|Canadian Level 4 virology facility]] revoked in a [[RCMP|federal police]] investigation; Canadian officials described this as an administrative matter and said that \"there is absolutely no risk to the Canadian public.\"<ref name=escorted>{{cite news |last1=Pauls |first1=Karen Pauls |title=Chinese researcher escorted from infectious disease lab amid RCMP investigation |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/chinese-researcher-escorted-from-infectious-disease-lab-amid-rcmp-investigation-1.5211567 |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |date=July 14, 2019 |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206011635/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/chinese-researcher-escorted-from-infectious-disease-lab-amid-rcmp-investigation-1.5211567 |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThis article was published by the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] (CBC);<ref name=\"buzz_doxx\">{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/a-pro-trump-blog-has-doxed-a-chinese-scientist-it-falsely |title=A Pro-Trump Blog Doxed A Chinese Scientist It Falsely Accused Of Creating The Coronavirus As A Bioweapon |last=Broderick |first=Ryan | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |website=BuzzFeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210034232/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/a-pro-trump-blog-has-doxed-a-chinese-scientist-it-falsely |archive-date=February 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> responding to the conspiracy theories, the CBC later stated that \"CBC reporting never claimed the two scientists were spies, or that they brought any version of the coronavirus to the lab in Wuhan\". While pathogen samples were transferred from the lab in [[Winnipeg]], Canada to Beijing, China, on March 31, 2019, neither of the samples was a coronavirus, the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] says that the shipment conformed to all federal policies, and there has not been any statement that the researchers under investigation were responsible for sending the shipment. The current location of the researchers under investigation by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] is not being released.<ref name=nofact>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/china-coronavirus-online-chatter-conspiracy-1.5442376 |title=Online claims that Chinese scientists stole coronavirus from Winnipeg lab have 'no factual basis' |last=Yates |first=Karen |last2=Pauls |first2=Jeff | name-list-format = vanc |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |time=January 27, 2020 |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208134329/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/china-coronavirus-online-chatter-conspiracy-1.5442376 |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E7%A7%91%E5%AD%A6%E5%AE%B6%E4%BB%8E%E6%B8%A9%E5%B0%BC%E4%BC%AF%E5%AE%9E%E9%AA%8C%E5%AE%A4%E4%B8%AD%E7%AA%83%E5%8F%96-%E5%86%A0%E7%8A%B6%E7%97%85%E6%AF%92%E7%9A%84%E7%BD%91%E7%BB%9C%E4%BC%A0%E8%A8%80-%E6%B2%A1%E6%9C%89%E4%BA%8B%E5%AE%9E%E6%A0%B9%E6%8D%AE-1.5448165 |title=Chinese translation: \u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\u5bb6\u4ece\u6e29\u5c3c\u4f2f\u5b9e\u9a8c\u5ba4\u4e2d\u7a83\u53d6 \u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u7684\u7f51\u7edc\u4f20\u8a00'\u6ca1\u6709\u4e8b\u5b9e\u6839\u636e' |last=Yates |first=Karen |last2=Pauls |first2=Jeff | name-list-format = vanc |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |time=January 27, 2020 |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201040447/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E7%A7%91%E5%AD%A6%E5%AE%B6%E4%BB%8E%E6%B8%A9%E5%B0%BC%E4%BC%AF%E5%AE%9E%E9%AA%8C%E5%AE%A4%E4%B8%AD%E7%AA%83%E5%8F%96-%E5%86%A0%E7%8A%B6%E7%97%85%E6%AF%92%E7%9A%84%E7%BD%91%E7%BB%9C%E4%BC%A0%E8%A8%80-%E6%B2%A1%E6%9C%89%E4%BA%8B%E5%AE%9E%E6%A0%B9%E6%8D%AE-1.5448165 |archive-date=February 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200128factcheck\">{{cite web |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/coronavirus-wasnt-sent-by-spy-from-canada/ |title=Coronavirus Wasn't Sent by 'Spy' From Canada |first=Saranac Hale |last=Spencer | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 28, 2020 |website=Factcheck.org |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130160015/https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/coronavirus-wasnt-sent-by-spy-from-canada/ |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the midst of the coronavirus epidemic, a senior research associate and expert in biological warfare with the [[Begin-Sadat Center for Strategic Studies]], referring to a [[NATO]] press conference, identified suspicions of espionage as the reason behind the expulsions from the lab, but made no suggestion that coronavirus was taken from the Canadian lab or that it is the result of bioweapons defense research in China.<ref name=20200129besacenter>{{cite web |url=https://besacenter.org/perspectives-papers/china-biological-warfare/ |title=China and Viruses: The Case of Dr. Xiangguo Qiu |last=Shoham | name-list-format = vanc |first=Dany |publisher=Begin-Sadat Center for Strategic Studies |date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Population control scheme ===\n\nAccording to the BBC, Jordan Sather, a conspiracy theory [[YouTuber]] supporting the [[QAnon|far-right QAnon conspiracy theory]] and the [[Vaccine hesitancy|anti-vax]] movement, has falsely claimed the outbreak was a population control scheme created by [[Pirbright Institute]] in England and by former [[Microsoft]] CEO [[Bill Gates]]. This belief is held mostly by [[Paleolibertarianism|right-wing libertarians]], [[New World Order (conspiracy theory)|NWO conspiracy theorists]], and [[Christian fundamentalism|Christian Fundamentalists]].<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\"20200123buzzfeednews\">{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/qanon-supporters-and-anti-vaxxers-are-spreading-a-hoax-that |title=QAnon Supporters And Anti-Vaxxers Are Spreading A Hoax That Bill Gates Created The Coronavirus |last=Broderick |first=Ryan | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 23, 2020 |website=BuzzFeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130075624/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/qanon-supporters-and-anti-vaxxers-are-spreading-a-hoax-that |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Accidental leakage ===\nA number of allegations have emerged on the [[Wuhan Institute of Virology#Concerns as source|link]] between the virus and [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] (WIV), among these is that the virus was an accidental leakage from WIV.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web | website=BBC News China | url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/chinese-news-51388024 | title=[TRANSLATED] Wuhan Pneumonia: \"Wuhan Virus Research Institute\" in the eyes of the outbreak and fake news storm | date=February 5, 2020 | access-date=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216162120/https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/chinese-news-51388024 | archive-date=February 16, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> In 2017, US molecular biologist [[Richard H. Ebright]], expressed caution when the WIV was expanded to become mainland China's first [[biosafety level 4]] (BSL\u20134) laboratory, noting previous escapes of the SARS virus at other Chinese laboratories.<ref name=\"nature\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Cyranoski D | title = Inside the Chinese lab poised to study world's most dangerous pathogens | journal = Nature | volume = 542 | issue = 7642 | pages = 399\u2013400 | date = February 2017 | pmid = 28230144 | doi = 10.1038/nature.2017.21487 | bibcode = 2017Natur.542..399C | doi-access = free }}</ref> While Ebright refuted several conspiracy theories regarding the WIV (e.g. bioweapons research, that the virus was engineered), he told BBC China that this did not represent the possibility that the virus can be \"completely ruled out\" from entering the population due to a laboratory accident.<ref name=\"BBC\" />\n\nOn 14 February 2020, Chinese scientist explored the possibility of accidental leakage and published speculations on scientific [[social networking]] website [[ResearchGate]]. The paper was neither [[peer-reviewed]] nor presented any evidence for its claims.<ref name=\"fullfact_0417origin\">{{cite web|url=https://fullfact.org/health/coronavirus-government-laboratory/|title=There's no evidence that the 2019 coronavirus originated in a Chinese government laboratory|date=17 February 2020|website=FullFact|last=Lewis|first=Kate}}</ref> On March 5, the author of paper told ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' in an interview why he decided to withdrew the paper by the end of February, stating: \"the speculation about the possible origins in the post was based on published papers and media, and was not supported by direct proofs.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/global-opinions/how-did-covid-19-begin-its-initial-origin-story-is-shaky/2020/04/02/1475d488-7521-11ea-87da-77a8136c1a6d_story.html|title=How did covid-19 begin? Its initial origin story is shaky. |website=Washington Post|last=Ignatius |first=David }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/coronavirus-epidemic-draws-scrutiny-to-labs-handling-deadly-pathogens-11583349777|title=Coronavirus Epidemic Draws Scrutiny to Labs Handling Deadly Pathogens|website=Wall Street Journal|last=Areddy|first=James T.|date=5 March 2020}}</ref> Several newspapers have referenced the paper.<ref name=\"fullfact_0417origin\" /> ''[[Scientific American]]'' reported that [[Shi Zhengli]], the lead researcher at WIV, started investigation on mishandling of experimental materials in the lab records, especially during disposal. She also tried to cross-check the novel coronavirus genome with the genetic information of other bat coronaviruses her team had collected. The result showed none of the sequences matched those of the viruses her team had sampled from bat caves.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/how-chinas-bat-woman-hunted-down-viruses-from-sars-to-the-new-coronavirus1/|title=How China\u2019s \u201cBat Woman\u201d Hunted Down Viruses from SARS to the New Coronavirus|website=Scientific American |date=11 March 2020|last=Qiu |first=Jane }}</ref>\n\nIn February, it has been alleged that the first person infected may have been a researcher at the institute named Huang Yanling.<ref name=\"scmp0216_huangyanling\" /> Rumours circulated on Chinese social media that the researcher had become infected and died, prompting a denial from WIV, saying that she was a graduate student enrolled in the Institute until 2015 and is not the patient zero.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whiov.ac.cn/tzgg_105342/202002/t20200216_5500201.html |title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\u9662\u6b66\u6c49\u75c5\u6bd2\u7814\u7a76\u6240\u58f0\u660e |date=February 16, 2020 |work=Wuhan Institute of Virology }}</ref><ref name=\"scmp0216_huangyanling\">{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3050872/chinese-research-lab-denies-rumours-links-first-coronavirus |title=Chinese research lab denies rumours of links to first coronavirus patient |date=16 February 2020|first=Jun |last= Mai | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> In April, the conspiracy theory started to circulate around on Youtube and got picked up by conservative media, ''National Review''.<ref name=20200403nationalreview>{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2020/04/coronavirus-china-trail-leading-back-to-wuhan-labs/ |title= The Trail Leading Back to the Wuhan Labs |first= Jim |last=Geraghty | name-list-format = vanc |date=April 3, 2020|work=National Review}}</ref><ref name=\"fp_0414conspiracy\"/>\n\nThe ''[[South China Morning Post]]'' (SCMP) reported that one of the WIV's lead researchers, [[Shi Zhengli]], was the particular focus of personal attacks in Chinese social media alleging that her work on bat-based viruses was the source of the virus; this led Shi to post: \"I swear with my life, [the virus] has nothing to do with the lab\". When asked by the SCMP to comment on the attacks, Shi responded: \"My time must be spent on more important matters\".<ref name=\"SCMP\">{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] | url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3049397/bat-ladys-cave-exploits-offer-hope-beat-virus-sneakier-sars | title=Coronavirus: bat scientist's cave exploits offer hope to beat virus 'sneakier than Sars' | first=Stephen | last=Chen | name-list-format = vanc | date=February 6, 2020 | access-date=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207210442/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3049397/bat-ladys-cave-exploits-offer-hope-beat-virus-sneakier-sars | archive-date=February 7, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Caixin]]'' reported Shi made further public statements against \"perceived [[Tinfoil hat|tinfoil-hat]] theories about the new virus's source\", quoting her as saying: \"The novel 2019 coronavirus is nature punishing the human race for keeping uncivilized living habits. I, Shi Zhengli, swear on my life that it has nothing to do with our laboratory\".<ref name=caixinglobal101512828>{{cite web | url=https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-02-07/wuhan-virology-lab-deputy-director-again-slams-coronavirus-conspiracies-101512828.html | title=Wuhan Virology Lab Deputy Director Again Slams Coronavirus Conspiracies | website=[[Caixin]] | first1=Yang | last1=Rui | first2=Feng | last2=Yuding | first3=Zhao | last3=Jinchao | first4=Matthew | last4=Walsh | name-list-format = vanc | date=February 7, 2020 | access-date=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219215801/https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-02-07/wuhan-virology-lab-deputy-director-again-slams-coronavirus-conspiracies-101512828.html | archive-date=February 19, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> Immunologist [[Vincent Racaniello]] stated that virus leaking theory \"reflect a lack of understanding of the genetic make-up of Sars-CoV-2 and its relationship to the bat virus\". He states that the bat virus researched in the institution \"would not have been able to infect humans \u2013 the human Sars-CoV-2 has additional changes that allows it to infect humans.\"<ref name=\"scmp0411\">{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3079391/bat-virus-bioweapon-what-science-says-about-covid-19-origins |title=Bat virus? Bioweapon? What the science says about Covid-19 origins |date=11 April 2020|first=Simone |last= McCarthy|first2=Stephen |last2=Chen | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref>\n\nOn April 14, the US [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]], General [[Mark A. Milley|Mark Milley]], in response to questions about the virus being manufactured in a lab, said \"... it\u2019s inconclusive, although the weight of evidence seems to indicate natural. But we don\u2019t know for certain.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/14/covid-19-origin-lab-general-mark-milley |title=US military chief: 'Weight of evidence' that Covid-19 did not originate in a lab |first=Julian |last=Borger | name-list-format = vanc |date= 14 April 2020 |work=The Guardian }}</ref> Days later, multiple media outlets confirmed that U.S. intelligence officials were investigating the possibility that the virus started in the WIV.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dilanian |first1=Ken |title=U.S. intel community examining whether coronavirus emerged accidentally from a Chinese lab |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/china/u-s-intel-community-examining-whether-coronavirus-emerged-accidentally-chinese-n1185371 |website=NBC News |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Strobel |first1=Warren P. |title=U.S. Intelligence Sifts Evidence for Origins of Coronavirus |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-intelligence-sifts-evidence-for-origins-of-coronavirus-11587077170 |website=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gazis |first1=Olivia |title=U.S. intelligence community still investigating origins of COVID-19 outbreak, including whether it was a lab accident |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-covid-19-origins-investigation-wuhan-lab-accident/ |website=CBS News |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Campbell |first1=Josh |title=US explores possibility that coronavirus spread started in Chinese lab, not a market |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/15/politics/us-intelligence-virus-started-chinese-lab/index.html |website=CNN |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n=== Nurse whistleblower ===\n\nOn January 24, a video circulated online appearing to be of a nurse named ''Jin Hui''<ref name=\"theinitium20200130\">{{cite web|url=https://theinitium.com/article/20200130-repost-pansci-2019ncov-misinformation/|title=\u6cdb\u79d1\u5b78\uff1a\u95dc\u65bc\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u768420\u500b\u50b3\u8a00\uff0c\u54ea\u4e9b\u662f\u771f\u54ea\u4e9b\u662f\u5047\uff1f|website=The Initium|date=January 30, 2020|language=Chinese|first1=Peiqi|last1=Luo|first2=Yingkai|last2=Liao| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=February 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202120919/https://theinitium.com/article/20200130-repost-pansci-2019ncov-misinformation/|archive-date=February 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> in [[Hubei]] describing a far more dire situation in Wuhan than purported by Chinese officials. The video claimed that more than 90,000 people had been infected with the virus in China, the virus can spread from one person to 14 people and the virus is starting the second mutation.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |title=Facebook, Twitter, and YouTube struggle with coronavirus hoaxes |last=Ghaffary |first=Shirin | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |website=Vox |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208004124/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The video attracted millions of views on various social media platforms and was mentioned in numerous online reports. However, the BBC noted that contrary to its English subtitles in one of the video's existing versions, the woman does not claim to be either a nurse or a doctor in the video and that her suit and mask do not match the ones worn by medical staff in Hubei.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /> The video's claim of 90,000 infected cases is noted to be 'unsubstantiated'.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\":10\" />\n\n=== Alleged leak of death toll ===\n\nOn February 25, ''[[Taiwan News]]'' published an article, claiming [[Tencent]] accidentally leaked the real numbers of death and infection in China. ''Taiwan News'' suggests the ''Tencent Epidemic Situation Tracker'' had briefly showed infected cases and death tolls many times higher of the official figure, citing a Facebook post by 38-year-old Taiwanese beverage store owner ''Hiroki Lo'' and an anonymous Taiwanese [[netizen]].<ref name=taiwannews3871594>{{cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3871594|title=Tencent may have accidentally leaked real data on Wuhan virus deaths|first=Keoni|last=Everington | name-list-format = vanc |website=[[Taiwan News]]|date=February 2, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200217020907/https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3871594|archive-date=February 17, 2020|access-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The article was referenced by other news outlets such as ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and widely circulated on Twitter, Facebook, 4chan, sparked a wide range of conspiracy theories that the screenshot indicates the real death toll instead of the ones published by health officials.<ref name=bloommag /> Justin Lessler, associate professor at the Bloomberg School of Public Health, claims the numbers of the alleged \"leak\" are unreasonable and unrealistic, citing the case fatality rate as far lower than the 'leaked information'. A spokesman of Tencent responded to the news article, claiming the image was doctored, and it features \"false information which we never published\".<ref name=inews1411992>{{cite web |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/coronavirus-death-toll-story-fake-china-virus-explained-1411992 |title=A massively shared story about the 'real' Coronavirus death toll is fake: Here's how we know |date=February 11, 2020 |website=iNews |last=Sharma |first=Ruchira | name-list-format = vanc |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229191409/https://inews.co.uk/news/coronavirus-death-toll-story-fake-china-virus-explained-1411992 |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nKeoni Everington, author of the original news article, defended and asserted the authenticity of the leak.<ref name=\"bloommag\" /> Brian Hioe and Lars Wooster of ''New Bloom Magazine'' debunked the theory from data on other websites, which were using Tencent's database to generate custom visualizations while showing none of the inflated figures appearing in the images promulgated by ''Taiwan News''. Thus, they concluded the screenshot was digitally fabricated.<ref name=\"bloommag\">{{cite web |url=https://newbloommag.net/2020/02/12/coronavirus-taiwan-news/ |title=TAIWAN NEWS PUBLISHES COVID-19 MISINFORMATION AS EPIDEMIC SPREADS |first=Brian |last=Hioe |first2=Lars |last2=Wooster | name-list-format = vanc |website=New Bloom Magazine |date=February 12, 2020 |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229191408/https://newbloommag.net/2020/02/12/coronavirus-taiwan-news/ |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Misinformation against Taiwan ===\n\n{{further|Cross-Strait relations}}\nOn February 26, 2020, Taiwanese [[Central News Agency (Republic of China)|Central News Agency]] reported that large amounts of misinformation had appeared on Facebook claiming [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Taiwan|the pandemic in Taiwan]] had lost control, the Taiwanese Government had covered up the total number of cases, and that President [[Tsai Ing-wen]] had been infected. The Taiwan fact-checking organization had suggested the misinformation on Facebook shared similarities with [[mainland China]] due to its use of [[simplified Chinese]] and mainland China vocabulary. The organization warns the purpose of the misinformation is to attack the government.<ref name=cna2020022604>{{cite news|url=https://www.cna.com.tw/news/firstnews/202002260428.aspx|script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u75ab\u60c5\u8b20\u8a00\u591a \u4e8b\u5be6\u67e5\u6838\u4e2d\u5fc3\u63073\u5927\u5171\u540c\u9ede|date=February 26, 2020|agency=[[Central News Agency (Republic of China)|Central News Agency]] |language=zh-tw}}</ref><ref name=taipeitimes2003731764>{{cite news |title=Virus Outbreak: Chinese trolls decried for fake news |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/02/28/2003731764 |work=Taipei Times |date=February 28, 2020 |access-date=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301114540/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/02/28/2003731764 |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=20200229reuters>{{cite news |title=Taiwan accuses China of waging cyber 'war' to disrupt virus fight |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/taiwan-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-39-idUSKBN20N09C |agency=Reuters |date=February 29, 2020 |access-date=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301160250/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/taiwan-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-39-idUSKBN20N09C |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Taiwan's [[Ministry of Justice Investigation Bureau]] warned that mainland China was trying to undermine trust in factual news by portraying the Taiwanese Government reports as fake news. Taiwanese authorities have been ordered to use all possible means to track whether the messages were linked to instructions given by the Communist Party of China. The PRC's [[Taiwan Affairs Office]] denied the claims calling them lies and said that Taiwan's [[Democratic Progressive Party]] was \"inciting hatred\" between the two sides. They then claimed that the \"DPP continues to politically manipulate the virus\".<ref name=20200303reuters>{{cite news |first1=Yimou |last1=Lee |first2=Ben |last2=Blanchard | name-list-format = vanc |title='Provocative' China pressures Taiwan with fighters, fake news amid virus outbreak |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-taiwan-china/provocative-china-pressures-taiwan-with-fighters-fake-news-amid-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN20Q08M |agency=Reuters |access-date=March 5, 2020 |quote=\"We have been told to track if the origins are linked to instructions given by the Communist Party, using all possible means,\" the official said, adding that authorities had increased scrutiny on online platforms, including chat rooms. |date=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305160849/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-taiwan-china/provocative-china-pressures-taiwan-with-fighters-fake-news-amid-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN20Q08M |archive-date=March 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to ''[[The Washington Post]]'', China has used organized disinformation campaigns against Taiwan for decades.<ref name=washingtonpost3400200>{{cite web |last1=Fifield |first1=Anna |title=Russia's disinformation campaign in the U.S. has nothing on China's efforts in Taiwan |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/russias-disinformation-campaign-in-the-us-has-nothing-on-chinas-efforts-in-taiwan/2020/01/08/3400200a-231a-11ea-b034-de7dc2b5199b_story.html |work=The Washington Post |access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNick Monaco the research director of the Digital Intelligence Lab at Institute for the Future analyzed the posts and concluded that the majority appear to have come from ordinary users in China not the state. However, he criticized the Chinese government making to decision to allow the information to spread beyond China's [[Great Firewall]] which he described as \"malicious.\"<ref name=npr814709530>{{cite web |title=With Odds Against It, Taiwan Keeps Coronavirus Corralled |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/13/814709530/with-odds-against-it-taiwan-keeps-coronavirus-corralled |publisher=NPR |access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> According to ''Taiwan News'', nearly 1 in 4 cases of misinformation are believed to be connected to mainland China.<ref name=taiwannews3904042>{{cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3904042|title=One-fourth of coronavirus misinformation in Taiwan comes from Chinese trolls: CIB|website=Taiwan News|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2020 the [[American Institute in Taiwan]] announced that it was partnering with the Taiwan FactCheck Center to help combat misinformation about the COVID-19 outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Chen |last1=Yun-yu |first2=Matthew |last2=Mazzetta | name-list-format = vanc |title=AIT partners with local group to combat COVID-19 disinformation |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003270016 |website=focustaiwan.tw |publisher=Focus Taiwan |access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Misrepresented World Population Project map ===\n\nIn early February, a decade-old map illustrating a hypothetical viral outbreak published by the World Population Project (part of the [[University of Southampton]]) was misappropriated by a number of Australian media news outlets (and British tabloids ''The Sun'', ''Daily Mail'' and ''Metro'')<ref name=\":4\" /> which claimed the map represented the 2020 coronavirus outbreak. This misinformation was then spread via the social media accounts of the same media outlets, and while some outlets later removed the map, the BBC reported that a number of news sites had yet to retract the map.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|author=Reality Check team|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51504512|title=How a misleading coronavirus map went global|date=February 19, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219013538/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51504512|archive-date=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Misreported death ===\nDespite sufficient data gathered in regards of case fatality rates by age group,<ref name=\"covidstats\">{{Cite journal|url=https://ourworldindata.org/coronavirus|title=Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19) \u2013 Statistics and Research|first1=Max|last1=Roser|first2=Hannah|last2=Ritchie|first3=Esteban|last3=Ortiz-Ospina|first4=Joe|last4=Hasell|date=March 4, 2020|journal=Our World in Data|via=ourworldindata.org}}</ref> rumours of young people with no premorbidities dying of [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]] virus were circulating social media and were even published by large daily newspapers.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52041709|title=Chloe Middleton: Woman, 21, died with 'no underlying health issues'|website=BBC|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"express\">{{cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/1260123/Chloe-Middleton-coronavirus-death-UK-latest-Facebook-video-COVID-19-symptoms|title=Heartbreak as healthy 21-year-old dies from coronavirus \u2013 'It's not just a virus'|website=Express|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> However, many of these media reports have proven to be false or misrepresented upon closer inspection \u2013 such cases included news about a 21-year old spanish football coach Francisco Garcia<ref name=\"yahoosport\">{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/spanish-football-coach-francisco-garcia-163153573.html|title=Spanish football coach Francisco Garcia dies of coronavirus aged 21|website=Sports Yahoo|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> and British 21-year old woman Chloe Middleton.<ref name=\"theguardian\">{{cite web|url=https://archive.is/20200329015127/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/27/chloe-middleton-death-21-year-old-not-recorded-nhs-covid-19-related|title=Chloe Middleton: death of 21-year-old not recorded as Covid-19|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"spiked\">{{cite web|url=https://www.spiked-online.com/2020/03/27/chloe-middleton-the-coronavirus-death-that-wasnt/|title=Chloe Middleton: the coronavirus death that wasn't|website=Spiked|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>{{MEDCN|date=April 2020}}<!--implication that young people without co-morbidities can't die-->\n\n=== Decline in cellphone subscriptions ===\nThere was a decrease of nearly 21 million cellphone subscriptions among the three largest cellphone carriers in China, which led to the spread of misinformation that this is evidence for millions of deaths due to the coronavirus in China.<ref name=laj-dicu /> However, the decline in cellphone subscriptions is actually attributed to people cancelling phone services as a result of a downturn in the social and economic life during the outbreak.<ref name=laj-dicu>{{cite web |last1=Lajka |first1=Arijeta |title=Drop in cellphone users in China wrongly attributed to coronavirus deaths |url=https://apnews.com/afs:Content:8717250566 |website=AP NEWS |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Medical misinformation ==\n{{Main|List of unproven methods against COVID-19}}\n<!--This article is becoming longer by the day. Please try to add new content in the :List of unproven methods against COVID-19\" page instead of doing so here-->\nWidely circulated posts on social media have made many unfounded claims of methods against coronavirus. Some of these claims are scams, and some promoted methods are dangerous and unhealthy.<ref name=WHO_myths /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Andrew |title=Social media awash with fake treatments for coronavirus |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/social-media-awash-with-fake-treatments-for-coronavirus-20200326-p54e9q.html |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> For misinformation that is a direct claim of a method to prevent, diagnose, or treat COVID-19, see [[List of unproven methods against COVID-19]]. This section deals only with other misinformation or prevent/diagnose/treat claims with wider social consquences.\n\n=== COVID-19 recovery ===\nIt has been wrongly claimed that anyone infected with COVID-19 will have the virus in their bodies for life. While there is no curative treatment, infected individuals can recover from the disease, eliminating the virus from their bodies; getting supportive medical care early can help.<ref name=WHO_myths />\n\n=== Vaccine pre-existence ===\nIt was reported that multiple social media posts have promoted a conspiracy theory claiming the virus was known and that a vaccine was already available. [[PolitiFact]] and [[FactCheck.org]] noted that no vaccine currently exists for COVID-19. The patents cited by various social media posts reference existing patents for genetic sequences and vaccines for other strains of coronavirus such as the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus|SARS coronavirus]].<ref name=20200123politifact>{{cite web |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/jan/23/facebook-posts/there-outbreak-china-wuhan-coronavirus-there-not-v/ |title=No, there is no vaccine for the Wuhan coronavirus |first=Tom |last=Kertscher | name-list-format = vanc |website=Politifact |date=January 23, 2020 |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207133056/https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/jan/23/facebook-posts/there-outbreak-china-wuhan-coronavirus-there-not-v/ |archive-date=February 7, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\" /> The WHO reported as of February 5, 2020 that amid news reports of \"breakthrough\" drugs being discovered to treat people infected with the virus, there were no known effective treatments;<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-treatments-who-idUSKBN1ZZ1M6 |title=WHO: 'no known effective' treatments for new coronavirus |date=February 5, 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=February 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205155653/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-treatments-who-idUSKBN1ZZ1M6 |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> this included antibiotics and herbal remedies not being useful.<ref name=aljazeera2002020934>{{cite news |title=Dispelling the myths around the new coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2020/02/dispelling-myths-coronavirus-outbreak-200202093426388.html |access-date=February 8, 2020 |publisher=Al Jazeera |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206033735/https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2020/02/dispelling-myths-coronavirus-outbreak-200202093426388.html?utm_source=website&utm_medium=article_page&utm_campaign=read_more_links |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[COVID-19 vaccine|Scientists are working to develop a vaccine]], but as of March 18, 2020, no vaccine candidates have completed clinical trials.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n=== Cocaine ===\nCocaine does not protect against COVID-19. Several viral tweets purporting that snorting [[cocaine]] would sterilize one's nostrils of the coronavirus spread around Europe and Africa. In response, the [[French Ministry of Health]] released a public service announcement debunking this claim, saying \"No, cocaine does NOT protect against COVID-19. It is an addictive drug that causes serious side effects and is harmful to people\u2019s health.\" The [[World Health Organisation]] also debunked the claim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/news/french-government-cocaine-coke-coronavirus-hoax/|title=Sorry to the French People Who Thought Cocaine Would Protect Them From Coronavirus|last=Crellin|first=Zac | name-list-format = vanc |website=Pedestrian.TV|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311082415/https://www.pedestrian.tv/news/french-government-cocaine-coke-coronavirus-hoax/|archive-date=March 11, 2020|url-status=live|date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Ethnic resistance/susceptibilty ===\n\nThere have been claims that specific [[ethnicities]] are more or less vulnerable to COVID-19. COVID-19 is a new [[zoonotic]] disease, so no population has yet had the time to develop [[population immunity]].{{medcn|date=April 2020}}\n\nBeginning on February 11, reports, quickly spread via Facebook, implied that a Cameroonian student in China had been completely cured of the virus due to his African genetics. While a student was successfully treated, other media sources have noted that no evidence implies Africans are more resistant to the virus and labeled such claims as false information.<ref name=20200212afp>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/black-people-arent-more-resistant-novel-coronavirus|title=Black people aren't more resistant to novel coronavirus|date=February 12, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|access-date=February 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216141447/https://factcheck.afp.com/black-people-arent-more-resistant-novel-coronavirus|archive-date=February 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Kenyan Secretary of Health [[Mutahi Kagwe]] explicitly refuted rumors that \"those with black skin cannot get coronavirus\", while announcing Kenya's first case on March 13.<ref name=20200313cnn>{{cite news|title=Minister rejects false rumors that 'those with black skin cannot get coronavirus' as Kenya records first case|first1=Mia|last1=Alberti|first2=Bethlehem|last2=Feleke| name-list-format = vanc |publisher=CNN|url=https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-13-20-intl-hnk/h_daa3fbd19db18fdbb4be569a9613fe96|date=March 13, 2020|access-date=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319003805/https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-13-20-intl-hnk/h_daa3fbd19db18fdbb4be569a9613fe96|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This myth was cited as a contributing factor in the disproportionately high rates of infection and death observed among African Americans.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Poston |first1=Ben |last2=Barboza |first2=Tony |last3=Jennings |first3=Angel | name-list-format = vanc |title=L.A. releases first racial breakdown of coronavirus fatalities; blacks have higher death rate|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=April 7, 2020 |access-date=April 10, 2020 |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-04-07/l-a-releases-first-racial-breakdown-of-coronavirus-fatalities-african-americans-have-higher-death-rate}}</ref><ref name=usatoday2961323001>{{cite news|last=Barfield Berry |first=Deborah | name-list-format = vanc  |title=Black people dying from coronavirus at much higher rates in cities across the USA | newspaper=USA Today |date=April 7, 2020 |access-date=April 10, 2020 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2020/04/07/who-dying-coronavirus-more-black-people-die-major-cities/2961323001/}}</ref>\n\nThere have been claims of \"Indian immunity\": that the people of India have more immunity to the COVID-19 virus due to living conditions in India. This idea was deemed \"absolute drivel\" by Dr. Anand Krishnan, professor at the Centre for Community Medicine of the [[All India Institute of Medical Sciences]] (AIIMS). He said that there was no [[population immunity]] to the COVID-19 virus yet, as it is new, and it is not even clear whether people who have recovered from COVID-19 will have lasting immunity, as this happens with some viruses but not with others.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vegetarian food, Indian immunity won\u2019t prevent Covid-19, says Anand Krishnan |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/coronavirus-cases-cure-symptoms-precautions-aiims-6314643/ |work=The Indian Express |date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] claimed that the virus was genetically targeted at Iranians by the USA, and this is why it is [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|seriously affecting Iran]]. He did not offer any evidence.<ref name=\"independent-corona\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Iran's leader suggests US cooked up 'special version' of virus to target country |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/iran-coronavirus-us-target-country-special-version-covid19-a9417206.html |work=The Independent |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=france2420200322>{{cite news |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200322-iran-s-supreme-leader-khamanei-refuses-us-help-to-fight-coronavirus-citing-conspiracy-theory |title=Iran's Khamanei refuses US help to fight coronavirus, citing conspiracy theory |date= March 22, 2020|publisher=France 24 }}</ref>\n\n===COVID-19 xenophobic blaming by ethnicity===<!--not sure if this doesn't belong with some of the nationally-based blaming above-->\nCOVID-19-related [[xenophobic]] attacks have been made against people the attacker blamed for COVID-19 on the basis of their ethnicity. The [[Asian Australian Alliance]] did a survey on attacks against Asian Australians in April 2020; 81% of victims said they believed the attack against them was related to the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zhou |first1=Naaman |title=Survey of Covid-19 racism against Asian Australians records 178 incidents in two weeks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/17/survey-of-covid-19-racism-against-asian-australians-records-178-incidents-in-two-weeks |work=The Guardian |date=17 April 2020}}</ref> [[White supremacist]] groups have blamed COVID-19 on non-whites and advocated deliberately infecting minorities they dislike, such as Jews.<ref>{{cite web |title=World \u2013 as-world-struggles-to-stop-deaths-far-right-celebrates-covid-19 \u2013 News \u2013 msn |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/as-world-struggles-to-stop-deaths-far-right-celebrates-covid-19/ |website=www.msn.com}}</ref>\n\n<!--On the basis of historical examples, there have been warnings about discriminating by immunity.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Olivarius |first1=Kathryn |title=The Dangerous History of Immunoprivilege |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/opinion/coronavirus-immunity-passports.html |website=The New York Times |date=12 April 2020}}</ref>-->\n\n=== 5G ===\nThe theories linking 5G mobile phone networks to COVID-19 were described as the \"worst kind of fake news\" by Professor Steve Powis, national medical director of [[NHS England]].<ref name=\"ie-mast-fires-surge-in-the-uk-over-easter-weekend-amid-5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theories\" /> Viruses cannot be transmitted by [[radio waves]]. COVID-19 is spreading in many countries which do not have 5G networks.<ref name=WHO_myths />\n\nIn February 2020, [[BBC News]] reported that conspiracy theorists on social media groups alleged a link between coronavirus and [[5G]] mobile networks, claiming that [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|Wuhan]] and [[Diamond Princess outbreak]]s were [[Wireless device radiation and health|directly caused by electromagnetic fields and the introduction of 5G and wireless technologies]]. Some conspiracy theorists also alleged that the coronavirus outbreak was [[cover-up]] for a 5G-related illness.<ref name=\"bbc-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51646309|title=Coronavirus: Fake news is spreading fast|work=[[BBC]]|date=February 26, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Rory|last=Cellan-Jones| name-list-format = vanc |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317062547/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51646309|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2020, Thomas Cowan, a [[Alternative medicine|holistic medical practitioner]] who trained as a physician and operates on probation with [[Medical Board of California]], alleged that coronavirus is caused by 5G, based on the claims that [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|African countries were not affected significantly by the pandemic]] and Africa was not a 5G region.<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\" /><ref name=\"cbc-5g\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/fact-check-viral-video-coronavirus-1.5506595|title= Viral video claiming 5G caused pandemic easily debunked|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date= March 23, 2020 |first1=Katie |last1=Nicholson |first2=Jason |last2=Ho |first3=Jeff |last3=Yates| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-date= March 26, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326125553/https://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/fact-check-viral-video-coronavirus-1.5506595}}</ref> Cowan also falsely alleged that the viruses were wastes from cells that are poisoned by electromagnetic fields and historical viral pandemics coincided with the major developments in radio technology.<ref name=\"cbc-5g\" /> The video of his claims went viral and was recirculated by celebrities including [[Woody Harrelson]], [[John Cusack]], and singer [[Keri Hilson]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Satariano |first1=Adam |last2=Alba |first2=Davey | name-list-format = vanc |title=Burning Cell Towers, Out of Baseless Fear They Spread the Virus |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/10/technology/coronavirus-5g-uk.html |work=The New York Times |date=10 April 2020}}</ref> The claims may also have been recirculated by an alleged \"coordinated disinformation campaign\", similar to campaigns used by the [[Internet Research Agency]] in Saint Petersburg, Russia.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gallagher |first1=Ryan |title=5G Virus Conspiracy Theory Fueled by Coordinated Effort |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-09/covid-19-link-to-5g-technology-fueled-by-coordinated-effort |access-date=12 April 2020 |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=9 April 2020}}</ref> The claims were criticized on social media and debunked by [[Reuters]],<ref name=\"reuters-5g\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-coronavirus-5g/false-claim-5g-networks-are-making-people-sick-not-coronavirus-idUSKBN2133TI|title=False claim: 5G networks are making people sick, not Coronavirus|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=March 17, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320023007/https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-coronavirus-5g/false-claim-5g-networks-are-making-people-sick-not-coronavirus-idUSKBN2133TI|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'',<ref name=usatoday2873731001>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/2020/03/21/did-5-g-cause-coronavirus-covid-19-pandemic/2873731001/ |title= Here's why 5G and coronavirus are not connected |last=O'Donnell |first=Bob | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 21, 2020 |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=March 22, 2020|archive-date=March 21, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321213438/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/2020/03/21/did-5-g-cause-coronavirus-covid-19-pandemic/2873731001/}}</ref> [[Full Fact]]<ref name=20200313fullfact>{{cite web |url=https://fullfact.org/online/coronavirus-5G/ |title= These claims about the new coronavirus and 5G are unfounded |last=Krishna |first= Rachael | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 13, 2020 |work=[[Full Fact]] |access-date=March 22, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320160841/https://fullfact.org/online/coronavirus-5G/|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[American Public Health Association]] executive director [[Georges C. Benjamin]].<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/youtube-video-suggests-5g-internet-causes-coronavirus-people-are-falling-it-1493321|title= Youtube Video Suggests 5G Internet Causes Coronavirus and People Are Falling For It|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=March 19, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Kelly|last=Wynne | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref><ref name=\"huffington-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/keri-hilson-5g-did-not-cause-coronavirus_n_5e6f8ba7c5b6dda30fce0348|title=No, Keri Hilson, 5G Did Not Cause Coronavirus|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=March 16, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Taryn|last=Finley| name-list-format = vanc |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319232700/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/keri-hilson-5g-did-not-cause-coronavirus_n_5e6f8ba7c5b6dda30fce0348|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter telecommunications masts in several parts of the United Kingdom were the subject of arson attacks, British Cabinet Office Minister [[Michael Gove]] said the theory that COVID-19 virus may be spread by [[5G]] wireless communication is \"just nonsense, dangerous nonsense as well.\"<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-britain-5g/5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory-is-dangerous-fake-nonsense-uk-says-idUSKBN21M0MS 5G coronavirus conspiracy theory is dangerous fake nonsense, UK says] Reuters Technology News, April 4, 2020</ref> [[Vodafone UK|Vodafone]] announced that two Vodafone masts and two it shares with [[O2 (UK)|O2]] had been targeted.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2020/04/06/5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory-telecom-tower-fires/|title=5G-coronavirus conspiracy theory spurs rash of telecom tower arson fires|website=Fortune}}</ref>\n\nBy April 6, 2020 at least 20 mobile phone masts in the UK had been vandalised since the previous Thursday.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims>{{Cite news|title=At least 20 UK phone masts vandalised over false 5G coronavirus claims|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/06/at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims|last=Waterson|first=Jim| name-list-format = vanc |date=April 6, 2020|access-date=April 11, 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|last2=Hern|first2=Alex}}</ref> Because of slow rollout of 5G in the UK, many of the damaged masts had only 3G and 4G equipment.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims /> Mobile phone and home broadband operators estimated there were at least 30 incidents of confronting engineers maintaining equipment in the week up to April 6.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims /> There have been eleven incidents of attempted arson at mobile phone masts in the Netherlands, including one case where \"Fuck 5G\" was written, as well as in Ireland and Cyprus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2330065-brand-bij-vier-zendmasten-heel-sterk-vermoeden-van-brandstichting.html|title=Brand bij vier zendmasten: 'Heel sterk vermoeden van brandstichting'|date=April 10, 2020|work=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting]]|access-date=April 11, 2020|url-status=live|language=nl}}</ref><!-- FT article not paywalled --><ref>{{cite news|last1=Fildes|first1=Nic|last2=Di Stefano|first2=Mark|last3=Murphy|first3=Hannah | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.ft.com/content/1eeedb71-d9dc-4b13-9b45-fcb7898ae9e1|title=How a 5G coronavirus conspiracy spread across Europe|work=Financial Times|date=16 April 2020|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> Facebook has deleted multiple messages encouraging attacks on 5G equipment.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims />\n\nEngineers working for [[Openreach]] posted pleas on anti-5G Facebook groups asking to be spared abuse as they are not involved with maintaining mobile networks.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies>{{Cite news|title=Broadband engineers threatened due to 5G coronavirus conspiracies|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/03/broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies|last=Waterson|first=Jim| name-list-format = vanc |date=April 3, 2020|access-date=April 5, 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Mobile UK said that the incidents were affecting attempts to maintain networks that support home working and provide critical connections to vulnerable customers, emergency services and hospitals.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies /> A widely circulated video shows people working for broadband company Community Fibre being abused by a woman who accuses them of installing 5G as part of a plan to kill the population.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies />\n\nYouTube announced that it would reduce the amount of content claiming links between 5G and coronavirus.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory>{{Cite news|title=YouTube moves to limit spread of false coronavirus 5G theory|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory|last=Hern|first=Alex| name-list-format = vanc |date=April 5, 2020|access-date=April 5, 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Videos that are conspiratorial about 5G that do not mention coronavirus would not be removed, though they might be considered \"borderline content\", removed from search recommendations and losing advertising revenue.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory /> The discredited theories had been promoted by British conspiracy theorist [[David Icke]] in videos (subsequently removed) on YouTube and Vimeo, and an interview by [[London Live]] TV network, prompting calls for action by [[Ofcom]].<ref name=bbc52198946>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-52198946  Leo Kelion, \"Coronavirus: YouTube tightens rules after David Icke 5G interview\", ''BBC News'', 7 April 2020]. Retrieved April 7, 2020</ref><ref name=extremetech308888>{{Cite web|url=https://www.extremetech.com/extreme/308888-youtube-says-it-will-remove-5g-misinformation-as-frightened-people-burn-cell-towers|title=YouTube Says It Will Remove 5G Misinformation After People Burn Cell Towers \u2013 ExtremeTech|website=extremetech.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 April 2020, [[Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na|Garda\u00ed]] were investigating fires at 5G masts in [[County Donegal]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]].<ref name=tj-5g-masts-set-on-fire-donegal>{{Cite news|title=Garda\u00ed suspect fires at 5G masts were deliberate after coal found|url=https://www.thejournal.ie/5g-masts-set-on-fire-donegal-5073466-Apr2020/|last=Maguire|first=Stephen| name-list-format = vanc |date=13 April 2020|access-date=14 April 2020|work=[[TheJournal.ie]]}}</ref> Garda\u00ed and fire services had attended the fires the previous night in an attempt to put them out.<ref name=tj-5g-masts-set-on-fire-donegal /> Although Garda\u00ed were awaiting results of tests they were treating the fires as deliberate.<ref name=tj-5g-masts-set-on-fire-donegal />\n\nThere were 20 suspected arson attacks on phone masts in the UK over the [[Easter]] 2020 weekend.<ref name=\"ie-mast-fires-surge-in-the-uk-over-easter-weekend-amid-5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theories\">{{cite news |title=Mast fires surge in the UK over Easter weekend amid 5G-coronavirus conspiracy theories |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/world/mast-fires-surge-in-the-uk-over-easter-weekend-amid-5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theories-994035.html |agency=Press Association |newspaper=[[Irish Examiner]]|date=14 April 2020}}</ref> These included an incident in [[Dagenham]] where three men were arrested on suspicion of arson, a fire in [[Huddersfield]] that affected a mast used by emergency services and a fire in a mast that provides mobile connectivity to the [[NHS Nightingale Hospital Birmingham]].<ref name=\"ie-mast-fires-surge-in-the-uk-over-easter-weekend-amid-5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theories\" />\n\n[[Ofcom]] issued guidance to [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]] following comments by [[Eamonn Holmes]] after comments made by Holmes about 5G and coronavirus on [[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]].<ref name=bbc-ofcom-rules-on-eamonn-holmes-and-david-icke-comments>{{Cite news|title=Coronavirus: Ofcom rules on Eamonn Holmes and David Icke comments|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-52358920|date=20 April 2020|access-date=20 April 2020|publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref> Ofcom said the comments were \"ambiguous\" and \"ill-judged\" and they \"risked undermining viewers' trust in advice from public authorities and scientific evidence\".<ref name=bbc-ofcom-rules-on-eamonn-holmes-and-david-icke-comments/> Ofcom also local channel [[London Live (TV channel)|London Live]] in breach of standards for an interview it had with David Icke who it said had \"\nexpressed views which had the potential to cause significant harm to viewers in London during the pandemic\".<ref name=bbc-ofcom-rules-on-eamonn-holmes-and-david-icke-comments/>\n\n=== Vegetarian immunity ===\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}<!--this seems to be more complex tahn just a claim that if you dont' eat meat you will not get infected-->\nClaims that [[vegetarian]]s are immune to coronavirus spread online in India, causing \"#NoMeat_NoCoronaVirus\" to trend on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web|access-date=March 3, 2020|title='No Meat, No Coronavirus' Makes No Sense|url=https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|website=The Wire|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303034133/https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>{{better source|date=April 2020}} Eating meat does not have an effect on COVID-19 spread, except for people [[zoonosis|near where animals are slaughtered]], said Dr. Anand Krishnan, professor at the Centre for Community Medicine of the [[All India Institute of Medical Sciences]] (AIIMS).<ref>{{cite web |title=Vegetarian food, Indian immunity won\u2019t prevent Covid-19, says Anand Krishnan |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/coronavirus-cases-cure-symptoms-precautions-aiims-6314643/ |website=The Indian Express |date=15 March 2020}}</ref> Fisheries, Dairying and Animal Husbandry Minister Giriraj Singh said that the rumour had significantly affected industry, with the price of a chicken falling to a third of pre-pandemic levels. He also described efforts to improve the hygiene of the meat supply chain.<ref>{{cite news |title=Non-vegetarian food does not cause COVID-19, says Minister |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/non-vegetarian-food-does-not-cause-covid-19-says-minister/article31003791.ece |work=The Hindu |date=6 March 2020 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\n=== Alcohol (ethanol and poisonous methanol) ===\nContrary to some reports, drinking alcohol does not protect against COVID-19, and can increase health risks<ref name=WHO_myths /> ([[Short-term effects of alcohol consumption|short term]] and [[Long-term effects of alcohol|long term]]). [[Drinking alcohol]] is [[ethanol]]; other [[alcohols]], such as [[methanol]], which causes [[methanol poisoning]], are acutely poisonous, and may be present in badly-prepared alcoholic beverages.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Beauchamp GA, Valento M | title = Toxic Alcohol Ingestion: Prompt Recognition And Management In The Emergency Department | journal = Emergency Medicine Practice | volume = 18 | issue = 9 | pages = 1\u201320 | date = September 2016 | pmid = 27538060 }}</ref>\n\nIran has reported incidents of methanol poisoning, caused by the false belief that drinking alcohol would cure or protect against coronavirus;<ref name=\"independent-methanol\" /> [[Alcohol in Iran|alcohol is banned in Iran]], and [[bootleg alcohol]] may [[Bootleg alcohol#Safety|contain methanol]].<ref name=\"slate-methanol\" /> According to Iranian media, nearly 300 people have died and over a thousand have become ill due to [[Methanol toxicity|methanol poisoning]], while [[Associated Press]] gave figures of around 480 deaths with 2,850 others affected.<ref name=\"ap-nytimes-methanol\" /> Iranian social media had circulated a story from British tabloids that a British man and others had been cured of coronavirus with [[whiskey]] and honey,<ref name=\"independent-methanol\" /><ref name=mirror21418662>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/coronavirus-first-brit-who-caught-21418662 |title=Coronavirus: British man who caught virus 'beat flu with glass of hot whisky' |work=The Mirror |date=February 3, 2020 }}</ref> which combined with the use of alcohol-based<!--not just ethanol!--> [[hand sanitizer]]s as disinfectants, led to the false belief that drinking high-proof alcohol can kill the virus.<ref name=\"independent-methanol\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/iran-coronavirus-methanol-drink-cure-deaths-fake-a9429956.html |title= Coronavirus: Hundreds dead in Iran from drinking methanol amid fake reports it cures disease |first=Bel |last=Trew| name-list-format = vanc  |work=[[The Independent]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"slate-methanol\">{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/03/hundreds-die-iran-drinking-bootleg-alcohol-methanol-coronavirus-cure-social-media.html |title= Hundreds Die in Iran From Bootleg Alcohol Being Peddled Online as Fake Coronavirus Remedy |first=Elliot |last=Hannon | name-list-format = vanc |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ap-nytimes-methanol\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/27/world/middleeast/ap-ml-virus-outbreak-iran-a-deadly-drink.html |title= In Iran, False Belief a Poison Fights Virus Kills Hundreds |work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 28, 2020|archive-date=March 28, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200328174609/https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/27/world/middleeast/ap-ml-virus-outbreak-iran-a-deadly-drink.html}}</ref>\n\nSimilar incidents have occurred in Turkey, with 30 [[Turkmens|Turkmenistan citizens]] dying from methanol poisoning related to coronavirus cure claims.<ref name=20200325cnnturk>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnnturk.com/video/turkiye/9-kisi-daha-saf-alkolden-oldu |title=9 ki\u015fi daha saf alkolden \u00f6ld\u00fc |date=March 25, 2020 |website=[[CNN T\u00fcrk]] |access-date=March 28, 2020 |language=Turkish}}</ref><ref name=hurriyet41473161>{{cite web |url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/katil-sahte-alkol-41473161 |title= Katil: Sahte alkol |date=March 20, 2020 |website=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |last=Ayd\u0131n |first=\u00c7etin | name-list-format = vanc |access-date=March 28, 2020 |language=Turkish}}</ref>\n\n=== Efficacy of hand sanitiser, \"antibacterial\" soaps ===\nClaims that [[hand sanitiser]] is merely \"antibacterial not antiviral\", and therefore not effective against the coronavirus, have spread widely on Twitter and other social networks, not only in the US but also elsewhere. While the effectiveness of sanitiser depends on the specific ingredients, most hand sanitiser sold commercially{{medical citation needed|date=April 2020}} does destroy the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/health/does-hand-sanitiser-sanitizer-kill-coronavirus-antiviral-antibacterial-viral-tweet/|title=Those Viral Posts Claiming Hand Sanitiser Doesn't Kill Coronavirus Are Wrong & Here's Why|last=Crellin|first=Zac | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 4, 2020|website=Pedestrian.TV|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305012603/https://www.pedestrian.tv/health/does-hand-sanitiser-sanitizer-kill-coronavirus-antiviral-antibacterial-viral-tweet/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> [[Hand sanitizer]] is recommended against COVID-19,<ref name=WHO_myths /> though unlike soap, it is not effective against all types of germs.<ref>{{cite web |title=Show Me the Science \u2013 When & How to Use Hand Sanitizer in Community Settings |author=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |url=https://www.cdc.gov/handwashing/show-me-the-science-hand-sanitizer.html |website=www.cdc.gov |language=en-us |date=3 March 2020}}</ref> Washing in soap and water for at least 20 seconds is recommended by the US Centers for Disease Control as the best way to clean hands in most situations. However, if soap and water are not available, a hand sanitizer that is at least 60% alcohol can be used instead, unless hands are visibly dirty or greasy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/disinfecting-your-home.html |website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |language=en-us |date=11 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=When and How to Wash Your Hands|author= Centers for Disease Control |url=https://www.cdc.gov/handwashing/when-how-handwashing.html |website=www.cdc.gov |language=en-us |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> The US CDC and the Food and Drug Administration recommend plain soap; there is no evidence that \"[[antibacterial soap]]s\" are any better, and limited evidence that they might be worse long-term.<ref>{{cite web |author=Center for Drug Evaluation and Research |title=Q&A for Consumers: Hand Sanitizers and COVID-19 |url=https://www.fda.gov/drugs/information-drug-class/qa-consumers-hand-sanitizers-and-covid-19 |website=FDA |language=en |date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Antibacterial Soap? You Can Skip It, Use Plain Soap and Water |url=https://www.fda.gov/consumers/consumer-updates/antibacterial-soap-you-can-skip-it-use-plain-soap-and-water |website=FDA |author=Office of the Commissioner |language=en |date=16 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Public use of face masks ===\nSeveral governments and institutions have initially dismissed the use of face masks by the general population, often with misleading or incomplete information about the usefulness of masks.<ref name=\"thenational.scot\">{{cite web |author= Watterson, Andrew |title=Through all the misinformation, what is the truth of wearing face masks? |url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/18385472.misinformation-truth-wearing-face-masks/ |website=The National |date=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vanityfair.com\">{{cite web |last1=Frank |first1=T. A. |title=\"I Was Looking at Them in the Wrong Way\": Mask Misinformation and the Failure of the Elites |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2020/04/mask-misinformation-and-the-failure-of-the-elites |website=Vanity Fair |date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=npr-wta>{{cite web |last1=Huo |first1=Jingnan |title=Why There Are So Many Different Guidelines For Face Masks For The Public |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/04/10/829890635/why-there-so-many-different-guidelines-for-face-masks-for-the-public |website=NPR.org |date=10 April 2020}}</ref> Zeynep Tufekci, an associate professor at the University of North Carolina, suggests that the authorities dismissed mask usage by the general public in their messaging to manage shortages of supplies rather than confronting the reality of the situation.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite web |last1=Tufekci |first1=Zeynep |title=Why Telling People They Don\u2019t Need Masks Backfired |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/opinion/coronavirus-face-masks.html |website=The New York Times |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> Some news commentators have also similarly suggested that this messaging is due to the shortages, as governments did not act quickly, and therefore goes beyond the science or was a lie.<ref name=npr-wta/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Carlson |first1=Tucker |title=Tucker Carlson: We understand there's a shortage of medical masks. Stop lying to us and tell the truth |url=https://www.foxnews.com/opinion/tucker-carlson-shortage-medical-masks-stop-lying |website=Fox News |date=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Abrupt reversals on face mask policy raise new questions |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200405-coronavirus-abrupt-reversal-on-mask-policy-in-france-and-the-us-raises-new-questions |website=France 24 |date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Walther |first1=Matthew |title=The noble lie about masks and coronavirus should never have been told |url=https://theweek.com/articles/906647/noble-lie-about-masks-coronavirus-should-never-have-been-told |website=The Week |date=4 April 2020}}</ref> Tufekci remarks that the public received contradictory pieces of information about the usage of face masks, while they had been better informed about other preventive measures such as hand washing and social distancing.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>\n\nJeremy Howard, researcher at the  University of San Francisco, stated that there is a \"senseless and unscientific push for the general public to avoid wearing masks\" and that delays for official recommendations to catch up with scientific thinking may prove to be disastrous.<ref name=hj-wapo /> He noted that there is no good reason given to avoid wearing a mask, even a home-made mask, in public, noting that the evidence does not support an anti-mask push to the public and quoting the [[Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention]] director-general [[George Fu Gao]]'s statement that \"Many people have asymptomatic or presymptomatic infections. If they are wearing face masks, it can prevent droplets that carry the virus from escaping and infecting others.\"<ref name=hj-wapo>{{cite web |last1=Howard |first1=Jeremy |title=Simple DIY masks could help flatten the curve. We should all wear them in public. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2020/03/28/masks-all-coronavirus/ |website=Washington Post |date=28 March 2020}}</ref> Lawrence Gostin, professor at the Georgetown University, mentioned that, few weeks ago, even informed members of the general public would have said that face masks do not work as a result of the [[World Health Organization]] and [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] guidelines, but that would not have been correct based upon the then-known science about potential benefits of masks for the public.<ref name=npr-wta />\n\nAndrew Watterson, professor at the University of Stirling, stated that, even though there is no evidence that non-medical masks are an effective means of respiratory protection, there is some evidence they may reduce the transmission of viruses, and that the WHO concluded that there was no evidence to recommend for or against non-medical face masks, which is different than stating that they do not work.<ref name=\"thenational.scot\" /> Harvard epidemiologist Bill Hanage remarked about masks that \"You're not wearing them to stop yourself getting infected, but to stop someone else getting infected,\" and said that the dismissive outlook of masks is a wrong way to look at it.<ref name=\"vanityfair.com\"/> Howard said that wearing masks is considered a [[prosocial behavior]] in which one protects others in one's community in certain countries, which is a stark contrast to the messaging in countries where mask wearing is discouraged, and should be part of the solution.<ref name=hj-wapo />\n\n=== Ibuprofen ===\nA tweet from French health minister [[Olivier V\u00e9ran]], a bulletin from the French health ministry, and a small speculative study in ''[[The Lancet Respiratory Medicine]]'' raised concerns about ibuprofen worsening COVID-19, which spread extensively on social media. The European Medicines Agency<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/03/18/818026613/advice-from-france-to-avoid-ibuprofen-for-covid-19-leaves-experts-baffled|title=Concerned About Taking Ibuprofen For Coronavirus Symptoms? Here's What Experts Say|website=NPR.org}}</ref> and the World Health Organization recommended COVID-19 patients keep taking ibuprofen as directed, citing lack of convincing evidence of any danger.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/health/medical/fact-finders-do-ibuprofen-and-other-common-medications-make-covid-19-symptoms-worse/ar-BB12O16s|title=Fact Finders: Do ibuprofen and other common medications make COVID-19 symptoms worse?|website=www.msn.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Helicopter spraying ===\nIn some Asian countries, it has been claimed that one should stay at home on particular days when helicopters spray disinfectant over homes for killing off COVID-19; no such spraying is taking place.<ref name=20200326afpA>{{cite news |title=False claim circulates online that certain countries in Asia are using helicopters to spray 'COVID-19 disinfectant' |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claim-circulates-online-certain-countries-asia-are-using-helicopters-spray-covid-19 |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330085147/https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claim-circulates-online-certain-countries-asia-are-using-helicopters-spray-covid-19|archive-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200320afp>{{cite news |title=Indian authorities refute 'fake' advisory which claimed disinfectant would be sprayed across India to tackle COVID-19 |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/indian-authorities-refute-fake-advisory-which-claimed-disinfectant-would-be-sprayed-across-india |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408121452/https://factcheck.afp.com/indian-authorities-refute-fake-advisory-which-claimed-disinfectant-would-be-sprayed-across-india|archive-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Mosquitos ===\nIt has been claimed that [[mosquitos]] transmit coronavirus. There is no evidence that this is true; coronavirus spreads through small droplets of saliva and snot.<ref name=WHO_myths /> Colder northern-hemisphere countries have had COVID-19 spread long before the first mosquitos of spring emerge.\n\n=== Cruise ships safety from infection ===\n[[File:COVID-19 Outbreak World Map per Capita.svg|thumb|upright=1.8|Claims by cruise-ship operators notwithstanding, there are many cases of coronaviruses in hot climates; some countries on the [[Caribbean]], the [[Mediterranean]], and the [[Persian Gulf]] are severely affected.]]\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships}}\nIn March 2020, the ''[[Miami New Times]]'' reported that managers at [[Norwegian Cruise Line]] had prepared a set of responses intended to convince wary customers to book cruises, including \"blatantly false\" claims that the coronavirus \"can only survive in cold temperatures, so the Caribbean is a fantastic choice for your next cruise\", that \"[s]cientists and medical professionals have confirmed that the warm weather of the spring will be the end of the [c]oronavirus\", and that the virus \"cannot live in the amazingly warm and tropical temperatures that your cruise will be sailing to.\"<ref name=\"nmt-cardona\">{{cite web|url=https://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/coronavirus-norwegian-cruise-line-leaked-emails-show-booking-strategy-11590056|title=Leaked Emails: Norwegian Pressures Sales Team to Mislead Potential Customers About Coronavirus|last1=Cardona|first1=Alexi C.|date=March 11, 2020|work=Miami New Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312003229/https://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/coronavirus-norwegian-cruise-line-leaked-emails-show-booking-strategy-11590056|archive-date=March 12, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFlu is seasonal (becoming less frequent in the summer) in some countries, but not in others. While it is possible that the COVID-19 coronavirus will also show some seasonality, it is not yet known.<ref name=\"newsweek-02-11-2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/could-coronavirus-really-killed-hot-weather-scientists-weigh-1486709|title=Could Coronavirus Really Be Killed by Hot Weather? Scientists Weigh In|last1=Gander|first1=Kashmira|date=February 11, 2020|magazine=Newsweek|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310145434/https://www.newsweek.com/could-coronavirus-really-killed-hot-weather-scientists-weigh-1486709|archive-date=March 10, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020|quote=Dr. Ravinder Kanda, senior lecturer in evolutionary genomics at Oxford Brookes University, U,.K., told Newsweek: \"Little is known about the seasonal dynamics of this particular virus\u2014we cannot take it for granted that the warmer weather will simply drive the virus out of existence.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"time-gunia\">{{cite news|url=https://time.com/5790880/coronavirus-warm-weather-summer/|title=Will Warmer Weather Stop the Spread of the Coronavirus? Don't Count on It, Say Experts|last1=Gunia|first1=Amy|date=February 28, 2020|magazine=Time|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309112416/https://time.com/5790880/coronavirus-warm-weather-summer/|archive-date=March 9, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020|quote=Dr. Nancy Messionnier of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, warned against assuming the number of cases will slow as the weather warms. \"I think it\u2019s premature to assume that,\" she said during a call with reporters on February 12. \"We haven\u2019t been through even a single year with this pathogen.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"fox-farber\">{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-die-out-warm-weather-trump|title=Will the coronavirus die out as the weather warms?|last1=Farber|first1=Madeline|date=February 20, 2020|publisher=Fox News Channel|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305173144/https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-die-out-warm-weather-trump|archive-date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020|quote=\"We hope that the gradual spring will help this virus recede, but our crystal ball is not very clear. The new coronavirus is a respiratory virus, and we know respiratory viruses are often seasonal, but not always. For example, influenza (flu) tends to be seasonal in the U.S., but in other parts of the world, it exists year-round. Scientists don\u2019t fully understand why even though we have been studying [the] flu for many years,\" Dr. William Schaffner, the medical director of the National Foundation for Infectious Diseases, told Fox News in an email.}}</ref>{{medical citation needed|date=April 2020}} The COVID-19 coronavirus spread along international air travel routes, including to tropical locations.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Venkatesh S, Memish ZA | title = SARS: the new challenge to international health and travel medicine | journal = Eastern Mediterranean Health Journal = La Revue De Sante De La Mediterranee Orientale = Al-Majallah Al-Sihhiyah Li-Sharq Al-Mutawassit | volume = 10 | issue = 4-5 | pages = 655\u201362 | date = 25 January 2004 | pmid = 16335659 | url = https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00885-w }}</ref> [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships|Outbreaks on cruise ships]], where an older population lives in close quarters, frequently touching surfaces which others have touched, were common.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Browne A, Ahmad SS, Beck CR, Nguyen-Van-Tam JS | title = The roles of transportation and transportation hubs in the propagation of influenza and coronaviruses: a systematic review | journal = Journal of Travel Medicine | volume = 23 | issue = 1 | pages = tav002 | date = January 2016 | pmid = 26782122 | doi = 10.1093/jtm/tav002 | url = https://academic.oup.com/jtm/article/23/1/tav002/2635586 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Mallapaty S | title = What the cruise-ship outbreaks reveal about COVID-19 | journal = Nature | volume = 580 | issue = 7801 | pages = 18 | date = April 2020 | pmid = 32218546 | doi = 10.1038/d41586-020-00885-w }}</ref>\n\nIt seems that COVID-19 can be transmitted in all climates.<ref name=WHO_myths>{{cite web |title=Myth busters |url=https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public/myth-busters |website=www.who.int |publisher=World Health Organization |language=en}}</ref> It has seriously affected many warm-climate countries. For instance, [[Dubai]], with an [[Climate of Dubai|year-round average daily high of 28.0 Celsius (82.3\u00b0F)]] and [[Dubai International Airport|the airport said to have the world's most international traffic]], has had [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Arab Emirates|thousands of cases]].\n\n=== Country-specific ===\n\n==== Australia ====\n\nA warning, claiming to be from the [[Australia Department of Health]] said that coronavirus  spreads through petrol pumps  and that everyone should wear gloves when filling up petrol in their cars.<ref name=20200325afpA>{{cite news |title=Australia's Department of Health did not issue a warning that 'using petrol pumps can spread COVID-19' |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/australias-department-health-did-not-issue-warning-using-petrol-pumps-can-spread-covid-19 |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331182810/https://factcheck.afp.com/australias-department-health-did-not-issue-warning-using-petrol-pumps-can-spread-covid-19|archive-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA Twitter post claimed that scientists from the \"Australian Medical University\" had developed a vaccine for the coronavirus. It accepted 0.1 [[Bitcoin]] as payment for a vaccination kit and promised shipping in 5\u201310 days. It was later removed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/social-media-awash-with-fake-treatments-for-coronavirus-20200326-p54e9q.html|title=Social media awash with fake treatments for coronavirus|last=Taylor|first=Andrew | name-list-format = vanc |date=2020-03-28|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407123958/https://www.smh.com.au/national/social-media-awash-with-fake-treatments-for-coronavirus-20200326-p54e9q.html|archive-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Brazil ====\nIn Brazil, a video was widely shared claiming that vinegar was more effective than hand sanitiser against the coronavirus. That was disproved, as \"there is no evidence that [[acetic acid]] is effective against the virus\" and, even if there was, \"its concentration in common household vinegar is low\".<ref name=20200304abril>{{cite web|url=https://saude.abril.com.br/blog/e-verdade-ou-fake-news/alcool-em-gel-nao-evita-infeccao-por-novo-coronavirus-e-fake/|title=\u00c1lcool em gel n\u00e3o evita infec\u00e7\u00e3o por novo coronav\u00edrus? \u00c9 fake!|last=Pinheiro|first=Chlo\u00e9 | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 4, 2020|language=pt-br|trans-title=Hand sanitiser does not prevent infection by coronavirus? Fake!|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nChloroform and ether based drug [[:pt:Cheirinho-da-lol\u00f3|''lol\u00f3'']] was said to cure the disease in messages spread in Brazil. Other so called cures in messages spreading in Brazil were avocado and mint tea, hot whiskey and honey, essential oils, vitamins C and D,<ref name=otempo2307041>{{cite web|url=https://www.otempo.com.br/cidades/e-fake-news-lolo-nao-cura-coronavirus-e-representa-risco-a-saude-1.2307041|title=\u00c9 fake news: lol\u00f3 n\u00e3o cura coronav\u00edrus e representa risco \u00e0 sa\u00fade|first=Rafaela|last=Mansur| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 6, 2020|language=pt|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307135307/https://www.otempo.com.br/cidades/e-fake-news-lolo-nao-cura-coronavirus-e-representa-risco-a-saude-1.2307041|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> fennel tea (supposedly similar to the medicine [[Tamiflu]], according to a false e-mail attributed to a hospital director) and cocaine.<ref name=20200304uol>{{cite web|url=https://noticias.uol.com.br/confere/ultimas-noticias/2020/03/04/lolo-cocaina-cha-nada-disso-mata-coronavirus-e-dicas-de-cura-sao-falsas.htm|title=Lol\u00f3, coca\u00edna, ch\u00e1: nada disso mata coronav\u00edrus, e dicas de cura s\u00e3o falsas|author=Lucas Borges Teixeira|date=March 4, 2020|language=pt|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316182615/https://noticias.uol.com.br/confere/ultimas-noticias/2020/03/04/lolo-cocaina-cha-nada-disso-mata-coronavirus-e-dicas-de-cura-sao-falsas.htm|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Canada ====\nA fake [[Costco]] [[product recall]] notice circulated on social media purporting that Kirkland-brand bath tissue had been contaminated with COVID-19 [sic] due to the item being made in China. No evidence supports that SARS-CoV 2 can survive for prolonged periods of time (like what might happen during shipping) on surfaces, and Costco has not issued such a recall.<ref name=20200313afp>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/costco-not-recalling-bath-tissue-due-novel-coronavirus-contamination|title=Costco is not recalling bath tissue due to novel coronavirus contamination|date=March 13, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/faq.html|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19)|date=February 11, 2020|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/coronavirus-can-stay-infectious-for-days-on-surfaces/2020/03/12/9b54a99e-6472-11ea-845d-e35b0234b136_story.html|title=Coronavirus can stay infectious for days on surfaces. But it's still okay to check your mail.|website=The Washington Post|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== China ====\n\nVarious national and party-held Chinese media heavily advertised an \"overnight research\" report by [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] and Shanghai Institute of Materia Medica, [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]], on how {{lang|zh-Latn|shuanghuanglian}}, an herb mixture from [[traditional Chinese medicine]] (TCM), can effectively inhibit the novel coronavirus. The report has led to a purchase craze of {{lang|zh-Latn|shuanghuanglian}}.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wee |first1=Sui-Lee |title=In Coronavirus, China Weighs Benefits of Buffalo Horn and Other Remedies |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/world/asia/coronavirus-traditional-chinese-medicine.html |work=The New York Times |date=February 5, 2020 |access-date=February 15, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200206125038/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/world/asia/coronavirus-traditional-chinese-medicine.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSince its third version, the COVID management guidelines from the [[National Health Commission]] recommends using TCM to treat the disease.<ref name=bbc51485559>{{cite news |script-title=zh:\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u6cbb\u7597\uff1a\u8bb2\u7a76\u5b9e\u8bc1\u7684\u897f\u533b\u548c\u81ea\u6211\u5b9a\u4f4d\u7684\u4e2d\u836f |url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/science-51485559 |website=BBC News |date=February 14, 2020 |language=zh-Hans |trans-title=Treating the novel coronavirus: the empirical Western medicine and the self-positioning Chinese medicine}}</ref> In Wuhan, the local authorities have pushed for a set of TCM prescriptions to be used for every case since early February.<ref name=cctv200125>{{cite web |language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u533b\u6765\u4e86\uff018\u4e2a\u9632\u6cbb\u201c\u534f\u5b9a\u65b9\u201d \u8f85\u52a9\u6cbb\u7597\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u80ba\u708e |url=http://news.cctv.com/2020/01/25/ARTIce5OB5W3sORPe90dPEJh200125.shtml |website=CCTV News |access-date=February 15, 2020 |trans-title=Here comes Chinese medicine! 8 \"agreed-on prescriptions\" help prevent and treat the new coronavirus pneumonia}}</ref><ref name=epochtimes11842894>{{cite web |language=zh-Hans |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u8981\u6c42\u6240\u6709\u60a3\u8005\u5fc5\u987b\u5403\u4e2d\u836f \u7f51\u6c11\u8d28\u7591 |url=https://www.epochtimes.com/gb/20/2/4/n11842894.htm |website=Epoch Times |access-date=February 15, 2020 |date=February 4, 2020 |trans-title=Wuhan wants all patients put on TCM; Netizens question}}</ref> One formula was promoted at the national level by mid February.<ref name=sina2164147>{{Cite news|url=http://news.sina.com.cn/o/2020-02-17/doc-iimxxstf2164147.shtml|script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u56fd\u53d1\u5e03 {{!}} \u56fd\u5bb6\u4e2d\u533b\u836f\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40\uff1a\u6e05\u80ba\u6392\u6bd2\u6c64\u5bf9\u6cbb\u7597\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u6709\u7597\u6548|work=Chinanet|publisher=Sina News|access-date=February 17, 2020|language=zh-Hans |trans-title=National Administration of Traditional Chinese Medicine: The \"lung-clearing detoxing decoction\" is effective against COVID-19}}</ref> The local field hospitals were explicitly TCM-oriented. According to state-owned media, as of March 16, 2020, 91.91% of all Hubei patients have used TCM, with the rate reaching 99% in field hospitals and 94% in bulk quarantine areas.<ref name=xinhuanet1125720410>{{cite news |script-title=zh:ICU\u5185\u5916\u7684\u4e2d\u897f\u533b\u5408\u4f5c\u2014\u2014\u4e13\u5bb6\u8c08\u4e2d\u533b\u836f\u5728\u6297\u51fb\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u4e2d\u7684\u91cd\u8981\u4f5c\u7528 |language=zh-Hans |trans-title=Co-operation between Chinese and Western medicine inside and outside of the ICU \u2013 experts talk about the vital role of TCM in the fight against COVID-19 |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/politics/2020-03/16/c_1125720410.htm |agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nClaims originating from China circulated, stating that saline solutions could kill the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/saline-solution-kills-china-coronavirus-experts-refute-online-rumour|title=Saline solution kills China coronavirus? Experts refute online rumour|date=2020-01-24|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401153714/https://factcheck.afp.com/saline-solution-kills-china-coronavirus-experts-refute-online-rumour|archive-date=2020-04-01|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Estonia ====\nOn February 27, 2020, the Estonian Minister of the Interior [[Mart Helme]] stated at a government press conference that the [[common cold]] had been renamed as the coronavirus and that in his youth nothing like that existed. He recommended wearing warm socks and mustard patches as well as spreading goose fat on one's chest as treatments for the virus. Helme also said that the virus would pass within a few days to a week just like the common cold.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.delfi.ee/news/paevauudised/eesti/video-mart-helme-kulmetushaigus-on-nuud-siis-umber-ristitud-koroonaviiruseks-mingit-hadaolukorda-eestis-pole?id=89066557date=2%20March%202020|title=VIDEO {{!}} Mart Helme: k\u00fclmetushaigus on n\u00fc\u00fcd siis \u00fcmber ristitud koroonaviiruseks. Mingit h\u00e4daolukorda Eestis pole|last=Vasli|first=Karoliina| name-list-format = vanc |date=February 27, 2020 |website=[[Delfi (web portal)|Delfi]] |url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311135111/https://www.delfi.ee/news/paevauudised/eesti/video-mart-helme-kulmetushaigus-on-nuud-siis-umber-ristitud-koroonaviiruseks-mingit-hadaolukorda-eestis-pole?id=89066557date=2%20March%202020|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Greece ====\nDespite the coronavirus outbreak, on March 9, the [[Church of Greece]] announced that the [[Holy Communion]], in which churchgoers eat pieces of bread soaked in wine from the same chalice, would continue as a practice.<ref name=\"Reuters 9 March\">{{cite news | first1=Michele |last1=Kambas |first2=George |last2=Georgiopoulos | name-list-format = vanc | title=In era of coronavirus, Greek church says Holy Communion will carry on | agency=Reuters | date=March 9, 2020 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-greece-church-idUSKBN20W2N1 | access-date=March 10, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312174830/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-greece-church-idUSKBN20W2N1 | archive-date=March 12, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Holy Synod#The Greek Holy Synod|Holy Synod]] stated that the Holy Communion \"cannot be the cause of the spread of illness\", with Metropolitan Seraphim saying that the wine was without blemish because it represented the blood and body of Christ, and that \"whoever attends Holy Communion is approaching God, who has the power to heal\".<ref name=\"Reuters 9 March\" />\n\nNew Democracy MP Elena Rapti also said that she was going and that if there was deep faith, the Communion was healing.<ref name=\"ref 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.heise.de/tp/features/Corona-Panik-nur-fuer-Unglaeubige-4678649.html|title=Corona-Panik nur f\u00fcr Ungl\u00e4ubige?|last=Aswestopoulos|first=Wassilis| name-list-format = vanc |website=heise online|language=de|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310205222/https://www.heise.de/tp/features/Corona-Panik-nur-fuer-Unglaeubige-4678649.html|archive-date=March 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Church furthermore refused to restrict Christians from taking the Holy Communion.<ref name=dw52742226>{{cite web|publisher=Deutsche Welle|title=Inside Europe: Greek Orthodox Church weighs in on coronavirus|date=March 13, 2020|url=https://www.dw.com/en/inside-europe-greek-orthodox-church-weighs-in-on-coronavirus/av-52742226|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318181239/https://www.dw.com/en/inside-europe-greek-orthodox-church-weighs-in-on-coronavirus/av-52742226|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In public statements, several clerics urged worshippers to continue taking part in the Holy Communion, justifying it by saying that Jesus never got sick,<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\">{{cite web | last=Brzozowski | first=Alexandra | last2=Michalopoulos | first2=Sarantis | name-list-format = vanc | title=Catholics take measures against coronavirus while Greek Orthodox Church 'prays' | website=euractiv.com | date=March 9, 2020 | url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/health-consumers/news/catholics-take-measures-against-coronavirus-while-greek-orthodox-church-prays/ |access-date=March 18, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318181234/https://www.euractiv.com/section/health-consumers/news/catholics-take-measures-against-coronavirus-while-greek-orthodox-church-prays/ | archive-date=March 18, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> while the Bishop of Piraeus Seraphim announced that only those who took part in masses without true faith could be affected.<ref name=\"ref 1\" /> There were furthermore reports that the CoVid 19 hotline was informing concerned believers that there was no risk of contagion at the sacrament.<ref name=\"ref 1\" />\n\nSome high-profile Greek medical doctors publicly supported the continuation of practicing Holy Communion, causing a sharp reaction by the Greek Association of Hospital Doctors.<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\" /> Eleni Giamarellou, a professor of infectious diseases at the University of Athens, announced that there was no danger, and that she was accepting communion with faith in God, so she could not become infected.<ref name=\"ref 1\" /> The Greek Association of Hospital Doctors criticized these professionals for putting their religious beliefs before science.<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\" />\n\nIt was also reported that a right-wing populist party leader of the party [[Greek Solution]], [[Kyriakos Velopoulos]], sells a hand cream via his TV shop, which supposedly would completely kill COVID-19, although it is not approved by medical authorities.<ref name=\"ref 1\" />\n\n==== India ====\n{{main|Misinformation related to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\nPolitical activist [[Chakrapani (politician)|Swami Chakrapani]] and [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|Member of the Legislative Assembly]] [[Suman Haripriya]] claimed that drinking cow urine and applying cow dung on the body can cure COVID-19.<ref name=indiatimes73952691>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|title=Coronavirus: Can cow dung and urine help cure the novel coronavirus?|website=The Times of India|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206035509/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=firstpost8111021>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|title=Novel coronavirus can be cured with gaumutra, gobar claims Assam BJP MLA Suman Haripriya|website=Firstpost|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304051130/https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> WHO's chief scientist [[Soumya Swaminathan (scientist)|Soumya Swaminathan]] criticised politicians incautiously spreading such misinformation without an evidence base.<ref name=20200303ndtv>{{cite web|url=https://swachhindia.ndtv.com/novel-coronavirus-outbreak-indias-response-and-surveillance-has-been-quite-robust-says-whos-chief-scientist-42015|title=Novel Coronavirus Outbreak: \"India's Response And Surveillance Has Been Quite Robust,\" Says WHO's Chief Scientist|publisher=NDTV|access-date=March 5, 2020|date=March 3, 2020|quote=\"Q: In a situation like this when we need scientific solution to a medical crisis, when you get in our country for examples, political leaders saying things like co''[sic]'' dung or cow urine can be beneficial in fixing something like coronavirus, do we end up taking a step back after such statements, as we need to deal with the issue in a modern scientific manner. <br />A: I completely agree, I think all the public figures including politicians need to be extra careful when it comes to making such statements, because they have such a huge following. Its really important for them to say things that are based on some scientific evidence and rationing''[sic; probably \"reasoning\" typo]''.... when it comes to the claims of cures of this infection we should be extremely careful about our statements and it should be made by the people who know what they\u2019re talking about. And has to be baked''[sic]'' by evidence\"}}</ref> Dr Shailendra Saxena of the [[Indian Virological Society]] stated that there is no evidence that cow urine has any anti-viral effect, and eating cow dung might even create a new [[zoonosis]].<ref name=BBC_tea>{{Cite news|last=team| name-list-format = vanc |first=Reality Check|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51910099|title=India's coronavirus health myths fact-checked|date=2020-03-25|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB}}</ref>{{medcn|date=April 2020}}<!--not clear if doc is a subject expert-->\n\nParliamentarian [[Ramesh Bidhuri]] of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] claimed that experts say using [[Namaste]] as a greeting prevents transmission of COVID-19, but using Arabic greetings like [[Adab (gesture)|Adab]] and [[As-salamu alaykum]] does not prevent it as they direct air into the mouth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/video/955329/coronavirus-saying-aadab-sends-infected-air-into-the-mouth-claims-bjp-leader-ramesh-bidhuri|title=Coronavirus: Saying aadab sends infected air into the mouth, claims BJP leader Ramesh Bidhuri|website=Scroll.in|access-date=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317065950/https://scroll.in/video/955329/coronavirus-saying-aadab-sends-infected-air-into-the-mouth-claims-bjp-leader-ramesh-bidhuri|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=deccanherald811390>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/experts-have-said-namaskar-not-adaab-or-assalamu-alaikum-will-help-prevent-coronavirus-says-bjp-mp-ramesh-bidhuri-811390.html|title=Experts have said namaskar, not adaab or assalamu alaikum, will help prevent coronavirus, says BJP MP Ramesh Bidhuri|website=Deccan Herald|access-date=March 15, 2020|date=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317192721/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/experts-have-said-namaskar-not-adaab-or-assalamu-alaikum-will-help-prevent-coronavirus-says-bjp-mp-ramesh-bidhuri-811390.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMisinformation that the government is spreading an \"anti-corona\" drug in the country during [[Janata curfew]], a stay-at-home curfew enforced in India, went viral on social media.<ref name=20200320hindustantimes>{{cite news |title=Is government spraying coronavirus vaccine using airplanes? No, it's fake news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/it-s-viral/is-government-spraying-coronavirus-vaccine-using-airplanes-no-it-s-fake-news/story-QmSDrfLW8SkSghT2TUf5cK.html |access-date=March 22, 2020 |work=Hindustan Times |date=March 20, 2020 }}</ref> The notion that the vibrations generated by clapping together during Janata curfew will kill the virus was debunked by the media.<ref name=thenewsminute120844>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/mohanlal-many-others-share-fake-info-clapping-may-kill-virus-pib-debunks-120844 |access-date=March 22, 2020 |work=thenewsminute.com |title=Mohanlal, many others share fake info that 'clapping may kill virus', PIB debunks}}</ref> [[Amitabh Bachchan]] was heavily criticised for one of his tweets, which claimed vibrations from clapping, blowing conch shells as part of Sunday's Janata Curfew would have reduced or destroyed coronavirus potency as it was \u2018[[Amavasya]]\u2019, the darkest day of the month.<ref>{{cite news |title=Amitabh Bachchan deletes post on 'clapping vibrations destroy virus potency' after being called out |url=https://trib.al/Bcqp2dp |work=The Hindu |date=March 23, 2020 }}</ref> Misinformation has spread that the lifetime of SARS-CoV-2 is only 12 hours and staying home for 14 hours during Janata curfew would break the chain of transmission.<ref name=indiatoday1>{{cite news |author=Ratna |title=Fact Check: Social media users give misleading twist to PM Modi's concept of 'Janta curfew' |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/fact-check/story/social-media-users-give-misleading-twist-pm-modi-janta-curfew-1658195-2020-03-21 |access-date=March 22, 2020 |work=India Today }}</ref> Another message claimed that observing Janata curfew will result in the reduction of COVID-19 cases by 40%.<ref name=indiatoday1 />\n\nIn India, fake news circulated that the [[World Health Organization]] warned against eating cabbage to prevent coronavirus infection.<ref name=20200331afp>{{cite news |title=WHO did not warn against eating cabbage during the COVID-19 pandemic |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/who-did-not-warn-against-eating-cabbage-during-covid-19-pandemic |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 31, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402070033/https://factcheck.afp.com/who-did-not-warn-against-eating-cabbage-during-covid-19-pandemic|archive-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The poisonous fruit of the [[Datura]] plant as a preventive measure for COVID-19 resulted in eleven people being hospitalized in India. They ate the fruit, following the instructions from a [[TikTok]] video that propagated misinformation regarding the prevention of COVID-19.<ref name=thenewsminute122136>{{cite news |title=11 in AP hospitalised after following TikTok poisonous 'remedy' for COVID-19 |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/11-ap-hospitalised-after-following-tiktok-poisonous-remedy-covid-19-122136 |access-date=April 9, 2020 |work=thenewsminute.com}}</ref><ref name=thehindu31282688>{{cite news |last1=Reporter |first1=Staff |title=Twelve taken ill after consuming 'coronavirus shaped' datura seeds |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/twelve-taken-ill-after-consuming-coronavirus-shaped-datura-seeds/article31282688.ece |access-date=April 9, 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=April 7, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nAn \"anti-coronavirus\" mattress was advertised as being anti-fungal, anti-allergic, dustproof and waterproof and that it could fight the coronavirus.<ref name=\":0CVP\">{{Cite news|last=team|first=Reality Check|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51910099|title=India's coronavirus health myths fact-checked|date=March 25, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nClaims of neem leaves or ''[[Azadirachta indica]]'' as remedies for COVID-19 were circulated in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1825466|title=No scientific evidence neem can cure COVID-19 infection \u2013 Experts|website=[[Bernama]]|date=26 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408122745/https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1825466|archive-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere were also claims that a 30 year-old Indian textbook lists aspirin, anti-histamines and nasal spray as treatments for COVID-19. The textbook actually talks about [[coronaviruses]] in general, as a family of viruses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/hoax-circulates-online-old-indian-textbook-lists-treatments-covid-19|title=Hoax circulates online that an old Indian textbook lists treatments for COVID-19|date=April 9, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n==== Italy ====\nThere are claims that wearing shoes at one's home is the reason behind the spread of the coronavirus in Italy.<ref name=20200409afp>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-refute-misleading-claim-wearing-shoes-indoors-main-reason-hike-covid-19-infections|title=Hoax circulates online that people wearing shoes indoors triggered hike in COVID-19 cases in Italy|date=April 9, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n==== Nigeria ====\nFollowing the first reported case of COVID-19 in Nigeria on February 28, untested cures and treatments began to spread via platforms like [[WhatsApp]].<ref name=qz1810219>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/africa/1810219/nigerias-coronavirus-case-may-spark-wave-of-fake-news-and-fears/|title=Nigeria's biggest battle with coronavirus will be beating misinformation|last=Kazeem|first=Yomi| name-list-format = vanc |website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz Africa]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162841/https://qz.com/africa/1810219/nigerias-coronavirus-case-may-spark-wave-of-fake-news-and-fears/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> There were also claims that chloroquine was used to cure over 12,000 COVID-19 patients.<ref name=20200221afp>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/anti-malaria-drug-has-proven-effective-treating-coronavirus-has-not-cured-12552-patients |title=Anti-malaria drug has proven effective in treating coronavirus but has not cured 12,552 patients &#124; AFP Fact Check |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=February 21, 2020 |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Pakistan ====\nReligious and scientific misconceptions related to the coronavirus was widespread in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news |title=Only 38% Pakistanis can recall state helpline for coronavirus: report |url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/282463-only-38-pakistanis-can-recall-state-helpline-for-coronavirus-report |access-date=13 April 2020 |work=www.geo.tv}}</ref> According to a survey research conducted by [[Ipsos]], 82% of people in Pakistan believed that performing [[wudu]]/ablution five times a day will keep them protected from contracting Coronavirus. Meanwhile 67% polled believed that jamaat (congregation prayer) cannot become a source of infection<ref name=\"thenews/1\">{{cite news |title=88pc Pakistanis aware of COVID-19 implications: poll |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/643643-88pc-pakistanis-aware-of-covid-19-implications-poll |access-date=13 April 2020 |work=www.thenews.com.pk |language=en}}</ref> and 48% people believed that shaking hands cannot infect anyone since it is [[Sunnah]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.samaa.tv/news/2020/04/myths-pakistanis-believe-wuzu-protects-you-from-covid/|title=Myths: Pakistanis believe wuzu protects you from COVID {{!}} SAMAA|publisher=Samaa TV|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Philippines ====\nPosts on social media claimed that volcanic ash from the eruption of the [[Taal Volcano]] on January 12, 2020 in the Philippines was the cause of low infection rates in the country, stating that it could kill the virus and had \"anti-viral\" and \"disinfectant qualities\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/world-health-organization-refutes-misleading-claim-volcanic-ash-can-kill-coronavirus|title=World Health Organization refutes misleading claim that volcanic ash can kill coronavirus|date=2020-03-09|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408104634/https://factcheck.afp.com/world-health-organization-refutes-misleading-claim-volcanic-ash-can-kill-coronavirus|archive-date=2020-04-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nClaims from the Philippines circulated that sap from [[Tinospora|''tinospora crispa'']] plants could serve as an antibiotic against the coronavirus when used as an eye drop. It also made the claim that the coronavirus is from the skin and crawls to the eyes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/philippine-health-experts-dismiss-misleading-online-claim-tinospora-crispa-plants-can-treat-novel|title=Philippine health experts dismiss misleading online claim that tinospora crispa plants can treat novel coronavirus|date=2020-02-05|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408105720/https://factcheck.afp.com/philippine-health-experts-dismiss-misleading-online-claim-tinospora-crispa-plants-can-treat-novel|archive-date=2020-04-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThere were also claims that an anti-viral injection was developed as a cure in the Philippines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/philippine-authorities-warn-anti-viral-injection-has-not-yet-been-approved-treating-covid-19|title=Philippine authorities warn anti-viral injection has not yet been approved for treating COVID-19|date=April 15, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n==== South Korea ====\nSouth Korean \"conservative populist\" Jun Kwang-hun told his followers that there was no risk to mass public gatherings as the virus was impossible to contract outdoors. Many of his followers are elderly.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Khatouki |first1=Christopher |title=Clandestine Cults and Cynical Politics: How South Korea Became the New Coronavirus Epicenter |url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/clandestine-cults-and-cynical-politics-how-south-korea-became-the-new-coronavirus-epicenter/ |website=thediplomat.com |publisher=The Diplomat |access-date=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313065620/https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/clandestine-cults-and-cynical-politics-how-south-korea-became-the-new-coronavirus-epicenter/ |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 17, around 79 church devotees were infected with the virus at the [[River of Grace Community Church]] after followers had salt-water sprayed into their mouths under the belief that this would protect them from the virus.<ref name=scmp3075421>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|title=Coronavirus: saltwater spray infects 46 church-goers in South Korea|date=March 16, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074249/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=upi9881584365>{{cite news|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|title=South Korea church used saltwater spray amid coronavirus outbreak|agency=United Press International|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074251/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There were also fake news of discovery of a vaccine against COVID-19.<ref name=20200325afpB>{{cite news |title=This photo shows a COVID-19 test kit developed by a South Korean company |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/photo-shows-covid-19-test-kit-developed-south-korean-company |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327125546/https://factcheck.afp.com/photo-shows-covid-19-test-kit-developed-south-korean-company|archive-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Senegal ====\nOn Facebook, a widely shared post claimed that 7 Senegalese children had died because they had received a COVID-19 vaccine. No such vaccine exists, although some are in clinical trials.<ref name=20200408afp>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/senegalese-children-did-not-die-coronavirus-vaccine-which-does-not-yet-exist|title=Senegalese children did not die from a coronavirus vaccine (which does not yet exist)|date=April 8, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n==== Sri Lanka ====\n\nA claim that [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] could protect against the coronavirus appeared on Youtube, along with a petition to legalize cannabis in Sri Lanka.<ref name=20200219afp>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/sri-lankan-health-experts-stress-there-no-evidence-cannabis-boosts-immunity-against-novel|title=Sri Lankan health experts stress there is no evidence that cannabis boosts immunity against the novel coronavirus|date=February 19, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> A fake [[Fox News]] article also claimed that [[Cannabidiol|CBD oil]] was a potential cure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/thomasbrewster/2020/03/19/coronavirus-scam-alert-beware-fake-fox-news-text-messages-promising-a-cbd-oil-cure/|title=Coronavirus Scam Alert: Beware Fake Fox News Articles Promising A CBD Oil Cure|last=Brewster|first=Thomas| name-list-format = vanc |website=Forbes|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Thailand ====\n\nClaims that Vitamin D pills could help prevent the coronavirus circulated on social media in Thailand.<ref name=20200227afp>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-say-there-no-evidence-vitamin-d-effective-preventing-novel-coronavirus-infection|title=Health experts say there is no evidence vitamin D is effective in preventing novel coronavirus infection|date=February 27, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA Thai media website stated that ''[[andrographis paniculata]]'' could boost the immune systems and relieve symptoms of coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/thai-health-experts-say-there-no-evidence-green-chiretta-herb-can-prevent-novel-coronavirus|title=Thai health experts say there is no evidence the 'green chiretta' herb can prevent the novel coronavirus|date=2020-02-06|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408110538/https://factcheck.afp.com/thai-health-experts-say-there-no-evidence-green-chiretta-herb-can-prevent-novel-coronavirus|archive-date=2020-04-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA widely shared post on Facebook claimed that Italian doctors who were infected with COVID-19 were treating patients as normal in Italy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/video-actually-shows-scene-mexican-television-series-aired-2010|title=This video actually shows a scene from a Mexican television drama|date=April 13, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n==== United States ====\nSome [[QAnon]] proponents, including Jordan Sather, and others, have promoted gargling \"[[Miracle Mineral Supplement]]\" (actually [[Chlorine dioxide]], a chemical used in some industrial applications as a bleach that may cause life-threatening reactions and even death) as a way of preventing or curing the disease. The Food and Drug Administration has warned multiple times that drinking MMS is \"dangerous\" as it may cause \"severe vomiting\" and \"acute liver failure\".<ref name=\"bleach\">{{cite news|last=Sommer|first=Will| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/qanon-conspiracy-theorists-magic-cure-for-coronavirus-is-drinking-lethal-bleach|title=QAnon-ers' Magic Cure for Coronavirus: Just Drink Bleach!|date=January 28, 2020|newspaper=[[Daily Beast]]|access-date=February 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210223501/https://www.thedailybeast.com/qanon-conspiracy-theorists-magic-cure-for-coronavirus-is-drinking-lethal-bleach|archive-date=February 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, [[televangelist]] [[Jim Bakker]] promoted a [[colloidal silver]] solution sold on his website, as a remedy for coronavirus COVID-19; [[naturopath]] Sherrill Sellman, a guest on his show, falsely stated that it \"hasn't been tested on this strain of the coronavirus, but it's been tested on other strains of the coronavirus and has been able to eliminate it within 12 hours.\"<ref name=newsweek1487069>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/televangelist-show-guest-promotes-silver-solution-cure-coronavirus-1487069|title=TELEVANGELIST SELLS $125 'SILVER SOLUTION' AS CURE FOR CORONAVIRUS|last1=Moyler|first1=Hunter|date=February 12, 2020|work=Newsweek|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215044054/https://www.newsweek.com/televangelist-show-guest-promotes-silver-solution-cure-coronavirus-1487069|archive-date=February 15, 2020|access-date=February 15, 2020}}</ref> The US Food and Drug Administration and New York Attorney General's office both issued cease-and-desist orders against Bakker, and he was sued by the state of Missouri over the sales.<ref name=npr814550474>{{cite news| first=Matthew S.| last=Schwartz | name-list-format = vanc | title=Missouri Sues Televangelist Jim Bakker For Selling Fake Coronavirus Cure| publisher=NPR| date=March 11, 2020| access-date=March 16, 2020| url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/11/814550474/missouri-sues-televangelist-jim-bakker-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-cure| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312105326/https://www.npr.org/2020/03/11/814550474/missouri-sues-televangelist-jim-bakker-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-cure| archive-date=March 12, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=20200309theguardian>{{cite news| last=Aratani| first=Lauren | name-list-format = vanc | title=New York attorney general to televangelist: stop touting product as coronavirus cure| newspaper=The Guardian| date=March 9, 2020| access-date=March 16, 2020| url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/09/jim-bakker-letitia-james-coronavirus-product-stop-promoting| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313205221/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/09/jim-bakker-letitia-james-coronavirus-product-stop-promoting| archive-date=March 13, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe New York Attorney General's office also issued a cease-and-desist order to radio host [[Alex Jones]], who was selling silver-infused toothpaste that he falsely claimed can kill the virus and had been verified by federal officials,<ref name=theverge21177998>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21177998/new-york-attorney-general-alex-jones-infowars-coronavirus-cures-prevention|title=Alex Jones ordered to stop selling fake coronavirus cures|last=Porter|first=Jon| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 13, 2020|website=The Verge|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316135410/https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21177998/new-york-attorney-general-alex-jones-infowars-coronavirus-cures-prevention|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> causing a Jones spokesman to deny the products had been sold for the purpose of treating any disease.<ref name=\"alex jones\" /> The FDA would later threaten Jones with legal action and seizure of several silver-based products if he continued to promote their use against coronavirus.<ref name=politico178629>{{cite news|last=Owermohle |first=Sarah | name-list-format = vanc | title=FDA warns Alex Jones over false coronavirus claims| date=April 9, 2020| access-date=April 9, 2020 | work=Politico| url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/09/fda-warns-alex-jones-over-false-coronavirus-claims-178629}}</ref>\n\nAnother televangelist, [[Kenneth Copeland]], claimed on Victory Channel during a programme called \"Standing Against Coronavirus\", that he can cure television viewers of {{nowrap|COVID-19}} directly from the TV studio. The viewers had to touch the television screen to receive the spiritual healing.<ref name=newsweek1492044>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/conservative-pastor-claims-he-healed-viewers-coronavirus-through-their-tv-screens-1492044|title=Conservative pastor claims he \"healed\" viewers of coronavirus through their TV screens|last=Lemon|first=Jason| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 12, 2020|website=Newsweek|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316135415/https://www.newsweek.com/conservative-pastor-claims-he-healed-viewers-coronavirus-through-their-tv-screens-1492044|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=20200313pinknews>{{cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/13/kenneth-copeland-anti-lgbt-televangelist-coronavirus-covid19-heal-virus-pandemic/|title=This anti-LGBT+ televangelist tried to heal people of the coronavirus through their televisions|date=March 13, 2020|website=PinkNews|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314150419/https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/13/kenneth-copeland-anti-lgbt-televangelist-coronavirus-covid19-heal-virus-pandemic/|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe US [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] arrested actor Keith Lawrence Middlebrook for selling a fake COVID-19 cure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/celebrity/actor-keith-middlebrook-arrested-by-fbi-for-allegedly-peddling-bogus-coronavirus-cure/ar-BB11LQpX?ocid=ientp|title=Actor Keith Middlebrook arrested by FBI for allegedly peddling bogus coronavirus cure|publisher=MSN|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe hypothesis of Stanford military historian Victor Davis Hanson, that the coronavirus was circulating in California in fall 2019, was widely shared but debunked by genetic analysis.<ref name=20200410slate>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/technology/2020/04/coronavirus-circulating-california-2019-bunk.html|title=No, You Did Not Get COVID-19 in the Fall of 2019|first=Jane C.|last=Hu | name-list-format = vanc |date=April 10, 2020|website=Slate}}</ref>\n\n==== Venezuela ====\nIn February 2020, {{ill|Mar\u00eda Alejandra D\u00edaz|es}}, a member of the [[2017 Constituent National Assembly|Venezuelan Constituent Assembly]], promoted a recipe that she claimed would cure COVID-19. The recipe consisted of ingredients often purported to prevent and cure colds, including [[Cymbopogon|lemon grass]], [[Sambucus|elder]], ginger, black pepper, lemon and honey. D\u00edaz also described the virus as a bioterrorism weapon.<ref name=20200305efectococuyo>{{cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/cocuyo-chequea/coronavirus-te-medicinal/|title=\u00bfEl coronavirus se puede curar con un t\u00e9 de plantas? #DatosCoronavirus|date=March 5, 2020|website=[[Efecto Cocuyo]]|language=Spanish|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Government ==\n=== American ===\n\nAccording to Washington Post, the US Republican government members were largely influenced by series of articles by [[Richard Epstein|Richard A. Epstein]] of the [[Hoover Institution]], who in a series of articles consistently played down the scale of the epidemics, ridiculed the \"panic\" being spread by \"progressives\", made a number of incorrect statements about the SARS-CoV-2 virus, misapplied and misconstrued Darwinian evolutionary theory in regards to the pandemics, and predicted \"about 500 deaths at the end\" of the epidemics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/q-and-a/the-contrarian-coronavirus-theory-that-informed-the-trump-administration|title=The Contrarian Coronavirus Theory That Informed the Trump Administration|last=Chotiner|first=Isaac | name-list-format = vanc |website=The New Yorker|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral members of the [[U.S. Senate]]\u2014particularly [[Richard Burr]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[North Carolina|NC]]) and [[Kelly Loeffler]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Georgia (U.S. state)|GA]])\u2014have come under [[2020 Congressional insider trading scandal|scrutiny for sales of large amounts of stocks]] before the financial markets crashed due to the outbreak, sparking accusations that they had insider knowledge from closed-door briefings, while many of them publicly downplayed the risks posed by the health crisis to the U.S. public.<ref name=hal-st>{{cite web |last1=Halper |first1=Evan |title=Stock trades by Senate Intelligence Committee chair after coronavirus briefings trigger investigation |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/story/2020-03-20/stock-trades-by-lawmakers-who-got-coronavirus-briefings |website=Los Angeles Times |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=vis-al2>{{cite web |last1=Visser |first1=Nick |title=At Least 2 GOP Senators Dumped Millions in Stock After Coronavirus Briefings |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/stock-sales-gop-senators-coronavirus_n_5e741524c5b63c3b648d8374 |website=HuffPost |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=bl-hd>{{cite web |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=How damning are Richard Burr's and Kelly Loeffler's coronavirus stock trades? Let's break it down. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/20/richard-burrs-kelly-loefflers-suspiciously-well-timed-stock-trades-during-coronavirus-examined/ |website=The Washington Post |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200320euractiv>{{cite web |last1=Lawton |first1=Sarah |title=As COVID-19 cases grew, US Senators sold off stocks and downplayed risks |url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/global-europe/news/as-covid-19-cases-grew-us-senators-sold-off-stocks-and-downplayed-risks/ |website=Euractiv |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> For instance, an audio recording from February 27 revealed that Burr ([[Senate Intelligence Committee]] chairman) gave dire warnings to a small group of well-connected constituents in private, contrasted in severity to his public statements and not known to the public, that the virus is \"much more aggressive in its transmission than anything that we have seen in recent history,\" advising against travel to Europe (13 days before official warnings, 15 days before the ban), saying that schools will be likely be closed (16 days before the closure), and suggesting that the military might be mobilized (learned three weeks later from the recording).<ref name=npr818192535>{{cite web |last1=Mak |first1=Tim |title=Weeks Before Virus Panic, Intelligence Chairman Privately Raised Alarm, Sold Stocks |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/19/818192535/burr-recording-sparks-questions-about-private-comments-on-covid-19 |publisher=NPR |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Bill de Blasio]], the mayor of New York City, gave wrong instructions during a [[photo op]] public [[3-1-1]] call.<ref name=20200326nymag>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/bill-de-blasio-had-his-worst-week-as-new-york-city-mayor.html|title=When New York Needed Him Most, Bill de Blasio Had His Worst Week As Mayor|last=Freedlander|first=David| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 26, 2020|website=Intelligencer|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Presidential ====\n{{See also|Veracity of statements by Donald Trump}}\nUS President [[Donald Trump]] and his top economic adviser [[Larry Kudlow]] have been accused of spreading misinformation about the coronavirus. On February 25, Trump said, \"I think that whole situation will start working out. We're very close to a vaccine.\"<ref name=20200225huffpost>{{cite news |title=Larry Kudlow Claims Coronavirus 'Contained' In U.S. as CDC Warns of Likely Spread |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/larry-kudlow-coronavirus-misinformation_n_5e556f11c5b64c1d5620ddb1 |work=[[HuffPost]] |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200226buzzfeednews>{{cite news |title=Trump's Biggest Supporters Think the Coronavirus Is a Deep State Plot |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/trump-supporters-coronavirus-deep-state-qanon |work=BuzzFeed |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=theverge21153035>{{cite news |title=Trump's reckless coronavirus statements put the entire US at risk |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/25/21153035/coronavirus-response-trump-vaccine-covid19-cdc-who-health-crisis |work=The Verge |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vox-mis\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/2/26/21154253/trump-ebola-tweets-coronavirus|title=Trump is facing a coronavirus threat. Let's look back at how he talked about Ebola|date=February 26, 2020|work=Vox}}</ref> At the time, [[SARS-CoV-2]] had been spreading in the United States undetected for weeks,<ref name=theatlantic607348>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/03/how-many-americans-really-have-coronavirus/607348/|title=The Official Coronavirus Numbers Are Wrong, and Everyone Knows It|first=Alexis C.|last=Madrigal| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 3, 2020|website=The Atlantic|access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307000203/https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/03/how-many-americans-really-have-coronavirus/607348/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and new vaccine development may require a minimum of a year to prove safety and efficacy to gain regulatory approval.<ref name=npr804628081>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/02/12/804628081/timetable-for-a-vaccine-against-the-new-coronavirus-maybe-this-fall|title=Timetable for a Vaccine Against the New Coronavirus? Maybe This Fall|publisher=NPR|first=Joe|last=Palc | name-list-format = vanc|date=February 12, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303155745/https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/02/12/804628081/timetable-for-a-vaccine-against-the-new-coronavirus-maybe-this-fall|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In an interview with [[Sean Hannity]] on March 4, Trump also claimed that the [[Mortality rate|death rate]] published by the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] was false, that the correct fatality rate was less than 1 percent, and said, \"Well, I think the 3.4 percent is really a false number\",<ref name=usatoday4961519002>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/05/coronavirus-trump-disputes-world-health-organization-death-rate/4961519002/|title=Coronavirus death rate is 3.4%, World Health Organization says, Trump says 'hunch' tells him that's wrong|first=David|last=Jackson| name-list-format = vanc |website=USA Today|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305211222/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/05/coronavirus-trump-disputes-world-health-organization-death-rate/4961519002/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SwqV0VHR4-E |title=Trump says he has a hunch about the coronavirus. Here are the facts \u2013 YouTube |access-date=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310145305/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SwqV0VHR4-E |archive-date=March 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=nbcnews1151006>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/just-my-hunch-trump-contradicts-health-experts-coronavirus-n1151006|title=Trump has many hunches about the coronavirus. Here's what the experts say.|publisher=NBC News|access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306162252/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/just-my-hunch-trump-contradicts-health-experts-coronavirus-n1151006|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> that the potential impact of the outbreak was exaggerated by Democrats plotting against him, and that it was safe for infected individuals to go to work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/05/trumps-latest-coronavirus-lies-have-galling-subtext/|title=Opinion {{!}} Trump's latest coronavirus lies have a galling subtext|first=Greg|last=Sargent| name-list-format = vanc |website=The Washington Post|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306034904/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/05/trumps-latest-coronavirus-lies-have-galling-subtext/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Walters|first=Joanna| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/trump-coronavirus-who-global-death-rate-false-number|title=Trump calls WHO's global death rate from coronavirus 'a false number'|date=March 5, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=March 5, 2020|last2=Aratani|first2=Lauren |issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305151056/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/trump-coronavirus-who-global-death-rate-false-number|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In a later tweet, Trump denied that he had made claims regarding infected individuals going to work, contrary to footage from the interview.<ref name=\":1\" />\n[[File:Coronavirus Press Conference USA.jpg|thumb|240px|President [[Donald Trump]] and members of the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] brief the media]]\nThe White House accused media of intentionally stoking fears of the virus to destabilize the administration.<ref name=bbc51667670>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51667670|title=Media 'using virus to topple Trump' \u2013 White House|date=February 28, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162842/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51667670|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''Stat News'' reported that \"President [[Cabinet of Donald Trump|Trump and members of his administration]] have also said that US containment of the virus is 'close to airtight' and that the virus is only as deadly as the seasonal flu. Their statements range from false to unproven, and in some cases, underestimate the challenges that public health officials must contend with in responding to the virus.\"<ref name=stat /> Around the same time that the \"airtight\" claim was made, SARS-CoV-2 was already past containment; the first case of community spread of the virus had been confirmed, and it was spreading faster than [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus]], with a [[case fatality rate]] at least seven times the rate for seasonal flu.<ref name=msnbc7944608558>{{cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow/watch/u-s-unready-to-deal-with-potential-coronavirus-spread-79446085581|title=U.S. unready to deal with potential coronavirus spread|publisher=MSNBC|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303192803/https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow/watch/u-s-unready-to-deal-with-potential-coronavirus-spread-79446085581|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/coronavirus-may-spread-faster-than-who-estimate|title=Coronavirus may spread faster than WHO estimate|website=Medical News Today|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304134154/https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/coronavirus-may-spread-faster-than-who-estimate|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=20200225statnews>{{cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/25/new-data-from-china-buttress-fears-about-high-coronavirus-fatality-rate-who-expert-says/|title=New China coronavirus data buttress fears about high fatality rate|date=February 25, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302010337/https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/25/new-data-from-china-buttress-fears-about-high-coronavirus-fatality-rate-who-expert-says/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nTrump has repeatedly compared COVID-19 to influenza, despite COVID-19 having a mortality rate estimated to be around ten times higher. On February 26, he stated: \"This is a flu. This is like a flu\". On March 9, Trump compared the 546 known U.S. cases of COVID-19 at the time and the 22 known deaths at the time to the tens of thousands of U.S. deaths from flu each year. On March 24, Trump argued that: \"We lose thousands and thousands of people a year to the flu ... But we've never closed down the country for the flu.\" On March 27, he stated: \"You can call it a flu\". On March 31, Trump changed his stance: \"It's not the flu ... It's vicious ... I knew everything. I knew it could be horrible, and I knew it could be maybe good.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Now Trump says it's wrong to compare coronavirus to regular flu |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200401-now-trump-says-it-s-wrong-to-compare-coronavirus-to-regular-flu |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |agency=[[Agence France Presse]] |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Baker |first1=Peter |title=Trump Confronts a New Reality Before an Expected Wave of Disease and Death |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/01/us/politics/coronavirus-trump.html |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 1, 2020 |archiveurl=http://archive.ph/i262n |archivedate=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Turse |first1=Nick |title=Misinformation hampered Ebola response. The same thing could happen with coronavirus |url=https://theintercept.com/2020/04/06/misinformation-coronavirus-ebola-congo/ |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |work=[[The Intercept]] |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Remarks by President Trump, Vice President Pence, and Members of the Coronavirus Task Force in a Fox News Virtual Town Hall |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-vice-president-pence-members-coronavirus-task-force-fox-news-virtual-town-hall/ |publisher=[[The White House]] |accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2, Trump told the media that he had heard that a [[COVID-19 vaccine]] would be available in \"a matter of months\", with \"a year [being] an outside number\", after Trump attended a discussion where his senior health official [[Anthony Fauci]] told him this process would take \"a year to a year and a half\" (at a minimum, Fauci later said). During that discussion, Trump repeatedly quizzed the leaders of pharmaceutical companies on the time needed to produce vaccines, stating \"I like the sound of a couple of months better\". The length of time required is due to regulatory bodies requiring multiple rounds of tests before vaccines being approved for the public's use.<ref name=20200303washingtonpost>{{cite news |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=Trump's baffling coronavirus vaccine event |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/03/trumps-baffling-coronavirus-vaccine-event/ |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, Trump blamed the [[Barack Obama administration]] for making \"a decision\" that delayed [[COVID-19 testing]] by the Trump administration. The policy in question had never been modified by the Obama administration, despite plans to do so. The policy's [[Project Bioshield Act|overall legal roots date to 2004]], before the Obama administration. Under the umbrella of [[Emergency Use Authorization]]s, the old policy stated that laboratory-developed tests \"should not be used for clinical diagnoses without FDA's approval, clearance, or authorization during an emergency declaration\". However, this policy was historically treated as a recommendation and generally unenforced, with no clear legal authority of the FDA in this area. The Trump administration continued to require laboratories to apply to the FDA for approval, but allowed the laboratories to test while the FDA processed the applications.<ref name=20200306politifact>{{cite news |last1=Greenberg |first1=Jon |title=False: Donald Trump stated on March 4, 2020 in a meeting at the White House: \"The Obama administration made a decision on testing that turned out to be very detrimental to what we're doing\" on the coronavirus. |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/mar/06/donald-trump/trump-wrongly-blames-obama-limits-coronavirus-test/ |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Politifact]] |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, Trump over-promised on the availability of COVID-19 testing in the United States, claiming that: \"Anybody that wants a test can get a test.\" Firstly, there were criteria needed to qualify for a test; recommendations were needed from doctors or health officials to approve testing. Secondly, the lack of test supplies resulted in some being denied tests even though doctors wanted to test them.<ref name=20200312khn>{{cite news |url=https://khn.org/news/donald-trumps-wrong-claim-that-anybody-can-get-tested-for-coronavirus/ |title=Donald Trump's Wrong Claim That 'Anybody' Can Get Tested For Coronavirus |last=Valverde |first=Miriam | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 12, 2020 |work=[[Kaiser Health News]] |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200320cnnA>{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |last2=Subramaniam |first2=Tara | name-list-format = vanc |title=Trump made 33 false claims about the coronavirus crisis in the first two weeks of March |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/22/politics/fact-check-trump-coronavirus-false-claims-march/index.html |access-date=March 23, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Trump falsely claimed that the drug [[chloroquine]] was approved by the [[Food and Drug Administration]] as a treatment for COVID-19. This led the FDA to state that it had not approved any drugs or therapies for COVID-19. While Trump claimed that \"we're going to be able to make that drug available almost immediately\", the leader of the FDA stated that the drug would still need to be tested in a \"large, pragmatic [[clinical trial]]\" on subjects infected with COVID-19.<ref name=20200320cnnB>{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |title=Fact check: Trump wrongly claims FDA 'approved' drug chloroquine to treat the coronavirus |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/19/politics/fact-check-chloroquine-trump-fda/index.html |access-date=March 22, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> While Trump promoted chloroquine as a potential \"game changer\", Fauci stated that positive results thus far were still based on \"anecdotal evidence\" and not \"definitive\" evidence from clinical trials.<ref name=go69716324>{{cite news |last1=Flaherty |first1=Anne |last2=Phelps |first2=Jordyn | name-list-format = vanc |title=Fauci throws cold water on Trump's declaration that malaria drug chloroquine is a 'game changer' |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fauci-throws-cold-water-trumps-declaration-malaria-drug/story?id=69716324 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[ABC News]] |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Trump also remarked that re-purposing existing drugs for COVID-19 is \"safe\" and \"not killing people\" (chloroquine is a form of treatment for malaria, while its derivative hydroxychloroquine is a form of treatment for lupus or arthritis), however most drugs may cause [[side effects]].<ref name=VerganoMarch23>{{cite news |last1=Vergano |first1=Dan |title=Chloroquine Is Being Touted As A Miracle Drug For Coronavirus, But There Are Reasons To Be Wary |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/danvergano/chloroquine-dangers-coronavirus?bfsource=relatedmanual |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Buzzfeed News]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Potentially serious side effects from chloroquine or hydroxychloroquine include [[irregular heartbeat]]s, [[tinnitus]], [[blurred vision]], [[muscle weakness]] or \"mental changes\".<ref name=VerganoMarch23 /><ref name=20200323military>{{cite news |last1=Kime |first1=Patricia |title=Drug Touted as COVID-19 Treatment Has Troubling Side Effects, Experts Say |url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2020/03/23/drug-touted-covid-19-treatment-has-troubling-side-effects-experts-say.html |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[military.com]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Overdoses of these drugs have been documented in scientific literature, including fatal overdoses.<ref name=VerganoMarch23 /> Demand for chloroquine in [[Lagos]], [[Nigeria]] sharply increased after Trump's comments, with three people overdosing by March 23.<ref name=20200323cnn>{{cite news |last1=Busari |first1=Stephanie |first2=Bukola |last2=Adebayo | name-list-format = vanc |title=Nigeria records chloroquine poisoning after Trump endorses it for coronavirus treatment |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/23/africa/chloroquine-trump-nigeria-intl/index.html|access-date=March 24, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> A married couple in their 60s living in the [[state of Arizona]] ingested a fish tank cleaner product containing chloroquine phosphate; the man died while the woman survived in critical condition. The woman stated that they intended to self-medicate against the coronavirus after hearing Trump tout the potential benefits of chloroquine during a public briefing.<ref name=nbcnews1167166>{{cite news |last1=Edwards |first1=Erika |last2=Hillyard |first2=Vaughn | name-list-format = vanc |title=Man dies after ingesting chloroquine in an attempt to prevent coronavirus |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/man-dies-after-ingesting-chloroquine-attempt-prevent-coronavirus-n1167166 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200323buzzfeednews>{{cite news |last1=Sacks |first1=Brianna |title=A Man Died After Self-Medicating with a Drug Trump Promoted As A Potential Treatment for the Coronavirus |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/briannasacks/man-died-chloroquine-phosphate-coronavirus |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Buzzfeed News]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, Trump addressed a shortage of [[ventilator]] supply in the United States, claiming that carmaker companies [[General Motors]] (GM) and [[Ford]] \"are making them right now\" when the companies were not producing ventilators at the time, and had yet to change their factories' production abilities.<ref name=20200323apnews>{{cite news |last1=Krisher |first1=Tom |last2=Yen |first2=Hope | name-list-format = vanc |title=AP FACT CHECK: Trump hype on auto industry and ventilators |url=https://apnews.com/17868870ddfc526c6c7f454d651b6d7f |access-date=March 24, 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Trump ordered General Motors to produce ventilators under the [[Defense Production Act]] on March 27. It was announced on April 8 that General Motors would deliver around 6,000 ventilators for the [[Strategic National Stockpile]] at the start of June; and around a further 24,000 by the end of August.<ref name=20200408cnbc>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/08/gm-to-build-30000-ventilators-for-us-for-489point4-million.html|publisher=CNBC|title=GM to build 30,000 ventilators for national stockpile for ,89.4&nbsp;million|date=April 8, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> At the end of March, Ford formed a partnership with [[General Electric]] to make ventilators, aiming to start production by April 20 and to deliver 50,000 ventilators by July 4.<ref name=20200330clickondetroit>{{cite news|url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/local/2020/03/30/ford-partners-with-ge-to-produce-50000-ventilators-in-100-days-amid-michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak/|date=March 30, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020|title=Ford partners with GE to produce 50,000 ventilators in 100 days amid Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak|work=Click On Detroit}}</ref><ref name=20200406cbsnews>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/ford-rawsonville-plant-michigan-ventilator-factory/|publisher=CBS|title=Ford converts Michigan auto plant into ventilator factory, promising 50,000 devices by July 4|date=April 6, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, Trump claimed that his administration \"inherited a broken test\" for COVID-19. \"That wasn't from us. That's been there a long time,\" he said. The claim was illogical because no previous administration could have prepared a test for a disease which had yet to emerge. COVID-19 emerged during Trump's presidency, at the end of 2019. The test was designed in 2020 by the Centers for Disease Control under the Trump administration.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Greenberg |first1=Jon |title=Trump blames past administrations for a flawed COVID-19 test. The test couldn't have existed earlier |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/mar/31/donald-trump/trump-blames-past-administrations-flawed-covid-19-/ |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |work=[[Politifact]] |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Trump continued to make the false claim on April 19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rupar |first1=Aaron |title=Why Trump\u2019s efforts to blame Obama for the coronavirus make absolutely no sense |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/4/20/21227903/trump-blames-obama-coronavirus |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Brazilian ===\n\n[[File:Jair Bolsonaro.jpg|thumb|Brazilian president [[Jair Bolsonaro]] repeatedly attempted to downplay the pandemic and even tried to force Brazilian states to revoke social isolation measures]]\nWhen the outbreak began in Brazil, many Brazilian states, including [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], which is the hotspot of the outbreak in Brazil, imposed harsh social isolation measures that included the shutdown of schools and non-essential business. Fearing an economic crash caused by those measures and the collapse of popular approval, the Brazilian Government, led by far-right president [[Jair Bolsonaro]], started to promote denialism of COVID-19's lethality, downplaying the disease by claiming that it was just a \"little Flu\" and accusing the media of promoting panic and hysteria.<ref name=bolsonaro />\n\nBolsonaro openly attempted to force sub-national governments (both states and municipalities) into revoking the social isolation measures by launching a campaign called \"o Brasil n\u00e3o pode parar\" (Brazil Can't stop), which received massive backlash from both the media and the public and was blocked by a court order.<ref name=bbc52080830>{{cite news|last=Watson |first=Katy | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-52080830 |title=Coronavirus: Brazil's Bolsonaro in denial and out on a limb |work=BBC News |date=March 29, 2020 |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=aljazeera2003301816>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Cowie  | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/indepth/features/deny-defy-bolsonaro-approach-coronavirus-brazil-200330181645501.html&ved=0ahUKEwiU3qnRhcboAhUXIbkGHVtIBuQQyM8BCEAwBQ&usg=AOvVaw2_LFMc5Zd8yIztZChUZKyg&ampcf=1 |title=Deny and defy: Bolsonaro's approach to the coronavirus in Brazil |publisher=Al Jazeera |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome analysts have noted that Bolsonaro's positions mimic the early positions of U.S. president [[Donald Trump]], who also tried to downplay the pandemic before adopting harsher measures.<ref name=vox21195469>{{cite web|first=Alex |last=Ward | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/30/21195469/coronavirus-usa-china-brazil-mexico-spain-italy-iran&ved=0ahUKEwiU3qnRhcboAhUXIbkGHVtIBuQQxfQBCDYwAw&usg=AOvVaw0DiuDCpjq5DJvxsE_0khld |title=Coronavirus: How Trump and other world leaders who denied the threat endangered us |date=March 30, 2020 |publisher=Vox |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Chinese ===\n==== Mishandling of crisis ====\n[[File:Xi jinping and Li keqiang.jpg|thumb|240px|[[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] general secretary [[Xi Jinping]] (left) and [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]] Premier [[Li Keqiang]]]]\n[[Whistleblower|Whistleblowing]] from various Chinese doctors, including [[Li Wenliang]] publishing data from [[Ai Fen]] on December 30, 2019, revealed that Wuhan hospital authorities were already aware that the virus was a SARS-like coronavirus and patients were already placed under quarantine.<ref>{{Citation|title=Wuhan doctor who was punished for trying to warn of coronavirus succumbs to the disease|date=February 6, 2020|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/02/06/wuhan-doctor-punished-trying-warn-coronavirus-dies-infection/|work=Hong Kong Free Press|access-date=March 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304083225/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/02/06/wuhan-doctor-punished-trying-warn-coronavirus-dies-infection/|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Wuhan Health Commission still insisted that the illness spreading in Wuhan at the time was not SARS on January 5, 2020.<ref name=20200105theguardian>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/05/mystery-illness-to-strike-chinese-city-is-not-sars-say-authorities-wuhan|title=Mystery illness in Chinese city not Sars, say authorities|website=The Guardian|date=January 5, 2020|access-date=March 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109170148/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/05/mystery-illness-to-strike-chinese-city-is-not-sars-say-authorities-wuhan|archive-date=January 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the early stages of the outbreak, the Chinese [[National Health Commission]] said that they had no \"clear evidence\" of human-to-human transmissions.<ref name=\"SCMPH2H\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3048460/paper-human-transmission-coronavirus-sets-social-media-storm|title=Paper on human transmission of coronavirus sets off social media storm in China|date=January 31, 2020|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205122018/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3048460/paper-human-transmission-coronavirus-sets-social-media-storm|archive-date=February 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On January 20, the Chinese National Health Commission announced that human-to-human transmission of the coronavirus had already occurred.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kuo |first1=Lily |title=China confirms human-to-human transmission of coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/20/coronavirus-spreads-to-beijing-as-china-confirms-new-cases |access-date=19 April 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=21 January 2020}}</ref> Later research published on January 29, 2020 indicated that among officially confirmed cases, human-to-human transmission may have started in December of the previous year, and the delay of disclosure on the results until then, rather than earlier in January, was met with criticism towards health authorities.<ref name=\"SCMPH2H\" /> [[Wang Guangfa]], one of the health officials, said that \"There was uncertainty regarding the human-to-human transmission\",<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://new.qq.com/omn/20200201/20200201A03EDU00.html|title=\u536b\u5065\u59d4\u4e13\u5bb6\u7ec4\u6210\u5458\u738b\u5e7f\u53d1\u56de\u5e94\"\u53ef\u9632\u53ef\u63a7\"\uff1a\u5e76\u65e0\u4e0d\u59a5 \u5916\u754c\u5b58\u5728\u8bef\u89e3_\u817e\u8baf\u65b0\u95fb|website=new.qq.com|access-date=March 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201074528/https://new.qq.com/omn/20200201/20200201A03EDU00.html|archive-date=February 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> but he was infected by a patient within 10 days of making the statement.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=creaders2181398>{{cite web|url=http://news.creaders.net/china/2020/01/21/2181398.html|title=\u4e0a\u592e\u89c6\u79f0\u75ab\u60c5\u53ef\u63a7 \u4e2d\u5171\u4e13\u5bb6\u81ea\u5df1\u4e2d\u62db\u88ab\u9694\u79bb \u2013 \u4e07\u7ef4\u8bfb\u8005\u7f51|website=news.creaders.net|access-date=March 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302172357/http://news.creaders.net/china/2020/01/21/2181398.html|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 27, 2020, the ''Daily Beast'' reported the editor of state-owned People's Daily tweeted an image of a [[Modular building|modular container building]] used for marketing purposes by Henan K-Home Steel Structure Co., Ltd. and not of the actual hospital. The tweet stated that the 1st building of the [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] had been completed in 16 hours. Some claim this post is part of the Chinese government's misinformation campaign to hype certain aspects of the government's response.<ref name=20200127thedailybeast>{{cite news |title=The Chinese Government Is Spreading Coronavirus Disinformation |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/coronavirus-disinformation-being-spread-by-chinese-government-to-convince-foreigners-its-doing-a-good-job |work=The Daily Beast |date=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\nThe tweet was later removed and replaced with a video of the modular container buildings being assembled at [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] again stating the first building had been completed in 16 hours.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=zlj517 |number=1221828307144134656 |date=March 22, 2020 |title=Lijian Zhao}}</ref>\n\nOn February 15, 2020, China's [[paramount leader]] and [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|Party general secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]] published an article which claimed he had been aware of the epidemic since January 7, 2020 and issued an order to contain the spread of the disease during a meeting on that day. However, a record of that same meeting released beforehand shows that there was zero mention of the epidemic throughout.<ref name=yahoo00163380>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.co.jp/byline/endohomare/20200216-00163380/|website=Yahoo! Japan News|date=February 16, 2020|title=\u7fd2\u8fd1\u5e73\u300c1\u67087\u65e5\u306b\u611f\u67d3\u5bfe\u7b56\u6307\u793a\u300d\u306f\u865a\u507d\u304b|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200216131334/https://news.yahoo.co.jp/byline/endohomare/20200216-00163380/|archive-date=February 16, 2020|url-status=live|quote=According to the issue of Chinese Communist Party Central Magazine \"[[Qiushi]]\" printed on February 15, Xi Jinping wrote, in the February 3rd meeting he claimed he had already warned about the novel coronavirus pneumonia on the January 7th meeting. However, there are no record of such in neither the February 3 meeting minute nor the January 7 meeting minute. Which indicate this is a retrospectively made excuse and Xi Jinping have made a lie.}}</ref><ref name=20200217cnn>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/17/asia/china-coronavirus-xi-jinping-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Did Xi Jinping know about the coronavirus outbreak earlier than first suggested?|date=February 17, 2020|publisher=CNN|first=James|last=Griffiths| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219052546/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/17/asia/china-coronavirus-xi-jinping-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Origin of virus ====\n\nIn response to the outbreak Chinese government officials launched a coordinated [[disinformation]] campaign seeking to spread doubt about the origin of the coronavirus and its outbreak.<ref name=RoginPost>{{cite web|first=Josh|last=Rogin| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/18/chinas-coronavirus-propaganda-campaign-is-putting-lives-risk/|title=China's coronavirus propaganda campaign is putting lives at risk|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=March 18, 2020|author-link=Josh Rogin|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319145226/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/18/chinas-coronavirus-propaganda-campaign-is-putting-lives-risk/|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat>{{cite news|first1=Ben|last1=Westcott|first2=Steven|last2=Jiang | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/13/asia/china-coronavirus-us-lijian-zhao-intl-hnk/index.html|publisher=CNN|date=March 13, 2020|title=Chinese diplomat promotes conspiracy theory that US military brought coronavirus to Wuhan|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182148/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/13/asia/china-coronavirus-us-lijian-zhao-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A review of Chinese state media and social media posts in early March 2020, conducted by the ''Washington Post'', found that anti-American conspiracy theories circulating among Chinese users \"gained steam through a mix of unexplained official statements magnified by social media, censorship and doubts stoked by state media and government officials.\"<ref name=ShihChinaEncourage>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/conspiracy-theorists-blame-the-us-for-coronavirus-china-is-happy-to-encourage-them/2020/03/05/50875458-5dc8-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|title=Conspiracy theorists blame U.S. for coronavirus. China is happy to encourage them.|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=March 5, 2020|first=Gerry|last=Shih| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318050859/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/conspiracy-theorists-blame-the-us-for-coronavirus-china-is-happy-to-encourage-them/2020/03/05/50875458-5dc8-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> U.S. Department of State officials,<ref name=AFPDangerous>{{cite news|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/03/16/us-summons-chinese-ambassador-dangerous-ridiculous-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/|title=US summons Chinese ambassador over 'dangerous and ridiculous' coronavirus conspiracy theory|agency=Agence France-Presse|date=March 16, 2020|first=Shaun|last=Tandon| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316125651/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/03/16/us-summons-chinese-ambassador-dangerous-ridiculous-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as University of Chicago political science professor [[Dali Yang]], an authority on Chinese politics, have stated that the  \"Chinese campaign\" appears intended to deflect attention away from the Chinese government's mishandling of the crisis.<ref name=ShihChinaEncourage />\n\nAt a press conference on March 12, 2020, two spokesmen for the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs ([[Zhao Lijian]] and [[Geng Shuang]]) promoted the conspiracy theory that the coronavirus had been \"bio-engineered\" by Western powers; and suggested that the U.S. government, specifically the U.S. Army, had spread the virus.<ref name=\"Taiwan News March 2020\" /><ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat /> No evidence supports these claims.<ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat /><ref name=20200318cnn>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/asia/trump-chinese-virus-tweet-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Trump and Beijing agree on the coronavirus crisis: It's someone else's fault|publisher=CNN|first=James|last=Griffiths| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 18, 2020|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318173526/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/asia/trump-chinese-virus-tweet-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Zhao also pushed these conspiracy theories on Twitter, which is [[Internet censorship in China|blocked in mainland China]] but is used as a [[public diplomacy]] tool by Chinese officials, who use the platform to promote the Chinese government and defend it against criticism.<ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat /> China's ambassador to South Africa also amplified these claims on Twitter.<ref name=RoginPost /><ref name=20200328voanews>{{Cite news|last=Yuwen|first=Cheng| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.voanews.com/usa/us-pushes-back-against-russian-chinese-iranian-coronavirus-disinformation|title=US Pushes Back Against Russian, Chinese, Iranian Coronavirus Disinformation|date=March 28, 2020|publisher=[[Voice of America]]|access-date=March 28, 2020|last2=Zhan|first2=Qiao}}</ref> Some Chinese state media had propagated the speculation that the virus may have spread in Italy before the Wuhan outbreak, after Italian doctor Giuseppe Remuzzi mentioned reports of strange pneumonia cases in November and December, he later said his words were twisted.<ref>{{cite news |title=An Italian doctor is now key to China's efforts to sow confusion over the coronavirus's origins |url=https://qz.com/1823417/italy-now-key-to-china-coronavirus-origin-propaganda-efforts/ |access-date=March 25, 2020 |work=Quartz}}</ref><ref name=scmp3076792>{{cite news |last1=Ho |first1=Matt |title=Italian professor repeats warning coronavirus may have spread outside China last year |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3076792/italian-professor-repeats-warning-coronavirus-may-have-spread |access-date=March 25, 2020 |work=South China Morning Post |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> In addition, articles from [[CounterPunch|''Counterpunch'']],<ref name=20200320counterpunch>{{Cite web|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2020/03/20/fighting-covid-19-in-cuba-china-and-the-united-states/|title=Fighting COVID 19 in Cuba, China and the United States|date=March 20, 2020|website=CounterPunch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> and ''[[Asia Times]]'',<ref name=20200317asiatimes>{{Cite web|url=https://asiatimes.com/2020/03/china-locked-in-hybrid-war-with-us/|title=China locked in hybrid war with US|last=Escobar|first=Pepe| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 17, 2020|website=Asia Times Online|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> as well as the Chinese scientist [[Zhong Nanshan]] have brought up speculations that the virus may not have originated in China.<ref name=scmp3077442>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3077442/coronavirus-pathogen-could-have-been-spreading-humans-decades|title=Coronavirus 'may have been quietly spreading long before pandemic'|date=March 29, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn \"intentional disinformation campaign\" by China was discussed among the [[Group of Seven]] (G7),<ref name=20200325reuters>{{cite news |first1=Arshad |last1=Mohammed |first2=David |last2=Brunnstrom | name-list-format = vanc |title=Pompeo says G7 discussed China's coronavirus 'disinformation' |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-heath-coronavirus-pompeo-china/pompeo-says-g7-discussed-chinas-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21C2N9 |agency=Reuters |access-date=March 31, 2020 |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> and the Chinese efforts were condemned by the U.S. Department of State,<ref name=RoginPost /> which criticized Chinese authorities for spreading \"dangerous and ridiculous\" conspiracy claims.<ref name=AFPDangerous /> The U.S. summoned China's ambassador to the United States, [[Cui Tiankai]], to issue a \"stern representation\" over the Chinese government's claims.<ref name=AFPDangerous />\n\n==== Statistics on fatalities ====\n\nOn March 27, 2020, doubts were raised about the accuracy of Chinese data relating to the official death toll of 2,535 in Wuhan as Chinese news outlet [[Caixin]] published photos of a truck unloading 2,500 boxed [[funeral urn]]s arriving from Hankou [[funeral home]] and a further 3,500 boxed funeral urns inside Jingya Hall. People collecting ashes faced large wait times because of poor communication, a lack of enough staff and the quantity of ashes that had to be searched to locate the correct box. It is alleged that this shows that many people who have died with COVID-19 symptoms but were not tested and those who have died of other health complications due to an overloaded medical system have been excluded from any official death counts.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-27/stacks-of-urns-in-wuhan-prompt-new-questions-of-virus-s-toll | title=Stacks of Urns in Wuhan Prompt New Questions of Virus's Toll | date=March 27, 2020 | access-date=March 28, 2020 | first1=Sharon | last1=Chen | first2=Dandan | last2=Li | first3=Claire| last3=Che | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref><ref name=20200327telegraph>{{cite newspaper| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/27/doubts-surface-chinese-virus-death-toll-thousands-urns-spotted/ | title=Doubts surface over Chinese virus death toll after thousands of urns spotted in Wuhan | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=March 27, 2020 | access-date=March 28, 2020 | first1=Sophia | last1=Yan | first2=Nicola| last2=Smith | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> It is unclear how many funeral urns have any relation to COVID-19 victims. Official records show that in 2019 there were around 14,000 cremations in Wuhan per quarter,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mzj.wuhan.gov.cn/tjxx/387166.jhtml | title=Wuhan Civil Affairs Bureau \u2013 Quarterly Report of Civil Affairs Statistics for the 4th Quarter of 2019 | date=March 13, 2020 | access-date=April 1, 2020 }}</ref> with 13,856 cremations reported for the 4th Quarter in Wuhan.<ref name=\"auto1\" /> Some articles<ref name=20200327japantimes>{{cite newspaper| url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/03/27/asia-pacific/science-health-asia-pacific/china-corona-toll/ | title=Stacks of urns in Wuhan prompt new questions about virus's toll | newspaper=[[Japan Times]] | date=March 27, 2020 | access-date=March 29, 2020 }}</ref> appearing in late March, however, initially reported an incorrect figure of 56,007 cremations in Wuhan for the 4th Quarter. This was based on a misunderstanding of how the Wuhan Civil Affairs data is reported, with quarterly figures representing the cumulative total of the year-to-date, rather than the quarter in question.<ref name=metabunk237642>{{cite web | url=https://www.metabunk.org/threads/wuhan-funeral-urns-as-an-indicator-of-death-rate.11175/#post-237642 | title=Wuhan Funeral Urns as an Indicator of Death Rate | date=March 31, 2020 | access-date=April 1, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n=== Cuban ===\nIn Cuba, Cuban president [[Miguel D\u00edaz Canel]] claimed on Twitter that Cuban [[Interferon alfa-2b]] was being used to treat and cure COVID-19 in China, linking to an article written by state-owned newspaper ''[[Granma (newspaper)|Granma]]''.{{ref|a}} The Chinese embassy in Cuba also made similar claims. Several Latin American news outlets<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvn-2.com/mundo/caribe/Medicamento-cubano-usado-China-coronavirus_0_5528447147.html|title=Medicamento cubano es usado en China contra el coronavirus|date=March 8, 2020|website=TVN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elperiodico-digital.com/2020/03/19/solicitan-a-la-presidente-que-considere-ingreso-de-medicina-cubana/|title=Solicitan a la presidente que considere ingreso de medicina cubana|work=El Peri\u00f3dico|date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> relayed the story, which was also relayed on social media, and the claims were eventually translated to Portuguese and French.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://factual.afp.com/el-antiviral-cubano-interferon-alfa-2b-se-usa-en-china-para-tratar-enfermos-del-nuevo-coronavirus|title=El antiviral cubano Interfer\u00f3n Alfa 2B se usa en China para tratar a enfermos del nuevo coronavirus, pero no es ni una vacuna ni una cura|date=March 18, 2020|website=AFP Factual}}</ref> In reality, the interferon was made by a Chinese company, in China, using Cuban technology, and it was under clinical trials in China as a potential cure, but it was not actively being used as such, as the claims suggested.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\n=== Iranian ===\n[[File:Ali Khamenei in 2020 Friday Prayer 06.jpg|thumb|Iran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] has suggested the U.S. government is responsible for the spread of coronavirus.]]\nIran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] said that the U.S. created \"a special version\" of the virus that is \"specifically built for Iran using the genetic data of Iranians which they have obtained through different means\".<ref name=\"independent-corona\" /><ref name=france2420200322 />\n\n=== Mexican ===\nMexico's federal government has been slow to respond to the COVID-19 pandemic as of late March 2020, with a great deal of criticism.<ref name=\"poor-coronavirus\">{{cite news |title=Mexican governor prompts outrage with claim poor are immune to coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/26/mexican-governor-miguel-barbosa-prompts-outrage-with-claim-poor-are-immune-to-covid-19 |work=The Guardian |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> President [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador]] has continued to hold rallies, be tactile with crowds, and downplay the threat of coronavirus to Mexicans' health and to the Mexican economy.<ref name=\"obrador=coronavirus\" /><ref name=20200402slate>{{cite news |title=AMLO Goes off the Rails |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/04/coronavirus-amlo-mexico-president.html |work=Slate |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Russian ===\nThe European Union watchdog group [[EUvsDisinfo]] reported that Russia was pushing what they believe was false information related to the [[SARS-CoV-2]] pandemic through \"pro-Kremlin outlets\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://euvsdisinfo.eu/the-kremlin-and-disinformation-about-coronavirus/|title=The Kremlin And Disinformation about Coronavirus|website=EUvsDisinfo|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 18, Russian presidential spokesman [[Dmitry Peskov]] denounced the findings.<ref>{{cite web |title='Russophobic': Kremlin Denies Evidence of Russian COVID-19 Disinformation Campaign |url=https://www.polygraph.info/a/kremlin-blames-russophobia-for-report-on-russian-coronavirus-disinfo/30498024.html |website=polygraph.info |access-date=March 31, 2020 |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Turkmen ===\n[[Reporters Without Borders]] reported that the [[government of Turkmenistan]] had banned the word \"coronavirus\" and that people could be arrested for wearing masks or discussing the pandemic.<ref name=\"Banned Use Of The Word\">{{cite news |title=Turkmenistan Has Banned Use of the Word 'Coronavirus' |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824611607/turkmenistan-has-banned-use-of-the-word-coronavirus |access-date=April 1, 2020 |publisher=NPR  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401090543/https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824611607/turkmenistan-has-banned-use-of-the-word-coronavirus |archive-date=April 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=npr824611607>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824611607/turkmenistan-has-banned-use-of-the-word-coronavirus |title=Turkmenistan Has Banned Use of the Word 'Coronavirus' : Coronavirus Live Updates |publisher=NPR |date=March 31, 2020 |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The organization later corrected their report, clarifying that the word itself was not banned, but maintained that it had been removed from informational brochures and that the government was restricting information about the virus and providing \"very one-sided information\".<ref name=20200331rsf>{{Cite web|url=https://rsf.org/en/news/coronavirus-limits-turkmenistan|title=Coronavirus off limits in Turkmenistan &#124; Reports Without Borders|date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> According to ''Chronicles of Turkmenistan'', state media did not begin reporting on the measures that had been taken until March 25.<ref name=20200402nytimes>{{cite news |last1=Kramer |first1=Andrew E. |title='The Fields Heal Everyone': Post-Soviet Leaders' Coronavirus Denial |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/02/world/asia/coronavirus-denial-post-soviet.html |access-date=April 2, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The BBC quoted an anonymous Turkmen citizen who stated that citizens may get into trouble for suggesting that the coronavirus is already on Turkmenistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-52186521|title=Why has this country reported no virus cases?|first=Abdujalil|last=Abdurasulov| name-list-format = vanc |date=April 7, 2020|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> The BBC article also states that the Turkmen government is working to control a possible outbreak.\n\n== Scams ==\n\nThe UN WHO has warned of criminal scams involving perpetrators who misrepresent themselves as representatives of the WHO seeking personal information from victims via email or phone.<ref name=un1058381>{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1058381 |title=UN health agency warns against coronavirus COVID-19 criminal scams |publisher=United Nations |date=February 29, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308013146/https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1058381 |archive-date=March 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also, the [[Federal Communications Commission]] has warned consumers not to click on links in suspicious emails or give out personal information in emails, text messages or phone calls claiming to be representatives from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcc.gov/covid-scams |title=COVID-19 Consumer Warnings and Safety Tips |publisher=Federal Communications Commission |date=March 31, 2020 |access-date=April 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Many financial companies, like [[Wells Fargo]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wellsfargo.com/jump/enterprise/coronavirus-response |title=COVID-19: We're here for you \u2013 Wells Fargo |publisher=Wells Fargo |access-date=April 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[LoanDepot]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://start.loandepot.com/assets/int-email/disaster/COVID19ServicingCommunicationv6.0.pdf |title=COVID-19 Information |publisher=LoanDepot |access-date=April 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> have posted similar warnings on their websites.\n\nCybersecurity firm [[Check Point]] stated there has been a large increase in [[phishing]] attacks to lure victims into unwittingly installing a computer virus under the guise of coronavirus-themed emails containing attachments. Cyber-criminals use deceptive domains such as \"cdc-gov.org\" instead of the correct \"cdc.gov\", or even [[domain spoofing|spoof the original domain]] so it resembles specific websites. Over 4,000 coronavirus-related domains have been registered.<ref name=vox21164745>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/5/21164745/coronavirus-phishing-email-scams |title=Coronavirus email scams are trying to cash in on your fear |work=vox.com |first=Sara |last=Morrison| name-list-format = vanc  |date=March 5, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306153955/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/5/21164745/coronavirus-phishing-email-scams |archive-date=March 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPolice in New Jersey, United States reported incidents of criminals knocking on people's doors and claiming to be from the CDC. They then attempt to sell products at inflated prices or otherwise scam victims under the guise of educating and protecting the public from the coronavirus.<ref name=yahoo171111975>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-sinister-people-knocking-doors-171111975.html |title=Coronavirus: Sinister people are knocking on doors claiming to be part of official disease response, police warn |work=The Independent |via=[[Yahoo! News]] |first=Andrew |last=Griffin | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 10, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311172735/https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-sinister-people-knocking-doors-171111975.html |archive-date=March 11, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nLinks that purportedly direct to the [[Johns Hopkins University]] coronavirus map, but instead direct to a false site that spreads [[malware]] have been circulating on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hackers are using coronavirus concerns to trick you, cybersecurity pros warn |date=March 15, 2020 |first=Wallace |last=Witkowski | name-list-format = vanc |work=[[MarketWatch]] |url= https://www.marketwatch.com/story/hackers-are-using-coronavirus-concerns-to-trick-you-cybersecurity-pros-warn-2020-03-12 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200407120751/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/hackers-are-using-coronavirus-concerns-to-trick-you-cybersecurity-pros-warn-2020-03-12 |archive-date=April 7, 2020 |url-status=live |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article241171546.html|title=Hackers made their own coronavirus map to spread malware, feds warn |work=The Miami Herald |date=March 13, 2020 |access-date=March 14, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200315021637/https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article241171546.html |archive-date=March 15, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Miscellaneous ==\n=== Bat soup ===\nSome media outlets, including ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and [[RT (TV network)|RT]], as well as individuals, disseminated a video showing a Chinese woman eating a bat, falsely suggesting that it was filmed in Wuhan and connecting it to the outbreak.<ref name=\"20200127foreignpolicy\">{{Cite news |first=James |last=Palmer | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-wuhan-virus/ |title=Don't Blame Bat Soup for the Wuhan Virus |date=January 27, 2020 |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |access-date=February 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203090706/https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-wuhan-virus/ |archive-date=February 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=20200130theguardianB /> However, the widely circulated video contains unrelated footage of a Chinese travel [[vlogger]], Wang Mengyun, eating bat soup in the island country of [[Palau]] in 2016.<ref name=20200127foreignpolicy /><ref name=\"20200130theguardianB\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum |title=Bat soup, dodgy cures and 'diseasology': the spread of coronavirus misinformation |first=Josh |last=Taylor | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 30, 2020 |website=The Guardian |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208030512/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200129news\">{{cite web |url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/food/food-warnings/chinese-influencer-wang-mengyun-aka-bat-soup-girl-breaks-silence/news-story/63ef0cec5b6d448d1843e2e1bcadb14d |title=Chinese influencer Wang Mengyun, aka 'Bat soup girl' breaks silence |first=Marnie |last=O'Neill | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 29, 2020 |website=news.au |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208145637/https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/food/food-warnings/chinese-influencer-wang-mengyun-aka-bat-soup-girl-breaks-silence/news-story/63ef0cec5b6d448d1843e2e1bcadb14d |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"fx-bso\">{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/food-drink/coronavirus-chinese-blogger-eats-bat-soup |title=Coronavirus: Outrage over Chinese blogger eating 'bat soup' sparks apology |last=Gaynor |first=Gerren Keith | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 28, 2020 |publisher=Fox News Channel |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204201417/https://www.foxnews.com/food-drink/coronavirus-chinese-blogger-eats-bat-soup |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Wang posted an apology on [[Microblogging in China|Weibo]],<ref name=20200129news /><ref name=fx-bso /> in which she said that she had received abuse and threats,<ref name=20200129news /> and that she had only wanted to showcase [[Palauan cuisine]].<ref name=20200129news /><ref name=fx-bso /> The spread of misinformation about bat consumption has been characterized by [[Xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|xenophobic and racist sentiment]] toward Asians.<ref name=al-watsm /><ref name=20200301washingtonpost>{{cite web |last1=Romm |first1=Tony |title=Millions of tweets peddled conspiracy theories about coronavirus in other countries, an unpublished U.S. report says |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/02/29/twitter-coronavirus-misinformation-state-department/ |website=The Washington Post |date=March 1, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309040454/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/02/29/twitter-coronavirus-misinformation-state-department/ |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=20200203latimes>{{cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Suhauna |title=Fear of coronavirus fuels racist sentiment targeting Asians |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-03/fear-panic-around-the-coronavirus-fuels-racist-sentiment |website=Los Angeles Times |date=February 3, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205072802/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-03/fear-panic-around-the-coronavirus-fuels-racist-sentiment |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In contrast, scientists suggest that the virus originated in bats and migrated into an intermediary host animal before infecting people.<ref name=al-watsm /><ref name=bru-14bc>{{cite web|first1=Hilary|last1=Brueck|access-date=March 7, 2020|title=14 bogus claims about the coronavirus, including a fake coconut-oil cure and a false link to imported packages|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/wuhan-coronavirus-myths-red-meat-bleach-antibiotics-and-sesame-oil-2020-2|website=Business Insider|date=February 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206102658/https://www.businessinsider.com/wuhan-coronavirus-myths-red-meat-bleach-antibiotics-and-sesame-oil-2020-2/|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Simpsons'' prediction ===\nClaims that ''[[The Simpsons]]'' had predicted the coronavirus pandemic in 1993, accompanied by a doctored screenshot from the show (where the text \"Corona Virus\" was layered over the original text \"Apocalypse Meow\", without blocking it from view), were later found out to be false, with the claim being widely spread on social media.<ref name=20200303afp>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/image-simpsons-was-digitally-altered-make-it-look-it-predicted-novel-coronavirus|title=An image from The Simpsons was digitally altered to make it look like it predicted the novel coronavirus|date=March 3, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref><ref name=chicagotribune20200229>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-ent-simpsons-predicts-coronavirus-20200229-q6ekedk665bzvlrgdcvdgm6eqy-story.html|title=Did 'The Simpsons' really predict the coronavirus outbreak? Twitter thinks so|first=Christi|last=Carras| name-list-format = vanc |website=Chicago Tribune}}</ref>\n\n=== Corona beer misassociation ===\nA poll was released showing that 38% of American beer-drinkers have refused to drink [[Corona (beer)|Corona-brand beer]].<ref name=prnewswire301012225>{{cite press release|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/5wpr-survey-reveals-38-of-beer-drinking-americans-wouldnt-buy-corona-now-301012225.html?mod=article_inline|title=5WPR Survey Reveals 38% of Beer-Drinking Americans Wouldn't Buy Corona Now|publisher=5W Public Relations|date=February 27, 2020|agency=PR Newswire}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/cornavirus-corona-beer-they-have-nothing-to-do-with-each-other/|first=Kate|last=Gibson| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 1, 2020|title=Survey finds 38% of beer-drinking Americans say they won't order a Corona|publisher=CBS News|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306171055/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/cornavirus-corona-beer-they-have-nothing-to-do-with-each-other/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This statistic is not considered a reliable indication of an American belief that drinking the beer causes the virus, even though assumptions have been made along this line in the media and among the public.<ref name=bar-astw /><ref name=theatlantic607240>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/about-corona-poll/607240/|title=What the Dubious Corona Poll Reveals|last=Mounk|first=Yascha| name-list-format = vanc |date=February 28, 2020|website=The Atlantic|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312073643/https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/about-corona-poll/607240/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There is no direct link between the virus and the beer brand,<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=bar-astw>{{cite web|url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/americans-say-they-wont-drink-corona-because-of-coronavirus-but-sales-are-up-5-51583610529|title=Americans Say They Won't Drink Corona Beer Because of Coronavirus. Sales Are Up 5% Anyway.|last=Root|first=Al| name-list-format = vanc |website=Barron's|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307220916/https://www.barrons.com/articles/americans-say-they-wont-drink-corona-because-of-coronavirus-but-sales-are-up-5-51583610529|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> but rather, both names draw upon the Latin ''corona'', meaning 'crown'.\n\n=== Hospital conditions ===\nU.S. hospitals have been silencing doctors and other staff, threatening to fire them if they publicly speak about inadequacies in working-conditions and lack of equipment.<ref name=bl-sil>{{cite web |last1= Carville |first1= Olivia |last2= Court |first2= Emma |last3= Brown |first3= Kristen V | name-list-format = vanc |title= Hospitals Tell Doctors They'll Be Fired If They Speak Out About Lack of Gear |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-31/hospitals-tell-doctors-they-ll-be-fired-if-they-talk-to-press |website= Bloomberg | date= March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200401businessinsider>{{cite web |last1= Collman |first1= Ashley |title= Hospitals are threatening to fire health workers who speak to the media during the coronavirus outbreak |url= https://www.businessinsider.com/coroanvirus-hospital-health-workers-speaking-to-media-threatened-lose-job-2020-4 |website= Business Insider |date= April 1, 2020}}</ref> The Washington State Nurses Association states that there is an effort by hospitals to preserve their image.<ref name=bl-sil />\n\nSome conservative figures{{Who|date=April 2020}} in the United States downplayed the scale of the pandemic, stating that it has been exaggerated{{by whom|date=April 2020}} as part of an effort to hurt President Trump. Some people pointed to empty hospital parking lots as evidence that the virus has been exaggerated. Despite the empty parking lots, many hospitals in New York City and other places experienced thousands of COVID-19-related hospitalizations.<ref name=20200401nationalobserver>{{cite web\n|url= https://www.nationalobserver.com/2020/04/01/analysis/right-wing-conspiracy-theories-go-mainstream-amid-mounting-covid-19-death-toll\n|title= Right-wing conspiracy theories go mainstream amid mounting COVID-19 death toll|first= Caroline|last= Orr| name-list-format = vanc\n|date= April 1, 2020|website= National Observer|access-date= April 2, 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n=== Return of wildlife ===\nDuring the pandemic, many false and misleading images or news reports about the environmental impact of the coronavirus pandemic were shared by [[clickbait]] journalism sources and social media.<ref name=\"natgeo\" />\n\nA viral post that originated on [[Weibo (company)|Weibo]] and spread on Twitter claimed that a pack of elephants descended on a village under quarantine in China's [[Yunnan]], got drunk on corn wine, and passed out in a tea garden.<ref name=20200319ktvb>{{cite web |url=https://www.ktvb.com/article/news/verify/verify-did-elephants-get-drunk-on-corn-wine-while-humans-were-social-distancing/277-0c48ef63-33ec-478f-be6a-4ebdeb4b0299 |title=Verify: Did elephants get drunk on corn wine while humans were social distancing? |last=Spry Jr |first=Terry | name-list-format = vanc  |publisher=KTVB |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The state-owned {{citation needed span|date=April 2020|[[China News Service]]|reason=National Geographic links to Xinhua, not China News Service}} debunked the claim that the elephants got drunk on corn wine and noted that wild elephants were a common sight in the village; the image attached to the post was originally taken at the Asian Elephant Research Center in Yunnan in December 2019.<ref name=\"natgeo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2020/03/coronavirus-pandemic-fake-animal-viral-social-media-posts/ |title=Fake animal news abounds on social media as coronavirus upends life |author=Daly, Natasha |work=National Geographic |date=March 20, 2020 |access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing reports of reduced pollution levels in Italy as a result of lockdowns, images purporting to show swans and dolphins swimming in [[Venice]] canals went viral on social media. The image of the swans was revealed to have been taken in [[Burano]], where swans are common, while footage of the dolphins was filmed at a port in [[Sardinia]] hundreds of miles away.<ref name=\"natgeo\" /> The Venice mayor's office clarified that the reported water clarity in the canals was due to the lack of sediment being kicked up by boat traffic, not due to a lack of water pollution that was initially reported.<ref name=thehill488286>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |title=As Italy quarantines over coronavirus, swans appear in Venice canals, dolphins swim up playfully |author=Srikanth, Anagha |work=The Hill |date=March 18, 2020 |access-date=March 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319215915/https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown of India]], a video clip purporting to show the extremely rare [[Malabar large-spotted civet|Malabar civet]] (a [[critically endangered]], possibly [[Extinction|extinct]] species) walking the empty streets of [[Meppayur]] went viral on social media. Experts later identified the civet in the video as actually being the much more common [[small Indian civet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/spotted-malabar-civet-coronavirus/|title=Was a Rare Malabar Civet Spotted During COVID-19 Lockdown?|website=Snopes.com|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Another viral Indian video clip showed a pod of [[humpback whale]]s allegedly returning to the [[Arabian Sea]] offshore from [[Mumbai]] following the shutdown of shipping routes; however, this video was found to have actually been taken in 2019 in the [[Java Sea]].<ref name=20200405hindustantimes>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/it-s-viral/fact-check-does-viral-video-show-whales-swimming-at-bombay-high-here-s-the-truth/story-zEOP8acFmCXrK39s4VGJaK.html|title=Fact Check: Does viral video show whales swimming at Bombay High? Here's the truth|date=April 5, 2020|website=Hindustan Times|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Lions freed on the streets ===\nA social media joke suggesting that lions had been freed to keep people off the streets in Moscow was passed around as if it were true.<ref name=bbc52118949>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/stories-52118949/coronavirus-how-can-you-stop-the-spread-of-misinformation|title=Coronavirus: How can you stop an 'infodemic'?|website=BBC News|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== UK\u00a320 banknote ===\nA tweet started an internet meme that [[Bank of England]] [[Bank of England \u00a320 note|\u00a320 banknotes]] contained a picture of a 5G mast and the SARSCoV-2 virus.  Facebook and YouTube removed items pushing this story, and fact checking organisations established that the picture is of [[Margate Lighthouse]] and the \"virus\" is the staircase at the [[Tate Britain]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fullfact.org/online/5g-coronavirus-20-note/|title=\u00a320 notes don't have a secret message about 5G and coronavirus|first=Grace|last=Rahman| name-list-format = vanc |website=Full Fact}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/banknotes/polymer-20-pound-note The new \u00a320 note] The Bank of England</ref><ref>[https://turnercontemporary.org/support-us/what-can-i-do-with-my-old-20-note/ New \u00a320 note to feature Margate's Turner Contemporary] Turner Contemporary</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Criticism of response to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n* [[Buck passing]]\n* [[List of conspiracy theories]]\n* [[SARS conspiracy theory]]\n\n== Notes ==\n\n: 1.{{note|a}}''Granma'' is owned by the ruling political party in Cuba, the Communist Party of Cuba.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public/myth-busters World Health Organization: Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) advice for the public: Myth busters]\n* [https://www.politifact.com/coronavirus/ Coronavirus] at [[Politifact]]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Conspiracy theories}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Misinformation related to the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Alternative medicine]]\n[[Category:Biological warfare]]\n[[Category:China\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Communication of falsehoods]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories in China]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories in the United States]]\n[[Category:Fake news]]\n[[Category:Medical-related conspiracy theories]]\n[[Category:Misinformation]]\n[[Category:Pseudohistory]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscience]]\n[[Category:Disinformation operations]]\n", "name_user": "MarioGom", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTypes and origin:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misinformation_related_to_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic"}
{"title_page": "Dubbo railway station", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox station\n|name                = Dubbo\n|type                = \n|style               = NSW TrainLink regional\n|image               = Dubbo NSW 2830, Australia - panoramio (31).jpg\n|image_size          = \n|image_caption       = \n|address             = Talbragar Street, [[Dubbo]], [[Dubbo Regional Council]], [[New South Wales]]\n|country             = Australia\n|coordinates         = {{coord|-32.2448|148.6095|region:AU-NSW_type:landmark|display=inline,title|format=dms}} \n|elevation           = \n|distance            = {{convert|462.20|km|abbr=on}} from [[Central railway station, Sydney|Central]]\n|line                = {{bulleted list|[[Main Western railway line|Main Western]] {{small|(train and coach)}}|[[Coonamble railway line|Coonamble]] {{small|(coach)}}|[[Molong-Dubbo railway line|Molong-Dubbo]] {{small|(coach)}}}}\n|other               = \n|structure           = Ground\n|platform            = 1\n|depth               = \n|levels              = \n|tracks              = 2\n|parking             = \n|bicycle             = \n|opened              = 1 February 1881\n|closed              = \n|rebuilt             = \n|electrified         = \n|disabled            = Yes\n|code                = [[List of New South Wales railway station codes|DBO]]\n|owned               = [[RailCorp]]\n|operator            = [[NSW TrainLink]]\n|zone                = \n|former              = \n|passengers          = \n|pass_year           = \n|pass_percent        = \n|pass_system         = \n|mpassengers         = \n|services            = \n{{s-rail|title=NSW TrainLink}}\n{{s-line|system=NSW TrainLink|line=Western|branch=Dubbo XPT|next=Geurie}}\n||map_locator         = New South Wales\n|web                 = \n|route_map           = \n|map_state           = \n|embedded =\n{{Infobox designation list\n| embed = yes\n| designation1 = New South Wales State Heritage Register\n| designation1_offname = ''Dubbo Railway Station and yard group''\n| designation1_type = State heritage (complex / group)\n| designation1_date = 2 April 1999\n| delisted1_date = \n| designation1_partof = \n| designation1_number = 1130\n| designation1_free1name =  Type\n| designation1_free1value = Railway Platform/ Station\n| designation1_free2name =  Category\n| designation1_free2value = Transport - Rail\n| designation1_free3name = Architect\n| designation1_free3value = [[John Whitton]] {{small|(attributed)}}\n| designation1_free4name = Builder\n| designation1_free4value = Henry Albert Brigg\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Dubbo railway station ''' is a [[heritage register|heritage-listed]] [[railway station]] and [[bus interchange]] located on the [[Main Western railway line|Main Western line]] in [[Dubbo]] in the [[Dubbo Regional Council]] local government area of [[New South Wales]], Australia. The station serves the city of Dubbo and was opened on 1 February 1881.<ref>[http://www.nswrail.net/locations/show.php?name=NSW:Dubbo Dubbo Station] NSWrail.net</ref> The station is also known as '''Dubbo Railway Station and yard group'''. The property is owned by [[RailCorp]], an [[government agency|agency]] of the [[Government of New South Wales]] and was added to the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 2 April 1999.<ref name=nswshr-1130>{{cite NSW SHR|5011998|Dubbo Railway Station and yards group|hr=01130|fn=EF10/22234|accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref> The station and associated yards were designed by the office of the Engineer-in-Chief of the [[New South Wales Government Railways|NSW Government Railways]], under the direction of [[John Whitton]].<ref name=nswshr-4806342>{{cite NSW SHR|4806342|Dubbo Railway Precinct|hr=|fn=|accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nDubbo was a major railway centre, being the junction for the Main Western, [[Molong-Dubbo railway line|Molong-Dubbo]] and [[Coonamble railway line|Coonamble]] lines and maintaining a sizeable locomotive depot. Dubbo was the limit for heavier [[New South Wales C36 class locomotive|36]], [[New South Wales C38 class locomotive|38]] and [[New South Wales AD60 class locomotive|60]] class locomotives, with smaller locomotives taking over for journeys further west.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Byways of Steam: Dubbo (Part 1)|journal=[[Roundhouse (periodical)|Roundhouse]]|date=October 1985|pages=4\u201328|issn=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Byways of Steam: Dubbo (Part 2)|journal=Roundhouse|date=January 1986|pages=4\u201314|issn=}}</ref> The station previously had a bay platform, which was removed in August 1988.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Signalling & Safeworking|journal=[[Railway Digest]]|date=October 1988|page=382|issn=}}</ref> Rail services east from [[Central railway station, Sydney|Central Sydney]] terminate at Dubbo and there are now services by coaches to the north west.\n\n==Services==\nDubbo was served by the ''[[Western Mail (train)|Western Mail]]'' from [[Central railway station, Sydney|Central Sydney]] until services ceased in November 1988.<ref>\"Last Passengers\" ''Railway Digest'' January 1989 page 20</ref><ref>\"The Last Post for the Last Mail\" ''Railway Digest'' February 1989 page 53</ref> At Dubbo it connected with the ''[[Far West Express]]'' to [[Bourke, New South Wales|Bourke]], [[Cobar]] and [[Coonamble]].<ref name=Railmotors&XPTs>{{Cite book|last1=Cooke|first=David|title=Railmotors and XPTs|publisher=Australian Railway Historical Society NSW Division|year=1984|isbn=0-909650-23-3}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1975, the [[Public Transport Commission]] introduced six [[Denning (bus manufacturer)|Denning coaches]] to replace all train services north and west from Dubbo.<ref>{{cite journal|title=State Rail Coach Services - The Vehicles|journal=Australian Bus Panorama|volume=9|number=3|date=October 1993|issn=}}</ref>\n\nToday Dubbo is served by [[NSW TrainLink]]'s daily ''[[Central West Express|Central West]] [[New South Wales XPT|XPT]]'' service operating to and from Central Sydney.<ref name=Timetable>{{Cite New South Wales transport timetables|Western Region}}</ref> NSW TrainLink also operate road coach services from Dubbo to [[Lithgow railway station|Lithgow]], [[Cootamundra railway station|Cootamundra]], [[Broken Hill railway station|Broken Hill]], [[Bourke, New South Wales|Bourke]], [[Nyngan]] and [[Lightning Ridge]].<ref name=Timetable/><ref>{{Cite New South Wales transport timetables|Southern Region}}</ref>\n\n{{Sydney Trains platform box\n|p1linename =  NSW Trainlink Western\n|p1stop     = services to [[Central railway station, Sydney|Sydney Central]] \n|p1notes    = }}\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Dubbo NSW 2830, Australia - panoramio (52).jpg|thumb|250px|Eastbound view of the platform]]\nMost of the stone structures comprising Dubbo Railway Station were built between 1879 and 1881 in preparation for its opening in 1881. The station master's residence was completed that same year. In the late 19th and early 20th centuries some additions were made to the precinct, including:<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n*1891 construction of the lamp room and wool stage;\n*1893 Dubbo West rail siding;\n*1897 carriage shed;\n*1898 the western end platform extension;\n*1893 opening of the Dubbo-Coonamble rail line;\n*1904 installation of a {{convert|20|t|ST|adj=on}} cart weighbridge and extensions to the [[Sydney]] end of the platform;\n*1908 grain shed.\n\nNumerous additions and alterations were made in the first two decades of the early 20th century, decreasing in frequency into the 1930s and 1940s.<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n\nBy 1975 passenger services to [[Bourke, New South Wales|Bourke]], [[Cobar]] and Coonamble were replaced by a road coach services connecting with the trains at Dubbo Railway Station.<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n\nThe 1980s saw demolition of several by-then anacrhonistic structural elements including the municipal gas siding, the livestock loading facility, the [[Darling Street]] gate house and the Institute Hall (relocated elsewhere). In 1988 the Dubbo-[[Molong]] line was decommissioned in 1988.<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n\nDubbo Railway Station remains an operational station on the western line, operated by RailCorp, although the station master's residence is now in private ownership.<ref name=nswshr-1130/><ref name=nswshr-1130-1649/>{{rp|13}}\n\n== Description ==\n===Buildings===\nThe station building is a type 5 stone first class station building, erected in 1881, with platform [[awnings]] cantilevered via [[Bracket (architecture)|brackets]] on steel posts. The station contained a railway refreshment room accommodation, also completed in stone in 1881.<ref name=nswshr-1130-1646>Lot 200/DP1165856</ref> There are two adjacent residences, the station master's house located at Talbragar Street,<ref name=nswshr-1130-1647>Lot 2/DP 1006205</ref> being a type 4 building, completed in 1881 in stone; and at 106 Darling Street, being a type 11 building in stone, originally used as a locomotive straight [[shed]].<ref name=nswshr-1130/><ref name=nswshr-1130-1648>Lot 4/DP 1006205</ref>\n\n===Structures===\nThe railway station platform faces were completed in 1881 in stone; and the location pump house was completed in [[Corrugated galvanised iron|corrugated iron]], attached to the bridge, and completed {{circa|1881}}.<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n\n=== Modifications and dates ===\n*1879-81 most of the stone structures of the station built in preparation for its 1881 opening. Station master's residence built 1881.<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n*1891 lamp room and wool stage built\n*1893 Dubbo West siding added\n*1896-1900 removal shop front (and rear?) at No 73\n*1897 carriage shed added\n*1898 western end platform extension made<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n*1903 Dubbo-Coonamble line opens this year.\n*1904 installation of {{convert|20|t|ST|adj=on}} cart weighbridge and extensions to Sydney end of the platform.\n*1906 addition of a transhipping shed\n*1908 grain shed added.<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n\nIn the first two decades of the 20th century numerous additions and alterations were made, decreasing in frequency into the 1930s and 1940s.<ref name=nswshr-1130/> By 1975 passenger services to Bourke, Cobar and Coonamble were replaced by a road coach service, connecting with trains at Dubbo.<ref name=nswshr-1130/> The 1980s saw demolition of several by-then anachronistic structural elements including the municipal gas siding, livestock loading facility, Darling Street gate house and Institute Hall (relocated). In 1988 the Dubbo-Molong line was decommissioned.<ref name=nswshr-1130/> In 2015 the Dubbo railway station was an operational rail station on the western line only, although the residence at 106 Darling Street is now in private ownership.<ref name=nswshr-1130/><ref name=nswshr-1130-1649>{{cite book|author=OzArk Environmental & Heritage Management P/L|date=2015|title=Statement of Heritage Impact: Dubbo Station Interchange Upgrade}}</ref>{{rp|12\u201313}}\n\n== Heritage listing ==\nDubbo station and residences is one of the few groups of buildings on the NSW system constructed in stone and one of the very few stone first class railway stations built. The surviving stone platform faces are rare and of high significance. The site is of high significance as it is situated adjacent to some excellent early industrial buildings used in relation to the railway and the railway hotel. The group is an important element in the townscape of Dubbo which is an historic centre which relies on tourism and its historic theme. The whole of the railway station group is of very high significance to the development and history of Dubbo and the railway system.<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n\nDubbo railway station was listed on the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 2 April 1999 having satisfied the following criteria.<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n\n'''The place possesses uncommon, rare or endangered aspects of the cultural or natural history of New South Wales.'''\n\nThis item is assessed as historically rare. This item is assessed as scientifically rare. This item is assessed as archaeologically rare. This item is assessed as socially rare.<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n\n== See also ==\n{{stack|{{Portal|New South Wales|Railways}}}}\n*[[:Category:Railway stations in New South Wales|List of railway stations in New South Wales]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite book|author=Cottee, J. M.|date=2004|title=Stations on the track: selected New South Wales country railway stations: an historical overview}}\n* {{cite book|author=OzArk Environmental & Heritage Management P/L|date=2015|title=Statement of Heritage Impact: Dubbo Station Interchange Upgrade}}\n\n=== Attribution ===\n* {{NSW-SHR-CC-contains|name=Dubbo Railway Station and yard group|dno=5011998|id=01130|year=2018|accessdate=2 June 2018}}\n* {{NSW-SHR-CC-contains|name=Dubbo Railway Precinct|dno=4806342|id=SRA342|year=2018|accessdate=22 June 2018}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category-inline}}\n*[https://transportnsw.info/stop?q=10155006#/ Dubbo station details] Transport for New South Wales\n\n{{Transport for New South Wales railway stations|Western Region=y|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Easy Access railway stations in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:John Whitton railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1881]]\n[[Category:Regional railway stations in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:1881 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:New South Wales State Heritage Register]]\n[[Category:Dubbo]]\n[[Category:Bus stations in Australia]]\n[[Category:Articles incorporating text from the New South Wales State Heritage Register]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox station\n|name                = Dubbo\n|type                = \n|style               = NSW TrainLink regional\n|image               = Dubbo NSW 2830, Australia - panoramio (31).jpg\n|image_size          = \n|image_caption       = \n|address             = Talbragar Street, [[Dubbo]], [[Dubbo Regional Council]], [[New South Wales]]\n|country             = Australia\n|coordinates         = {{coord|-32.2448|148.6095|region:AU-NSW_type:landmark|display=inline,title|format=dms}} \n|elevation           = \n|distance            = {{convert|462.20|km|abbr=on}} from [[Central railway station, Sydney|Central]]\n|line                = {{bulleted list|[[Main Western railway line|Main Western]] {{small|(train and coach)}}|[[Coonamble railway line|Coonamble]] {{small|(coach)}}|[[Molong-Dubbo railway line|Molong-Dubbo]] {{small|(coach)}}}}\n|other               = \n|structure           = Ground\n|platform            = 1\n|depth               = \n|levels              = \n|tracks              = 2\n|parking             = \n|bicycle             = \n|opened              = 1 February 1881\n|closed              = \n|rebuilt             = \n|electrified         = \n|disabled            = Yes\n|code                = [[List of New South Wales railway station codes|DBO]]\n|owned               = [[RailCorp]]\n|operator            = [[NSW TrainLink]]\n|zone                = \n|former              = \n|passengers          = \n|pass_year           = \n|pass_percent        = \n|pass_system         = \n|mpassengers         = \n|services            = \n{{s-rail|title=NSW TrainLink}}\n{{s-line|system=NSW TrainLink|line=Western|branch=Dubbo XPT|next=Geurie}}\n||map_locator         = New South Wales\n|web                 = \n|route_map           = \n|map_state           = \n|embedded =\n{{Infobox designation list\n| embed = yes\n| designation1 = New South Wales State Heritage Register\n| designation1_offname = ''Dubbo Railway Station and yard group''\n| designation1_type = State heritage (complex / group)\n| designation1_date = 2 April 1999\n| delisted1_date = \n| designation1_partof = \n| designation1_number = 1130\n| designation1_free1name =  Type\n| designation1_free1value = Railway Platform/ Station\n| designation1_free2name =  Category\n| designation1_free2value = Transport - Rail\n| designation1_free3name = Architect\n| designation1_free3value = [[John Whitton]] {{small|(attributed)}}\n| designation1_free4name = Builder\n| designation1_free4value = Henry Albert Brigg\n}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Dubbo railway station ''' is a [[heritage register|heritage-listed]] [[railway station]] and [[bus interchange]] located on the [[Main Western railway line|Main Western line]] in [[Dubbo]] in the [[Dubbo Regional Council]] local government area of [[New South Wales]], Australia. The station serves the city of Dubbo and was opened on 1 February 1881.<ref>[http://www.nswrail.net/locations/show.php?name=NSW:Dubbo Dubbo Station] NSWrail.net</ref> The station is also known as '''Dubbo Railway Station and yard group'''. The property is owned by [[RailCorp]], an [[government agency|agency]] of the [[Government of New South Wales]] and was added to the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 2 April 1999.<ref name=nswshr-1130>{{cite NSW SHR|5011998|Dubbo Railway Station and yards group|hr=01130|fn=EF10/22234|accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref> The station and associated yards were designed by the office of the Engineer-in-Chief of the [[New South Wales Government Railways|NSW Government Railways]], under the direction of [[John Whitton]].<ref name=nswshr-4806342>{{cite NSW SHR|4806342|Dubbo Railway Precinct|hr=|fn=|accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nDubbo was a major railway centre, being the junction for the Main Western, [[Molong-Dubbo railway line|Molong-Dubbo]] and [[Coonamble railway line|Coonamble]] lines and maintaining a sizeable locomotive depot. Dubbo was the limit for heavier [[New South Wales C36 class locomotive|36]], [[New South Wales C38 class locomotive|38]] and [[New South Wales AD60 class locomotive|60]] class locomotives, with smaller locomotives taking over for journeys further west.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Byways of Steam: Dubbo (Part 1)|journal=[[Roundhouse (periodical)|Roundhouse]]|date=October 1985|pages=4\u201328|issn=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Byways of Steam: Dubbo (Part 2)|journal=Roundhouse|date=January 1986|pages=4\u201314|issn=}}</ref> The station previously had a bay platform, which was removed in August 1988.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Signalling & Safeworking|journal=[[Railway Digest]]|date=October 1988|page=382|issn=}}</ref> Rail services east from [[Central railway station, Sydney|Central Sydney]] terminate at Dubbo and there are now services by coaches to the north west.\n\n==Services==\nDubbo was served by the ''[[Western Mail (train)|Western Mail]]'' from [[Central railway station, Sydney|Central Sydney]] until services ceased in November 1988.<ref>\"Last Passengers\" ''Railway Digest'' January 1989 page 20</ref><ref>\"The Last Post for the Last Mail\" ''Railway Digest'' February 1989 page 53</ref> At Dubbo it connected with the ''[[Far West Express]]'' to [[Bourke, New South Wales|Bourke]], [[Cobar]] and [[Coonamble]].<ref name=Railmotors&XPTs>{{Cite book|last1=Cooke|first=David|title=Railmotors and XPTs|publisher=Australian Railway Historical Society NSW Division|year=1984|isbn=0-909650-23-3}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1975, the [[Public Transport Commission]] introduced six [[Denning (bus manufacturer)|Denning coaches]] to replace all train services north and west from Dubbo.<ref>{{cite journal|title=State Rail Coach Services - The Vehicles|journal=Australian Bus Panorama|volume=9|number=3|date=October 1993|issn=}}</ref>\n\nToday Dubbo is served by [[NSW TrainLink]]'s daily ''[[Central West Express|Central West]] [[New South Wales XPT|XPT]]'' service operating to and from Central Sydney.<ref name=Timetable>{{Cite New South Wales transport timetables|Western Region}}</ref> NSW TrainLink also operate road coach services from Dubbo to [[Lithgow railway station|Lithgow]], [[Cootamundra railway station|Cootamundra]], [[Broken Hill railway station|Broken Hill]], [[Bourke, New South Wales|Bourke]], [[Nyngan]] and [[Lightning Ridge]].<ref name=Timetable/><ref>{{Cite New South Wales transport timetables|Southern Region}}</ref>\n\n{{Sydney Trains platform box\n|p1linename =  NSW Trainlink Western\n|p1stop     = services to [[Central railway station, Sydney|Sydney Central]] \n|p1notes    = }}\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Dubbo NSW 2830, Australia - panoramio (52).jpg|thumb|250px|Eastbound view of the platform]]\nMost of the stone structures comprising Dubbo Railway Station were built between 1879 and 1881 in preparation for its opening in 1881. The station master's residence was completed that same year. In the late 19th and early 20th centuries some additions were made to the precinct, including:<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n*1891 construction of the lamp room and wool stage;\n*1893 Dubbo West rail siding;\n*1897 carriage shed;\n*1898 the western end platform extension;\n*1893 opening of the Dubbo-Coonamble rail line;\n*1904 installation of a {{convert|20|t|ST|adj=on}} cart weighbridge and extensions to the [[Sydney]] end of the platform;\n*1908 grain shed.\n\nNumerous additions and alterations were made in the first two decades of the early 20th century, decreasing in frequency into the 1930s and 1940s.<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n\nBy 1975 passenger services to [[Bourke, New South Wales|Bourke]], [[Cobar]] and Coonamble were replaced by a road coach services connecting with the trains at Dubbo Railway Station.<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n\nThe 1980s saw demolition of several by-then anacrhonistic structural elements including the municipal gas siding, the livestock loading facility, the [[Darling Street]] gate house and the Institute Hall (relocated elsewhere). In 1988 the Dubbo-[[Molong]] line was decommissioned in 1988.<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n\nDubbo Railway Station remains an operational station on the western line, operated by RailCorp, although the station master's residence is now in private ownership.<ref name=nswshr-1130/><ref name=nswshr-1130-1649/>{{rp|13}}\n\n== Description ==\n===Buildings===\nThe station building is a type 5 stone first class station building, erected in 1881, with platform [[awnings]] cantilevered via [[Bracket (architecture)|brackets]] on steel posts. The station contained a railway refreshment room accommodation, also completed in stone in 1881.<ref name=nswshr-1130-1646>Lot 200/DP1165856</ref> There are two adjacent residences, the station master's house located at Talbragar Street,<ref name=nswshr-1130-1647>Lot 2/DP 1006205</ref> being a type 4 building, completed in 1881 in stone; and at 106 Darling Street, being a type 11 building in stone, originally used as a locomotive straight [[shed]].<ref name=nswshr-1130/><ref name=nswshr-1130-1648>Lot 4/DP 1006205</ref>\n\n===Structures===\nThe railway station platform faces were completed in 1881 in stone; and the location pump house was completed in [[Corrugated galvanised iron|corrugated iron]], attached to the bridge, and completed {{circa|1881}}.<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n\n=== Modifications and dates ===\n*1879-81 most of the stone structures of the station built in preparation for its 1881 opening. Station master's residence built 1881.<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n*1891 lamp room and wool stage built\n*1893 Dubbo West siding added\n*1896-1900 removal shop front (and rear?) at No 73\n*1897 carriage shed added\n*1898 western end platform extension made<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n*1903 Dubbo-Coonamble line opens this year.\n*1904 installation of {{convert|20|t|ST|adj=on}} cart weighbridge and extensions to Sydney end of the platform.\n*1906 addition of a transhipping shed\n*1908 grain shed added.<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n\nIn the first two decades of the 20th century numerous additions and alterations were made, decreasing in frequency into the 1930s and 1940s.<ref name=nswshr-1130/> By 1975 passenger services to Bourke, Cobar and Coonamble were replaced by a road coach service, connecting with trains at Dubbo.<ref name=nswshr-1130/> The 1980s saw demolition of several by-then anachronistic structural elements including the municipal gas siding, livestock loading facility, Darling Street gate house and Institute Hall (relocated). In 1988 the Dubbo-Molong line was decommissioned.<ref name=nswshr-1130/> In 2015 the Dubbo railway station was an operational rail station on the western line only, although the residence at 106 Darling Street is now in private ownership.<ref name=nswshr-1130/><ref name=nswshr-1130-1649>{{cite book|author=OzArk Environmental & Heritage Management P/L|date=2015|title=Statement of Heritage Impact: Dubbo Station Interchange Upgrade}}</ref>{{rp|12\u201313}}\n\n== Heritage listing ==\nDubbo station and residences is one of the few groups of buildings on the NSW system constructed in stone and one of the very few stone first class railway stations built. The surviving stone platform faces are rare and of high significance. The site is of high significance as it is situated adjacent to some excellent early industrial buildings used in relation to the railway and the railway hotel. The group is an important element in the townscape of Dubbo which is an historic centre which relies on tourism and its historic theme. The whole of the railway station group is of very high significance to the development and history of Dubbo and the railway system.<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n\nDubbo railway station was listed on the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 2 April 1999 having satisfied the following criteria.<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n\n'''The place possesses uncommon, rare or endangered aspects of the cultural or natural history of New South Wales.'''\n\nThis item is assessed as historically rare. This item is assessed as scientifically rare. This item is assessed as archaeologically rare. This item is assessed as socially rare.<ref name=nswshr-1130/>\n\n== See also ==\n{{stack|{{Portal|New South Wales|Railways}}}}\n*[[:Category:Railway stations in New South Wales|List of railway stations in New South Wales]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite book|author=Cottee, J. M.|date=2004|title=Stations on the track: selected New South Wales country railway stations: an historical overview}}\n* {{cite book|author=OzArk Environmental & Heritage Management P/L|date=2015|title=Statement of Heritage Impact: Dubbo Station Interchange Upgrade}}\n\n=== Attribution ===\n* {{NSW-SHR-CC-contains|name=Dubbo Railway Station and yard group|dno=5011998|id=01130|year=2018|accessdate=2 June 2018}}\n* {{NSW-SHR-CC-contains|name=Dubbo Railway Precinct|dno=4806342|id=SRA342|year=2018|accessdate=22 June 2018}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category-inline}}\n*[https://transportnsw.info/stop?q=10155006#/ Dubbo station details] Transport for New South Wales\n\n{{Transport for New South Wales railway stations|Western Region=y|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Easy Access railway stations in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:John Whitton railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1881]]\n[[Category:Regional railway stations in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:1881 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:New South Wales State Heritage Register]]\n[[Category:Dubbo]]\n[[Category:Bus stations in Australia]]\n[[Category:Articles incorporating text from the New South Wales State Heritage Register]]\n", "name_user": "Fork99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed \u2018the\u2019 as the starting word as the following word is a singular noun", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dubbo_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "Web page", "text_new": "{{short description|Information provided by a website and accessed in a web browser}}\n\n[[File:United States Antarctic Program website from 2018 02 22.png|thumb|right|240px|The [[home page]] of the [[United States Antarctic Program|usap.gov]] website]]\n\nA '''web page''' (also written as '''webpage''') is a specific collection of information provided by a [[website]] and displayed to a [[user (computing)|user]] in a [[web browser]]. A website typically consists of many web pages [[hyperlink|linked]] together in a coherent fashion. The name \"web page\" is a metaphor of [[Page (paper)|paper pages]] bound together into a [[book]].\n\n==Elements==\n\nThe core element of a web page is one or more [[text file]]s written in the [[HTML|Hypertext Markup Language]] (HTML).<ref name=\"elems\"/> Many web pages also make use of [[JavaScript]] [[source code|code]] for [[JavaScript#Website client-side usage|dynamic behavior]] and [[Cascading Style Sheets]] (CSS) code for [[presentation semantics]].<ref name=\"elems\">{{cite book|last1=Flanagan|first1=David|title=JavaScript - The definitive guide|page=1|edition=6|quote=JavaScript is part of the triad of technologies that all Web developers must learn: HTML to specify the content of web pages, CSS to specify the presentation of web pages and JavaScript to specify the behaviour of web pages.}}</ref> [[Image]]s, [[video]]s, and other [[multimedia]] files are also often embedded in web pages.\n\n== Navigation ==\n\nEach web page is identified by a distinct [[URL|Uniform Resource Locator]] (URL). When the user inputs a URL into their browser, that page's elements are downloaded from [[web server|servers]]. The browser then [[browser engine|transforms]] all of the elements into an interactive visual representation on the user's device.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://taligarsiel.com/Projects/howbrowserswork1.htm|title=Behind the scenes of modern web browsers|publisher=Tali Garsiel|accessdate=2018-04-21}}</ref>\n\nIf the user [[point and click|clicks]] or [[touchscreen|taps]] a [[hyperlink|link]] to another page, the browser repeats this process to display the new page, which could be part of the current website or a different one.\n\n== Deployment ==\n\nFrom the perspective of [[server-side]] website deployment, there are two types of web pages: [[static web page|static]] and [[dynamic web page|dynamic]]. Static pages are retrieved from the web server's [[file system]] without any modification,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://smallbusiness.chron.com/difference-between-dynamic-static-pages-69951.html|title=The Difference Between Dynamic & Static Web Pages|last=Melendez|first=Steven|date=2018-08-10|website=Chron|format=html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320233700/https://smallbusiness.chron.com/difference-between-dynamic-static-pages-69951.html|archive-date=2018-03-20|access-date=2019-03-20|quote=Static by definition means something that does not change. The first pages on the World Wide Web were largely static and unchanged, delivering the same information about a particular topic to anyone who visited. In some cases, sites may evolve slightly over time but are still largely static, meaning that they only change when manually changed by their creators, not on a regular and automated basis.|df=dmy-all}} </ref> while dynamic pages must be created by the web server [[wikt:on the fly|on the fly]], typically drawing from a [[database]] to fill out a [[web template]], before being sent to the user's browser.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcmag.com/encyclopedia/term/42199/dynamic-web-page|title=Definition of: dynamic Web page|website=[[PC Magazine]]|format=html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170117040526/https://www.pcmag.com/encyclopedia/term/42199/dynamic-web-page|archive-date=2017-01-17|access-date=2019-03-20|quote=A Web page that provides custom content for the user based on the results of a search or some other request.|df=dmy-all}}</ref>Big orange planet is a denver web design and development company.<ref>{{cite web |title=Denver web design and development company|url=https://www.bigorangeplanet.com/|accessdate=2019-03-20}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Web Page}}\n[[Category:Web design]]\n[[Category:Website management]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Information provided by a website and accessed in a web browser}}\n\n[[File:United States Antarctic Program website from 2018 02 22.png|thumb|right|240px|The [[home page]] of the [[United States Antarctic Program|usap.gov]] website]]\n\nA '''web page''' (also written as '''webpage''') is a specific collection of information provided by a [[website]] and displayed to a [[user (computing)|user]] in a [[web browser]]. A website typically consists of many web pages [[hyperlink|linked]] together in a coherent fashion. The name \"web page\" is a metaphor of [[Page (paper)|paper pages]] bound together into a [[book]].\n\n==Elements==\n\nThe core element of a web page is one or more [[text file]]s written in the [[HTML|Hypertext Markup Language]] (HTML).<ref name=\"elems\"/> Many web pages also make use of [[JavaScript]] [[source code|code]] for [[JavaScript#Website client-side usage|dynamic behavior]] and [[Cascading Style Sheets]] (CSS) code for [[presentation semantics]].<ref name=\"elems\">{{cite book|last1=Flanagan|first1=David|title=JavaScript - The definitive guide|page=1|edition=6|quote=JavaScript is part of the triad of technologies that all Web developers must learn: HTML to specify the content of web pages, CSS to specify the presentation of web pages and JavaScript to specify the behaviour of web pages.}}</ref> [[Image]]s, [[video]]s, and other [[multimedia]] files are also often embedded in web pages.\n\n== Navigation ==\n\nEach web page is identified by a distinct [[URL|Uniform Resource Locator]] (URL). When the user inputs a URL into their browser, that page's elements are downloaded from [[web server|servers]]. The browser then [[browser engine|transforms]] all of the elements into an interactive visual representation on the user's device.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://taligarsiel.com/Projects/howbrowserswork1.htm|title=Behind the scenes of modern web browsers|publisher=Tali Garsiel|accessdate=2018-04-21}}</ref>\n\nIf the user [[point and click|clicks]] or [[touchscreen|taps]] a [[hyperlink|link]] to another page, the browser repeats this process to display the new page, which could be part of the current website or a different one.\n\n== Deployment ==\n\nFrom the perspective of [[server-side]] website deployment, there are two types of web pages: [[static web page|static]] and [[dynamic web page|dynamic]]. Static pages are retrieved from the web server's [[file system]] without any modification,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://smallbusiness.chron.com/difference-between-dynamic-static-pages-69951.html|title=The Difference Between Dynamic & Static Web Pages|last=Melendez|first=Steven|date=2018-08-10|website=Chron|format=html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320233700/https://smallbusiness.chron.com/difference-between-dynamic-static-pages-69951.html|archive-date=2018-03-20|access-date=2019-03-20|quote=Static by definition means something that does not change. The first pages on the World Wide Web were largely static and unchanged, delivering the same information about a particular topic to anyone who visited. In some cases, sites may evolve slightly over time but are still largely static, meaning that they only change when manually changed by their creators, not on a regular and automated basis.|df=dmy-all}} </ref> while dynamic pages must be created by the web server [[wikt:on the fly|on the fly]], typically drawing from a [[database]] to fill out a [[web template]], before being sent to the user's browser.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcmag.com/encyclopedia/term/42199/dynamic-web-page|title=Definition of: dynamic Web page|website=[[PC Magazine]]|format=html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170117040526/https://www.pcmag.com/encyclopedia/term/42199/dynamic-web-page|archive-date=2017-01-17|access-date=2019-03-20|quote=A Web page that provides custom content for the user based on the results of a search or some other request.|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Web Page}}\n[[Category:Web design]]\n[[Category:Website management]]\n", "name_user": "37.111.248.206", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eDeployment)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_page"}
{"title_page": "Fulham, South Australia", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type                = suburb\n| name                = Fulham\n| city                = Adelaide\n| state               = sa\n| image               = House in suburban Adelaide, SA.JPG\n| caption             = This is actually my house and I am not sure why it is here without my concent.\n| pop                 = 2702\n| pop_year            = {{CensusAU|2016}}\n| pop_footnotes       = <ref name=ABS>{{Census 2016 AUS |id =SSC40462 |name=Fulham (State Suburb) |accessdate= 6 August 2019| quick=on}}</ref>\n| est                 = \n| postcode            = 5024<ref name=Postcodes>{{cite web |url=http://www.postcodes-australia.com/areas/sa/adelaide/fulham |title=Fulham, South Australia (Adelaide) |author= |date= |work=Postcodes-Australia |publisher=Postcodes-Australia.com |accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref>\n| area                = \n| dist1               = 8\n| dir1                = west\n| location1           = [[Adelaide city centre]]<ref name=Postcodes/>\n| lga                 = City of West Torrens\n| stategov            = [[Electoral district of Colton|Colton]] <small>''(2011)''</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecsa.sa.gov.au/apps/news/?year=2010 |title=Electoral Districts - Electoral District for the 2010 Election |publisher=Electoral Commission SA |accessdate=20 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110822191822/http://www.ecsa.sa.gov.au/apps/news/?year=2010 |archivedate=22 August 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n| fedgov              = [[Division of Hindmarsh|Hindmarsh]] <small>''(2011)''</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://apps.aec.gov.au/esearch |title=Find my electorate |date=15 April 2011 |publisher=Australian Electoral Commission |accessdate=20 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430090535/http://apps.aec.gov.au/esearch |archivedate=30 April 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n| near-n              = [[Fulham Gardens, South Australia|Fulham Gardens]]\n| near-ne             = [[Lockleys, South Australia|Lockleys]]\n| near-e              = [[Lockleys, South Australia|Lockleys]]\n| near-se             = [[Lockleys, South Australia|Lockleys]]\n| near-s              = [[West Beach, South Australia|West Beach]]\n| near-sw             = [[West Beach, South Australia|West Beach]]\n| near-w              = [[Henley Beach South, South Australia|Henley Beach South]]\n| near-nw             = [[Henley Beach, South Australia|Henley Beach]]\n}}\n[[File:Weetunga, Fulham.JPG|thumb|''Weetunga'', built in 1878 by Samuel White]]\n\n'''Fulham''' is a western [[Suburbs and localities (Australia)|suburb]] of [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]]. It is located in the [[City of West Torrens]].\n\n==History==\nThe area incorporating the current suburb of Fulham was purchased c. 1836 by John White (? \u201330 December 1860), who named it ''Fulham Farm'' after the suburb of [[Fulham]] in his native [[London]].<ref name=Manning>{{cite web |url=http://www.slsa.sa.gov.au/manning/pn/f/f5.htm#fulham |title=Place Names of South Australia |author= |date= |work=The Manning Index of South Australian History |publisher=State Library of South Australia |accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref> The White family home, ''[[Weetunga]]'', built by his son, Samuel White (1835?\u201316 November 1880), father of [[Samuel Albert White]] (1870\u20131954) which took three years to build,<ref>Linn, Rob. (1989): ''Nature's Pilgrim. The life and journeys of Captain S.A.White, naturalist, author and conservationist''. SA Government Printer: Adelaide. {{ISBN|0724365486}}</ref> remained with the family until placed on the market in 2014,<ref>[http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/realestate/news/iconic-fulham-mansion-weetunga-placed-on-the-market-for-the-first-time-in-its-135year-history/story-fni0ci8n-1226872688883 Iconic Fulham mansion 'Weetunga' placed on the market for the first time in its 135-year history] ''The Advertiser'', 2 April 2014. Retrieved 24 May 2014.</ref> and sold to another South Australian resident for $2.5 million in August 2015.<ref>[http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/messenger/west-beaches/why-ive-sold-the-house-uncle-john-built-135-years-ago/story-fni9llx9-1227477634619 Why I\u2019ve sold the house Uncle John built 135 years ago] ''The Weekly Times'', 10 August 2015. Retrieved 10 August 2015.</ref> The new owner of the home plans on restoring the home back to its former glory and building a wing to the east of the home.\n\nBoth Weetunga and ''[[The Oaks, Fulham|The Oaks]]'' in Henley Beach Road are listed on the [[South Australian Heritage Register]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://maps.sa.gov.au/heritagesearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=9134 | title=Dwelling ('Weetunga'), including Main House, former Kitchen, Servants' Quarters, Museum and Laundry | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://maps.sa.gov.au/heritagesearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=9133 | title=Dwelling ('The Oaks') and row of cottages | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nFulham sits on a bend in the [[River Torrens]]. The suburb also sits astride the intersection of [[Tapleys Hill Road]] and [[Henley Beach Road]].<ref name=UBD>{{cite book |title=Adelaide and surrounds street directory|last= |first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |edition= 47th|year=2009 |publisher=UBD |location= |isbn=978-0-7319-2336-6 |page= |pages= |url= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Update|section|date=August 2019}}\nThe 2006 census by the [[Australian Bureau of Statistics]] counted 2,611 persons in Fulham on census night. Of these, 49.8% were male and 50.2% were female.<ref name=ABS2006>{{Census 2006 AUS |id =SSC41541 |name=Fulham (State Suburb) |accessdate=20 April 2011 | quick=on}}</ref>\n\nThe majority of residents (73.5%) are of Australian birth, with other common census responses being [[Italy]] (5.4%) and [[England]] (5.1%).<ref name=ABS2006/>\n\nThe age distribution of Fulham residents is skewed towards an older population than the greater Australian population. 74.1% of residents were over 25 years in 2006, compared to the Australian average of 66.5%; and 25.9% were younger than 25 years, compared to the Australian average of 33.5%.<ref name=ABS2006/>\n\n==Community==\nThe local newspaper is the ''[[Weekly Times Messenger]]''. Other regional and national newspapers such as ''[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]'' and ''[[The Australian]]'' are also available.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com.au/SA/ |title=South Australian Newspapers |author= |date= |work=Newspapers.com.au |publisher=Australia G'day |accessdate=20 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429202448/http://www.newspapers.com.au/SA/ |archive-date=29 April 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Facilities and attractions==\n\n===Shopping and dining===\n* [[BP]]\n* [[Subway (restaurant)|Subway]]\n* Romeo's [[Foodland (South Australia)|Foodland]]\n* [[Hungry Jack's]]\n*[[Domino's Pizza]]\n\n===Parks===\nThe largest greenspace in Fulham is [[Torrens Linear Park|Linear Park]], lying along the [[River Torrens]] on the suburb's southern boundary.<ref name=UBD/>\n\n==Transportation==\n\n===Roads===\nFulham is serviced by [[Henley Beach Road]], connecting the suburb to [[Adelaide city centre]], and [[Tapleys Hill Road, Adelaide|Tapleys Hill Road]], one of the major [[arterial road]]s in the western suburbs of Adelaide.<ref name=UBD/>\n\n===Public transport===\nFulham is serviced by public transport run by the [[Adelaide Metro]].<ref name=Metro>{{cite web|url=http://timetables.adelaidemetro.com.au/ttsearch.php |title=Public Transport in Adelaide |date=12 January 2011 |work=Adelaide Metro official website |publisher=Dept. for Transport, Energy and Infrastructure, Public Transport Division |accessdate=20 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110426182058/http://timetables.adelaidemetro.com.au/ttsearch.php |archivedate=26 April 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n*H22 to Henley Beach South\n*H30 to West Lakes\n*H32 to Henley Beach South\n*H31 to Henley Square\n\n===Bicycle routes===\nA bicycle path extends along [[Torrens Linear Park|Linear Park]].<ref name=UBD/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Adelaide suburbs]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Fulham, South Australia}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.wtcc.sa.gov.au |title=City of West Torrens|author= |date= |work=Official website |publisher=City of West Torrens |accessdate=20 April 2011}}\n\n{{Coord|-34.927|138.512|format=dms|type:city_region:AU-SA|display=title}}\n{{City of West Torrens suburbs}}\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Adelaide]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type                = suburb\n| name                = Fulham\n| city                = Adelaide\n| state               = sa\n| image               = House in suburban Adelaide, SA.JPG\n| caption             = A post-war residential house in Fulham\n| pop                 = 2702\n| pop_year            = {{CensusAU|2016}}\n| pop_footnotes       = <ref name=ABS>{{Census 2016 AUS |id =SSC40462 |name=Fulham (State Suburb) |accessdate= 6 August 2019| quick=on}}</ref>\n| est                 = \n| postcode            = 5024<ref name=Postcodes>{{cite web |url=http://www.postcodes-australia.com/areas/sa/adelaide/fulham |title=Fulham, South Australia (Adelaide) |author= |date= |work=Postcodes-Australia |publisher=Postcodes-Australia.com |accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref>\n| area                = \n| dist1               = 8\n| dir1                = west\n| location1           = [[Adelaide city centre]]<ref name=Postcodes/>\n| lga                 = City of West Torrens\n| stategov            = [[Electoral district of Colton|Colton]] <small>''(2011)''</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecsa.sa.gov.au/apps/news/?year=2010 |title=Electoral Districts - Electoral District for the 2010 Election |publisher=Electoral Commission SA |accessdate=20 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110822191822/http://www.ecsa.sa.gov.au/apps/news/?year=2010 |archivedate=22 August 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n| fedgov              = [[Division of Hindmarsh|Hindmarsh]] <small>''(2011)''</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://apps.aec.gov.au/esearch |title=Find my electorate |date=15 April 2011 |publisher=Australian Electoral Commission |accessdate=20 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430090535/http://apps.aec.gov.au/esearch |archivedate=30 April 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n| near-n              = [[Fulham Gardens, South Australia|Fulham Gardens]]\n| near-ne             = [[Lockleys, South Australia|Lockleys]]\n| near-e              = [[Lockleys, South Australia|Lockleys]]\n| near-se             = [[Lockleys, South Australia|Lockleys]]\n| near-s              = [[West Beach, South Australia|West Beach]]\n| near-sw             = [[West Beach, South Australia|West Beach]]\n| near-w              = [[Henley Beach South, South Australia|Henley Beach South]]\n| near-nw             = [[Henley Beach, South Australia|Henley Beach]]\n}}\n[[File:Weetunga, Fulham.JPG|thumb|''Weetunga'', built in 1878 by Samuel White]]\n\n'''Fulham''' is a western [[Suburbs and localities (Australia)|suburb]] of [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]]. It is located in the [[City of West Torrens]].\n\n==History==\nThe area incorporating the current suburb of Fulham was purchased c. 1836 by John White (? \u201330 December 1860), who named it ''Fulham Farm'' after the suburb of [[Fulham]] in his native [[London]].<ref name=Manning>{{cite web |url=http://www.slsa.sa.gov.au/manning/pn/f/f5.htm#fulham |title=Place Names of South Australia |author= |date= |work=The Manning Index of South Australian History |publisher=State Library of South Australia |accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref> The White family home, ''[[Weetunga]]'', built by his son, Samuel White (1835?\u201316 November 1880), father of [[Samuel Albert White]] (1870\u20131954) which took three years to build,<ref>Linn, Rob. (1989): ''Nature's Pilgrim. The life and journeys of Captain S.A.White, naturalist, author and conservationist''. SA Government Printer: Adelaide. {{ISBN|0724365486}}</ref> remained with the family until placed on the market in 2014,<ref>[http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/realestate/news/iconic-fulham-mansion-weetunga-placed-on-the-market-for-the-first-time-in-its-135year-history/story-fni0ci8n-1226872688883 Iconic Fulham mansion 'Weetunga' placed on the market for the first time in its 135-year history] ''The Advertiser'', 2 April 2014. Retrieved 24 May 2014.</ref> and sold to another South Australian resident for $2.5 million in August 2015.<ref>[http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/messenger/west-beaches/why-ive-sold-the-house-uncle-john-built-135-years-ago/story-fni9llx9-1227477634619 Why I\u2019ve sold the house Uncle John built 135 years ago] ''The Weekly Times'', 10 August 2015. Retrieved 10 August 2015.</ref> The new owner of the home plans on restoring the home back to its former glory and building a wing to the east of the home.\n\nBoth Weetunga and ''[[The Oaks, Fulham|The Oaks]]'' in Henley Beach Road are listed on the [[South Australian Heritage Register]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://maps.sa.gov.au/heritagesearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=9134 | title=Dwelling ('Weetunga'), including Main House, former Kitchen, Servants' Quarters, Museum and Laundry | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://maps.sa.gov.au/heritagesearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=9133 | title=Dwelling ('The Oaks') and row of cottages | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nFulham sits on a bend in the [[River Torrens]]. The suburb also sits astride the intersection of [[Tapleys Hill Road]] and [[Henley Beach Road]].<ref name=UBD>{{cite book |title=Adelaide and surrounds street directory|last= |first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |edition= 47th|year=2009 |publisher=UBD |location= |isbn=978-0-7319-2336-6 |page= |pages= |url= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Update|section|date=August 2019}}\nThe 2006 census by the [[Australian Bureau of Statistics]] counted 2,611 persons in Fulham on census night. Of these, 49.8% were male and 50.2% were female.<ref name=ABS2006>{{Census 2006 AUS |id =SSC41541 |name=Fulham (State Suburb) |accessdate=20 April 2011 | quick=on}}</ref>\n\nThe majority of residents (73.5%) are of Australian birth, with other common census responses being [[Italy]] (5.4%) and [[England]] (5.1%).<ref name=ABS2006/>\n\nThe age distribution of Fulham residents is skewed towards an older population than the greater Australian population. 74.1% of residents were over 25 years in 2006, compared to the Australian average of 66.5%; and 25.9% were younger than 25 years, compared to the Australian average of 33.5%.<ref name=ABS2006/>\n\n==Community==\nThe local newspaper is the ''[[Weekly Times Messenger]]''. Other regional and national newspapers such as ''[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]'' and ''[[The Australian]]'' are also available.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com.au/SA/ |title=South Australian Newspapers |author= |date= |work=Newspapers.com.au |publisher=Australia G'day |accessdate=20 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429202448/http://www.newspapers.com.au/SA/ |archive-date=29 April 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Facilities and attractions==\n\n===Shopping and dining===\n* [[BP]]\n* [[Subway (restaurant)|Subway]]\n* Romeo's [[Foodland (South Australia)|Foodland]]\n* [[Hungry Jack's]]\n*[[Domino's Pizza]]\n\n===Parks===\nThe largest greenspace in Fulham is [[Torrens Linear Park|Linear Park]], lying along the [[River Torrens]] on the suburb's southern boundary.<ref name=UBD/>\n\n==Transportation==\n\n===Roads===\nFulham is serviced by [[Henley Beach Road]], connecting the suburb to [[Adelaide city centre]], and [[Tapleys Hill Road, Adelaide|Tapleys Hill Road]], one of the major [[arterial road]]s in the western suburbs of Adelaide.<ref name=UBD/>\n\n===Public transport===\nFulham is serviced by public transport run by the [[Adelaide Metro]].<ref name=Metro>{{cite web|url=http://timetables.adelaidemetro.com.au/ttsearch.php |title=Public Transport in Adelaide |date=12 January 2011 |work=Adelaide Metro official website |publisher=Dept. for Transport, Energy and Infrastructure, Public Transport Division |accessdate=20 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110426182058/http://timetables.adelaidemetro.com.au/ttsearch.php |archivedate=26 April 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n*H22 to Henley Beach South\n*H30 to West Lakes\n*H32 to Henley Beach South\n*H31 to Henley Square\n\n===Bicycle routes===\nA bicycle path extends along [[Torrens Linear Park|Linear Park]].<ref name=UBD/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Adelaide suburbs]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Fulham, South Australia}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.wtcc.sa.gov.au |title=City of West Torrens|author= |date= |work=Official website |publisher=City of West Torrens |accessdate=20 April 2011}}\n\n{{Coord|-34.927|138.512|format=dms|type:city_region:AU-SA|display=title}}\n{{City of West Torrens suburbs}}\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Adelaide]]\n", "name_user": "220.245.112.55", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fulham,_South_Australia"}
{"title_page": "Yuga", "text_new": "{{About||the 2006 '''film'''|Yuga (film)}}\n{{short description|Epoch or era in Hinduism: Maha, Satya, Treta, Dvapara and Kali Yuga}}\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2018}}\n{{Hinduism small}}\n\nIn [[Hinduism]], a '''Yuga''' ({{lang-sa|\u092f\u0941\u0917|yuga|age}}) is an [[unit of time|epoch]] or [[era]]. There are a total of four yugas\u2014''[[Satya Yuga]]'', ''[[Treta Yuga]],'' ''[[Dvapara Yuga]], and'' ''[[Kali Yuga]]''\u2014each having 1/4<sup>th</sup> less duration and [[dharma]] than the previous (''Satya'' most, ''Kali'' least).{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nA '''Maha Yuga''' ({{lang-sa|\u092e\u0939\u093e\u092f\u0941\u0917|mah\u0101yuga|great age}})\u2014also known as a '''Chatur Yuga''' ({{lang-sa|\u091a\u0924\u0941\u0930\u094d\u092f\u0941\u0917|caturyuga|four ages}}) or '''Yuga Cycle'''\u2014is an [[unit of time|epoch]] or [[era]]. A ''Maha Yuga'' is cyclical and contains a cycle of the four yugas: ''Satya'', ''Treta'', ''Dvapara'', and ''Kali''.<ref name=\"sb-12-2-39\"></ref> Each ''Maha Yuga'' consists of a descending set of the yugas: (S,T,D,K) (S,T,D,K).<ref name=\"sb-12-2-39\"></ref> Some spiritual leaders believe in an equinox based cycle where each ''Maha Yuga'' consists of much shorter descending and ascending sets of the yugas: (S,T,D,K,K,D,T,S) (S,T,D,K,K,D,T,S).{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Yuga characteristics ==\n\nThere are a total of four yugas\u2014''[[Satya Yuga]]'', ''[[Treta Yuga]],'' ''[[Dvapara Yuga]], and'' ''[[Kali Yuga]]''\u2014each having 1/4 less duration and [[dharma]] than the previous (''Satya'' most, ''Kali'' least). The descending yugas see a '''gradual decline'''{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} of dharma, wisdom, knowledge, intellectual capability, lifespan, emotional and physical strength.\n\nWithin a yuga is a starting ''Sandhya'' and ending ''Sandhyansa'', both lasting 1/10<sup>th</sup> the duration of the yuga.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Most of the characteristic changes can occur in these ''Sandhyas'' and ''Sandhyansas'', especially if that change is from ''Kali Yuga'' to ''Satya Yuga'' (two extremes).{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n* '''[[Satya Yuga]]''' (''Krita Yuga'', \"The age of truth\" or \"[[Golden Age#Hindu|Golden Age]]\"): The first and best yuga. It was the age of truth and perfection. This yuga had no crimes and all humans were kind and friendly. The ''Krita Yuga'' was so named because there was but one religion, and all men were saintly: therefore they were not required to perform religious ceremonies. Humans were long lived, powerfully built, honest, youthful, vigorous, erudite and virtuous. The Vedas were one. All mankind could attain to supreme blessedness. There was no agriculture or mining as the earth yielded those riches on its own. Weather was pleasant and everyone was happy. There were no religious sects. There was no disease, decrepitude or fear of anything.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}} Virtue reigns supreme. Human stature was 21 cubits (33 ft 6 inches). Average human lifespan was 100,000 years.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n* '''[[Treta Yuga]]''': This is the second yuga in order. However, \"treta\" means the \"third\". In this age, virtue diminishes slightly. At the beginning of the age, many emperors rise to dominance and conquer the world. Wars become frequent and weather begins to change to extremities. People become slightly diminished compared to their predecessors. Agriculture, labour and mining become existent.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}} There was 3 quarter virtue and 1 quarter sin. Normal human stature was 14 cubits (22 ft 4 inches). Average human lifespan was 10,000 years.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n* '''[[Dvapara Yuga]]''': This is the third yuga in order. However, \"dvapara\" means \"two\". In this age, people become tainted with qualities and aren't as strong as their ancestors. Diseases become rampant. Humans are discontent and fight each other. Vedas are divided into four parts. People still possess characteristics of youth in old age. Average lifespan of humans is around a few centuries.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} There was 1 half virtue and 1 half sin. Normal human stature was 7 cubits (11 ft 2 inches). Average human lifespan was 1,000 years.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n* '''[[Kali Yuga]]''': The final age. It is the age of darkness and ignorance. People stop following [[Dharma]] and lack virtue. They become slaves to their passions and are barely as powerful as their earliest ancestors in the ''Satya Yuga''. Society falls into disuse and people become liars and hypocrites. Knowledge is lost and scriptures are diminished. Humans eat forbidden and dirty food. The environment is polluted, water and food become scarce. Wealth is heavily diminished. Families become non-existent.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}} There is 1 quarter virtue and 3 quarter sin. Normal human stature is 3.5 cubits (5 ft 3 inches). Average human lifespan will be 100 years.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Current yuga==\n{{See also|Kali_Yuga#Possible_starting_and_ending_dates}}\n\nAccording to [[Purana|Puranic sources]],<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">The Bhagavata Purana (1.18.6), Vishnu Purana  (5.38.8), and Brahma Purana (212.8), the day Krishna left the earth was the day that the Dvapara Yuga ended and the Kali Yuga began.</ref> [[krishna|Krishna's]] departure marks the end of ''Dvapara Yuga'' and the start of '''''Kali Yuga''''', which is dated to 17/18 February 3102 BCE.<ref name=\"auto p139\">See: Matchett, Freda, \"The Puranas\", p 139 and Yano, Michio, \"Calendar, astrology and astronomy\" in {{Cite book|last=Flood| first=Gavin (Ed)|  year=2003| title=Blackwell companion to Hinduism| place=| publisher= [[Blackwell Publishing]]| edition=| isbn=978-0-631-21535-6|ref=harv}}</ref> ''Kali Yuga'' ends in 428899 CE (432,000 years). (See [[Kali_Yuga#Possible_starting_and_ending_dates|Kali Yuga]]).\n\n===Equinox yuga cycle===\nSome spiritual leaders believe in an equinox based ''Yuga Cycle'' where ascending ''Kali Yuga'' has ended and '''ascending ''Dvapara Yuga''''' has started such as:\n\n* [[Swami Sri Yukteswar Giri]]<ref name=\"jssy-hs\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Te-ftAEACAAJ&dq=yukteswar+1949|title=The Holy Science|author=Swami Yukteswar|publisher=Yogoda Sat-Sanga Society of India|year=1949|page={{page needed|date=August 2018}}|quote=According to Sri Yukteswar Giri, guru of Paramahansa Yogananda, The ascending  phase of the Kali Yuga began in September 499 CE (not exactly). Since September 1699, we have been in the ascending phase of the Dwapara Yuga. According to Sri yukteswar, since nobody wanted to announce the bad news of the beginning of the descending Kali Yuga, so they kept adding years to the Dvapara date (at that time 2400 Dvapara) only retitling the epoch to Kali.}}.</ref> who first theorized an equinox based ''Yuga Cycle'' and past it on to his primary disciple [[Paramahansa Yogananda]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=\nhttp://yogananda.com.au/gurus/yogananda_quotes38crisis.html|title=\nWorld Crisis \u2014 Paramahansa Yogananda Best Quotes|website=Paramahansa Yogananda|access-date=2020-04-20|quote=The life cycles of the earth. These cycles consist of 24,000 years, divided into four yugas or ages\u201412,000 years of ascending through these yugas to increasing enlightenment, and then 12,000 years of descending through the yugas to increasing ignorance and materialism. Each of these half-cycles is called a Daiva Yuga. The earth has already passed through many complete cycles since the dawn of creation. The four ages of each Daiva Yuga are Kali Yuga, the dark or materialistic age, Dwapara Yuga, the electrical or atomic age, Treta Yuga, the mental age; and Satya Yuga, the age of truth or enlightenment. The earth has already passed through Kali Yuga, the materialistic age of 1,200 years' duration. According to the calculations of my guru, Swami Sri Yukteswar, we are about 314 [2014] years into Dwapara Yuga, the second age, which consists of 2,400 years. Now in its ascendancy, this is the electrical age, even though it may yet seem very materialistic.}}</ref> and then to the world through his book: ''The Holy Science''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=\nhttps://www.ananda.org/ask/are-we-in-kali-yuga-or-dwapara-yuga-2/|title=Are We in Kali Yuga or Dwapara Yuga?|website=Ananda|access-date=2020-04-20|quote=In his book Religion in the New Age, Swami Kriyananda writes about the \u201cYuga Cycle Theory\u201d of Swami Sri Yukteswar, who passed along the information to his primary disciple, Paramhasa Yogananda and to the world, via his book The Holy Science.}}</ref> <p>''Dvapara'': 1700 CE - 4100 CE (2,400 years).</p>\n* [[Jaggi Vasudev|Jaggi Vasudev (Sadhguru)]]<ref name=\"jv-tgcoy\">{{Cite web|url=\nhttps://isha.sadhguru.org/sg/en/wisdom/article/kali-yuga-end-lies-ahead|title=\nKali Yuga \u2013 When Did it End and What Lies Ahead?|website=isha|access-date=2020-04-20|quote=The story of Mahabharat needs to be seen in a certain context. In 3140 BCE, the Kurukshetra War ended, and in 3102 BCE, Krishna left his body. Three to four months after the war, the Kali Yuga began. As of 2012 AD, Krishna\u2019s era ended 5,114 years ago. If you subtract 2592, which is the cumulative number of years of the two Kali Yugas that are at the bottom of the ellipse which describes the axial precession, you arrive at 2522 years. That means we have already completed 2522 years of Dwapara Yuga, and since its total duration is 2592 years, we still have 70 years until its completion. In the year 2082, we will complete Dwapara Yuga and move on to Treta Yuga. The world will go through another upheaval, not necessarily in terms of war but probably in terms of population explosion and natural calamities, before moving on to this new era of wellbeing and upward movement of human consciousness.}}</ref><p>''Dvapara'': 511 BCE - 2082 CE (2,592 years).</p>\n\n===Empirical evidence===\nAlthough conditioned [[jiva|jivas]] aren't perfect,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedabase.io/en/library/bg/introduction/|title=Bhagavad-g\u012bt\u0101 As It Is: Introduction|website=Bhaktivedanta Vedabase|access-date=2020-04-19|quote=Vedic knowledge is received from transcendental sources, and the first words were spoken by the Lord Himself. The words spoken by the Lord are called apauru\u1e63eya, meaning that they are different from words spoken by a person of the mundane world who is infected with four defects. A mundaner (1) is sure to commit mistakes, (2) is invariably illusioned, (3) has the tendency to cheat others and (4) is limited by imperfect senses. With these four imperfections, one cannot deliver perfect information of all-pervading knowledge.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedabase.io/en/library/iso/introduction/|title=\u015ar\u012b \u012a\u015bopani\u1e63ad: Introduction|website=Bhaktivedanta Vedabase|access-date=2020-04-19|quote=Veda means knowledge. Any knowledge you accept is veda, for the teachings of the Vedas are the original knowledge. In the conditioned state, our knowledge is subjected to many deficiencies. The difference between a conditioned soul and a liberated soul is that the conditioned soul has four kinds of defects. The first defect is that he must commit mistakes. ... To err is human. This is one defect of the conditioned soul. Another defect: to be illusioned. Illusion means to accept something which is not: m\u0101y\u0101. M\u0101y\u0101 means \u201cwhat is not.\u201d Everyone is accepting the body as the self. ... But you are not this body. This is illusion. The third defect is the cheating propensity. Everyone has the propensity to cheat others. Although a person is fool number one, he poses himself as very intelligent. Although it is already pointed out that he is in illusion and makes mistakes, he will theorize: \u201cI think this is this, this is this.\u201d But he does not even know his own position. He writes books of philosophy, although he is defective. That is his disease. That is cheating. Lastly, our senses are imperfect. We are very proud of our eyes. Often, someone will challenge, \u201cCan you show me God?\u201d But do you have the eyes to see God? You will never see if you haven\u2019t the eyes. If immediately the room becomes dark, you cannot even see your hands. So what power do you have to see? We cannot, therefore, expect knowledge (veda) with these imperfect senses. With all these deficiencies, in conditioned life we cannot give perfect knowledge to anyone. Nor are we ourselves perfect. Therefore we accept the Vedas as they are.}}</ref> one can compare each yuga's characteristics (human lifespan, dharma, etc.) to the present and historic state of the world and [[empirical evidence|empirically]] deduce which is the current yuga.\n\nFor example, the average human [[life expectancy]] worldwide since the 1700s has been below 80 years. Life expectancy starts from birth, so if the ~56 million yearly abortions<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sedgh|first1=Gilda|last2=Bearak|first2=Jonathan|last3=Singh|first3=Susheela|last4=Bankole|first4=Akinrinola|last5=Popinchalk|first5=Anna|last6=Ganatra|first6=Bela|last7=Rossier|first7=Cl\u00e9mentine|last8=Gerdts|first8=Caitlin|last9=Tun\u00e7alp|first9=\u00d6zge|last10=Johnson|first10=Brooke Ronald|last11=Johnston|first11=Heidi Bart|last12=Alkema|first12=Leontine|title=Abortion incidence between 1990 and 2014: global, regional, and subregional levels and trends|journal=The Lancet|date=May 2016|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(16)30380-4|pmid=27179755|volume=388|issue=10041|pages=258\u201367|pmc=5498988}}</ref> and other pre-birth deaths were included, the average lifespan would be far less. In '''''Kali Yuga''''', the average human lifespan is described as 100 years or less.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} '''''Kali Yuga''''' is also described as having the least [[dharma]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} which speaks to the massive amount of abortions<ref>{{Cite web|url=\nhttp://indiafacts.org/abortion-dharmic-perspective-iv-abortion-murder/|title=Abortion, a Dharmic Perspective\u2013 IV: Is Abortion murder?|website=indiafacts: truth be told|access-date=2020-04-19|quote=Dharmic texts perceive abortion as Adharma since, it prevents a Jiva from taking a physical birth, for which it was entitled to based on its prarabdha Karma.}}</ref> and other [[adharma|adharmic]] activities rampant in the world.\n\n==Puranic yuga cycle==\n[[File:Time Units in Hindu Cosmology.png|frame|Relationship between various time units in Hindu cosmology]]\n\nThe cycle of the yugas has been mentioned in the [[Mahabharata]] and it is widely accepted since ancient times.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nEach cycle of a ''Maha Yuga'' repeats the four yugas (ages) in the following order: ''Satya Yuga'', ''Treta Yuga'', ''Dvapara Yuga'' and ''Kali Yuga''.<ref name=\"sb-12-2-39\">{{Cite web|url=\nhttps://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/12/2/39/|title=\n\u015ar\u012bmad-Bh\u0101gavatam (Bh\u0101gavata Pur\u0101\u1e47a) 12.2.39|website=Bhaktivedanta Vedabase|access-date=2020-04-17|quote=The cycle of four ages \u2014 Satya, Tret\u0101, Dv\u0101para and Kali \u2014 continues perpetually among living beings on this earth, repeating the same general sequence of events.}}</ref>\n\n{{Cquote|text=The cycle of four ages \u2014 Satya, Tret\u0101, Dv\u0101para and Kali \u2014 continues perpetually among living beings on this earth, repeating the same general sequence of events.|source=[https://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/12/2/39/ Bh\u0101gavata Pur\u0101\u1e47a 12.2.39]}}\n\nLength of yugas:<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sm0BfUKwct0C&pg=PA50&lpg=PA50&dq=4,000+%2B+400+%2B+400+%3D+4,800+divine+years+(%3D+1,728,000+human+years)#v=onepage&q=4%2C000%20%2B%20400%20%2B%20400%20%3D%204%2C800%20divine%20years%20(%3D%201%2C728%2C000%20human%20years)&f=false|title=Tracing The Way: Spiritual Dimensions of the World Religions|page=50|first=Hans|last=Kng|publisher=A&C Black|isbn=9780826494238|date=2006-10-31}}</ref><ref name=\"sb-3-11-18\">{{Cite web|url=\nhttps://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/3/11/18/|title=\n\u015ar\u012bmad-Bh\u0101gavatam (Bh\u0101gavata Pur\u0101\u1e47a) 3.11.18|website=Bhaktivedanta Vedabase|access-date=2020-04-17|quote=Maitreya said: O Vidura, the four millenniums are called the Satya-, Tret\u0101-, Dv\u0101para- and Kali-yuga. The aggregate number of years of all of these combined is equal to twelve thousand years of the demigods.<p>Purport: The years of the demigods are equal to 360 years of humankind. As will be clarified in the subsequent verses, 12,000 of the demigods\u2019 years, including the transitional periods which are called yuga-sandhy\u0101s, comprise the total of the aforementioned four millenniums. Thus the aggregate of the above-mentioned four millenniums is 4,320,000 years.</p>}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=\nhttps://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/3/11/19/|title=\n\u015ar\u012bmad-Bh\u0101gavatam (Bh\u0101gavata Pur\u0101\u1e47a) 3.11.19|website=Bhaktivedanta Vedabase|access-date=2020-04-17|quote=The duration of the Satya millennium equals 4,800 years of the years of the demigods; the duration of the Tret\u0101 millennium equals 3,600 years of the demigods; the duration of the Dv\u0101para millennium equals 2,400 years; and that of the Kali millennium is 1,200 years of the demigods.<p>Purport: As aforementioned, one year of the demigods is equal to 360 years of the human beings. The duration of the Satya-yuga is therefore 4,800 \u00d7 360, or 1,728,000 years. The duration of the Tret\u0101-yuga is 3,600 \u00d7 360, or 1,296,000 years. The duration of the Dv\u0101para-yuga is 2,400 \u00d7 360, or 864,000 years. And the last, the Kali-yuga, is 1,200 \u00d7 360, or 432,000 years.</p>}}</ref> (See [[List of numbers in Hindu scriptures|Hindu numbers]]).\n* ''[[Satya Yuga]]''\u20141,728,000 years (4800 divine)\n* ''[[Treta Yuga]]''\u20141,296,000 years (3600 divine)\n* ''[[Dvapara Yuga]]''\u2014864,000 years (2400 divine)\n* ''[[Kali Yuga]]''\u2014432,000 years (1200 divine)\n\nWith one ''Maha Yuga'' containing a set of descending yugas (S,T,D,K), it lasts for '''4,320,000 years (12,000 divine years)'''.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pQHNDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA137|title=The Power of Stars|publisher=Springer|page=182|first=Bryan E.|last=Penprase|isbn=9783319525976|date=2017-05-05}}</ref><ref name=\"sb-3-11-18\"></ref>\n\nThis ''Maha Yuga'' length has been used to calculate the lifespan of the universe and [[Brahma]]. (See the \"Current Date\" section of [[Hindu units of time]]).\n\n==Yukteswar yuga cycle==\n[[File:Four Yugas of Hindu Eschatology.svg|thumb|368x368px|The Four Yugas in one cycle according to some spiritual leaders, Hindu Cosmology]]\n\nThe kriya yogi, guru and astrologer [[Swami Sri Yukteswar Giri]] (1855\u20131936) wrote a slim treatise called ''[[The Holy Science]]'' (1894). In the first part of it, speaking from ''[[Manusmriti|The Laws of Manu]]'', he postulates that a 24,000 year Manu era cycle is as long as an astronomically calculated [[Great Year]] or Platonic Year (25,772 years). The difference of 1,772 years was ignored which will lead to greater calculation errors as time passes.\n\n<ref name=\"nvg-nuss\">{{Cite web|url=http://oaks.nvg.org/nuss.html|title=Four Ages and Yukteswar's Argument|website=The Gold Scales|access-date=2020-04-21|quote=The kriya yogi, guru and astrologer Yukteswar (1855\u20131936) wrote a slim treatise called The Holy Science (1894). In the first part of it, he erroneously postulates that a 24,000 year long cycle is as long as an astronomical cycle of about 25,770 years, the so-called Great Year, and builds time calculations as if the Great Year were 24,000 years. That is a mistake, and time calculations that are based on his error, will grow worse as time passes. ...<p>Speculation going into calendars for folks. It stands out that Yukteswar uses improper calculations for telling the times. He says the bottom of a main cycle was reached around 500 CE. But the data for saying so should be questioned. Also take into account that others have other such \"cycle bottom\" and \"cycle start\" years. There are divergent views. ...</p><p>(1) the calculations are at fault, and (2) their set low ebb and \"bottom\" smacks of idiosyncratic speculation. ...</p><p>The astronomically calculated Platonic Years of 25,770 years cannot be squared full well with Manu's yugas, since 24,000 is not 25,770. Should we seek to resolve the mismatch by stretching the Manu yugas so that they become Platonic Years? If so, we get other yuga calculations than Yukteswar. If not, we are out of step with current astronomical knowledge. ...</p><p>In The Holy Science (1972) Yukteswar Giri (1855-1936) speaks from The Laws of Manu (1984) ( and aligns the Manu eras of 24,000 years with the Platonic Years of 25770 years by disregarding the differences. That is not a passable error. In other words, he claims that the Ages Cycle of 24,000 years is the same as the cycle of the retrograde movement of the vernal equinox \u2013 in astronomy it is also called the precession of the vernal equinox around the heavenly equator, a movement that is considered to take ca. 25,770 years, which is called the Great Year and the Platonic Year. Yukteswar's time calculations will be wrong for thousands of years.</p>}}</ref>\n\nAlso, he has calculated a 500 CE \"cycle botton\" (desc. -> asc. ''Kali Yuga'') which differs from \"cycle bottom\" and \"cycle start\" years calculated by others.<ref name=\"nvg-nuss\"></ref>\n\nWith a 12,000 half cycle and a 500 CE \"cycle bottom\", the cycle be 11501 BCE - 12500 CE (24,000 years). [Note, 1 BCE to 1 CE is 1 year, not 2].\n\nThese astrological calculation errors are indicative by the varying interpretations on the start, end, and duration of the astronomical ages such as [[Astrological_age#The_Age_of_Pisces_(The_Piscean_Age)|The Age of Pisces]]:\n* 1 CE - 2150 CE (2,149 years) [Neil Mann]\n* 498 CE - 2654 CE (2,156 years) [Heindel-Rosicrucian]\n* 6 BCE - 1994 CE (1,999 years) [Patrick Burlingame]\n* 100/90 BC - ~2680 CE (~2,779/~2,769 years) [Shephard Simpson]\n* ~138 BCE - 2012 CE (~2,149 years) [12/21/12 Great Cosmic Alignment]\n* etc.\n\nIn the equinox based ''Yuga Cycle'', the '''approximate''' length of each yuga is:\n* ''[[Satya Yuga]]''\u20144800 years\n* ''[[Treta Yuga]]''\u20143600 years\n* ''[[Dvapara Yuga]]''\u20142400 years\n* ''[[Kali Yuga]]''\u20141200 years\n\nWith one ''Maha Yuga'' containing a set of descending and ascending yugas (S,T,D,K,K,D,T,S),{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} it lasts for '''about 24,000 years'''.\n\nSome other authors{{Who|date=April 2020}} believe in a '''25,772 year''' cycle (a more precise [[Great Year]]) because it coincides with [[axial precession]], [[astronomical precession]] and another planetary body ([[Planet Nine]]) that influences our solar system.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ayanamsa]]\n* [[Hindu units of time]]\n* [[List of numbers in Hindu scriptures]].\n* [[Vedic-Puranic chronology]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://veda.wikidot.com/vedic-time-system Vedic knowledge online, ''Vedic Time System '']\n{{Time in religion and mythology}}\n{{Brahmanda}}\n{{Legendary progenitors}}\n\n[[Category:Hindu astronomy]]\n[[Category:Hindu philosophical concepts]]\n[[Category:Units of time]]\n[[Category:Theories of history]]\n[[Category:Time in Hinduism]]\n[[Category:Four Yugas| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the 2006 '''film'''|Yuga (film)}}\n{{short description|Epoch or era in Hinduism: Maha, Satya, Treta, Dvapara and Kali Yuga}}\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2018}}\n{{Hinduism small}}\n\nIn [[Hinduism]], a '''Yuga''' ({{lang-sa|\u092f\u0941\u0917|yuga|age}}) is an [[unit of time|epoch]] or [[era]]. There are a total of four yugas\u2014''[[Satya Yuga]]'', ''[[Treta Yuga]],'' ''[[Dvapara Yuga]], and'' ''[[Kali Yuga]]''\u2014each having 1/4<sup>th</sup> less duration and [[dharma]] than the previous (''Satya'' most, ''Kali'' least).{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nA '''Maha Yuga''' ({{lang-sa|\u092e\u0939\u093e\u092f\u0941\u0917|mah\u0101yuga|great age}})\u2014also known as a '''Chatur Yuga''' ({{lang-sa|\u091a\u0924\u0941\u0930\u094d\u092f\u0941\u0917|caturyuga|four ages}}) or '''Yuga Cycle'''\u2014is an [[unit of time|epoch]] or [[era]]. A ''Maha Yuga'' is cyclical and contains a cycle of the four yugas: ''Satya'', ''Treta'', ''Dvapara'', and ''Kali''.<ref name=\"sb-12-2-39\"></ref> Each ''Maha Yuga'' consists of a descending set of the yugas: (S,T,D,K) (S,T,D,K).<ref name=\"sb-12-2-39\"></ref> Some spiritual leaders believe in an equinox based cycle where each ''Maha Yuga'' consists of much shorter descending and ascending sets of the yugas: (S,T,D,K,K,D,T,S) (S,T,D,K,K,D,T,S).{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Yuga characteristics ==\n\nThere are a total of four yugas\u2014''[[Satya Yuga]]'', ''[[Treta Yuga]],'' ''[[Dvapara Yuga]], and'' ''[[Kali Yuga]]''\u2014each having 1/4 less duration and [[dharma]] than the previous (''Satya'' most, ''Kali'' least). The descending yugas see a '''gradual decline'''{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} of dharma, wisdom, knowledge, intellectual capability, lifespan, emotional and physical strength.\n\nWithin a yuga is a starting ''Sandhya'' and ending ''Sandhyansa'', both lasting 1/10<sup>th</sup> the duration of the yuga.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Most of the characteristic changes can occur in these ''Sandhyas'' and ''Sandhyansas'', especially if that change is from ''Kali Yuga'' to ''Satya Yuga'' (two extremes).{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n* '''[[Satya Yuga]]''' (''Krita Yuga'', \"The age of truth\" or \"[[Golden Age#Hindu|Golden Age]]\"): The first and best yuga. It was the age of truth and perfection. This yuga had no crimes and all humans were kind and friendly. The ''Krita Yuga'' was so named because there was but one religion, and all men were saintly: therefore they were not required to perform religious ceremonies. Humans were long lived, powerfully built, honest, youthful, vigorous, erudite and virtuous. The Vedas were one. All mankind could attain to supreme blessedness. There was no agriculture or mining as the earth yielded those riches on its own. Weather was pleasant and everyone was happy. There were no religious sects. There was no disease, decrepitude or fear of anything.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}} Virtue reigns supreme. Human stature was 21 cubits (33 ft 6 inches). Average human lifespan was 100,000 years.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n* '''[[Treta Yuga]]''': This is the second yuga in order. However, \"treta\" means the \"third\". In this age, virtue diminishes slightly. At the beginning of the age, many emperors rise to dominance and conquer the world. Wars become frequent and weather begins to change to extremities. People become slightly diminished compared to their predecessors. Agriculture, labour and mining become existent.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}} There was 3 quarter virtue and 1 quarter sin. Normal human stature was 14 cubits (22 ft 4 inches). Average human lifespan was 10,000 years.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n* '''[[Dvapara Yuga]]''': This is the third yuga in order. However, \"dvapara\" means \"two\". In this age, people become tainted with qualities and aren't as strong as their ancestors. Diseases become rampant. Humans are discontent and fight each other. Vedas are divided into four parts. People still possess characteristics of youth in old age. Average lifespan of humans is around a few centuries.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} There was 1 half virtue and 1 half sin. Normal human stature was 7 cubits (11 ft 2 inches). Average human lifespan was 1,000 years.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n* '''[[Kali Yuga]]''': The final age. It is the age of darkness and ignorance. People stop following [[Dharma]] and lack virtue. They become slaves to their passions and are barely as powerful as their earliest ancestors in the ''Satya Yuga''. Society falls into disuse and people become liars and hypocrites. Knowledge is lost and scriptures are diminished. Humans eat forbidden and dirty food. The environment is polluted, water and food become scarce. Wealth is heavily diminished. Families become non-existent.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}} There is 1 quarter virtue and 3 quarter sin. Normal human stature is 3.5 cubits (5 ft 3 inches). Average human lifespan will be 100 years.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Current yuga==\n{{See also|Kali_Yuga#Possible_starting_and_ending_dates}}\n\nAccording to [[Purana|Puranic sources]],<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">The Bhagavata Purana (1.18.6), Vishnu Purana  (5.38.8), and Brahma Purana (212.8), the day Krishna left the earth was the day that the Dvapara Yuga ended and the Kali Yuga began.</ref> [[krishna|Krishna's]] departure marks the end of ''Dvapara Yuga'' and the start of '''''Kali Yuga''''', which is dated to 17/18 February 3102 BCE.<ref name=\"auto p139\">See: Matchett, Freda, \"The Puranas\", p 139 and Yano, Michio, \"Calendar, astrology and astronomy\" in {{Cite book|last=Flood| first=Gavin (Ed)|  year=2003| title=Blackwell companion to Hinduism| place=| publisher= [[Blackwell Publishing]]| edition=| isbn=978-0-631-21535-6|ref=harv}}</ref> ''Kali Yuga'' ends in 428899 CE (432,000 years). (See [[Kali_Yuga#Possible_starting_and_ending_dates|Kali Yuga]]).\n\n===Equinox yuga cycle===\nSome spiritual leaders believe in an equinox based ''Yuga Cycle'' where ascending ''Kali Yuga'' has ended and '''ascending ''Dvapara Yuga''''' has started such as:\n\n* [[Swami Sri Yukteswar Giri]]<ref name=\"jssy-hs\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Te-ftAEACAAJ&dq=yukteswar+1949|title=The Holy Science|author=Swami Yukteswar|publisher=Yogoda Sat-Sanga Society of India|year=1949|page={{page needed|date=August 2018}}|quote=According to Sri Yukteswar Giri, guru of Paramahansa Yogananda, The ascending  phase of the Kali Yuga began in September 499 CE (not exactly). Since September 1699, we have been in the ascending phase of the Dwapara Yuga. According to Sri yukteswar, since nobody wanted to announce the bad news of the beginning of the descending Kali Yuga, so they kept adding years to the Dvapara date (at that time 2400 Dvapara) only retitling the epoch to Kali.}}.</ref> who first theorized an equinox based ''Yuga Cycle'' and past it on to his primary disciple [[Paramahansa Yogananda]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=\nhttp://yogananda.com.au/gurus/yogananda_quotes38crisis.html|title=\nWorld Crisis \u2014 Paramahansa Yogananda Best Quotes|website=Paramahansa Yogananda|access-date=2020-04-20|quote=The life cycles of the earth. These cycles consist of 24,000 years, divided into four yugas or ages\u201412,000 years of ascending through these yugas to increasing enlightenment, and then 12,000 years of descending through the yugas to increasing ignorance and materialism. Each of these half-cycles is called a Daiva Yuga. The earth has already passed through many complete cycles since the dawn of creation. The four ages of each Daiva Yuga are Kali Yuga, the dark or materialistic age, Dwapara Yuga, the electrical or atomic age, Treta Yuga, the mental age; and Satya Yuga, the age of truth or enlightenment. The earth has already passed through Kali Yuga, the materialistic age of 1,200 years' duration. According to the calculations of my guru, Swami Sri Yukteswar, we are about 314 [2014] years into Dwapara Yuga, the second age, which consists of 2,400 years. Now in its ascendancy, this is the electrical age, even though it may yet seem very materialistic.}}</ref> and then to the world through his book: ''The Holy Science''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=\nhttps://www.ananda.org/ask/are-we-in-kali-yuga-or-dwapara-yuga-2/|title=Are We in Kali Yuga or Dwapara Yuga?|website=Ananda|access-date=2020-04-20|quote=In his book Religion in the New Age, Swami Kriyananda writes about the \u201cYuga Cycle Theory\u201d of Swami Sri Yukteswar, who passed along the information to his primary disciple, Paramhasa Yogananda and to the world, via his book The Holy Science.}}</ref> <p>''Dvapara'': 1700 CE - 4100 CE (2,400 years).</p>\n* [[Jaggi Vasudev|Jaggi Vasudev (Sadhguru)]]<ref name=\"jv-tgcoy\">{{Cite web|url=\nhttps://isha.sadhguru.org/sg/en/wisdom/article/kali-yuga-end-lies-ahead|title=\nKali Yuga \u2013 When Did it End and What Lies Ahead?|website=isha|access-date=2020-04-20|quote=The story of Mahabharat needs to be seen in a certain context. In 3140 BCE, the Kurukshetra War ended, and in 3102 BCE, Krishna left his body. Three to four months after the war, the Kali Yuga began. As of 2012 AD, Krishna\u2019s era ended 5,114 years ago. If you subtract 2592, which is the cumulative number of years of the two Kali Yugas that are at the bottom of the ellipse which describes the axial precession, you arrive at 2522 years. That means we have already completed 2522 years of Dwapara Yuga, and since its total duration is 2592 years, we still have 70 years until its completion. In the year 2082, we will complete Dwapara Yuga and move on to Treta Yuga. The world will go through another upheaval, not necessarily in terms of war but probably in terms of population explosion and natural calamities, before moving on to this new era of wellbeing and upward movement of human consciousness.}}</ref><p>''Dvapara'': 511 BCE - 2082 CE (2,592 years).</p>\n\n===Empirical evidence===\nAlthough conditioned [[jiva|jivas]] aren't perfect,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedabase.io/en/library/bg/introduction/|title=Bhagavad-g\u012bt\u0101 As It Is: Introduction|website=Bhaktivedanta Vedabase|access-date=2020-04-19|quote=Vedic knowledge is received from transcendental sources, and the first words were spoken by the Lord Himself. The words spoken by the Lord are called apauru\u1e63eya, meaning that they are different from words spoken by a person of the mundane world who is infected with four defects. A mundaner (1) is sure to commit mistakes, (2) is invariably illusioned, (3) has the tendency to cheat others and (4) is limited by imperfect senses. With these four imperfections, one cannot deliver perfect information of all-pervading knowledge.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedabase.io/en/library/iso/introduction/|title=\u015ar\u012b \u012a\u015bopani\u1e63ad: Introduction|website=Bhaktivedanta Vedabase|access-date=2020-04-19|quote=Veda means knowledge. Any knowledge you accept is veda, for the teachings of the Vedas are the original knowledge. In the conditioned state, our knowledge is subjected to many deficiencies. The difference between a conditioned soul and a liberated soul is that the conditioned soul has four kinds of defects. The first defect is that he must commit mistakes. ... To err is human. This is one defect of the conditioned soul. Another defect: to be illusioned. Illusion means to accept something which is not: m\u0101y\u0101. M\u0101y\u0101 means \u201cwhat is not.\u201d Everyone is accepting the body as the self. ... But you are not this body. This is illusion. The third defect is the cheating propensity. Everyone has the propensity to cheat others. Although a person is fool number one, he poses himself as very intelligent. Although it is already pointed out that he is in illusion and makes mistakes, he will theorize: \u201cI think this is this, this is this.\u201d But he does not even know his own position. He writes books of philosophy, although he is defective. That is his disease. That is cheating. Lastly, our senses are imperfect. We are very proud of our eyes. Often, someone will challenge, \u201cCan you show me God?\u201d But do you have the eyes to see God? You will never see if you haven\u2019t the eyes. If immediately the room becomes dark, you cannot even see your hands. So what power do you have to see? We cannot, therefore, expect knowledge (veda) with these imperfect senses. With all these deficiencies, in conditioned life we cannot give perfect knowledge to anyone. Nor are we ourselves perfect. Therefore we accept the Vedas as they are.}}</ref> one can compare each yuga's characteristics (human lifespan, dharma, etc.) to the present and historic state of the world and [[empirical evidence|empirically]] deduce which is the current yuga.\n\nFor example, the average human [[life expectancy]] worldwide since the 1700s has been below 80 years. Life expectancy starts from birth, so if the ~56 million yearly abortions<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sedgh|first1=Gilda|last2=Bearak|first2=Jonathan|last3=Singh|first3=Susheela|last4=Bankole|first4=Akinrinola|last5=Popinchalk|first5=Anna|last6=Ganatra|first6=Bela|last7=Rossier|first7=Cl\u00e9mentine|last8=Gerdts|first8=Caitlin|last9=Tun\u00e7alp|first9=\u00d6zge|last10=Johnson|first10=Brooke Ronald|last11=Johnston|first11=Heidi Bart|last12=Alkema|first12=Leontine|title=Abortion incidence between 1990 and 2014: global, regional, and subregional levels and trends|journal=The Lancet|date=May 2016|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(16)30380-4|pmid=27179755|volume=388|issue=10041|pages=258\u201367|pmc=5498988}}</ref> and other pre-birth deaths were included, the average lifespan would be far less. In '''''Kali Yuga''''', the average human lifespan is described as 100 years or less.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} '''''Kali Yuga''''' is also described as having the least [[dharma]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} which speaks to the massive amount of abortions<ref>{{Cite web|url=\nhttp://indiafacts.org/abortion-dharmic-perspective-iv-abortion-murder/|title=Abortion, a Dharmic Perspective\u2013 IV: Is Abortion murder?|website=indiafacts: truth be told|access-date=2020-04-19|quote=Dharmic texts perceive abortion as Adharma since, it prevents a Jiva from taking a physical birth, for which it was entitled to based on its prarabdha Karma.}}</ref> and other [[adharma|adharmic]] activities rampant in the world.\n\n==Puranic yuga cycle==\n[[File:Time Units in Hindu Cosmology.png|frame|Relationship between various time units in Hindu cosmology]]\n\nThe cycle of the yugas has been mentioned in the [[Mahabharata]] and it is widely accepted since ancient times.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nEach cycle of a ''Maha Yuga'' repeats the four yugas (ages) in the following order: ''Satya Yuga'', ''Treta Yuga'', ''Dvapara Yuga'' and ''Kali Yuga''.<ref name=\"sb-12-2-39\">{{Cite web|url=\nhttps://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/12/2/39/|title=\n\u015ar\u012bmad-Bh\u0101gavatam (Bh\u0101gavata Pur\u0101\u1e47a) 12.2.39|website=Bhaktivedanta Vedabase|access-date=2020-04-17|quote=The cycle of four ages \u2014 Satya, Tret\u0101, Dv\u0101para and Kali \u2014 continues perpetually among living beings on this earth, repeating the same general sequence of events.}}</ref>\n\n{{Cquote|text=The cycle of four ages \u2014 Satya, Tret\u0101, Dv\u0101para and Kali \u2014 continues perpetually among living beings on this earth, repeating the same general sequence of events.|source=[https://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/12/2/39/ Bh\u0101gavata Pur\u0101\u1e47a 12.2.39]}}\n\nLength of yugas:<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sm0BfUKwct0C&pg=PA50&lpg=PA50&dq=4,000+%2B+400+%2B+400+%3D+4,800+divine+years+(%3D+1,728,000+human+years)#v=onepage&q=4%2C000%20%2B%20400%20%2B%20400%20%3D%204%2C800%20divine%20years%20(%3D%201%2C728%2C000%20human%20years)&f=false|title=Tracing The Way: Spiritual Dimensions of the World Religions|page=50|first=Hans|last=Kng|publisher=A&C Black|isbn=9780826494238|date=2006-10-31}}</ref><ref name=\"sb-3-11-18\">{{Cite web|url=\nhttps://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/3/11/18/|title=\n\u015ar\u012bmad-Bh\u0101gavatam (Bh\u0101gavata Pur\u0101\u1e47a) 3.11.18|website=Bhaktivedanta Vedabase|access-date=2020-04-17|quote=Maitreya said: O Vidura, the four millenniums are called the Satya-, Tret\u0101-, Dv\u0101para- and Kali-yuga. The aggregate number of years of all of these combined is equal to twelve thousand years of the demigods.<p>Purport: The years of the demigods are equal to 360 years of humankind. As will be clarified in the subsequent verses, 12,000 of the demigods\u2019 years, including the transitional periods which are called yuga-sandhy\u0101s, comprise the total of the aforementioned four millenniums. Thus the aggregate of the above-mentioned four millenniums is 4,320,000 years.</p>}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=\nhttps://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/3/11/19/|title=\n\u015ar\u012bmad-Bh\u0101gavatam (Bh\u0101gavata Pur\u0101\u1e47a) 3.11.19|website=Bhaktivedanta Vedabase|access-date=2020-04-17|quote=The duration of the Satya millennium equals 4,800 years of the years of the demigods; the duration of the Tret\u0101 millennium equals 3,600 years of the demigods; the duration of the Dv\u0101para millennium equals 2,400 years; and that of the Kali millennium is 1,200 years of the demigods.<p>Purport: As aforementioned, one year of the demigods is equal to 360 years of the human beings. The duration of the Satya-yuga is therefore 4,800 \u00d7 360, or 1,728,000 years. The duration of the Tret\u0101-yuga is 3,600 \u00d7 360, or 1,296,000 years. The duration of the Dv\u0101para-yuga is 2,400 \u00d7 360, or 864,000 years. And the last, the Kali-yuga, is 1,200 \u00d7 360, or 432,000 years.</p>}}</ref> (See [[List of numbers in Hindu scriptures|Hindu numbers]]).\n* ''[[Satya Yuga]]''\u20141,728,000 years (4800 divine)\n* ''[[Treta Yuga]]''\u20141,296,000 years (3600 divine)\n* ''[[Dvapara Yuga]]''\u2014864,000 years (2400 divine)\n* ''[[Kali Yuga]]''\u2014432,000 years (1200 divine)\n\nWith one ''Maha Yuga'' containing a set of descending yugas (S,T,D,K), it lasts for '''4,320,000 years (12,000 divine years)'''.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pQHNDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA137|title=The Power of Stars|publisher=Springer|page=182|first=Bryan E.|last=Penprase|isbn=9783319525976|date=2017-05-05}}</ref><ref name=\"sb-3-11-18\"></ref>\n\nThis ''Maha Yuga'' length has been used to calculate the lifespan of the universe and [[Brahma]]. (See the \"Current Date\" section of [[Hindu units of time]]).\n\n==Yukteswar yuga cycle==\n[[File:Four Yugas of Hindu Eschatology.svg|thumb|368x368px|The Four Yugas in one cycle according to some spiritual leaders, Hindu Cosmology]]\n\nThe kriya yogi, guru and astrologer [[Swami Sri Yukteswar Giri]] (1855\u20131936) wrote a slim treatise called ''[[The Holy Science]]'' (1894). In the first part of it, speaking from ''[[Manusmriti|The Laws of Manu]]'', he postulates that a 24,000 year long cycle (Manu era) is as long as an astronomical cycle of about 25,770 years, the so-called [[Great Year]] or Platonic Year.<ref name=\"nvg-nuss\">{{Cite web|url=http://oaks.nvg.org/nuss.html|title=Four Ages and Yukteswar's Argument|website=The Gold Scales|access-date=2020-04-21|quote=The kriya yogi, guru and astrologer Yukteswar (1855\u20131936) wrote a slim treatise called The Holy Science (1894). In the first part of it, he erroneously postulates that a 24,000 year long cycle is as long as an astronomical cycle of about 25,770 years, the so-called Great Year, and builds time calculations as if the Great Year were 24,000 years. That is a mistake, and time calculations that are based on his error, will grow worse as time passes. ...<p>Speculation going into calendars for folks. It stands out that Yukteswar uses improper calculations for telling the times. He says the bottom of a main cycle was reached around 500 CE. But the data for saying so should be questioned. Also take into account that others have other such \"cycle bottom\" and \"cycle start\" years. There are divergent views. ...</p><p>(1) the calculations are at fault, and (2) their set low ebb and \"bottom\" smacks of idiosyncratic speculation. ...</p><p>The astronomically calculated Platonic Years of 25,770 years cannot be squared full well with Manu's yugas, since 24,000 is not 25,770. Should we seek to resolve the mismatch by stretching the Manu yugas so that they become Platonic Years? If so, we get other yuga calculations than Yukteswar. If not, we are out of step with current astronomical knowledge. ...</p><p>In The Holy Science (1972) Yukteswar Giri (1855-1936) speaks from The Laws of Manu (1984) ( and aligns the Manu eras of 24,000 years with the Platonic Years of 25770 years by disregarding the differences. That is not a passable error. In other words, he claims that the Ages Cycle of 24,000 years is the same as the cycle of the retrograde movement of the vernal equinox \u2013 in astronomy it is also called the precession of the vernal equinox around the heavenly equator, a movement that is considered to take ca. 25,770 years, which is called the Great Year and the Platonic Year. Yukteswar's time calculations will be wrong for thousands of years.</p>}}</ref>\n\nSri Yukteswar attempted to align the Manu eras of 24,000 years with the astronomically calculated Platonic Years of 25,770 years by disregarding the differences. Also, his 500 CE \"cycle botton\" (desc. -> asc. ''Kali Yuga'') differs from \"cycle bottom\" and \"cycle start\" years calculated by others. Calculations based on his errors will grow worse as time passes.<ref name=\"nvg-nuss\"></ref>\n\nWith a 12,000 half cycle and a 500 CE \"cycle bottom\", the cycle would run 11501 BCE - 12500 CE (24,000 years). [Note, 1 BCE to 1 CE is 1 year, not 2].\n\nThese astrological calculation errors are indicative by the varying interpretations on the start, end, and duration of the astronomical ages such as [[Astrological_age#The_Age_of_Pisces_(The_Piscean_Age)|The Age of Pisces]]:\n* 1 CE - 2150 CE (2,149 years) [Neil Mann]\n* 498 CE - 2654 CE (2,156 years) [Heindel-Rosicrucian]\n* 6 BCE - 1994 CE (1,999 years) [Patrick Burlingame]\n* 100/90 BC - ~2680 CE (~2,779/~2,769 years) [Shephard Simpson]\n* ~138 BCE - 2012 CE (~2,149 years) [12/21/12 Great Cosmic Alignment]\n* etc.\n\nIn the equinox based ''Yuga Cycle'', the '''approximate''' length of each yuga is:\n* ''[[Satya Yuga]]''\u20144800 years\n* ''[[Treta Yuga]]''\u20143600 years\n* ''[[Dvapara Yuga]]''\u20142400 years\n* ''[[Kali Yuga]]''\u20141200 years\n\nWith one ''Maha Yuga'' containing a set of descending and ascending yugas (S,T,D,K,K,D,T,S),{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} it lasts for '''about 24,000 years'''.\n\nSome other authors{{Who|date=April 2020}} believe in a '''25,772 year''' cycle (a more precise [[Great Year]]) because it coincides with [[axial precession]], [[astronomical precession]] and another planetary body ([[Planet Nine]]) that influences our solar system.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ayanamsa]]\n* [[Hindu units of time]]\n* [[List of numbers in Hindu scriptures]].\n* [[Vedic-Puranic chronology]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://veda.wikidot.com/vedic-time-system Vedic knowledge online, ''Vedic Time System '']\n{{Time in religion and mythology}}\n{{Brahmanda}}\n{{Legendary progenitors}}\n\n[[Category:Hindu astronomy]]\n[[Category:Hindu philosophical concepts]]\n[[Category:Units of time]]\n[[Category:Theories of history]]\n[[Category:Time in Hinduism]]\n[[Category:Four Yugas| ]]\n", "name_user": "Jroberson108", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reword.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yuga"}
{"title_page": "Shoaib Akhtar", "text_new": "{{short description|Pakistani cricketer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = Shoaib drugtar\n| image = Shoaib drugtar (13927458981).jpg\n| caption = \n| fullname = Shoaib drugtar\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1975|8|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Rawalpindi]], [[Punjab, Pakistan]]\n| country = Pakistan\n| nickname = Rawalpindi Express, Tiger\n| height = 6ft 0in<ref>[https://www.cricbuzz.com/profiles/30/shoaib-akhtar Shoaib Akhtar's profile] on [[CricBuzz]]</ref>\n| batting = Right-handed\n| bowling = Right-arm [[Fast bowling|fast]]\n| role = [[Bowler (cricket)|Bowler]]\n| international = true\n| internationalspan = 1997\u20132011\n| testcap = 150\n| testdebutagainst = West Indies\n| testdebutdate = 29 November\n| testdebutyear = 1997\n| lasttestagainst = India\n| lasttestdate = 8 December\n| lasttestyear = 2007\n| odicap = 123\n| odidebutagainst = Zimbabwe\n| odidebutdate = 28 March\n| odidebutyear = 1998\n| lastodiagainst = New Zealand\n| lastodidate = 8 March\n| lastodiyear = 2011\n| T20Idebutdate = 28 August\n| T20Idebutyear = 2006\n| T20Idebutagainst = England\n| lastT20Idate = 28 December\n| lastT20Iyear = 2010\n| lastT20Iagainst = New Zealand\n| T20Icap = 9\n| odishirt = 14\n| columns = 3\n| column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n| column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n| column3 = [[Twenty20 International|T20I]]\n| runs1 = 544\n| matches1 = 46\n| bat avg1 = 10.07\n| 100s/50s1 = 0/0\n| top score1 = 47\n| deliveries1 = 8,143\n| wickets1 = 176\n| bowl avg1 = 25.69\n| fivefor1 = 12\n| tenfor1 = 2\n| best bowling1 = 6/11\n| catches/stumpings1 = 12/\u2013\n| matches2 = 163\n| runs2 = 394\n| bat avg2 = 8.95\n| 100s/50s2 = 0/0\n| top score2 = 43\n| deliveries2 = 7,764\n| wickets2 = 247\n| bowl avg2 = 24.97\n| fivefor2 = 4\n| tenfor2 = 0\n| best bowling2 = 6/16\n| catches/stumpings2 = 20/\u2013\n| matches3 = 15\n| runs3 = 21\n| bat avg3 = 7.00\n| 100s/50s3 = 0/0\n| top score3 = 8[[not out|*]]\n| deliveries3 = 318\n| wickets3 = 19\n| bowl avg3 = 22.73\n| fivefor3 = 0\n| tenfor3 = 0\n| best bowling3 = 3/38\n| catches/stumpings3 = 2/\u2013\n| date = 8 November\n| year = 2016\n| source = http://www.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/player/42655.html Cricinfo\n}}\n\n'''Shoaib Akhtar''' ({{audio|Shoaib Akhtar Pronunciation.ogg|pronunciation}}; born 13 August 1975) is a Pakistani cricket commentator, YouTuber, and former cricketer who played all formats of the game over a fourteen year career. He is recognized as the [[Fast bowling|fastest bowler]] in the history of [[cricket]], delivering a world record top speed of 161.3{{nbsp}}km/h (100.23{{nbsp}}mph) in a pool match against England during the [[2003 Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/records-10000/fastest-bowl-of-a-cricket-ball/|title=Fastest delivery of a cricket ball (male)|author=|date=|work=[[Guinness World Records]]|accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref> Akhtar was nicknamed \"Rawalpindi Express\" and \"Tiger\" as a tribute to his hometown and fast bowling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.tribune.com.pk/story/25921/shoaib-akhtar-the-legend-the-sensation-the-enigma/|title=Shoaib Akhtar \u2013 the legend, the sensation, the enigma|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://purbat.com/most-feared-fast-bowlers-cricket/|title=10 Most feared fast bowlers in Cricket history - Purbat.com|date=1 October 2016|publisher=}}</ref> He is also the first bowler to break the 100&nbsp;mph barrier, doing so twice in his career.\n\nAkhtar made his [[Test cricket|Test]] debut in November 1997 as an opening [[fast bowling|fast bowler]] and played his first [[One Day International]] three months later. Akhtar has been involved in several controversies during his career, often accused of unsportsmanlike conduct, despite his commendations for significantly impacting games in Pakistan's favour. Akhtar was sent home during a Test match series in Australia in 2005 for alleged poor attitude. A year later, he was embroiled in a drug scandal after testing positive for the performance-enhancing substance [[nandrolone]]. However, the ban imposed on him was lifted on appeal.\n\nIn September 2007, he received a ban.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/other_international/pakistan/7039633.stm |title=PCB bans Shoaib Akhtar for an indefinite period |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150614042556/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/other_international/pakistan/7039633.stm |archivedate=14 June 2015 }}</ref> On 1 April 2008, Akhtar was banned for five years for publicly criticising the [[Pakistan Cricket Board]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ibnlive.com/news/shoaib-akhtar-gets-5year-ban-for-foul-delivery---its-unfair/62443-5.html |title=Shoaib Akhtar gets 5-year ban for foul delivery &#124; It's unfair |publisher=Ibnlive.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403102400/http://www.ibnlive.com/news/shoaib-akhtar-gets-5year-ban-for-foul-delivery---its-unfair/62443-5.html |archive-date=3 April 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In October 2008, the [[Lahore High Court]] in Pakistan suspended the five-year ban and Akhtar was selected in the 15-man squad for the Twenty20 Quadrangular Tournament in Canada.<ref>{{cite news\n| url = http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/372804.html\n| title = Shoaib in for Canada, not Yousuf\n}}</ref> Pakistani judge [[Rana Bhagwandas]] once stated that Akhtar is a legend of Pakistan cricket.<ref>{{cite web |title=The law is equal for everyone in Pakistan |url=http://in.rediff.com/news/2006/feb/14inter1.htm |author=Rediffnews |quote=I have little interest in cricket. People are crazy about cricket and we feel happy when our country wins. The names of Hanif Mohammad, Imran Khan, Shoaib Akhtar all come to my mind once I think about cricket. These are legends of Pakistani cricket}}</ref> Akhtar retired from international cricket after the [[2011 Cricket World Cup|2011 World Cup]].\n\n==Personal life==\nAkhtar was born in a small town in Morgah near [[Rawalpindi]], Pakistan. His father, Mohammad Akhtar, \"from a hardworking economically unprivileged family of the [[Gujjar]] community\", who worked as a night watchman at a petrol station belonging to the [[Attock Refinery Limited|Attock oil refinery]], married his mother, Hameeda [[Awan (tribe)|Awan]], when she was still a teenager, and they had five children: four sons, Shoaib being the fourth after Shahid, Tahir and Obaid, followed by a daughter, Shumaila.<ref>Shoaib Akhtar; Anshu Dogra, ''Controversially yours'', [[HarperCollins]] (2011), p. 6</ref>\n\nHe married Rubab Khan on 11 November 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Haripur: Shoaib Akhtar tie the knot with Rubbabb|url=http://dunyanews.tv/index.php/en/Cricket/226712-Haripur-Shoaib-Akhtar-tie-the-knot-with-Rubab|publisher=dunyanews.tv|accessdate=26 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Shoaib Akhtar secretly marries 20-year old Rubab Khan|url=http://www.india.com/sports/shoaib-akhtar-secretly-marries-20-year-old-rubab-khan-84313/|publisher=india.com|accessdate=3 March 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140629102747/http://www.india.com/sports/shoaib-akhtar-secretly-marries-20-year-old-rubab-khan-84313/|archivedate=29 June 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nA good student, Akhtar was admitted to the [[Government College Asghar Mall Rawalpindi|Asghar Mall College]], but disrupted his studies to attend trials for the [[Pakistan International Airlines cricket team|PIA team]]'s Karachi division to be held in Lahore. Lacking the money for a bus ticket, he waited for the bus to start and got onto the roof.<ref>Shoaib Akhtar; Anshu Dogra, ''Controversially yours'', [[HarperCollins]] (2011), pp. 42-43</ref> After some struggle, starting his [[List A]] career during the 1993/1994 season and his [[First-class cricket|First-class]] career during the 1994/1995 one, he caught the eye of [[Majid Khan (cricketer, born 1946)|Majid Khan]], then the chief executive of the [[Pakistan Cricket Board|PCB]], and after a good performance for the [[Pakistan A]] team's tour of England, in 1996, he was rewarded his maiden Test cap against the West Indies, in 1997.<ref>Shoaib Akhtar; Anshu Dogra, ''Controversially yours'', [[HarperCollins]] (2011), pp. 58-59</ref>\n\n==International career==\nConsidering his subsequent high profile in cricket, Akhtar's test career started rather modestly. He was first picked to play on his home ground in Rawalpindi during the 2nd Test of the West Indies 1997/98 tour of Pakistan. He was subsequently included in the tour of South Africa during the winter of 1998, where he played in all three Tests. He was notably the spearhead of a depleted Pakistani bowling attack in the Peshawar Test against the visiting Australians later in 1998, where Mark Taylor scored his famous unbeaten 334 in Australia's first innings. Subsequently, after 8 tests and 16 innings, Akhtar had accumulated only 18 wickets.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/42655.html |title=Player profile: Shoaib Akhtar |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=7 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nAkhtar's run of average performances started in 1999, during a pre-World Cup series against India. It was followed by high-class bowling performances in [[Sharjah (city)|Sharjah]] and later in the [[1999 Cricket World Cup]].\n\nIn 2002, he was selected for the Pakistan team against [[Australia cricket team|Australia]] and achieved  a small amount of success. However he performed poorly during the [[2003 Cricket World Cup]] and after the tournament he was dropped from the Pakistan squad. \nHe was selected back into the Pakistan squad as they had no choice in the 2004 Test match series against [[New Zealand cricket team|New Zealand]], but struggled in a losing Test series against [[India national cricket team|India]] in 2004. The series ended with a controversy when he left the field citing an injury leading to suspicions by former Pakistan captain, [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]], about his commitment to the team. As a result, his relationship with [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]] and former Pakistan coach [[Bob Woolmer]] deteriorated. A medical panel was set up by the [[Pakistan Cricket Board]] to investigate the nature of his injury, however Pakistan officials dispelled all suspicions.<ref>{{cite web | year = 2004 | url = http://www.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/140776.html | title = Bone scan puts Akhtar in the clear | accessdate = 10 April 2006 }}</ref>\n[[File:Shoaib Akhtar2.jpg|thumb]]\nIn 2005, Akhtar regained his reputation as a fast bowler for his side. Playing in a three Test home series against [[England cricket team|England]], he made a series of impressive bowling performances. His effective use of slower deliveries proved to be unplayable by the English batsmen. Akhtar emerged as the highest wicket taker of the series with seventeen wickets. His comeback was also remarkable as prior to his return, he had been criticised from all corners; such as by the Worcestershire chairman John Elliot for his celebrity attitude and lack of commitment to the team. His performance was also acknowledged by the English captain [[Michael Vaughan]], who remarked \"I thought he (Shoaib) was a big difference between the two teams\".<ref>{{cite web | year = 2004 | url = http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/228332.html | title = Vaughan \u2013 Batsmen to blame | accessdate = 10 April 2006 }}</ref> He is also known as one of only three bowlers to have ever broken the 100&nbsp;mph barrier in cricket history, with a delivery of 100.2&nbsp;mph, during a one-day international against England in World cup 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/149874.html|title=Blink and you'll miss it|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Struggle for form and consistent injuries (2007\u20132009)===\nOn 29 October 2007, Akhtar made his return to cricket, from his 13 match ban and performed well, taking 4 wickets for 43 runs against [[South Africa cricket team|South Africa]] in the fifth and deciding One Day International series in Lahore in Pakistan. Subsequently, he was included in the 16-man Pakistan squad for the [[Pakistani cricket team in India in 2007\u201308|2007 tour of India]].\n\n===Rehabilitation and final years (2010\u20132011)===\nAkhtar made a return to international cricket albeit in the shorter format of the game. In May 2010, PCB named him in a list of 35 probables for the [[2010 Asia Cup|Asia Cup]]. On 15 June 2010, Akhtar made his return, taking 3 wickets for 28 runs in the first match of the Asia Cup against Sri Lanka.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ravindran|first=Siddarth|title=Shoaib Akhtar makes a respectable return|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/asia2010/content/story/463287.html|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=15 June 2010}}</ref> He narrowly missed out a spot in the [[2010 ICC World Twenty20]] in place of the injured Umar Gul.\n\nIn July 2010, he was selected for the Twenty20 [[Australian cricket team against Pakistan in England in 2010|series against Australia]] but the selectors decided not to play him in the Test squad so that he would not get injured. He was subsequently selected for the ODI and Twenty20 series against [[Pakistan cricket team in England in 2010|England in September 2010]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Geo TV|title=Shoaib Akhtar selected for ODI and Twenty20 series against England in September 2010|url=http://geo.tv/8-24-2010/70453.htm|publisher=Jang News|accessdate=26 August 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100830183713/http://www.geo.tv/8-24-2010/70453.htm|archivedate=30 August 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAkhtar returned to the national side representing the country against England in the Twenty20 International. He bowled an impressive spell and returned with figures of 2 wickets for 23 runs.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pakistan bowler Shoaib Akhtar breathes new life into cricket's fast show|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/england/7985127/Pakistan-bowler-Shoaib-Akhtar-breathes-new-life-into-crickets-fast-show.html|publisher=Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=6 November 2010|location=London|first=Steve|last=James|date=7 September 2010}}</ref> He continued to bowl well in the ODI series in the absence of regular fast-bowlers, [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammad Asif]] and [[Mohammad Amir]], who were suspended by the International Cricket Council amid allegations of [[Spot-fixing]]. Despite his relatively good bowling form, Pakistani coach [[Waqar Younis]] insisted that the bowling attack must not become reliant on Akhtar, as he is 35 years of age and fitness troubles continue to affect him.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shoaib Akhtar can't do miracle at this age: Waqar |url=http://geo.tv/10-21-2010/73211.htm |publisher=Geo.tv |accessdate=6 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101024225147/http://geo.tv/10-21-2010/73211.htm |archivedate=24 October 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref> Akhtar was selected for the tour of New Zealand and started his campaign off well with 3 wickets on Boxing Day in the first of two Twenty20 Internationals against New Zealand.\n\nAkhtar was selected in Pakistan's 15-man squad to play in the [[2011 Cricket World Cup|2011 World Cup]] hosted by Bangladesh, India, and Sri Lanka in February to March. During the tournament, he announced that he would retire from international cricket at the end of the World Cup. He was dropped from the squad after group matches and was not included in the quarter final either.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/506599.html |title=Shoaib Akhtar to retire after World Cup |first=Osman |last=Samiuddin |publisher=Cricinfo |date=17 March 2011 |accessdate=17 March 2011}}</ref> In September, Akhtar released his autobiography, ''[[Controversially Yours]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.geo.tv/9-24-2011/86642.htm |title=Shoaib Akhtar's ''Controversially Yours'' released |publisher=GEO Sports |date=24 September 2011 |accessdate=24 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926232325/http://www.geo.tv/9-24-2011/86642.htm |archivedate=26 September 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Domestic career==\n\n===England county cricket===\nAkhtar has played for three English [[county cricket]] clubs: [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]] in 2001, [[Durham County Cricket Club|Durham]] in 2003 and 2004 and [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] in 2005. He did achieve his moments of success, such as taking 5 wickets for 35 runs for Durham against Somerset in the [[National League (cricket)|National League]] in 2003 and claiming 6 wickets for 16 runs in the same competition for Worcestershire against [[Gloucestershire County Cricket Club|Gloucestershire]] two years later, but he suffered from fitness problems, as well as a perception that he was less than interested in his task. This was particularly the case at Worcestershire: chairman John Elliott said \"Players like that are no good to our club. In fact, Akhtar has been no good for any club he's been at. He's a superstar and just does what he wants.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/wisdencricketer/content/current/story/295629.html | title=Dodgy overseas signings | author=Steve Pittard and John Stern | date=24 May 2007 | accessdate=24 May 2007 | publisher=[[Cricinfo]]}}</ref>\n\n===Indian Premier League===\nAkhtar made a successful return to cricket in his first game in the [[Indian Premier League]], playing for the [[Kolkata Knight Riders]] against the [[Delhi Daredevils]]. Defending a low score of 133 runs, Akhtar took four top order wickets which ultimately led to the Daredevils being restricted to 110 runs. He ended with figures of 4 wickets for 11 runs from three overs, a performance which earned him the player of the match award.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ipl/engine/match/336017.html Indian Premier League \u2013 35th match, Kolkata Knight Riders v Delhi Daredevils]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 14 May 2008.</ref><ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ipl/content/story/350889.html Shoaib leads Delhi drubbing]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 14 May 2008.</ref> Akhtar denied that he had any point to prove with his performance, stating, \"I just wanted to win the game.\" Knight Riders' captain [[Sourav Ganguly]] also acknowledged Akhtar's performance, \"He came to the country with lots [of things] happening behind him...But he showed a lot of character.\"<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ipl/content/story/350924.html I have no point to prove \u2013 Shoaib]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 14 May 2008.</ref>\n\nHe has also played for [[Cyclones of Chittagong]] in Bangladesh's [[Bangladesh NCL (National Cricket League) Twenty20|NCL T20 Bangladesh]].\n\n==Cricket controversies and injuries==\nAkhtar's career has been plagued with injuries, controversies and accusations of poor attitude. After a poor performance in the 2003 Cricket World Cup, he got involved in a verbal conflict with former Pakistan captain and fast bowler [[Waqar Younis]]. Later on Akhtar was sacked along with other players, including Younis. In a triangular series in 2003 held in Sri Lanka, he was caught [[ball tampering]] making him the second player in cricket to be banned on ball tampering charges. The same year he was banned for one Test match and two One Day International matches for abusing South African spin bowler [[Paul Adams (cricketer)|Paul Adams]], during a match against South Africa. In the 2004 home series with India, he struggled with wrist and back injuries, which raised questions about his commitment to the team.\n\nHe was sent back from the 2005 Australia tour with a hamstring injury amid rumours of indiscipline, lack of commitment and attitudinal complaints. He was subsequently fined by the Pakistan Cricket Board for avoiding a late night curfew.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/sport/content/200502/s1305514.htm ABC Sport \u2013 Cricket \u2013 Pakistan's Akhtar fined for Australian disco jaunt] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020024458/http://www.abc.net.au/sport/content/200502/s1305514.htm |date=20 October 2007 }}</ref> The rest of his cricketing career was riddled with ankle and knee injuries which forced him to undergo a surgery in February 2006, until finally he was banned for two years for allegedly using performance-enhancing drugs.\n\nIn November 2006, an officer assigned to the Pakistan team in India, Anil Kaul, alleged that Akhtar had slapped former coach Bob Woolmer following a fight over the music to be played in the team bus on the eve of ICC Champions Trophy. Both Akhtar and Woolmer have strongly denied these allegations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cricket.indiatimes.com/articleshow/374409.cms |work=The Times of India |title=Cricket |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120707151418/http://cricket.indiatimes.com/articleshow/374409.cms |archivedate=7 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Drug scandal===\nOn 16 October 2006 Akhtar was suspended by the [[Pakistan Cricket Board]], along with [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammed Asif]] after they tested positive for a performance-enhancing substance [[nandrolone]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/iccct2006/content/current/story/263238.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Asif and Akhtar to return home |publisher=Content-usa.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> They were consequently pulled out from the [[2006 ICC Champions Trophy]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/story/0,8659,20589658-23212,00.html |title=Shoaib returns positive test |date=16 October 2006 |author=Staff writers and wires |work=[[Fox Sports (Australia)|FOX SPORTS Australia]]}}</ref> Former Pakistan Cricket Board chairman later stated that he had always suspected Akhtar of substance abuse due to his consistent \"reservations\" to drug tests.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cricket.indiatimes.com/articleshow/2191504.cms |work=The Times of India |title=Cricket |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120714064906/http://cricket.indiatimes.com/articleshow/2191504.cms |archivedate=14 July 2012 }}</ref> Former Pakistan captain [[Inzamam ul-Haq]] had also previously complained about Akhtar's drug abuse but was not reported to the Pakistan Cricket Board.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://paktribune.com/news/index.shtml?158859 |title=Pakistan News Service \u2013 PakTribune |publisher=Paktribune.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> Akhtar immediately declared his innocence and he declined knowingly taking any performance-enhancing drugs. In a statement issued to the press, he claimed that he could never cheat teammates or opponents.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/6054724.stm | work=BBC News | title=Shocked Shoaib protests innocence | date=16 October 2006 | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref> During a hearing with the Pakistan Cricket Board Anti-Doping Committee, he along with Asif maintained taking non-steroidal dietary supplements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-ind.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/266665.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Sad but we had to make an example of Shoaib \u2013 Alam |publisher=Content-ind.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> He, however, failed to convince the committee of his innocence. In its report submitted to the Pakistan Cricket Board, the Anti-Doping Committee recommended a two-year ban.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcboard.com.pk/Pakistan/Articles/5/5298.html |title=Pakistan Cricket Board \u2013 official website |publisher=Pcboard.com.pk |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 November 2006 the Pakistan Cricket Board handed down a two-year suspension to Akhtar and a one-year suspension to Asif, banning them from professional cricket during the period.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.cricinfo.com/ci/content/current/story/266573.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Shoaib and Asif banned for drugs use |publisher=Uk.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> Shoaib had subsequently been added to [[Pakistan Olympic Association]] list of doping offenders.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/stuff/0,2106,3847919a10133,00.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=1 November 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927191359/http://www.stuff.co.nz/stuff/0,2106,3847919a10133,00.html |archive-date=27 September 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, on 5 December 2006 represented by his lawyer [[Abid Hassan Minto]], Akhtar was cleared on appeal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/australia/content/current/story/271241.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Shoaib and Asif acquitted |publisher=Content-usa.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 December 2006 Akhtar and Asif were acquitted by the tribunal appointed to review their appeals. After a clear hearing from Akhtar's lawyer [[Abid Hassan Minto]], the three-man committee, voted two to one in favour of the acquittal. Justice Fakhruddin Ebrahim, committee head, and Haseeb Ahsan, former Test cricketer, were in favour of the acquittal. The third member, Danish Zaheer, differed. \"Exceptional circumstances\" were cited including discrepancies between the instantaneous offence charges of doping that were laid and the quick delivery of a very harsh verdict. The complete drug testing procedure was concluded to have been technically flawed as it did not follow standard procedures. Other established facts by the committee included that the duo were not aware of the banned drug to be present in their supplements because the Pakistan Cricket Board itself had not informed them of the dangers of contaminated supplements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-pak.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/271241.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Shoaib and Asif acquitted |publisher=Content-pak.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/271347.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Dope on the doping scandal |publisher=Content-usa.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nAkhtar and Asif, however, did not play in the subsequent Test match series against the West Indies because the Pakistan Cricket Board had recommended that they play domestic games first to recover form and fitness.{{cn|date=November 2017}} On 1 March 2007 Akhtar and Asif were ruled out of the Pakistani squad for the [[2007 Cricket World Cup]] by team officials, minutes before the squad was to depart for the [[West Indies]]. The team management along with the Pakistan Cricket Board said their injuries were too severe to risk taking them to the Caribbean. Since neither of the two had been declared fit they did not undergo official doping tests.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/wc2007/content/current/story/281976.html Shoaib and Asif out of the World Cup]:</ref>\n\n[[World Anti-Doping Agency]] ( WADA) challenged Pakistan's decision to lift bans on fast bowlers Akhtar and Asif by taking the case to the [[Court of Arbitration for Sport]] in [[Lausanne]], Switzerland.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/other_international/pakistan/6183997.stm |title=BBC SPORT &#124; Cricket &#124; International Teams &#124; Pakistan &#124; Pakistan to face doping challenge |publisher=BBC News |date=15 December 2006 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref> The ICC supported the WADA appeal adding that it was committed to a dope free game. On 2 July 2007, the Court of Arbitration for Sport dropped the case, ruling it had no jurisdiction to challenge the decision made by PCB.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/300348.html Court has no jurisdiction in doping case]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 3 July 2007.</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/other_international/pakistan/6260498.stm Court cannot rule on Pakistan duo]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 3 July 2007.</ref>\n\n===Other controversies===\nIn August 2007, Akhtar was reported to have used foul language against Pakistan Cricket Board protesting the imposing of fine of Rs. 300,000 for indiscipline during the national camp in Karachi.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://in.sports.yahoo.com/070811/139/6jbmc.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120713153808/http://in.sports.yahoo.com/070811/139/6jbmc.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-13 |title=Shoaib uses foul language to protest PCB decision }}</ref> In the week before the inaugural [[2007 ICC World Twenty20|World Twenty20]], held in South Africa, Akhtar was rumoured to have hit Pakistani teammate Mohammad Asif with a bat after an argument in the dressing room. It started after Akhtar was ridiculed by Asif and [[Shahid Afridi]] for comparing himself with [[Imran Khan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/story/215130.html|title=Latest News, Breaking News Live, Current Headlines, India News Online \u2013 The Indian Express|website=www.indianexpress.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430055753/http://www.indianexpress.com/story/215130.html|archivedate=30 April 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/309867.html\n| title = Asif injured in dressing room spat by Akhtar\n}}</ref> After the initial inquiry, Akhtar was found to be at fault and was subsequently recalled from the Twenty20 World Cup squad<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/cricketNews/idUKSP16843120070907|title=Pakistan send Akhtar home after bustup|first=Reuters|last=Editorial|publisher=}}</ref> and was sent home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/twenty20wc/content/current/story/309891.html |title=Shoaib to be sent home after incident |publisher=Content-uk.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> He was also banned for 5 matches by the Pakistan Cricket Board.<ref>[http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2007%5C09%5C08%5Cstory_8-9-2007_pg1_8 Shoaib banned for five matches] 8 September 2007 [[Daily Times (Pakistan)|Daily Times]] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020032255/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2007%5C09%5C08%5Cstory_8-9-2007_pg1_8 |date=20 October 2012 }}</ref> Akhtar later claimed that Afridi was responsible for the fight, saying \"He made some ill remarks about my family. And I could not tolerate them.\" Afridi however, denied these allegations adding that Asif would have suffered more injuries but for his intervention.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/cricketNews/idUKL0834991020070908 | work=Reuters | title=Cricket-Pakistan's Akhtar accuses Afridi of instigating spat | date=8 September 2007}}</ref> Even Asif chipped in saying that Akhtar was lying and that \"Shahid Afridi had nothing to do with the fight\", saying that \"he has not apologised to me.\"<ref>[http://pakistancrickethighlights.info/controversies-in-pakistan-cricket-history Shoaib is not speaking the truth: Asif] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620003908/http://pakistancrickethighlights.info/controversies-in-pakistan-cricket-history |date=20 June 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn 1 April 2008 Akhtar was banned for five years for violating the players' code of conduct. The ban extended to all cricket for and in Pakistan.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/344698.html Shoaib banned for five years]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> Despite the ban not preventing him from playing in the [[Indian Premier League]], the IPL governing council decided not to allow Akhtar to play in the tournament until the end of the ban or unless it is lifted. [[IS Bindra]], a member of the council, was quoted as saying, \"Even though they [the PCB] have cleared him to play for IPL, we felt that international discipline needs to be respected.\"<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/344908.html Shoaib cannot play in IPL]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> Meanwhile, Akhtar vowed to go to great lengths to fight the ban, \"I will appeal, as is my right. If that fails I will go to court, if that fails then I will go to the Supreme Court.\"<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/344784.html 'I have been victimised' \u2013 Shoaib]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> On 3 April, Pakistan Cricket Board chairman [[Nasim Ashraf]] served a legal notice on Akhtar, calling on him to retract statements he made to a news channel, alleging the ban was punishment in return for refusing to give the chairman a share of his earnings from the Indian Premier League, Ashraf also sought damages of Rs 100 million (approximately US$1.6&nbsp;million) for \"defaming him personally\" and an additional Rs 100&nbsp;million to the Pakistan Cricket Board for \"sullying the name of the Pakistan Cricket Board and the Pakistan Cricket team.\"<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/344913.html Ashraf files notice against Shoaib]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> A three-man appellate tribunal announced on 30 April that they had temporarily upheld Akhtar's five-year ban, deciding to revist the appeal hearing in June.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/348077.html Shoaib's five-year ban upheld]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> Despite Akhtar's later retracting his claims and also issuing an unconditional apology for \"any grief or embarrassment that may have been caused to the nation, particularly to the Pakistan Cricket Board chairman Dr Nasim Ashraf\", Ashraf's legal counsel filed a Rs 220&nbsp;million (approx US$3.37&nbsp;million) defamation suit against Akhtar in a civil court in Lahore on 2 May.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/348423.html Ashraf files defamation suit against Shoaib]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> On 4 May, the Pakistan Cricket Board's appellate tribunal suspended the five-year ban for one month, until they reconvene on 4 June, allowing Akhtar to take part in the ongoing Indian Premier League.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/349950.html Shoaib cleared to play in IPL]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 4 May 2008.</ref> A day later, the Pakistan Cricket Board announced that they will no longer pursue the defamation suit following a reconciliation between Akhtar and chairman Nasim Ashraf at the house of Rehman Malik, a key political official, in [[Islamabad]]. \"My honour has been vindicated and now the defamation lawsuit will not be pursued,\" Ashraf was quoted as saying.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/350007.html PCB softens stance on Shoaib]. ''[[Cricinfo.com]].'' Retrieved on 5 May 2008.</ref>\n\nOn 4 September 2008, Akhtar was sent back home from Heathrow airport by British immigration officials on visa grounds; Akhtar only had a  visit visa but not a working visa, which is required to play in county cricket. He subsequently obtained the necessary visa and returned to play with English county club Surrey.<ref>[http://www.cricdb.com/archive/international/news/detail.php?nid=904 Akhtar returns home after visa hitch] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213161951/http://www.cricdb.com/archive/international/news/detail.php?nid=904 |date=13 February 2009 }}. ''Cricdb.com.'' Retrieved on 4 September 2008.</ref>\n\nOn 21 May 2009, Akhtar was dropped from [[2009 ICC World Twenty20]] Pakistan squad because of [[genital warts|genital viral warts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/wt202009/content/story/405415.html |title=Shoaib pulled from World Twenty20 squad &#124; Cricket News &#124; ICC World Twenty20 2009 &#124; Cricinfo.com |publisher=Content.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Twenty20 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/twenty20/5363321/Shoaib-Akhtars-genital-warts-keep-him-out-of-Pakistans-World-Twenty-20-squad.html |title=Shoaib Akhtar's genital warts keep him out of Pakistan's World Twenty 20 squad.|publisher=Telegraph.co.uk |date=21 May 2009 |accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2012, Akhtar accused the PCB stating that there was too much \"politics\" in the Board and some of its officials did not want Pakistani team to win.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.indianexpress.com/news/shoaib-akhtar-accuses-politicised-pcb-of-wanting-team-to-lose/974418/ | title= Shoaib Akhtar accuses 'politicised' PCB of 'wanting team to lose'| date= 14 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=November 2017}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#cccccc\" \n! Year !! Show !! Role !! Language !! Country\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Comedy Nights with Kapil]]'' || Guest || [[Hindi]] || ''[[India]]''\n|-   \n| 2016 || ''[[Mazaak Mazaak Mein]]'' || Judge || [[Hindi]] || ''[[India]]'' \n|-\n| 2016/17|| ''[[PTV Sports#Game On Hai!|Game On Hai!]]'' || Guest || [[Urdu]] || ''[[Pakistan]]''\n|-   \n| 2017 || ''[[Geo Khelo Pakistan]]'' || Host || [[Urdu]] || ''[[Pakistan]]''\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[YouTube Rewind 2019: For the Record|YouTube Rewind 2019]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.ramizansari.com/2019/12/06/shoaib-akhtar-first-pakistani-that-made-it-to-youtube-rewind/|title=Shoaib Akhtar, First Pakistani that made it to Youtube Rewind|last=Ansari|first=Ramiz|date=2019-12-06|website=Blog by Ramiz Ansari|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>''\n|Self\n|[[English language|English]]\n|''International''\n|}\n\n== International bowling records ==\n{{Main|List of international cricket five-wicket hauls by Shoaib Akhtar}}\n\n=== Test 10 Wicket hauls ===\n\n{| class=\