 Pakistani cricket]]\n[[Category:Pakistan International Airlines cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistan One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers from Rawalpindi]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:Rawalpindi cricketers]]\n[[Category:Rawalpindi B cricketers]]\n[[Category:Rawalpindi Rams cricketers]]\n[[Category:Somerset cricketers]]\n[[Category:Surrey cricketers]]\n[[Category:Worcestershire cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani cricket commentators]]\n[[Category:Pakistani expatriates in India]]\n[[Category:Pakistani YouTubers]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4070:599:b2fe::1ee1:78b1", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shoaib_Akhtar"}
{"title_page": "1 vs. 100 (American game show)", "text_new": "{{short description|American game show}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name          = 1 vs. 100\n| image              = 1 vs 100 gameshow.png\n| genre              = [[Game show]]\n| runtime            = 41\u201343&nbsp;minutes (2006\u201308)<!--THE INFOBOX DOES NOT COUNT COMMERCIAL BREAKS--><br />20\u201322 minutes (2010\u201311)\n| executive_producer = Scott St. John\n| language           = English\n| presenter          = [[Bob Saget]] (NBC)<br />[[Carrie Ann Inaba]] (GSN)\n| narrated           = [[Joe Cipriano]] (NBC)\n| picture_format     = [[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])<br>(2006-2008)<br>[[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])<br>(2010\u20132011)\n| company            = [[Endemol#Endemol USA|Endemol USA]]\n| country            = United States\n| network            = [[NBC]] (2006\u201308) <br />[[Game Show Network|GSN]] (2010\u201311)\n| first_aired        = NBC:<br>{{start date|2006|10|13}} \u2013 {{end date|2008|2|22}}<br /> GSN: <br> {{start date|2010|11|15}}\n| last_aired         = {{end date|2011|1|11}}\n| num_seasons        = 3 <small>(2 on NBC, 1 on GSN)</small>\n| num_episodes       = NBC: 28<br>GSN: 40\n| website            = https://web.archive.org/web/20110406011726/http://tv.gsn.com/shows/1vs100/\n}}\n\n'''''1 vs. 100''''' is an American game show that was broadcast by [[NBC]] from 2006 to 2008 and revived on [[Game Show Network]] (GSN) with a new series, which ran from 2010 to 2011. The game features a single player (the \"1\") competing against 100 other contestants (known as \"the Mob\") in a trivia match. The 1 earns prize money depending on how many Mob members he or she has eliminated from the game, but loses all winnings with an incorrect answer at any point. The host of the original NBC version was [[Bob Saget]], while [[Carrie Ann Inaba]] hosted the GSN revival.\n\n==Gameplay==\nThe game is played with the main contestant acting as the \"1\" answering questions against 100 other people collectively known as the \"Mob\", for the top prize of $1,000,000 ($50,000 or $100,000 in the GSN revival). The contestant's goal must be the last player standing, and by eliminating all 100 members of the Mob by correctly answering general-knowledge questions in succession.<ref name=\"Stanley\"/>\n\nTo begin the game, a multiple-choice question is revealed with three options, with one being the correct answer. Once all of the Mob members have locked in their answers, the contestant is given the opportunity to answer the question. If the contestant is correct, all Mob members who answered incorrectly are eliminated from the game, bringing the \"1\" closer to winning the game. The amount of money in the contestant's bank also increases by an amount dependent on the number of mob members eliminated in that question (season 1), or at a level per every 10 mobs eliminated (season 2). If the contestant eliminates all 100 mob members, his or her winnings was augmented to the top prize . \n\nAfter every correct answer, the contestant is given the choice to either walk away with the money he or she has earned or continue playing. In conjunction with the various changes made in the sixth episode, the contestant could now only walk away after correctly answering the third question, the fifth question, and every question thereafter. If the \"1\" continues and misses the question, the game ends and the contestant won nothing, while any surviving Mob members who answered the last question correctly evenly split the \"1\"'s winnings accumulated up to that point in the game.<ref name=\"Stanley\"/>\n\n===Helps===\nTo assist the main contestant, assistance from the mob is offered in the form of \"helps\". Originally there were two helps, which could only be used in order.<ref name=\"NBC1Premiere\">{{cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|season=1|number=1|network=NBC|date=October 13, 2006}}</ref> Starting with the sixth episode, a third option was added, the three helps were given names, and contestants could choose any of the three at any point in the game. The helps were, in order:<ref name=\"NBC Rules\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc.com/Casting/Applications/1v100_rules.pdf|title=''1 vs 100'' Official Rules|work=NBC.com|publisher=NBC Universal|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070422021424/http://www.nbc.com/Casting/Applications/1v100_rules.pdf|archivedate=April 22, 2007}}</ref>\n\n*\"Poll The Mob\": Originally known as the first help, the contestant selects one of the three answers to get more information about. The number of Mob members who chose that answer is revealed, and the contestant chooses one of the revealed mob members to discuss his or her response.<ref name=\"NBC1Premiere\"/>\n*\"Ask The Mob\": Originally known as the second help, two Mob members are randomly selected: one who answered correctly and one who answered incorrectly. Each explains his or her decision to the contestant, which in turn eliminates the third choice from consideration.<ref name=\"NBC1Premiere\"/>\n*\"Trust The Mob\" (added in episode six): The contestant is automatically committed to the answer chosen most frequently by the Mob.<ref name=\"Season1Ep6\">{{Cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|network=NBC|date=December 1, 2006|season=1|number=6}}</ref>\n\nAfter reaching a certain point in the game, contestants can be given a \"Sneak Peek\" which allows the contestant to see their next question (but not the three answers) before deciding whether or not to answer the next question. In season one, it was used when a player eliminated 90 or more members of the mob;<ref name=\"NBC Rules\"/> it eventually became available once a contestant used all his or her helps in season two.<ref>{{cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|network=NBC|date=January 25, 2008|season=2|number=4}}</ref>\n\n===Payout structure===\nOriginally, contestants were awarded a cumulative amount of money after each individual question for each Mob member eliminated; this amount increased with each question as the game went on. For example, a contestant who eliminated eight Mob members on his or her second question would be awarded $500 per member, adding up to $4,000 to add to his or her total.<ref name=\"NBC1Premiere\"/> The payout structure was tweaked slightly prior to the third episode of the season<ref name=\"Season1Ep3\">{{Cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|network=NBC|date=October 27, 2006|season=1|number=3}}</ref> and changed once again on the sixth episode in conjunction with introduction of the \"Trust the Mob\" help.<ref name=\"NBC Rules\"/><ref name=\"Season1Ep6\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Question\n! colspan=\"3\"| Value\n|-\n! Episodes 1\u20132<ref name=\"NBC1Premiere\"/>\n! Episodes 3\u20135<ref name=\"Season1Ep3\"/>\n! Episodes 6\u201320<ref name=\"Season1Ep6\"/>\n|-\n| align=center|13+\n| align=center colspan=\"3\"|$10,000\n|-\n| align=center|12\n| align=center colspan=\"2\"|$10,000\n| align=center|$9,000\n|-\n| align=center|11\n| align=center|$9,000\n| align=center|$7,500\n| align=center|$8,000\n|-\n| align=center|10\n| align=center|$8,000\n| align=center|$6,000\n| align=center|$7,000\n|-\n| align=center|9\n| align=center|$7,000\n| align=center|$5,000\n| align=center|$6,000\n|-\n| align=center|8\n| align=center|$6,000\n| align=center|$4,000\n| align=center|$5,000\n|-\n| align=center|7\n| align=center|$5,000\n| align=center|$3,000\n| align=center|$4,000\n|-\n| align=center|6\n| align=center|$4,000\n| align=center|$2,000\n| align=center|$3,000\n|-\n| align=center|5\n| align=center|$3,000\n| align=center|$1,500\n| align=center rowspan=\"2\"|$2,000\n|-\n| align=center|4\n| align=center|$2,000\n| align=center|$1,000\n|-\n| align=center|3\n| align=center|$1,000\n| align=center|$500\n| align=center rowspan=\"3\"|$1,000\n|-\n| align=center|2\n| align=center|$500\n| align=center|$250\n|-\n| align=center|1\n| align=center colspan=\"2\"|$100\n|}\n\nIn the second season, the payout structure was simplified to award contestants for every tenth Mob member eliminated.<ref name=\"NBC2Premiere\"/> On the GSN version, the structure of the second NBC season was used, though the amounts were significantly reduced. Towards the end of the series' run, the top prize was briefly raised to $100,000 before reverting to $50,000 for the final two episodes.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Mob members<br />eliminated\n! colspan=\"4\"| Contestants' total\n|-\n! NBC (season two)<ref name=\"NBC2Premiere\"/>\n! GSN (episodes 1\u201317)<ref>{{cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|season=1|number=1|network=GSN|date=November 15, 2010}}</ref>\n! GSN (episodes 18\u201333, 39\u201340)<ref>{{cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|season=1|number=18|network=GSN|date=December 8, 2010}}</ref>\n! GSN (episodes 34\u201338)<ref>{{cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|season=1|number=34\u201338|network=GSN|date=January 3\u20137, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=center|100\n| align=center|'''$1,000,000'''\n| align=center colspan=\"2\"|'''$50,000'''\n| align=center|'''$100,000'''\n|-\n| align=center|90\u201399\n| align=center|$500,000\n| align=center colspan=\"2\"|$25,000\n| align=center|$50,000\n|-\n| align=center|80\u201389\n| align=center|$250,000\n| align=center colspan=\"2\"|$10,000\n| align=center|$25,000\n|-\n| align=center|70\u201379\n| align=center|$100,000\n| align=center colspan=\"2\"|$5,000\n| align=center|$10,000\n|-\n| align=center|60\u201369\n| align=center|$75,000\n| align=center|$2,500\n| align=center|$4,000\n| align=center|$8,000\n|-\n| align=center|50\u201359\n| align=center|$50,000\n| align=center|$2,000\n| align=center|$3,000\n| align=center|$6,000\n|-\n| align=center|40\u201349\n| align=center|$25,000\n| align=center|$1,500\n| align=center|$2,000\n| align=center|$4,000\n|-\n| align=center|30\u201339\n| align=center|$10,000\n| align=center|$1,000\n| align=center|$1,500\n| align=center|$2,000\n|-\n| align=center|20\u201329\n| align=center|$5,000\n| align=center|$750\n| align=center colspan=\"2\"|$1,000\n|-\n| align=center|10\u201319\n| align=center|$1,000\n| align=center colspan=\"3\"|$500\n|-\n| align=center|Fewer than 10\n| align=center colspan=\"4\"|$0\n|}\n\n==Production==\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = right\n | total_width = 400\n\n | image1 = Bob Saget.jpg\n | width1 = 195\n\n | image2 = Carrie Ann Inaba.jpg\n | width2 = 195\n\n | footer = [[Bob Saget]] hosts the NBC version (left), and [[Carrie Ann Inaba]] on the GSN revival (right).\n}}\n\n===NBC===\nThe show first premiered on NBC as a five-episode series on October 13, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zap2it.com/tv/news/zap-nbc1vs100premiere,0,5382105.story?coll=zap-tv-headlines |title=NBC Gets Its (Other) Game On |accessdate=October 15, 2006 |date=September 27, 2006 |work=Zap2It |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222222804/http://www.zap2it.com/tv/news/zap-nbc1vs100premiere%2C0%2C5382105.story?coll=zap-tv-headlines |archivedate=February 22, 2014}}</ref> On October 20, 2006, it was reported that NBC ordered ten additional episodes of ''1 vs. 100'', citing the show's encouraging ratings performance.<ref name=\"Encouraging\">{{cite web|url=http://www.realitytvmagazine.com/blog/2006/10/1_vs_100_reward.html|title=''1 vs. 100'' Rewarded With Additional Episodes|work=Reality TV Magazine|accessdate=November 3, 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061021050555/http://www.realitytvmagazine.com/blog/2006/10/1_vs_100_reward.html |archivedate = October 21, 2006}}</ref> The series returned to NBC's schedule with these new episodes on December 1, 2006.<ref name=\"Season1Ep6\"/>\n\nIn May, NBC announced that ''1 vs. 100'' would return for its second season in Fall 2007 with an eight-episode run. ''[[The Singing Bee (American game show)|The Singing Bee]]'' was originally scheduled to air after the initial run of ''1 vs. 100'', but its premiere was moved up to July to compete with [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]'s new game show ''[[Don't Forget the Lyrics! (American game show)|Don't Forget the Lyrics!]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zap2it.com/tv/news/zap-nbcsingingbeepremiere,0,4096927.story |title=Karaoke Wars: NBC Rushes ''Singing Bee'' |publisher=Zap2it |date=June 21, 2007 |accessdate=July 4, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626053727/http://www.zap2it.com/tv/news/zap-nbcsingingbeepremiere%2C0%2C4096927.story |archivedate=June 26, 2007}}</ref> In July, NBC announced some fall scheduling updates that included ''1 vs. 100''{{'}}s season two premiere being temporarily delayed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/CA6460608.html?display=Breaking+News&referral=SUPP&q=1+vs%2E+100 |title=Ben Silverman Comes Out Swinging |first=Ben |last=Grossman |publisher=Broadcasting & Cable |date=July 16, 2007 |accessdate=August 30, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211153524/http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/CA6460608.html?display=Breaking%2BNews&referral=SUPP&q=1%2Bvs.%2B100 |archivedate=December 11, 2008 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn late 2007, as a result of the [[2007\u201308 Writers Guild of America strike]], NBC announced that ''1 vs. 100'' would return as a winter replacement sometime in January,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/04/business/media/04strike.html|title=As Scripted Shows Dry Up, Reality Sets In|authorlink=Brian Stelter|last=Stelter|first=Brian|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=December 4, 2007|accessdate=September 27, 2017}}</ref> and the series debuted its second season on January 4, 2008,<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news.aspx?id=20071130nbc01 |title=Breaking News \u2013 NBC Announces Exciting Line-Up of Reality Series Premieres in January as New ''American Gladiators'' Debuts Along with Brand New Season of ''The Biggest Loser'' and Return of Popular Game Show ''1 vs 100'' |work=The Futon Critic|publisher=Futon Media |date=November 30, 2007 |accessdate=February 29, 2012}}</ref> with a revamped new set and payout structure.<ref name=\"NBC2Premiere\"/>\n\n====Special episodes====\nThere are six episodes throughout the series:\n*On an episode aired December 1, 2006, the top prize was briefly raised to $3,000,000 for the episode's first contestant. The episode also features several celebrities in the Mob, including game show hosts [[Wink Martindale]] and [[Bob Eubanks]].<ref name=\"Season1Ep6\"/><ref name=\"TVGuide6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/1-vs-100/episode-6-season-1/1-vs-100/283805/|title=Season 1, Episode 6: ''1 vs 100''|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=November 28, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"TVGuide6\"/><ref name=\"TVGuide6\"/>\n*A Christmas special aired on December 25, 2006. Christmas-related questions were answered in this episode, while the Mob were dressed with members in character representing \"[[The Twelve Days of Christmas (song)|The 12 Days of Christmas]].\"<ref>{{cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|season=1|number=9|network=NBC|date=December 25, 2006}}</ref>\n*A kids edition was played on the February 2, 2007, episode in which the Mob consisted of entirely 100 children. The contestant lost $94,000 on a question (\"What was a common feature (motto) relating to the [[Boy Scouts of America]] and [[Girl Scouts of the USA]]\" \u2013 founder, motto or badge system; the correct answer was Motto; the contestant incorrectly answer Badge system) and evenly split $18,800 to the last five (out of 20 remaining) children.<ref>{{cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|season=1|number=14|network=NBC|date=February 2, 2007}}</ref>\n*On February 9, 2007, a special entitled \"Last Man Standing\" was aired, featuring a Mob consisting largely of former top Mob members (Sister Rose and [[Annie Duke]]) and game show champions (such as [[Jeopardy!]] veterans [[Brad Rutter]] and [[Ken Jennings]], and [[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire (American game show)|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire]] winners Nancy Christy and Kevin Olmstead), pitting for a $250,000 prize money. Several rules modified in which that no helps were given and questions are not valued, and the \"1\" was not allowed to leave the game at any point; if the contestant is incorrect, the \"1\" is eliminated from further play and another Mob member is replaced on their behalf. The \"1\" was randomly selected from the Mob and the gameplay was thus 1 vs. 99; Duke was chosen to play as the \"1\". The winner of the $250,000 went to entertainment lawyer and former actor [[Larry Zerner]], who was the only Mob member among the five remaining contestants (including Duke and Jennings) to correctly answer the question (The question was \"Who has been married the most times? \u2013 [[Henry VIII of England|King Henry VIII]], [[Larry King]], or 'King of Pop', [[Michael Jackson]]; Zerner correctly answered Larry King, while the rest incorrectly answered King Henry VIII).<ref>{{cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|season=1|number=15|network=NBC|date=February 9, 2007}}</ref>\n*The season two premiered on January 4, 2008 was entitled \"Battle of the Sexes\", featuring a mob entirely of 100 members in a gender, and the \"1\" from the opposing gender. This was also the first episode to used a revamped set and a new payout ladder system. During this episode, the female contestant Katherine Kazorla played first but lost $50,000 to the last of the 39 surviving male Mob members; the male contestant, Jason Luna, became the show's first (and only) contestant to beat all 100 female Mob members and won the $1,000,000 top prize (Luna's final question was \"According to [[Hallmark Cards|Hallmark]], what is the biggest card-giving holiday of the year?\" \u2013 [[Christmas]], [[Valentine's Day]] or [[Mother's Day]]; Luna correctly answered Christmas while the last 15 female Mob members were incorrect).<ref name=\"NBC2Premiere\">{{cite episode|season=2|number=1|series=1 vs. 100|network=NBC|date=January 4, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiegomagazine.com/San-Diego-Magazine/March-2008/Front-Pages/|title=Mr. Trivia|work=San Diego Magazine|date=February 28, 2008|accessdate=September 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===GSN repeats and revival===\n[[Game Show Network]] (GSN) began airing reruns of the show on June 6, 2009.<ref>{{cite press release|author=GSN Corporate|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2009/05/12/popular-game-shows-deal-or-no-deal-and-1-vs-100-to-debut-on-gsn-june-1-and-june-6-31320/20090512gsn01/|title=Popular Game Shows ''Deal Or No Deal'' and ''1 vs. 100'' to Debut on Gsn, June 1 and June 6|work=The Futon Critic|publisher=Futon Media|date=May 12, 2009|accessdate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> With the ratings success of those shows in reruns,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/31/business/media/31adco.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=At the Game Show Network, Winning Is Everything|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|last=Bernhard|first=Lisa|date=August 30, 2010|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref> GSN announced a casting call in August 2010, implying that the network would be producing new episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realitywanted.com/call/8093-now-casting-1-vs-100-is-back |title=GSN is now casting new series of ''1 vs. 100'' |publisher=Reality Wanted |accessdate=February 29, 2012| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140221143941/http://www.realitywanted.com/call/8093-now-casting-1-vs-100-is-back | archivedate = February 21, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gameshows.about.com/b/2010/08/19/more-on-gsns-version-of-1-vs-100.htm|title=More on GSN's Version of ''1 vs. 100''|work=About.com|publisher=About Entertainent|date=August 19, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414121417/http://gameshows.about.com/b/2010/08/19/more-on-gsns-version-of-1-vs-100.htm|archivedate=April 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn October 13, 2010, GSN announced plans to premiere an original revival series, hosted by then-''[[Dancing with the Stars]]'' judge [[Carrie Ann Inaba]].<ref name=\"GSNpress\">{{cite press release|url=http://corp.gsn.com/press/releases/gsn-premiere-all-new-version-popular-game-show-1-vs-100-produced-endemol-usa-and-host|title=GSN to Premiere All-New Version of Popular Game Show ''1 vs. 100'', Produced by Endemol USA and Hosted by Carrie Ann Inaba, Premieres Monday, November 15|publisher=GSN Corporate|date=October 13, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101105224835/http://corp.gsn.com/press/releases/gsn-premiere-all-new-version-popular-game-show-1-vs-100-produced-endemol-usa-and-host|archivedate=November 5, 2010}}</ref> The initial order of 40 half-hour episodes began airing weekdays on November 15, 2010.<ref name=\"GSNpress\"/> The Mob members participated via [[webcam]], while the \"1\" plays for the top prize of $50,000 ($100,000 on some episodes). Contestants also only had two of the NBC version's helps available: \"Poll the Mob\" and \"Trust the Mob\".<ref name=\"GSNpress\"/> In addition, contestants were only given the option to leave the game upon reaching at least $1,000 on the prize ladder, while the \"Sneak Peek\" was not used until the contestant had reached at least $10,000.\n\nThe season finale of GSN's ''1 vs. 100'' aired on January 11, 2011. Inaba confirmed that she would neither be returning the series<ref>{{cite web|last=Grosvenor|first=Carrie| url = http://gameshows.about.com/b/2011/07/29/carrie-ann-inaba-not-returning-to-gsns-1-vs-100-will-the-show-go-on.htm| title = Carrie Ann Inaba Not Returning to GSN's ''1 vs. 100'' \u2013 Will the Show Go On?|work=About.com|publisher=About Entertainent| accessdate =August 2, 2011| date = July 29, 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140414120528/http://gameshows.about.com/b/2011/07/29/carrie-ann-inaba-not-returning-to-gsns-1-vs-100-will-the-show-go-on.htm |archivedate=April 14, 2014}}</ref> nor renewing for another season, leading to the show's cancellation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/1-vs-100/|title=Showatch: ''1 vs. 100''|work=The Futon Critic|publisher=Futon Media|accessdate=September 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe series quickly became a ratings success for NBC, with the debut episode earning 12,800,000 viewers and a 4.2/13 rating/share among adults 18\u201349.<ref name=\"Encouraging\"/> Despite the high ratings, criticism emerged asserting that the questions tended to be far less difficult than those seen on other quiz shows. ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]''{{'}}s Troy Patterson noted: \"Indeed, the only problem with ''1 vs. 100'' is its determined idiocy....The quality of the quiz is of no importance to the new breed of quiz shows....All that matters is the show of emotion\u2014the contestant's joyful squeals, worried quivers, and relieved slumps.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/television/2006/12/pressing_their_luck.html|title=Pressing Their Luck|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|last=Patterson|first=Troy|date=December 18, 2006|accessdate=September 28, 2017}}</ref> Brian Lowry of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' added: \"Endemol and NBC have managed the seemingly impossible \u2014 combining on a quiz/trivia show nearly as mentally undemanding as their no-skill-required hit ''[[Deal or No Deal (American game show)|Deal or No Deal]]''....the questions are so simple that amassing thousands isn't much harder than guessing which case to open.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2006/tv/reviews/1-vs-100-1200512736/|title=''1 vs. 100''|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Lowry|first=Brian|date=October 11, 2006|accessdate=September 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Ray Richmond]] argued that while the series' format is \"not a terrible game\", it was easier than it was promoted to be: \"While the idea of having one contestant take on 100 people in a game of trivia skill sounds on paper like a hugely challenging undertaking, in truth it probably is 100 times less challenging than ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire (American game show)|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire]]'' because 1) the questions tend to be far less brainy, and 2) the competition ain\u2019t all it is cracked up to be.\"<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.entertainment-news.org/nbc-quiz-show-1-100-unremarkable/| title = New NBC quiz show ''1 vs. 100'' unremarkable| accessdate = October 15, 2006| last = Richmond| first = Ray|authorlink=Ray Richmond| date = October 13, 2006| work = Entertainment Weekly| publisher = Reuters| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100802075726/http://www.entertainment-news.org/nbc-quiz-show-1-100-unremarkable/| archivedate = August 2, 2010}}</ref> Ed Bark, a former television critic at ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'', gave the series a \"C-minus\" grade, calling it \"another NBC big-money game show that really should be titled ''Dumb or Super-Dumb''. How else to gauge the candle power required to answer the show's opening question: 'The 2003 movie ''[[Seabiscuit (film)|Seabiscuit]]'' featured what kind of animal?'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unclebarky.com/fall_files/7fbb781499850f7660daadaf49321941-22.html|title=New Series Review: ''1 vs 100'' (NBC)|work=Uncle Barky's Bytes|last=Bark|first=Ed|date=October 18, 2006|accessdate=September 28, 2017}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]''{{'}}s [[Alessandra Stanley]] opined, \"the point of ''1 vs 100'' is different: knowledge is beside the point.\"<ref name=\"Stanley\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/13/arts/television/13game.html|title=In Battle for Bucks, Personality Beats Intellect|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=The New York Times Company|authorlink=Alessandra Stanley|last=Stanley|first=Alessandra|date=October 13, 2006|accessdate=September 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Merchandise==\nThe success of the series inspired several home versions to be released. These included media home versions in the form of an interactive DVD game,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/1-vs-100/dvd-957707|title=''1 vs. 100'' (DVD)|publisher=IGN|accessdate=September 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/105056/1-vs-100-dvd-board-game|title=''1 vs. 100'' DVD Board Game (2007)|publisher=[[BoardGameGeek]]|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> a mobile app,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/1-vs-100/cell-908156|title=''1 vs. 100'' Review|publisher=IGN|accessdate=September 23, 2017}}</ref> a [[Handheld TV game|plug-and-play game]], a version for the PC, a [[1 vs. 100 (2008 video game)|version for the Nintendo DS]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/08/01/1-vs-100-review|title=''1 vs. 100'' Review|last=Pereira|first=Mike|publisher=IGN|date=August 1, 2008|accessdate=September 23, 2017}}</ref> and an [[1 vs. 100 (2009 video game)|interactive version for Xbox Live]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jun/03/entertainment/et-hundred3|title=''1 vs 100'' may change how we watch and participate in game shows -- or not|last=Fritz|first=Ben|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=Tribune Company|date=June 3, 2009|accessdate=September 23, 2017}}</ref> Other home versions were a board game released by [[Pressman Toy Corporation]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/31136/1-vs-100-board-game|title=''1 vs. 100'' Board Game (2006)|publisher=[[BoardGameGeek]]|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> a card game published by Cardinal,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/27681/1-vs-100-card-game|title=''1 vs. 100'' Card Game (2006)|publisher=[[BoardGameGeek]]|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> and a 100-piece puzzle that formed a home version of the game once assembled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/31570/1-vs-100-puzzle-game|title=''1 vs. 100'': The Puzzle Game (2007)|publisher=[[BoardGameGeek]]|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://web.archive.org/web/20061116044458/http://www.nbc.com/1vs100/}} (NBC) at the [[Wayback Machine]]\n* {{Official website|https://web.archive.org/web/20110406011726/http://tv.gsn.com/shows/1vs100/}} (GSN) at the [[Wayback Machine]]\n* {{IMDb title|0843318|1 vs. 100}}\n\n{{Game Show Network}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1 vs. 100}}\n[[Category:1 vs. 100]]\n[[Category:2000s American game shows]]\n[[Category:2006 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2008 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2010s American game shows]]\n[[Category:2010 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2011 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Game Show Network original programming]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by Endemol]]\n[[Category:Television series by Universal Television]]\n[[Category:American television series based on Dutch television series]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American game show}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name          = 1 vs. 100\n| image              = 1 vs 100 gameshow.png\n| genre              = [[Game show]]\n| runtime            = 41\u201343&nbsp;minutes (2006\u201308)<!--THE INFOBOX DOES NOT COUNT COMMERCIAL BREAKS--><br />20\u201322 minutes (2010\u201311)\n| executive_producer = Scott St. John\n| language           = English\n| presenter          = [[Bob Saget]] (NBC)<br />[[Carrie Ann Inaba]] (GSN)\n| narrated           = [[Joe Cipriano]] (NBC)\n| picture_format     = [[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])<br>(2006-2008)<br>[[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])<br>(2010\u20132011)\n| company            = [[Endemol#Endemol USA|Endemol USA]]\n| country            = United States\n| network            = [[NBC]] (2006\u201308) <br />[[Game Show Network|GSN]] (2010\u201311)\n| first_aired        = NBC:<br>{{start date|2006|10|13}} \u2013 {{end date|2008|2|22}}<br /> GSN: <br> {{start date|2010|11|15}}\n| last_aired         = {{end date|2011|1|11}}\n| num_seasons        = 3 <small>(2 on NBC, 1 on GSN)</small>\n| num_episodes       = NBC: 28<br>GSN: 40\n| website            = https://web.archive.org/web/20110406011726/http://tv.gsn.com/shows/1vs100/\n}}\n\n'''''1 vs. 100''''' is an American game show that was broadcast by [[NBC]] from 2006 to 2008 and revived on [[Game Show Network]] (GSN) with a new series, which ran from 2010 to 2011. The game features a single player (the \"1\") competing against 100 other contestants (known as \"the Mob\") in a trivia match. The 1 earns prize money depending on how many Mob members he or she has eliminated from the game, but loses all winnings with an incorrect answer at any point. The host of the original NBC version was [[Bob Saget]], while [[Carrie Ann Inaba]] hosted the GSN revival.\n\n==Gameplay==\nThe game is played with the main contestant acting as the \"1\" answering questions against 100 other people collectively known as the \"Mob\", for the top prize of $1,000,000 ($50,000 or $100,000 in the GSN revival). The contestant's goal must be the last player standing, and by eliminating all 100 members of the Mob by correctly answering general-knowledge questions in succession.<ref name=\"Stanley\"/>\n\nTo begin the game, a multiple-choice question is revealed with three options, with one being the correct answer. Once all of the Mob members have locked in their answers, the contestant is given the opportunity to answer the question. If the contestant is correct, all Mob members who answered incorrectly are eliminated from the game, bringing the \"1\" closer to winning the game. The amount of money in the contestant's bank also increases by an amount dependent on the number of mob members eliminated in that question (season 1), or at a level per every 10 mobs eliminated (season 2). If the contestant eliminates all 100 mob members, his or her winnings was augmented to the top prize . \n\nAfter every correct answer, the contestant is given the choice to either walk away with the money he or she has earned or continue playing. In conjunction with the various changes made in the sixth episode, the contestant could now only walk away after correctly answering the third question, the fifth question, and every question thereafter. If the \"1\" continues and misses the question, the game ends and the contestant won nothing, while any surviving Mob members who answered the last question correctly evenly split the \"1\"'s winnings accumulated up to that point in the game.<ref name=\"Stanley\"/>\n\n===Helps===\nTo assist the main contestant, assistance from the mob is offered in the form of \"helps\". Originally there were two helps, which could only be used in order.<ref name=\"NBC1Premiere\">{{cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|season=1|number=1|network=NBC|date=October 13, 2006}}</ref> Starting with the sixth episode, a third option was added, the three helps were given names, and contestants could choose any of the three at any point in the game. The helps were, in order:<ref name=\"NBC Rules\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc.com/Casting/Applications/1v100_rules.pdf|title=''1 vs 100'' Official Rules|work=NBC.com|publisher=NBC Universal|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070422021424/http://www.nbc.com/Casting/Applications/1v100_rules.pdf|archivedate=April 22, 2007}}</ref>\n\n*\"Poll The Mob\": Originally known as the first help, the contestant selects one of the three answers to get more information about. The number of Mob members who chose that answer is revealed, and the contestant chooses one of the revealed mob members to discuss his or her response.<ref name=\"NBC1Premiere\"/>\n*\"Ask The Mob\": Originally known as the second help, two Mob members are randomly selected: one who answered correctly and one who answered incorrectly. Each explains his or her decision to the contestant, which in turn eliminates the third choice from consideration.<ref name=\"NBC1Premiere\"/>\n*\"Trust The Mob\" (added in episode six): The contestant is automatically committed to the answer chosen most frequently by the Mob.<ref name=\"Season1Ep6\">{{Cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|network=NBC|date=December 1, 2006|season=1|number=6}}</ref>\n\nAfter reaching a certain point in the game, contestants can be given a \"Sneak Peek\" which allows the contestant to see their next question (but not the three answers) before deciding whether or not to answer the next question. In season one, it was used when a player eliminated 90 or more members of the mob;<ref name=\"NBC Rules\"/> it eventually became available once a contestant used all his or her helps in season two.<ref>{{cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|network=NBC|date=January 25, 2008|season=2|number=4}}</ref>\n\n===Payout structure===\nOriginally, contestants were awarded a cumulative amount of money after each individual question for each Mob member eliminated; this amount increased with each question as the game went on. For example, a contestant who eliminated eight Mob members on his or her second question would be awarded $500 per member, adding up to $4,000 to add to his or her total.<ref name=\"NBC1Premiere\"/> The payout structure was tweaked slightly prior to the third episode of the season<ref name=\"Season1Ep3\">{{Cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|network=NBC|date=October 27, 2006|season=1|number=3}}</ref> and changed once again on the sixth episode in conjunction with introduction of the \"Trust the Mob\" help.<ref name=\"NBC Rules\"/><ref name=\"Season1Ep6\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Question\n! colspan=\"3\"| Value\n|-\n! Episodes 1\u20132<ref name=\"NBC1Premiere\"/>\n! Episodes 3\u20135<ref name=\"Season1Ep3\"/>\n! Episodes 6\u201320<ref name=\"Season1Ep6\"/>\n|-\n| align=center|13+\n| align=center colspan=\"3\"|$10,000\n|-\n| align=center|12\n| align=center colspan=\"2\"|$10,000\n| align=center|$9,000\n|-\n| align=center|11\n| align=center|$9,000\n| align=center|$7,500\n| align=center|$8,000\n|-\n| align=center|10\n| align=center|$8,000\n| align=center|$6,000\n| align=center|$7,000\n|-\n| align=center|9\n| align=center|$7,000\n| align=center|$5,000\n| align=center|$6,000\n|-\n| align=center|8\n| align=center|$6,000\n| align=center|$4,000\n| align=center|$5,000\n|-\n| align=center|7\n| align=center|$5,000\n| align=center|$3,000\n| align=center|$4,000\n|-\n| align=center|6\n| align=center|$4,000\n| align=center|$2,000\n| align=center|$3,000\n|-\n| align=center|5\n| align=center|$3,000\n| align=center|$1,500\n| align=center rowspan=\"2\"|$2,000\n|-\n| align=center|4\n| align=center|$2,000\n| align=center|$1,000\n|-\n| align=center|3\n| align=center|$1,000\n| align=center|$500\n| align=center rowspan=\"3\"|$1,000\n|-\n| align=center|2\n| align=center|$500\n| align=center|$250\n|-\n| align=center|1\n| align=center colspan=\"2\"|$100\n|}\n\nIn the second season, the payout structure was simplified to award contestants for every tenth Mob member eliminated.<ref name=\"NBC2Premiere\"/> On the GSN version, the structure of the second NBC season was used, though the amounts were significantly reduced. Towards the end of the series' run, the top prize was briefly raised to $100,000 before reverting to $50,000 for the final two episodes.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Mob members<br />eliminated\n! colspan=\"4\"| Contestants' total\n|-\n! NBC (season two)<ref name=\"NBC2Premiere\"/>\n! GSN (episodes 1\u201317)<ref>{{cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|season=1|number=1|network=GSN|date=November 15, 2010}}</ref>\n! GSN (episodes 18\u201333, 39\u201340)<ref>{{cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|season=1|number=18|network=GSN|date=December 8, 2010}}</ref>\n! GSN (episodes 34\u201338)<ref>{{cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|season=1|number=34\u201338|network=GSN|date=January 3\u20137, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=center|100\n| align=center|'''$1,000,000'''\n| align=center colspan=\"2\"|'''$50,000'''\n| align=center|'''$100,000'''\n|-\n| align=center|90\u201399\n| align=center|$500,000\n| align=center colspan=\"2\"|$25,000\n| align=center|$50,000\n|-\n| align=center|80\u201389\n| align=center|$250,000\n| align=center colspan=\"2\"|$10,000\n| align=center|$25,000\n|-\n| align=center|70\u201379\n| align=center|$100,000\n| align=center colspan=\"2\"|$5,000\n| align=center|$10,000\n|-\n| align=center|60\u201369\n| align=center|$75,000\n| align=center|$2,500\n| align=center|$4,000\n| align=center|$8,000\n|-\n| align=center|50\u201359\n| align=center|$50,000\n| align=center|$2,000\n| align=center|$3,000\n| align=center|$6,000\n|-\n| align=center|40\u201349\n| align=center|$25,000\n| align=center|$1,500\n| align=center|$2,000\n| align=center|$4,000\n|-\n| align=center|30\u201339\n| align=center|$10,000\n| align=center|$1,000\n| align=center|$1,500\n| align=center|$2,000\n|-\n| align=center|20\u201329\n| align=center|$5,000\n| align=center|$750\n| align=center colspan=\"2\"|$1,000\n|-\n| align=center|10\u201319\n| align=center|$1,000\n| align=center colspan=\"3\"|$500\n|-\n| align=center|Fewer than 10\n| align=center colspan=\"4\"|$0\n|}\n\n==Production==\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = right\n | total_width = 400\n\n | image1 = Bob Saget.jpg\n | width1 = 195\n\n | image2 = Carrie Ann Inaba.jpg\n | width2 = 195\n\n | footer = [[Bob Saget]] hosts the NBC version (left), and [[Carrie Ann Inaba]] on the GSN revival (right).\n}}\n\n===NBC===\nThe show first premiered on NBC as a five-episode series on October 13, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zap2it.com/tv/news/zap-nbc1vs100premiere,0,5382105.story?coll=zap-tv-headlines |title=NBC Gets Its (Other) Game On |accessdate=October 15, 2006 |date=September 27, 2006 |work=Zap2It |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222222804/http://www.zap2it.com/tv/news/zap-nbc1vs100premiere%2C0%2C5382105.story?coll=zap-tv-headlines |archivedate=February 22, 2014}}</ref> On October 20, 2006, it was reported that NBC ordered ten additional episodes of ''1 vs. 100'', citing the show's encouraging ratings performance.<ref name=\"Encouraging\">{{cite web|url=http://www.realitytvmagazine.com/blog/2006/10/1_vs_100_reward.html|title=''1 vs. 100'' Rewarded With Additional Episodes|work=Reality TV Magazine|accessdate=November 3, 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061021050555/http://www.realitytvmagazine.com/blog/2006/10/1_vs_100_reward.html |archivedate = October 21, 2006}}</ref> The series returned to NBC's schedule with these new episodes on December 1, 2006.<ref name=\"Season1Ep6\"/>\n\nIn May, NBC announced that ''1 vs. 100'' would return for its second season in Fall 2007 with an eight-episode run. ''[[The Singing Bee (American game show)|The Singing Bee]]'' was originally scheduled to air after the initial run of ''1 vs. 100'', but its premiere was moved up to July to compete with [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]'s new game show ''[[Don't Forget the Lyrics! (American game show)|Don't Forget the Lyrics!]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zap2it.com/tv/news/zap-nbcsingingbeepremiere,0,4096927.story |title=Karaoke Wars: NBC Rushes ''Singing Bee'' |publisher=Zap2it |date=June 21, 2007 |accessdate=July 4, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626053727/http://www.zap2it.com/tv/news/zap-nbcsingingbeepremiere%2C0%2C4096927.story |archivedate=June 26, 2007}}</ref> In July, NBC announced some fall scheduling updates that included ''1 vs. 100''{{'}}s season two premiere being temporarily delayed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/CA6460608.html?display=Breaking+News&referral=SUPP&q=1+vs%2E+100 |title=Ben Silverman Comes Out Swinging |first=Ben |last=Grossman |publisher=Broadcasting & Cable |date=July 16, 2007 |accessdate=August 30, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211153524/http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/CA6460608.html?display=Breaking%2BNews&referral=SUPP&q=1%2Bvs.%2B100 |archivedate=December 11, 2008 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn late 2007, as a result of the [[2007\u201308 Writers Guild of America strike]], NBC announced that ''1 vs. 100'' would return as a winter replacement sometime in January,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/04/business/media/04strike.html|title=As Scripted Shows Dry Up, Reality Sets In|authorlink=Brian Stelter|last=Stelter|first=Brian|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=December 4, 2007|accessdate=September 27, 2017}}</ref> and the series debuted its second season on January 4, 2008,<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news.aspx?id=20071130nbc01 |title=Breaking News \u2013 NBC Announces Exciting Line-Up of Reality Series Premieres in January as New ''American Gladiators'' Debuts Along with Brand New Season of ''The Biggest Loser'' and Return of Popular Game Show ''1 vs 100'' |work=The Futon Critic|publisher=Futon Media |date=November 30, 2007 |accessdate=February 29, 2012}}</ref> with a revamped new set and payout structure.<ref name=\"NBC2Premiere\"/>\n\n====Special episodes====\nThere are six episodes throughout the series:\n*On an episode aired December 1, 2006, the top prize was briefly raised to $3,000,000 for the episode's first contestant. The episode also features several celebrities in the Mob, including game show hosts [[Wink Martindale]] and [[Bob Eubanks]].<ref name=\"Season1Ep6\"/><ref name=\"TVGuide6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/1-vs-100/episode-6-season-1/1-vs-100/283805/|title=Season 1, Episode 6: ''1 vs 100''|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=November 28, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"TVGuide6\"/> The episode also featured <ref name=\"TVGuide6\"/>\n*A Christmas special aired on December 25, 2006. Christmas-related questions were answered in this episode, while the Mob were dressed with members in character representing \"[[The Twelve Days of Christmas (song)|The 12 Days of Christmas]].\"<ref>{{cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|season=1|number=9|network=NBC|date=December 25, 2006}}</ref>\n*A kids edition was played on the February 2, 2007, episode in which the Mob consisted of entirely 100 children. The contestant lost $94,000 on a question (a common feature (motto) relating to the [[Boy Scouts of America]] and [[Girl Scouts of the USA]]; the contestant incorrectly answer Badge system, and other incorrect answer as Founder) and evenly split $18,800 to the last five (out of 20) children who correctly answered the last question.<ref>{{cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|season=1|number=14|network=NBC|date=February 2, 2007}}</ref>\n*On February 9, 2007, a special entitled \"Last Man Standing\" was aired, featuring a Mob consisting largely of former top Mob members and game show champions, including [[Brad Rutter]], [[Ken Jennings]], Nancy Christy, Kevin Olmstead, and [[Annie Duke]] among others, for a $250,000 prize money. Several rules modified in which that no helps were given and questions are not valued, and the \"1\" was not allowed to leave the game at any point; if the contestant is incorrect, the \"1\" is eliminated and another Mob member is chosen to take on the place. The \"1\" was randomly selected from the Mob and the gameplay was thus 1 vs. 99; Duke was chosen to play as the \"1\". The winner of the $250,000 went to entertainment lawyer and former actor [[Larry Zerner]], who was the only Mob member among the five remaining contestants (including Duke and Jennings) answering the question (The question was \"Who has been married the most times? \u2013 [[Henry VIII of England|King Henry VIII]], [[Larry King]], or 'King of Pop', [[Michael Jackson]]; Zerner correctly answered Larry King, while the rest incorrectly answered King Henry VIII).<ref>{{cite episode|series=1 vs. 100|season=1|number=15|network=NBC|date=February 9, 2007}}</ref>\n*The season two premiered on January 4, 2008 was entitled \"Battle of the Sexes\", featuring a mob entirely of 100 members in a gender, and the \"1\" on the opposing gender. This was also the first episode to used a revamped set and a new payout ladder system. During this episode, the female contestant Katherine Kazorla lost $50,000 to the last of the 39 surviving male Mob members; the male contestant, Jason Luna, became the show's first (and only) contestant to beat all 100 female Mob members and won the $1,000,000 grand prize (Luna's final question was \"According to [[Hallmark Cards|Hallmark]], what is the biggest card-giving holiday of the year?\" \u2013 [[Christmas]], [[Valentine's Day]] or [[Mother's Day]]; Luna correctly answered Christmas while the last 15 female Mob members were incorrect).<ref name=\"NBC2Premiere\">{{cite episode|season=2|number=1|series=1 vs. 100|network=NBC|date=January 4, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiegomagazine.com/San-Diego-Magazine/March-2008/Front-Pages/|title=Mr. Trivia|work=San Diego Magazine|date=February 28, 2008|accessdate=September 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===GSN repeats and revival===\n[[Game Show Network]] (GSN) began airing reruns of the show on June 6, 2009.<ref>{{cite press release|author=GSN Corporate|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2009/05/12/popular-game-shows-deal-or-no-deal-and-1-vs-100-to-debut-on-gsn-june-1-and-june-6-31320/20090512gsn01/|title=Popular Game Shows ''Deal Or No Deal'' and ''1 vs. 100'' to Debut on Gsn, June 1 and June 6|work=The Futon Critic|publisher=Futon Media|date=May 12, 2009|accessdate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> With the ratings success of those shows in reruns,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/31/business/media/31adco.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=At the Game Show Network, Winning Is Everything|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|last=Bernhard|first=Lisa|date=August 30, 2010|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref> GSN announced a casting call in August 2010, implying that the network would be producing new episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realitywanted.com/call/8093-now-casting-1-vs-100-is-back |title=GSN is now casting new series of ''1 vs. 100'' |publisher=Reality Wanted |accessdate=February 29, 2012| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140221143941/http://www.realitywanted.com/call/8093-now-casting-1-vs-100-is-back | archivedate = February 21, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gameshows.about.com/b/2010/08/19/more-on-gsns-version-of-1-vs-100.htm|title=More on GSN's Version of ''1 vs. 100''|work=About.com|publisher=About Entertainent|date=August 19, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414121417/http://gameshows.about.com/b/2010/08/19/more-on-gsns-version-of-1-vs-100.htm|archivedate=April 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn October 13, 2010, GSN announced plans to premiere an original revival series, hosted by then-''[[Dancing with the Stars]]'' judge [[Carrie Ann Inaba]].<ref name=\"GSNpress\">{{cite press release|url=http://corp.gsn.com/press/releases/gsn-premiere-all-new-version-popular-game-show-1-vs-100-produced-endemol-usa-and-host|title=GSN to Premiere All-New Version of Popular Game Show ''1 vs. 100'', Produced by Endemol USA and Hosted by Carrie Ann Inaba, Premieres Monday, November 15|publisher=GSN Corporate|date=October 13, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101105224835/http://corp.gsn.com/press/releases/gsn-premiere-all-new-version-popular-game-show-1-vs-100-produced-endemol-usa-and-host|archivedate=November 5, 2010}}</ref> The initial order of 40 half-hour episodes began airing weekdays on November 15, 2010.<ref name=\"GSNpress\"/> The Mob members participated via [[webcam]], while the \"1\" plays for the top prize of $50,000 ($100,000 on some episodes). Contestants also only had two of the NBC version's helps available: \"Poll the Mob\" and \"Trust the Mob\".<ref name=\"GSNpress\"/> In addition, contestants were only given the option to leave the game upon reaching at least $1,000 on the prize ladder, while the \"Sneak Peek\" was not used until the contestant had reached at least $10,000.\n\nThe season finale of GSN's ''1 vs. 100'' aired on January 11, 2011. Inaba confirmed that she would neither be returning the series<ref>{{cite web|last=Grosvenor|first=Carrie| url = http://gameshows.about.com/b/2011/07/29/carrie-ann-inaba-not-returning-to-gsns-1-vs-100-will-the-show-go-on.htm| title = Carrie Ann Inaba Not Returning to GSN's ''1 vs. 100'' \u2013 Will the Show Go On?|work=About.com|publisher=About Entertainent| accessdate =August 2, 2011| date = July 29, 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140414120528/http://gameshows.about.com/b/2011/07/29/carrie-ann-inaba-not-returning-to-gsns-1-vs-100-will-the-show-go-on.htm |archivedate=April 14, 2014}}</ref> nor renewing for another season, leading to the show's cancellation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/1-vs-100/|title=Showatch: ''1 vs. 100''|work=The Futon Critic|publisher=Futon Media|accessdate=September 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe series quickly became a ratings success for NBC, with the debut episode earning 12,800,000 viewers and a 4.2/13 rating/share among adults 18\u201349.<ref name=\"Encouraging\"/> Despite the high ratings, criticism emerged asserting that the questions tended to be far less difficult than those seen on other quiz shows. ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]''{{'}}s Troy Patterson noted: \"Indeed, the only problem with ''1 vs. 100'' is its determined idiocy....The quality of the quiz is of no importance to the new breed of quiz shows....All that matters is the show of emotion\u2014the contestant's joyful squeals, worried quivers, and relieved slumps.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/television/2006/12/pressing_their_luck.html|title=Pressing Their Luck|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|last=Patterson|first=Troy|date=December 18, 2006|accessdate=September 28, 2017}}</ref> Brian Lowry of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' added: \"Endemol and NBC have managed the seemingly impossible \u2014 combining on a quiz/trivia show nearly as mentally undemanding as their no-skill-required hit ''[[Deal or No Deal (American game show)|Deal or No Deal]]''....the questions are so simple that amassing thousands isn't much harder than guessing which case to open.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2006/tv/reviews/1-vs-100-1200512736/|title=''1 vs. 100''|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Lowry|first=Brian|date=October 11, 2006|accessdate=September 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Ray Richmond]] argued that while the series' format is \"not a terrible game\", it was easier than it was promoted to be: \"While the idea of having one contestant take on 100 people in a game of trivia skill sounds on paper like a hugely challenging undertaking, in truth it probably is 100 times less challenging than ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire (American game show)|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire]]'' because 1) the questions tend to be far less brainy, and 2) the competition ain\u2019t all it is cracked up to be.\"<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.entertainment-news.org/nbc-quiz-show-1-100-unremarkable/| title = New NBC quiz show ''1 vs. 100'' unremarkable| accessdate = October 15, 2006| last = Richmond| first = Ray|authorlink=Ray Richmond| date = October 13, 2006| work = Entertainment Weekly| publisher = Reuters| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100802075726/http://www.entertainment-news.org/nbc-quiz-show-1-100-unremarkable/| archivedate = August 2, 2010}}</ref> Ed Bark, a former television critic at ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'', gave the series a \"C-minus\" grade, calling it \"another NBC big-money game show that really should be titled ''Dumb or Super-Dumb''. How else to gauge the candle power required to answer the show's opening question: 'The 2003 movie ''[[Seabiscuit (film)|Seabiscuit]]'' featured what kind of animal?'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unclebarky.com/fall_files/7fbb781499850f7660daadaf49321941-22.html|title=New Series Review: ''1 vs 100'' (NBC)|work=Uncle Barky's Bytes|last=Bark|first=Ed|date=October 18, 2006|accessdate=September 28, 2017}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]''{{'}}s [[Alessandra Stanley]] opined, \"the point of ''1 vs 100'' is different: knowledge is beside the point.\"<ref name=\"Stanley\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/13/arts/television/13game.html|title=In Battle for Bucks, Personality Beats Intellect|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=The New York Times Company|authorlink=Alessandra Stanley|last=Stanley|first=Alessandra|date=October 13, 2006|accessdate=September 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Merchandise==\nThe success of the series inspired several home versions to be released. These included media home versions in the form of an interactive DVD game,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/1-vs-100/dvd-957707|title=''1 vs. 100'' (DVD)|publisher=IGN|accessdate=September 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/105056/1-vs-100-dvd-board-game|title=''1 vs. 100'' DVD Board Game (2007)|publisher=[[BoardGameGeek]]|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> a mobile app,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/1-vs-100/cell-908156|title=''1 vs. 100'' Review|publisher=IGN|accessdate=September 23, 2017}}</ref> a [[Handheld TV game|plug-and-play game]], a version for the PC, a [[1 vs. 100 (2008 video game)|version for the Nintendo DS]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/08/01/1-vs-100-review|title=''1 vs. 100'' Review|last=Pereira|first=Mike|publisher=IGN|date=August 1, 2008|accessdate=September 23, 2017}}</ref> and an [[1 vs. 100 (2009 video game)|interactive version for Xbox Live]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jun/03/entertainment/et-hundred3|title=''1 vs 100'' may change how we watch and participate in game shows -- or not|last=Fritz|first=Ben|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=Tribune Company|date=June 3, 2009|accessdate=September 23, 2017}}</ref> Other home versions were a board game released by [[Pressman Toy Corporation]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/31136/1-vs-100-board-game|title=''1 vs. 100'' Board Game (2006)|publisher=[[BoardGameGeek]]|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> a card game published by Cardinal,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/27681/1-vs-100-card-game|title=''1 vs. 100'' Card Game (2006)|publisher=[[BoardGameGeek]]|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> and a 100-piece puzzle that formed a home version of the game once assembled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/31570/1-vs-100-puzzle-game|title=''1 vs. 100'': The Puzzle Game (2007)|publisher=[[BoardGameGeek]]|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://web.archive.org/web/20061116044458/http://www.nbc.com/1vs100/}} (NBC) at the [[Wayback Machine]]\n* {{Official website|https://web.archive.org/web/20110406011726/http://tv.gsn.com/shows/1vs100/}} (GSN) at the [[Wayback Machine]]\n* {{IMDb title|0843318|1 vs. 100}}\n\n{{Game Show Network}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1 vs. 100}}\n[[Category:1 vs. 100]]\n[[Category:2000s American game shows]]\n[[Category:2006 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2008 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2010s American game shows]]\n[[Category:2010 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2011 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Game Show Network original programming]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by Endemol]]\n[[Category:Television series by Universal Television]]\n[[Category:American television series based on Dutch television series]]\n", "name_user": "TVSGuy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSpecial episodes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1_vs._100_(American_game_show)"}
{"title_page": "Brown Bess", "text_new": "{{short description|British flintlock musket}}\n{{More footnotes|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox weapon\n| name               = British Land Pattern Musket<br /><small>a.k.a. Brown Bess</small>\n| image              = British Military Short Land Pattern Musket.jpg \n| image_size         = 300\n| caption            = A Short Land Pattern Musket\n| origin             = [[Kingdom of Great Britain]]\n| type               = [[Musket]]\n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_ranged          = yes\n| is_bladed          =\n| is_explosive       =\n| is_artillery       =\n| is_vehicle         =\n| is_missile         =\n| is_UK              = yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service            = [[British Army]] 1722 \u2014 1838\n| used_by            = [[British Empire]], various [[Native Americans in the United States|American Indian tribes]], [[United States]], [[Kingdom of Sweden]] (1808\u201418??), [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]] (1814\u20141821), [[United Mexican States]], [[Empire of Brazil]], [[Zulu Kingdom]]\n| wars               = [[Indian Wars]], [[Maroon (people)|Maroon Wars]], [[Chickasaw Wars]], [[Dummer's War]], [[War of the Austrian Succession]], [[French and Indian Wars]], [[the '45|Jacobite rising of 1745]], [[Karnatic Wars|Carnatic Wars]], [[Seven Years' War]], [[Anglo-Mysore Wars]], [[Anglo-Maratha Wars]], [[American Revolutionary War]], [[Xhosa Wars]], [[Australian Frontier Wars]], [[Haitian Revolution]], [[French Revolutionary Wars]], [[Kandyan Wars]], [[Irish Rebellion of 1798]], [[Napoleonic Wars]], [[Temne War]], [[Robert Emmet|Emmet's Insurrection]], [[British Expedition to Ceylon]], [[Ashanti-Fante War]], [[Finnish War]], [[Musket Wars]], [[Ga-Fante War]], [[War of 1812]], [[Greek War of Independence]], [[Anglo-Ashanti Wars]], [[Anglo-Burmese Wars]], [[Naning War]], [[Baptist war]], [[Texas Revolution]] (limited), [[Rebellions of 1837]], [[First Opium War]], [[Mexican\u2013American War]], [[Second Opium War]], [[Sepoy Mutiny|Indian Rebellion of 1857]], [[American Civil War]] (limited), [[Paraguayan War]], [[Anglo-Zulu War]]<!-- Production history -->\n| designer           =  \n| design_date        = 1722\n| manufacturer       = Various\n| unit_cost          = \n| production_date    = 1722 \u2014 1860s (all variants)\n| number             = 4,300,000\n| variants           = Long Land Pattern, Short Land Pattern, Sea Service Pattern, India Pattern, New Land Pattern, New Light Infantry Land Pattern, Cavalry Carbine\n<!-- General specifications -->\n| spec_label         =\n| weight             = {{convert|10.5|lb|abbr=on}}\n| length             = {{convert|58.5|in|abbr=on}}\n| part_length        = {{convert|42.0|in|abbr=on}}\u2013{{convert|46.0|in|abbr=on}}\n| width              =  \n| height             = \n| diameter           = \n| crew               =  \n<!-- Ranged weapon specifications -->\n| cartridge          = [[Paper cartridge]], [[Buck and ball]] / [[Round shot|musket ball]] undersized (.69/17.526&nbsp;mm) to reduce the effects of powder [[fouling]] \n| caliber            = .75 (19.05mm)\n| barrels            = [[Smoothbore]]\n| action             = [[Flintlock]]; [[single-shot]]\n| rate               = User dependent; usually 3 to 6 rounds every 1 minute\n| velocity           = {{convert|1300|ft/s|abbr=on}} to {{convert|1800|ft/s|abbr=on}} <ref>Benjamin Robins, New Principles of Gunnery: Containing the Determination of the Force of Gun-Powder</ref>\n| range              = {{convert|109|yd|m|0|abbr=on}} <small>&nbsp;(point target)</small> {{convert|328|yd|m|0|abbr=on}} <small>&nbsp;(area target)</small> <ref>Hughes B. P. Firepower. Weapons effectives on the battlefield, 1630\u20131850</ref><ref>Haythornthwaite Ph. J. Napoleonic Infantry: Napoleonic Weapons and Warfare</ref>\n| max_range          = {{convert|1203|yd|m|0|abbr=on}} <small>&nbsp;(the maximum range of the bullet when fired at an angle of 60 degrees)<ref>https://journals.lib.unb.ca/index.php/MCR/article/view/17669/22312#no10</ref>\n| feed               = [[Muzzleloader|Muzzle-loaded]]\n| sights             = ''None''\n\n|era=[[Napoleonic Wars]]\n|platform=Individual\n|target=Personnel\n|spec_type=Musket\n}}\n'''\"Brown Bess\"''' is a nickname of uncertain origin for the [[British Army]]'s [[Muzzleloader|muzzle-loading]] smoothbore [[flintlock]] '''Land Pattern Musket''' and its [[derivative]]s. This [[musket]] was used in the era of the expansion of the [[British Empire]] and acquired symbolic importance at least as significant as its physical importance. It was in use for over a hundred years with many incremental changes in its [[design]]. These versions include the Long Land Pattern, the Short Land Pattern, the India Pattern, the New Land Pattern Musket and the Sea Service Musket.\n\nThe Long Land Pattern musket and its derivatives, all 0.75 inch [[Calibre|caliber]] flintlock muskets, were the standard [[long gun]]s of the [[British Empire]]'s land forces from 1722 until 1838, when they were superseded by a [[percussion cap]] [[smoothbore]] musket. The [[Glossary of British ordnance terms|British Ordnance System]] converted many [[flintlock]]s into the new [[Caplock mechanism|percussion system]] known as the Pattern 1839 Musket. A fire in 1841 at the [[Tower of London]] destroyed many muskets before they could be converted. Still, the Brown Bess saw service until the middle of the nineteenth century.\n\nMost male citizens of the [[British America|American Colonies]] were required by law to own arms and [[ammunition]] for [[militia]] duty.<ref>{{cite web |last=Linder |first=Doug |title=United States vs. Miller (U.S. 1939) |work=Exploring Constitutional Law |publisher=University of Missouri-Kansas City Law School |year=2008 |url=http://www.law.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/conlaw/millervus.html |accessdate=26 July 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20011123170327/http://www.law.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/conlaw/millervus.html |archive-date=23 November 2001 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Long Land Pattern was a common [[firearm]] in use by both sides in the [[American War of Independence]].<ref>Neumann, George. [http://www.americanrifleman.org/ArticlePage.aspx?id=2037&cid=0 \"The Redcoats' Brown Bess,\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722051841/http://www.americanrifleman.org/ArticlePage.aspx?id=2037&cid=0 |date=22 July 2011 }} ''American Rifleman'', posted 2009.</ref>\n\nIn 1808 during the age of [[Napoleon]], the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] subsidised [[Sweden]] (during the [[Sweden\u2013Finland]] period) in various ways as the [[British government|British]] anxiously wanted to keep an ally in the [[Baltic Sea]] area, this included among other things, deliveries of war material including significant numbers of Brown Bess muskets for use in the [[Finnish War]] of 1808 to 1809.<ref>Norrbottens museum, M\u00e5nadens f\u00f6rem\u00e5l 2009/September Flintl\u00e5sgev\u00e4r med bajonett.</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Musket Wars]] (1820s\u20141830s), [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori warriors]] used Brown Besses, having purchased them from European traders at the time. Some muskets were sold to the [[Mexican Army]], which used them during the [[Texas Revolution]] of 1836 and the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] of 1846 to 1848. Brown Besses saw service in the [[First Opium War]] and during the [[Indian rebellion of 1857]]. [[Zulu people|Zulu warriors]], who had also purchased them from European traders, used them during the [[Anglo-Zulu War]] in 1879. One was even used in the [[Battle of Shiloh]] in 1862.<ref>Brown, Dee Alexander. ''The Bold Cavaliers''. (1959) p. 50.</ref>\n\n==Origins of the name==\nOne hypothesis is that the '''\"Brown Bess\"''' was named after [[Elizabeth I of England]], but this lacks support. Jonathan Ferguson, Firearms Curator of the [[Royal Armouries]], traces the name to at least the 1760s, and his research suggests the name was adopted for slang for a lowly woman, [[mistress (lover)|mistress]], or [[prostitute]] who also appear in period sources referred to as \"Brown Bess.\" He writes, \"'Bess' was a [[generic term|generic]] and sometimes [[derogatory]] name, a bit like 'Sheila' in modern [[Australian English]],\" and \"brown\" simply meant plain or drab. Ferguson discounts, with evidence, many of the other theories previously popular.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://royalarmouries.org/stories/our-collection/brown-bess-musket-or-mistress/|title=History of the term 'Brown Bess' {{!}} Royal Armouries|date=2017-05-17|work=Royal Armouries|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nEarly uses of the term include the [[newspaper]], the ''[[The Hartford Courant|Connecticut Courant]]'' in April 1771, which said \"...&nbsp;but if you are afraid of the sea, take Brown Bess on your shoulder and march.\" This familiar use indicates widespread use of the term by that time. The 1785 ''Dictionary of the Vulgar Tongue'', a contemporary work that defined vernacular and [[Slang|slang terms]], contained this entry: \"Brown Bess: A soldier's firelock. To hug Brown Bess; to carry a fire-lock, or serve as a private soldier.\" [[Military]] and [[government]] records of the time do not use this poetical name but refer to ''firelocks'', ''flintlock'', ''muskets'' or by the weapon's model designations.[[File:Officer and Serjeant of a Highland Regiment.jpg|thumb|left|Soldiers of the [[42nd Regiment of Foot|Black Watch]] armed with a musket (Brown Bess) and a [[halberd]], circa 1790]]\n\nPopular explanations of the use of the word \"Brown\" include that it was a reference to either the colour of the [[walnut]] [[Stock (firearm)|stocks]], or to the characteristic brown colour that was produced by russeting, an early form of [[metal]] treatment. However, in the case of russeting at least, the [[Oxford English Dictionary]] (OED) and Ferguson note that \"[[Browning (steel)|browning]]\" was only introduced in the early 19th century, well after the term had come into general use.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://royalarmouries.org/stories/our-collection/brown-bess-musket-or-mistress/|title=History of the term 'Brown Bess' {{!}} Royal Armouries|date=2017-05-17|work=Royal Armouries|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en-GB}}</ref> Others argue that mass-produced weapons of the time were coated in brown [[varnish]] on metal parts as a rust preventative and on [[wood]] as a sealer (or in the case of unscrupulous [[General contractor|contractor]]s, to disguise inferior or non-regulation types of wood), an entirely different thing from russeting.\n\nSimilarly, the word \"Bess\" is commonly held to either derive from the word ''[[arquebus]]'' or ''[[blunderbuss]]'' (predecessors of the musket) or to be a reference to Elizabeth I, possibly given to commemorate her death. The OED has citations for \"brown musket\" dating back to the early 18th century that refer to the same weapon. Another suggestion is that the name is simply the counterpart to the earlier [[Bill (weapon)|Brown Bill]].\n[[image:Brown Bess.png|thumb|right|400px|A modern reproduction of the Short Land Pattern Musket]]\nHowever, the origin of the name may be much simpler, if vulgar.\n\n{{poemquote|In the days of lace-ruffles, perukes, and brocade\nBrown Bess was a partner whom none could despise\u2013\nAn out-spoken, flinty-lipped, brazen-faced jade,\nWith a habit of looking men straight in the eyes\u2013\nAt [[Battle of Blenheim|Blenheim]] and [[Battle of Ramillies|Ramillies]], fops would confess\nThey were pierced to the heart by the charms of Brown Bess ...|sign=[[Rudyard Kipling]], \"Brown Bess\", 1911}}\n\nKipling may have based his poem on an earlier but similar \"Brown Bess\" poem published in \"Flights of Fancy\" (No. 16) in 1792. Of course, the name could have been initially inspired by the older term of the \"Brown Bill\" and perhaps the barrels were originally varnished brown, but it is well known in literary circles that the name \"Brown Bess\" during the period in question in the 17th to early 19th centuries is not a reference to a color or a weapon but to simply refer to a wanton prostitute [or harlot].<ref>A Dictionary of Sexual Language and Imagery in Shakespearean and Stuart Literature, Gordon Williams (1994) pgs 102-103</ref> Such a nickname would have been a delight to the soldiers of the era who were from the lower classes of English and then British society. So far, the earliest use noted so far of the term \"Brown Bess\" was in a 1631 publication, John Done's \"POLYDORON: OR A Mescellania of Morall, Philosophicall, and Theological Sentences.\" at Page 152:\n\n{{quote|Things profferd and easie to come by, diminish themselves in reputation & price: for how full of pangs and dotage is a wayling lover, for it may bee some browne bessie? But let a beautie fall a weeping, overpressed with the sicke passion; she favours in our thoughts, something Turnbull.}}\n\n==The Land Pattern Muskets==\n[[Image:Brown-Bess-Musket.png|thumb|upright|The Long Land Pattern \"Brown Bess\" musket was the British infantryman's basic arm from about 1740 until the 1830s]]\n\nFrom the seventeenth century to the early years of the eighteenth century, most nations did not specify standards for military firearms. Firearms were individually procured by officers or [[regiment]]s as late as 1745, and were often custom-made to the tastes of the purchaser. As the firearm gained ascendancy on the [[battlefield]], this lack of [[standardisation]] led to increasing difficulties in the supply of [[ammunition]] and repair materials. To address these difficulties, armies began to adopt standardised \"patterns\". A military service selected a \"pattern musket\" to be stored in a \"pattern room\". There it served as a reference for [[Gunsmith|arms maker]]s, who could make comparisons and take measurements to ensure that their products matched the standard.\n\nStress-bearing parts of the Brown Bess, such as the [[Gun barrel|barrel]], [[Mechanism (engineering)|lockwork]], and [[Sling (firearms)|sling]]-[[swivel]]s, were customarily made of [[iron]], while other furniture pieces such as the butt plate, [[trigger guard]] and ramrod pipe were found in both iron and [[brass]]. It weighed around {{convert|10|lb|kg}} and it could be fitted with a 17-inch (432&nbsp;mm) [[Multiview projection|triangular cross-section]] [[bayonet]]. The weapon did not have [[Open sights|sights]], although the [[bayonet lug]] doubled as a crude front sight.\n\nThe earliest models had iron fittings, but these were replaced by brass in models built after 1736. Wooden [[Ramrod|scouring stick]]s were used with the first guns but were replaced by iron ones, although guns with wooden scouring sticks were still issued to troops on American service until 1765 and later to [[Loyalist (American Revolution)|loyalist]] units in the [[American Revolution]]. Wooden scouring sticks were also used in the [[Dragoon]] version produced from 1744\u20141771 for [[Navy]] and [[Marines|Marine]] use.\n\nThe [[Accuracy and precision|accuracy]] of the Brown Bess was fair, as with most other muskets. In 1811, in [[London]], a test [[shooting]] was conducted at the site. The [[Shooting target|target]] was a wooden [[shield]] the size of an [[infantry]] or a [[cavalry]] line. The results of the practice were as follows: at a distance of 100 yards (91.44 m) 53% hits, 200 yards (182.88 m) 30% hits, 300 yards (274.32 m) 23% hits. We can say that the accuracy of the Brown Bess was in line with most other smoothbore muskets of the 18th to 19th centuries. But it should be borne in mind that this is the result of shooting by ordinary soldiers who had a very low [[Military education and training|training]]. Soldiers of [[Light infantry]] had a more severe training and were taught accurate shooting, even in single target.<ref>British Light Infantry and Rifle Tactics of the Napoleonic Wars</ref>\n\nIt is also worth considering that in battle, soldiers suffered [[fear]], [[fatigue]] and [[stress (biology)|stress]], which led to a decrease in accuracy.\n\nThe Brown Bess was used not only in the [[Line infantry]], but also [[Light infantry]]. As well as [[Rogers' Rangers]], hunters, [[Skirmisher]], [[Indigenous Americans|Indians]] and many other [[Irregular military|irregular troops]] who used non-standard [[Military tactics|tactics]].\n\nThere is no doubt that the Brown Bess's bullet was lethal at its full range of effective fire. In the mid-18th century, Robertson measured the speed of musket bullets on a ballistic [[pendulum]]. According to him, the speed of a round musket bullet [[Slug (unit)|slug]] was about 1804.462 feet per second (550&nbsp;m/s). That is, the [[muzzle (firearms)|muzzle]] [[energy]] of the musket was about 3,500 to 4,000 [[joules]], which is comparable to the energy of modern [[rifle cartridge]]s. Modern [[Ballistics|ballistic]] tests have confirmed these data.<ref>https://journals.lib.unb.ca/index.php/MCR/article/view/17669/22312#no10</ref>\nAccording to the Russian Lieutenant-General Ivan G. Gogel, all the muskets of the [[List of sovereign states and dependent territories in Europe|European nations]], was able to penetrate a wooden [[shield]] with a thickness of 1 inch (2.54&nbsp;cm), at a distance of 300 yards.<ref>https://search.rsl.ru/ru/record/01002987782</ref>\n\nBritish soldiers armed with Brown Besses preferred to reduce the standard procedures for loading a musket. To do this, they lower the [[Paper cartridge|cartridge]] into the barrel and hit the butt on the ground. This made it possible to do without the use of a scouring stick. This method of loading allowed to increase the rate of fire approximately twice.<ref>Thomas Anburey. \"Here I cannot help observing to you, whether it proceeded from an idea of self-preservation, or natural instinct, but the soldiers greatly improved the mode they were taught in, as to expedition. For as soon as they had primed their pieces and put the [[Paper cartridge|cartridge]] into the barrel, instead of [scouring] ramming it down with their scouring sticks, they struck the butt plate of the piece upon the ground, and bringing it to the present, fired it off.\u201d</ref>\n\n===Variations===\n[[File:Buck&Ball musket StormWreck.jpg|thumb|X-ray of a Brown Bess musket recovered by [[St. Augustine Light#Lighthouse Archaeological Maritime Program (LAMP)|LAMP]] archaeologists from an American Revolutionary War era shipwreck lost in December 1782. It is believed to be a 1769 Short Land Pattern, and is loaded with [[buck and ball]]]]\n\nMany variations and modifications of the standard pattern musket were created over its long history. The earliest version was the Long Land Pattern of 1722, a 62-inch (1,575&nbsp;mm) long (without bayonet) and with a 46-inch (1,168&nbsp;mm) barrel. It was later found that shortening the barrel did not detract from accuracy but made handling easier, giving rise to the Militia (or Marine) Pattern of 1756 and the Short Land Pattern of 1768, which both had a 42-inch (1,067&nbsp;mm) barrel. Another version with a 39-inch (991&nbsp;mm) barrel was first manufactured for the [[British East India Company]], and was eventually adopted by the British Army in 1790 as the India Pattern.\n\nTowards the end of the life of the weapon, there was a change in the system of ignition. The [[flintlock mechanism]], which was prone to misfiring, especially in [[Moisture content|wet weather]], was replaced by the more reliable percussion cap. The last flintlock pattern manufactured was selected for conversion to the new system as the Pattern 1839. As a fire at the Tower of London destroyed large stocks of these in 1841, a new Pattern 1842 musket was manufactured. These remained in service until the outbreak of the [[Crimean War]] when they were replaced by the [[Mini\u00e9 rifle|Mini\u00e9]] and the [[P53 Enfield]] [[rifled musket]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left; width:10%;\"|Pattern\n! style=\"text-align:left; width:25%;\"|Picture\n! style=\"text-align:left; width:20%;\"|In service\n! style=\"text-align:left; width:15%;\"|Barrel Length\n! style=\"text-align:left; width:15%;\"|Overall Length\n! style=\"text-align:left; width:15%;\"|Weight\n|-\n|Long Land Pattern || [[File:Long Land Pattern.jpg|300px]] || 1722 \u2014 1793<br>standard Infantry Musket 1722 \u2014 1768<br>(supplemented by Short Land Pattern from 1768) || {{convert|46|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|62.5|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|10.4|lb|kg}}\n|-\n|Short Land Pattern || [[File:Short Land Pattern.jpg|300px]] || 1740 \u2014 1797<br>1740 (Dragoons)<br>1768 (Infantry)<br>standard Infantry Musket 1793 \u2014 1797 || {{convert|42|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|58.5|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|10.5|lb|kg}}\n|-\n|India Pattern || [[File:India 3rd Pattern Brown Bess.jpg|300px]] || 1797 \u2014 1854<br>standard Infantry Musket 1797 \u2014 1854<br>(Some in use pre-1797 purchased from the East India Company for use in Egypt) || {{convert|39|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|55.25|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|9.68|lb|kg}}\n|-\n|New Land Pattern || [[File:New Land Pattern.jpg|300px]] || 1802 \u2014 1854<br>Issued only to the Foot Guards and 4th Regiment of Foot || {{convert|39|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|55.5|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|10.06|lb|kg}}\n|-\n|New Light Infantry Land Pattern || The detail differences between this musket and the standard New Land Pattern were a scrolled trigger guard similar to that of the [[Baker Rifle]] except more rounded, a browned barrel and a notch back-sight, the bayonet lug being used as the fore-sight.\n || 1811 \u2014 1854<br>Issued only to the 43rd, 51st, 52nd, 68th, 71st and 85th [[Light Infantry]] and the Battalions of the 60th Foot not armed with rifles || {{convert|39|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|55.5|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|10.06|lb|kg}}\n|-\n|Cavalry Carbine || [[File:Brown Bess Carbine.jpg|300px]] || 1796 \u2014 1838<br>Issued to cavalry units || {{convert|26|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|42.5|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|7.37|lb|kg}}\n|-\n|Sea Service Pattern || [[File:Sea Pattern Brown Bess.jpg|300px]] || 1778 \u2014 1854<br>Issued to Royal Navy ships, drawn by men as required, Marines used Sea Service weapons when deployed as part of a ship's company but were issued India Pattern weapons when serving ashore || {{convert|37|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|53.5|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|9.00|lb|kg}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Brown Bess}}\n* [[British military rifles]]\n* [[List of wars involving England]]\n* [[List of wars involving Great Britain]]\n* [[List of wars involving the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Military history of England]]\n* [[Military history of Britain]]\n* [[Military history of the United Kingdom]]\n* [[British Armed Forces]]\n* [[United Kingdom Special Forces]]\n* [[Charleville musket]]\n* [[Potzdam Musket|Potzdam musket]]\n* [[Jezail]]\n* [[M1752 Musket|Spanish Model 1752 Musket]]\n* [[Springfield musket]]\n* [[Musket]]\n* [[Rifle]]\n* [[Carbine]]\n* [[Pistoleer]]\n* [[Historical reenactment]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Other references==\n* Cumpston, Mike. \"The Guns of Empire: 18th Century Martial Muskets\" ''Guns Magazine'', August 2008, p.&nbsp;60. FMG Publications, San Diego, CA\n* Reid, Stuart. ''British Redcoat (2) 1793\u20131815'' Warrior Series, Osprey Publishing\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Brown Bess}}\n* [http://www.militaryheritage.com/muskets.htm Detailed Brown Bess Images and Information. Correct Source of Images with Blue Background.]\n* [http://www.lincolnminutemen.org/brown-bess-musket-misconception/ Brown Bess - Musket Misconception]\n* [http://www.poemhunter.com/poem/brown-bess-2/ Kipling's poem \"Brown Bess\"]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SJMbxZ1k9NQ Brown Bess Musket: Three shots in 46 seconds (video)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3oPPF6hk8u4 Live Fire (Brown Bess) Volley at 60 yards www.kings8th.com (video)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=569ItSV64FM Revolutionary War Soldier Explaining (Brown Bess) Flintlock Musket (Colonial Williamsburg) (video)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lrRSy55XJNA A demonstration of a British Brown Bess Musket (video)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tiQUYnv64mQ (Brown Bess) Musket Firing Demonstration Part 1 (Minuteman National Park) (video)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VgrLWwZeVYQ (Brown Bess) Musket Firing Demonstration Part 2 (Minuteman National Park) (video)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ho-QCmnNMl8 How to fire a Brown Bess musket - English Heritage (video)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=trgZmM9fNS0 Brown Bess Flintlock Musket Accuracy - updated (Australia) (video)]\n\n{{BritishEmpireWeapons}}\n{{Early firearms}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n\n[[Category:18th-century weapons]]\n[[Category:American Civil War weapons]]\n[[Category:British Army equipment]]\n[[Category:Guns of the American West]]\n[[Category:Military equipment of the Early Modern era]]\n[[Category:Military equipment of the Industrial era]]\n[[Category:Muskets]]\n[[Category:Weapons and ammunition introduced in 1722]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British flintlock musket}}\n{{More footnotes|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox weapon\n| name               = British Land Pattern Musket<br /><small>a.k.a. Brown Bess</small>\n| image              = British Military Short Land Pattern Musket.jpg \n| image_size         = 300\n| caption            = A Short Land Pattern Musket\n| origin             = [[Kingdom of Great Britain]]\n| type               = [[Musket]]\n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_ranged          = yes\n| is_bladed          =\n| is_explosive       =\n| is_artillery       =\n| is_vehicle         =\n| is_missile         =\n| is_UK              = yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service            = [[British Army]] 1722 \u2014 1838\n| used_by            = [[British Empire]], various [[Native Americans in the United States|American Indian tribes]], [[United States]], [[Kingdom of Sweden]] (1808\u201418??), [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]] (1814\u20141821), [[United Mexican States]], [[Empire of Brazil]], [[Zulu Kingdom]]\n| wars               = [[Indian Wars]], [[Maroon (people)|Maroon Wars]], [[Chickasaw Wars]], [[Dummer's War]], [[War of the Austrian Succession]], [[French and Indian Wars]], [[the '45|Jacobite rising of 1745]], [[Karnatic Wars|Carnatic Wars]], [[Seven Years' War]], [[Anglo-Mysore Wars]], [[Anglo-Maratha Wars]], [[American Revolutionary War]], [[Xhosa Wars]], [[Australian Frontier Wars]], [[Haitian Revolution]], [[French Revolutionary Wars]], [[Kandyan Wars]], [[Irish Rebellion of 1798]], [[Napoleonic Wars]], [[Temne War]], [[Robert Emmet|Emmet's Insurrection]], [[British Expedition to Ceylon]], [[Ashanti-Fante War]], [[Finnish War]], [[Musket Wars]], [[Ga-Fante War]], [[War of 1812]], [[Greek War of Independence]], [[Anglo-Ashanti Wars]], [[Anglo-Burmese Wars]], [[Naning War]], [[Baptist war]], [[Texas Revolution]] (limited), [[Rebellions of 1837]], [[First Opium War]], [[Mexican\u2013American War]], [[Second Opium War]], [[Sepoy Mutiny|Indian Rebellion of 1857]], [[American Civil War]] (limited), [[Paraguayan War]], [[Anglo-Zulu War]]<!-- Production history -->\n| designer           =  \n| design_date        = 1722\n| manufacturer       = Various\n| unit_cost          = \n| production_date    = 1722 \u2014 1860s (all variants)\n| number             = 4,300,000\n| variants           = Long Land Pattern, Short Land Pattern, Sea Service Pattern, India Pattern, New Land Pattern, New Light Infantry Land Pattern, Cavalry Carbine\n<!-- General specifications -->\n| spec_label         =\n| weight             = {{convert|10.5|lb|abbr=on}}\n| length             = {{convert|58.5|in|abbr=on}}\n| part_length        = {{convert|42.0|in|abbr=on}}\u2013{{convert|46.0|in|abbr=on}}\n| width              =  \n| height             = \n| diameter           = \n| crew               =  \n<!-- Ranged weapon specifications -->\n| cartridge          = [[Paper cartridge]], [[Buck and ball]] / [[Round shot|musket ball]] undersized (.69/17.526&nbsp;mm) to reduce the effects of powder [[fouling]] \n| caliber            = .75 (19.05mm)\n| barrels            = [[Smoothbore]]\n| action             = [[Flintlock]]; [[single-shot]]\n| rate               = User dependent; usually 3 to 6 rounds every 1 minute\n| velocity           = {{convert|1300|ft/s|abbr=on}} to {{convert|1800|ft/s|abbr=on}} <ref>Benjamin Robins, New Principles of Gunnery: Containing the Determination of the Force of Gun-Powder</ref>\n| range              = {{convert|109|yd|m|0|abbr=on}} <small>&nbsp;(point target)</small> {{convert|328|yd|m|0|abbr=on}} <small>&nbsp;(area target)</small> <ref>Hughes B. P. Firepower. Weapons effectives on the battlefield, 1630\u20131850</ref><ref>Haythornthwaite Ph. J. Napoleonic Infantry: Napoleonic Weapons and Warfare</ref>\n| max_range          = {{convert|1203|yd|m|0|abbr=on}} <small>&nbsp;(the maximum range of the bullet when fired at an angle of 60 degrees)<ref>https://journals.lib.unb.ca/index.php/MCR/article/view/17669/22312#no10</ref>\n| feed               = [[Muzzleloader|Muzzle-loaded]]\n| sights             = ''None''\n\n|era=[[Napoleonic Wars]]\n|platform=Individual\n|target=Personnel\n|spec_type=Musket\n}}\n'''\"Brown Bess\"''' is a nickname of uncertain origin for the [[British Army]]'s [[Muzzleloader|muzzle-loading]] smoothbore [[flintlock]] '''Land Pattern Musket''' and its [[derivative]]s. This [[musket]] was used in the era of the expansion of the [[British Empire]] and acquired symbolic importance at least as significant as its physical importance. It was in use for over a hundred years with many incremental changes in its [[design]]. These versions include the Long Land Pattern, the Short Land Pattern, the India Pattern, the New Land Pattern Musket and the Sea Service Musket.\n\nThe Long Land Pattern musket and its derivatives, all 0.75 inch [[Calibre|caliber]] flintlock muskets, were the standard [[long gun]]s of the [[British Empire]]'s land forces from 1722 until 1838, when they were superseded by a [[percussion cap]] [[smoothbore]] musket. The [[Glossary of British ordnance terms|British Ordnance System]] converted many [[flintlock]]s into the new [[Caplock mechanism|percussion system]] known as the Pattern 1839 Musket. A fire in 1841 at the [[Tower of London]] destroyed many muskets before they could be converted. Still, the Brown Bess saw service until the middle of the nineteenth century.\n\nMost male citizens of the [[British America|American Colonies]] were required by law to own arms and [[ammunition]] for [[militia]] duty.<ref>{{cite web |last=Linder |first=Doug |title=United States vs. Miller (U.S. 1939) |work=Exploring Constitutional Law |publisher=University of Missouri-Kansas City Law School |year=2008 |url=http://www.law.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/conlaw/millervus.html |accessdate=26 July 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20011123170327/http://www.law.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/conlaw/millervus.html |archive-date=23 November 2001 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Long Land Pattern was a common [[firearm]] in use by both sides in the [[American War of Independence]].<ref>Neumann, George. [http://www.americanrifleman.org/ArticlePage.aspx?id=2037&cid=0 \"The Redcoats' Brown Bess,\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722051841/http://www.americanrifleman.org/ArticlePage.aspx?id=2037&cid=0 |date=22 July 2011 }} ''American Rifleman'', posted 2009.</ref>\n\nIn 1808 during the age of [[Napoleon]], the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] subsidised [[Sweden]] (during the [[Sweden\u2013Finland]] period) in various ways as the [[British government|British]] anxiously wanted to keep an ally in the [[Baltic Sea]] area, this included among other things, deliveries of war material including significant numbers of Brown Bess muskets for use in the [[Finnish War]] of 1808 to 1809.<ref>Norrbottens museum, M\u00e5nadens f\u00f6rem\u00e5l 2009/September Flintl\u00e5sgev\u00e4r med bajonett.</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Musket Wars]] (1820s\u20141830s), [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori warriors]] used Brown Besses, having purchased them from European traders at the time. Some muskets were sold to the [[Mexican Army]], which used them during the [[Texas Revolution]] of 1836 and the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] of 1846 to 1848. Brown Besses saw service in the [[First Opium War]] and during the [[Indian rebellion of 1857]]. [[Zulu people|Zulu warriors]], who had also purchased them from European traders, used them during the [[Anglo-Zulu War]] in 1879. One was even used in the [[Battle of Shiloh]] in 1862.<ref>Brown, Dee Alexander. ''The Bold Cavaliers''. (1959) p. 50.</ref>\n\n==Origins of the name==\nOne hypothesis is that the '''\"Brown Bess\"''' was named after [[Elizabeth I of England]], but this lacks support. Jonathan Ferguson, Firearms Curator of the [[Royal Armouries]], traces the name to at least the 1760s, and his research suggests the name was adopted for slang for a lowly woman, [[mistress (lover)|mistress]], or [[prostitute]] who also appear in period sources referred to as \"Brown Bess.\" He writes, \"'Bess' was a [[generic term|generic]] and sometimes [[derogatory]] name, a bit like 'Sheila' in modern [[Australian English]],\" and \"brown\" simply meant plain or drab. Ferguson discounts, with evidence, many of the other theories previously popular.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://royalarmouries.org/stories/our-collection/brown-bess-musket-or-mistress/|title=History of the term 'Brown Bess' {{!}} Royal Armouries|date=2017-05-17|work=Royal Armouries|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nEarly uses of the term include the [[newspaper]], the ''[[The Hartford Courant|Connecticut Courant]]'' in April 1771, which said \"...&nbsp;but if you are afraid of the sea, take Brown Bess on your shoulder and march.\" This familiar use indicates widespread use of the term by that time. The 1785 ''Dictionary of the Vulgar Tongue'', a contemporary work that defined vernacular and [[Slang|slang terms]], contained this entry: \"Brown Bess: A soldier's firelock. To hug Brown Bess; to carry a fire-lock, or serve as a private soldier.\" [[Military]] and [[government]] records of the time do not use this poetical name but refer to ''firelocks'', ''flintlock'', ''muskets'' or by the weapon's model designations.[[File:Officer and Serjeant of a Highland Regiment.jpg|thumb|left|Soldiers of the [[42nd Regiment of Foot|Black Watch]] armed with a musket (Brown Bess) and a [[halberd]], circa 1790]]\n\nPopular explanations of the use of the word \"Brown\" include that it was a reference to either the colour of the [[walnut]] [[Stock (firearm)|stocks]], or to the characteristic brown colour that was produced by russeting, an early form of [[metal]] treatment. However, in the case of russeting at least, the [[Oxford English Dictionary]] (OED) and Ferguson note that \"[[Browning (steel)|browning]]\" was only introduced in the early 19th century, well after the term had come into general use.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://royalarmouries.org/stories/our-collection/brown-bess-musket-or-mistress/|title=History of the term 'Brown Bess' {{!}} Royal Armouries|date=2017-05-17|work=Royal Armouries|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en-GB}}</ref> Others argue that mass-produced weapons of the time were coated in brown [[varnish]] on metal parts as a rust preventative and on [[wood]] as a sealer (or in the case of unscrupulous [[General contractor|contractor]]s, to disguise inferior or non-regulation types of wood), an entirely different thing from russeting.\n\nSimilarly, the word \"Bess\" is commonly held to either derive from the word ''[[arquebus]]'' or ''[[blunderbuss]]'' (predecessors of the musket) or to be a reference to Elizabeth I, possibly given to commemorate her death. The OED has citations for \"brown musket\" dating back to the early 18th century that refer to the same weapon. Another suggestion is that the name is simply the counterpart to the earlier [[Bill (weapon)|Brown Bill]].\n[[image:Brown Bess.png|thumb|right|400px|A modern reproduction of the Short Land Pattern Musket \u2013 [[prototype]], hence no bayonet lug]]\nHowever, the origin of the name may be much simpler, if vulgar.\n\n{{poemquote|In the days of lace-ruffles, perukes, and brocade\nBrown Bess was a partner whom none could despise\u2013\nAn out-spoken, flinty-lipped, brazen-faced jade,\nWith a habit of looking men straight in the eyes\u2013\nAt [[Battle of Blenheim|Blenheim]] and [[Battle of Ramillies|Ramillies]], fops would confess\nThey were pierced to the heart by the charms of Brown Bess ...|sign=[[Rudyard Kipling]], \"Brown Bess\", 1911}}\n\nKipling may have based his poem on an earlier but similar \"Brown Bess\" poem published in \"Flights of Fancy\" (No. 16) in 1792. Of course, the name could have been initially inspired by the older term of the \"Brown Bill\" and perhaps the barrels were originally varnished brown, but it is well known in literary circles that the name \"Brown Bess\" during the period in question in the 17th to early 19th centuries is not a reference to a color or a weapon but to simply refer to a wanton prostitute [or harlot].<ref>A Dictionary of Sexual Language and Imagery in Shakespearean and Stuart Literature, Gordon Williams (1994) pgs 102-103</ref> Such a nickname would have been a delight to the soldiers of the era who were from the lower classes of English and then British society. So far, the earliest use noted so far of the term \"Brown Bess\" was in a 1631 publication, John Done's \"POLYDORON: OR A Mescellania of Morall, Philosophicall, and Theological Sentences.\" at Page 152:\n\n{{quote|Things profferd and easie to come by, diminish themselves in reputation & price: for how full of pangs and dotage is a wayling lover, for it may bee some browne bessie? But let a beautie fall a weeping, overpressed with the sicke passion; she favours in our thoughts, something Turnbull.}}\n\n==The Land Pattern Muskets==\n[[Image:Brown-Bess-Musket.png|thumb|upright|The Long Land Pattern \"Brown Bess\" musket was the British infantryman's basic arm from about 1740 until the 1830s]]\n\nFrom the seventeenth century to the early years of the eighteenth century, most nations did not specify standards for military firearms. Firearms were individually procured by officers or [[regiment]]s as late as 1745, and were often custom-made to the tastes of the purchaser. As the firearm gained ascendancy on the [[battlefield]], this lack of [[standardisation]] led to increasing difficulties in the supply of [[ammunition]] and repair materials. To address these difficulties, armies began to adopt standardised \"patterns\". A military service selected a \"pattern musket\" to be stored in a \"pattern room\". There it served as a reference for [[Gunsmith|arms maker]]s, who could make comparisons and take measurements to ensure that their products matched the standard.\n\nStress-bearing parts of the Brown Bess, such as the [[Gun barrel|barrel]], [[Mechanism (engineering)|lockwork]], and [[Sling (firearms)|sling]]-[[swivel]]s, were customarily made of [[iron]], while other furniture pieces such as the butt plate, [[trigger guard]] and ramrod pipe were found in both iron and [[brass]]. It weighed around {{convert|10|lb|kg}} and it could be fitted with a 17-inch (432&nbsp;mm) [[Multiview projection|triangular cross-section]] [[bayonet]]. The weapon did not have [[Open sights|sights]], although the [[bayonet lug]] doubled as a crude front sight.\n\nThe earliest models had iron fittings, but these were replaced by brass in models built after 1736. Wooden [[Ramrod|scouring stick]]s were used with the first guns but were replaced by iron ones, although guns with wooden scouring sticks were still issued to troops on American service until 1765 and later to [[Loyalist (American Revolution)|loyalist]] units in the [[American Revolution]]. Wooden scouring sticks were also used in the [[Dragoon]] version produced from 1744\u20141771 for [[Navy]] and [[Marines|Marine]] use.\n\nThe [[Accuracy and precision|accuracy]] of the Brown Bess was fair, as with most other muskets. In 1811, in [[London]], a test [[shooting]] was conducted at the site. The [[Shooting target|target]] was a wooden [[shield]] the size of an [[infantry]] or a [[cavalry]] line. The results of the practice were as follows: at a distance of 100 yards (91.44 m) 53% hits, 200 yards (182.88 m) 30% hits, 300 yards (274.32 m) 23% hits. We can say that the accuracy of the Brown Bess was in line with most other smoothbore muskets of the 18th to 19th centuries. But it should be borne in mind that this is the result of shooting by ordinary soldiers who had a very low [[Military education and training|training]]. Soldiers of [[Light infantry]] had a more severe training and were taught accurate shooting, even in single target.<ref>British Light Infantry and Rifle Tactics of the Napoleonic Wars</ref>\n\nIt is also worth considering that in battle, soldiers suffered [[fear]], [[fatigue]] and [[stress (biology)|stress]], which led to a decrease in accuracy.\n\nThe Brown Bess was used not only in the [[Line infantry]], but also [[Light infantry]]. As well as [[Rogers' Rangers]], hunters, [[Skirmisher]], [[Indigenous Americans|Indians]] and many other [[Irregular military|irregular troops]] who used non-standard [[Military tactics|tactics]].\n\nThere is no doubt that the Brown Bess's bullet was lethal at its full range of effective fire. In the mid-18th century, Robertson measured the speed of musket bullets on a ballistic [[pendulum]]. According to him, the speed of a round musket bullet [[Slug (unit)|slug]] was about 1804.462 feet per second (550&nbsp;m/s). That is, the [[muzzle (firearms)|muzzle]] [[energy]] of the musket was about 3,500 to 4,000 [[joules]], which is comparable to the energy of modern [[rifle cartridge]]s. Modern [[Ballistics|ballistic]] tests have confirmed these data.<ref>https://journals.lib.unb.ca/index.php/MCR/article/view/17669/22312#no10</ref>\nAccording to the Russian Lieutenant-General Ivan G. Gogel, all the muskets of the [[List of sovereign states and dependent territories in Europe|European nations]], was able to penetrate a wooden [[shield]] with a thickness of 1 inch (2.54&nbsp;cm), at a distance of 300 yards.<ref>https://search.rsl.ru/ru/record/01002987782</ref>\n\nBritish soldiers armed with Brown Besses preferred to reduce the standard procedures for loading a musket. To do this, they lower the [[Paper cartridge|cartridge]] into the barrel and hit the butt on the ground. This made it possible to do without the use of a scouring stick. This method of loading allowed to increase the rate of fire approximately twice.<ref>Thomas Anburey. \"Here I cannot help observing to you, whether it proceeded from an idea of self-preservation, or natural instinct, but the soldiers greatly improved the mode they were taught in, as to expedition. For as soon as they had primed their pieces and put the [[Paper cartridge|cartridge]] into the barrel, instead of [scouring] ramming it down with their scouring sticks, they struck the butt plate of the piece upon the ground, and bringing it to the present, fired it off.\u201d</ref>\n\n===Variations===\n[[File:Buck&Ball musket StormWreck.jpg|thumb|X-ray of a Brown Bess musket recovered by [[St. Augustine Light#Lighthouse Archaeological Maritime Program (LAMP)|LAMP]] archaeologists from an American Revolutionary War era shipwreck lost in December 1782. It is believed to be a 1769 Short Land Pattern, and is loaded with [[buck and ball]]]]\n\nMany variations and modifications of the standard pattern musket were created over its long history. The earliest version was the Long Land Pattern of 1722, a 62-inch (1,575&nbsp;mm) long (without bayonet) and with a 46-inch (1,168&nbsp;mm) barrel. It was later found that shortening the barrel did not detract from accuracy but made handling easier, giving rise to the Militia (or Marine) Pattern of 1756 and the Short Land Pattern of 1768, which both had a 42-inch (1,067&nbsp;mm) barrel. Another version with a 39-inch (991&nbsp;mm) barrel was first manufactured for the [[British East India Company]], and was eventually adopted by the British Army in 1790 as the India Pattern.\n\nTowards the end of the life of the weapon, there was a change in the system of ignition. The [[flintlock mechanism]], which was prone to misfiring, especially in [[Moisture content|wet weather]], was replaced by the more reliable percussion cap. The last flintlock pattern manufactured was selected for conversion to the new system as the Pattern 1839. As a fire at the Tower of London destroyed large stocks of these in 1841, a new Pattern 1842 musket was manufactured. These remained in service until the outbreak of the [[Crimean War]] when they were replaced by the [[Mini\u00e9 rifle|Mini\u00e9]] and the [[P53 Enfield]] [[rifled musket]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left; width:10%;\"|Pattern\n! style=\"text-align:left; width:25%;\"|Picture\n! style=\"text-align:left; width:20%;\"|In service\n! style=\"text-align:left; width:15%;\"|Barrel Length\n! style=\"text-align:left; width:15%;\"|Overall Length\n! style=\"text-align:left; width:15%;\"|Weight\n|-\n|Long Land Pattern || [[File:Long Land Pattern.jpg|300px]] || 1722 \u2014 1793<br>standard Infantry Musket 1722 \u2014 1768<br>(supplemented by Short Land Pattern from 1768) || {{convert|46|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|62.5|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|10.4|lb|kg}}\n|-\n|Short Land Pattern || [[File:Short Land Pattern.jpg|300px]] || 1740 \u2014 1797<br>1740 (Dragoons)<br>1768 (Infantry)<br>standard Infantry Musket 1793 \u2014 1797 || {{convert|42|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|58.5|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|10.5|lb|kg}}\n|-\n|India Pattern || [[File:India 3rd Pattern Brown Bess.jpg|300px]] || 1797 \u2014 1854<br>standard Infantry Musket 1797 \u2014 1854<br>(Some in use pre-1797 purchased from the East India Company for use in Egypt) || {{convert|39|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|55.25|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|9.68|lb|kg}}\n|-\n|New Land Pattern || [[File:New Land Pattern.jpg|300px]] || 1802 \u2014 1854<br>Issued only to the Foot Guards and 4th Regiment of Foot || {{convert|39|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|55.5|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|10.06|lb|kg}}\n|-\n|New Light Infantry Land Pattern || The detail differences between this musket and the standard New Land Pattern were a scrolled trigger guard similar to that of the [[Baker Rifle]] except more rounded, a browned barrel and a notch back-sight, the bayonet lug being used as the fore-sight.\n || 1811 \u2014 1854<br>Issued only to the 43rd, 51st, 52nd, 68th, 71st and 85th [[Light Infantry]] and the Battalions of the 60th Foot not armed with rifles || {{convert|39|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|55.5|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|10.06|lb|kg}}\n|-\n|Cavalry Carbine || [[File:Brown Bess Carbine.jpg|300px]] || 1796 \u2014 1838<br>Issued to cavalry units || {{convert|26|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|42.5|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|7.37|lb|kg}}\n|-\n|Sea Service Pattern || [[File:Sea Pattern Brown Bess.jpg|300px]] || 1778 \u2014 1854<br>Issued to Royal Navy ships, drawn by men as required, Marines used Sea Service weapons when deployed as part of a ship's company but were issued India Pattern weapons when serving ashore || {{convert|37|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|53.5|in|mm|adj=on}} || {{convert|9.00|lb|kg}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Brown Bess}}\n* [[British military rifles]]\n* [[List of wars involving England]]\n* [[List of wars involving Great Britain]]\n* [[List of wars involving the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Military history of England]]\n* [[Military history of Britain]]\n* [[Military history of the United Kingdom]]\n* [[British Armed Forces]]\n* [[United Kingdom Special Forces]]\n* [[Charleville musket]]\n* [[Potzdam Musket|Potzdam musket]]\n* [[Jezail]]\n* [[M1752 Musket|Spanish Model 1752 Musket]]\n* [[Springfield musket]]\n* [[Musket]]\n* [[Rifle]]\n* [[Carbine]]\n* [[Pistoleer]]\n* [[Historical reenactment]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Other references==\n* Cumpston, Mike. \"The Guns of Empire: 18th Century Martial Muskets\" ''Guns Magazine'', August 2008, p.&nbsp;60. FMG Publications, San Diego, CA\n* Reid, Stuart. ''British Redcoat (2) 1793\u20131815'' Warrior Series, Osprey Publishing\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Brown Bess}}\n* [http://www.militaryheritage.com/muskets.htm Detailed Brown Bess Images and Information. Correct Source of Images with Blue Background.]\n* [http://www.lincolnminutemen.org/brown-bess-musket-misconception/ Brown Bess - Musket Misconception]\n* [http://www.poemhunter.com/poem/brown-bess-2/ Kipling's poem \"Brown Bess\"]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SJMbxZ1k9NQ Brown Bess Musket: Three shots in 46 seconds (video)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3oPPF6hk8u4 Live Fire (Brown Bess) Volley at 60 yards www.kings8th.com (video)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=569ItSV64FM Revolutionary War Soldier Explaining (Brown Bess) Flintlock Musket (Colonial Williamsburg) (video)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lrRSy55XJNA A demonstration of a British Brown Bess Musket (video)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tiQUYnv64mQ (Brown Bess) Musket Firing Demonstration Part 1 (Minuteman National Park) (video)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VgrLWwZeVYQ (Brown Bess) Musket Firing Demonstration Part 2 (Minuteman National Park) (video)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ho-QCmnNMl8 How to fire a Brown Bess musket - English Heritage (video)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=trgZmM9fNS0 Brown Bess Flintlock Musket Accuracy - updated (Australia) (video)]\n\n{{BritishEmpireWeapons}}\n{{Early firearms}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n\n[[Category:18th-ce